<SLUG> BC-BBO-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERETT NOT SHY ABOUT TAKING HIS RIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Carl Everett walked into Veterans Stadium
Saturday afternoon, said hello to Bret Saberhagen, shared a joke
with Nomar Garciaparra, briefly watched a big-screen TV showing two
boxers punishing each other, jokingly told 53-year-old bullpen
coach John Cumberland that he was going to knock him out and,
finally, stepped to his own locker for a shocking announcement:
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now,'' he said, ``I suck.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett said that before the Red Sox took the gruesome carpet in
this stadium, a place that is so 1970s that the ragged turf could
be replaced with shag carpeting and few would complain. Everett
spoke before the Sox lost to the Phillies, a team that frequently
plays tag with the Astros for the worst record in the National
League. Everett also got it wrong. He's terrible? I don't think so.
Some of his teammates should be willing to make the same bold
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have already had a bad weekend. They lost Saturday
night's game, 9-3, which ensures them of losing this series.
</P>
<P>
   Until Friday night, the Sox thought Pedro Martinez would be the
pitcher who would oppose the Phillies' Randy Wolf. Now, if anyone
wants to argue whether a pitcher should be an MVP, tell them this:
Martinez has given up nine runs all season; the men who pitched in
his slot _ Tim Wakefield, Dan Smith, and Rob Stanifer _ helped the
Phillies score nine runs.
</P>
<P>
   So, no Carl, you are not the problem. Neither is Garciaparra,
whose average is .377. Neither is John Wasdin, who was strangely
optioned to Triple A Pawtucket and replaced by Stanifer. I have
never confused Wasdin with Sandy Koufax, but is there really a
difference between Wasdin and Stanifer? Phillies catcher Mike
Lieberthal probably doesn't think so. He hit two home runs, one of
them a shot to left off Stanifer.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the Sox are in the throes of something that
is preventing them from being themselves. They are a socialistic
baseball team, with everyone contributing his share of something.
But the only thing they have been able to do collectively lately is
catch colds. They are 4-9 in their last 13 games. This is not
necessarily a crisis. It is more shame than crisis because they are
wasting good opportunities. They have wasted a chance to separate
from the Yankees, who lost Saturday. They have also wasted some
amazing efforts by the man who _ incorrectly _ says he is no good.
</P>
<P>
   Everett has 10 RBIs in his last five games and 23 in his last
17. He has 18 home runs, including four in the previous five games.
He is on pace for a ridiculous 58-homer season. He had 11 RBIs last
week. If he keeps all this up, he will certainly be an All-Star.
He's not impressed with anything, particularly the homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what? That's one hit,'' he said. ``I haven't done anything
else. What else have I done? Guys have been on first and third and
I'll punch out. Or ground out. I normally make solid contact. Right
now, I'm rolling out to the infield and hitting soft fly balls to
the shortstop.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett is batting .327. He had a run-scoring single in the
fourth that scored Garciaparra. He was up with the bases loaded in
the eighth, but sent a sacrifice fly to right to drive in another
run. He cursed himself after that, thinking he should have had
more. But at least he got the RBI, a run that made it 6-3 with one
out and a man on third. Jason Varitek was up next, but the catcher
couldn't bring in another run.
</P>
<P>
   A man stranded on third with fewer than two outs. When you are
playing in a power era and are not known for your power, you have
to find a way to score there. These are the things the Sox are
struggling with lately. They need to get back to their socialistic
roots.
</P>
<P>
   After a weekend like this, fans will be calling for Dan Duquette
to trade for Juan Gonzalez or Jose Canseco. Everett won't be one of
those fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa, nobody would be
thinking about home runs like they are right now,'' he said. ``When
you see a highlight, all they think about is a home run. Mark
McGwire doesn't hit three-run homers because other guys hit homers,
too. He hits them because those other guys got base hits. I'm all
about the base hit.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. The Sox don't necessarily need someone else capable
of hitting 430-foot homers. They have in-house solutions. For
example, Troy O'Leary is a .283 career hitter. He was on the bench,
nursing a .221 average. Jose Offerman is hurt. In a lot of ways.
He's on the disabled list with a .231 average. Both of their slumps
are much more obvious than Everett's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the Scottie Pippen of baseball,'' Everett said. ``I'll do
whatever you want me to do. If you want me to take a guy out, I'll
take him out. Want me to hit, I'll hit. Want me to catch, I'll
catch.'' Everett added that he will even take his friends out on
the basepaths because, ``Hell, we can be buddies after the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Sox needed more than that. Everett, Garciaparra, and
Mike Stanley were the only starters to hit the ball out of the
infield. That's a problem that is even out of Everett's reach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
