<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S CURTAINS FOR SOMEONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The giant distiller that is the NBA playoffs has
reduced a magnificent Los Angeles Lakers season to a singular event
that could be as cruel as it is enticing, as unforgiving as it is
promising, with equal potential for devastation or elation.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-eight games later, all their winning streaks and records
and accolades have been boiled down to a simple proposition: Win
today and meet the Indiana Pacers in the NBA Finals, lose and
render all those nifty achievements meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the last six days, the Lakers failed to finish off the
Portland Trail Blazers, and let control of the Western Conference
finals slip away.
</P>
<P>
   Yet among the many emotions that flashed in the aftermath of
Friday's Game 6 loss - anger, frustration, bewilderment - the most
striking came from the man hired to end the Lakers' long string of
postseason disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   From coach Phil Jackson: defiance.
</P>
<P>
   He was also calm and reflective and upbeat, and quick with the
one-liners Saturday, prior to a workout at Staples Center. But with
regard to Portland, which won two straight to tie this series,
Jackson was resolute: the greatest challenge still belongs to the
Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   Because to win the series would mean beating the Lakers three
straight times. And of the many hallmarks of this season, among the
most impressive is the Lakers never lost three consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of meaning to it. It says a lot about our
team,'' Jackson said. ``And as I told the team last night, it's
tough to beat a team three times in a row, on their home court.
Well, guess what, Portland's gotta beat us three times in a row on
our home court. It's going to be a damn tough game for them to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet so far, the Blazers have overcome every hurdle in this
series.
</P>
<P>
   They have bounced back from a 3-1 deficit. Won twice on the
road. And in the biggest game of the year, held Shaquille O'Neal to
17 points - his lowest output in 10 meetings with Portland this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the Blazers have chipped away at the feeling of
invincibility that Jackson said his team had created after sweeping
Games 3 and 4 at the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Lakers regrouped Saturday, regret was one emotion
they didn't show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just watched film, our normal routine,'' Derek Fisher said.
``There was no cutting off of heads or anything like that going on
in there. Just taking care of the business at hand.''
</P>
<P>
   They have no doubt kicked themselves for not putting away the
Blazers in Game 5, when they were at home, or in Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't do that now,'' said Kobe Bryant. ``After we win the
game, we'll think about it a little bit. We'll be like, `damn!' We
love putting ourselves in these types of situations, but right now,
you can't think about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't let yourself get too down. For what? You can't kill
yourself over it. This is our situation, and now we've got to deal
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The time for major adjustments is long past, so the Lakers - who
won 67 games behind O'Neal - will lean hard on the league MVP once
more. With, they hope, better results than in Friday's loss, when
O'Neal went 7 for 17 from the field and 3 for 10 from the line.
</P>
<P>
   When the Lakers have won, O'Neal has beaten the Blazers' quick
double- teams or exploited them with deft passing. Friday, he was
shuttered in and shut out, and - according to the Lakers - also
chopped and hacked without officials blowing the whistle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy, though,'' mused Robert Horry. ``When he does that,
the next night he's in another world. So hopefully everything will
stay true to form and he'll come out and carry us like he has all
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know him, he's going to get hacked and not get calls. ...
He's MVP, they claim he should be able to handle all that stuff.
But stuff like that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Said O'Neal: ``I don't make excuses. We just have to come back.
We'll be at home. Hopefully, those shots will fall for myself and
some of my teammates.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who has maintained all season that he can't read his
team, said he had no clue what to expect from them today - fast
start or slow, high energy or low, defensive-minded or offensively
fluid.
</P>
<P>
   But he reflected the general mood of the team in viewing today's
event as inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers and Blazers circled each other all season, finished
with the two best records in the NBA and have evenly split their 10
meetings. It is, perhaps, only appropriate that it all comes down
to one game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're all anxious, there's no doubt about our anxiety
level is high,'' Jackson said. ``And it should be. We're all
pointing towards (this) game with a lot of anticipation. We're all
wanting everybody to step up and play well, and supportive. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that this is all queued in to be a seven-game series
at the beginning,'' he said, then added with a smile, ``and I think
the NBA and NBC got exactly what they wanted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
