r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     06-04 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ'S LEGACY DEPENDS ON THIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Somebody asked Shaquille O'Neal's opinion Saturday
on Arvydas Sabonis' play against him in these Western Conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   The look O'Neal shot his inquisitor was what you'd expect if
Diana Ross was asked how it was sharing a stage with the Supremes.
</P>
<P>
   A less frosty mug got Portland forward Rasheed Wallace thrown
out of Game 1 of this best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   The deciding Game 7 is today at the Staples Center. A good
thing, too, because what started as a confluence of the two teams
with the NBA's best regular-season records has deteriorated into a
toxic tributary.
</P>
<P>
   Any further games after this one and they'd have to dispense
with the three officials and bring in Jerry Springer.
</P>
<P>
   We were worried O'Neal was going to go one-on-one with the
reporter who had Sabonis on the brain. His was a fair line of
questioning inasmuch as Friday marked the first game in this series
where the 7-foot-3 center stayed out of foul trouble long enough to
be effective against a player who long has owned him.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal saw it differently, of course, which is what happens when
you're blinded by pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't done anything,'' O'Neal said curtly. ``He has three
players helping him. I don't give him any credit at all. None.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ask me about a one-on-one matchup. No one will ever play
me one-on-one. I've got four players on me. I'm angry because you
ask me about (bleeping) Sabonis. He can't (bleeping) play.''
</P>
<P>
   Ladies and gentlemen of the media, meet ``The Big Combustible.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's explosion wasn't all bad. It was a relief to see him
breathe some fire, however misdirected his fury.
</P>
<P>
   The eighth-year center was strangely subdued in the 10-point
loss at the Rose Garden that forced today's winner-take-all grudge
match. Sabonis, Brian Grant and Rasheed Wallace used a triangle
defense on O'Neal that had the same effect on him as would 48
minutes in a sauna.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal moved lethargically on defense, doing little to clog the
lanes that the Trail Blazers used as express routes to the basket.
He was sluggish in the paint, shooting as though he first required
permission. And his free-throw shooting was an affront to charity.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal proved in Game 4 he can be a fabulous foul shooter when
he puts his mind to it; he made all nine free throws he tried in
that game and was a decent 7 for 12 in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   The main thing O'Neal has to do today, besides bend his knees
when shooting free throws, is come out and play from the opening
tip as though his legacy depends on it.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, 28, won his first league MVP title this season by
elevating his individual game to heights not seen since Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar and Wilt Chamberlain patrolled the paint.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a terrific year in a resplendent career.
</P>
<P>
   And yet ...
</P>
<P>
   Fair or foul, the fact is this: O'Neal won't gain entry into the
circle of basketball's all-time greats until he succeeds in
exerting his individual will on the collective body otherwise known
as his supporting cast.
</P>
<P>
   We're not saying he has to take 30 shots or score 61 points.
We're not suggesting he lead the search party trying to find Robert
Horry's jumper or help Glen Rice get his mojo back.
</P>
<P>
   All O'Neal has to do is lead by example. If he plays with
abandon and asserts himself early, his teammates will follow him
all the way to the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, O'Neal suffers from the same persecution complex
that plagued Abdul-Jabbar and Chamberlain. It is the curse of the
big man, this feeling of being picked on by a world thrown a bit
off its axis by one's size.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Jackson, for one, thinks that what O'Neal feels is real.
The Lakers' first-year coach sees the bruises that cover O'Neal's
body like tattoos. He knows they are the marks of a warrior.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal largely keeps quiet because nobody likes to see a big man
cry. On Saturday, Jackson wondered anew if that's the right
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I feel that he should be more demonstrative about
what he's going through out there,'' Jackson said. ``He stays so
compliant at times that I think it takes away from the energy level
of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, a former NBA forward for whom emotion was his primary
fuel, could appreciate O'Neal's acquiescence on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're on a visiting court and you make an issue and
you're a pariah like he is in a town like Portland, it's going to
draw more and more animosity from the fans,'' Jackson said. ``And
we're trying to keep the crowd out of it. So that's part of Shaq's
game that I admire. (His compliance) is more than I could have done
as a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Today is different.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are playing at Staples Center, where O'Neal isn't a
pariah but a prince. He can count on having 19,000 fans in his
entourage. They all will have his back. Where he leads, they will
follow.
</P>
<P>
   The stage belongs to O'Neal. The setting couldn't be more
perfect. Ready or not, it's time for his close-up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
