<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAGE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNSKILLED VALLEY JOBS PAY ABOVE MINIMUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY RICCARDO A. DAVIS  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - In this economy, even baby-sitting is lucrative.
</P>
<P>
   Baby-sitters are asking, and getting, $8 an hour, nearly $3
above the national minimum wage. And they're not the only ones
drawing higher-than-ever wages in the Phoenix area.
</P>
<P>
   Starting pay for most entry-level positions, such as customer
service representatives, nurses assistants and office clerks, is
$10 an hour, according to area companies.
</P>
<P>
   That's well above the national minimum wage of $5.15 an hour,
even well above the higher minimum wage of $6.15 an hour being
proposed by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It's gotten so that ``nobody pays the minimum wage` anymore,
said Tom Silverman, co-owner of the Chaparral Suites Hotel in
Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman, chairman of the Arizona Department of Tourism, said
the service industry already is paying more than minimum wage for
beginning employees, competing in the marketplace against
restaurants and stores.
</P>
<P>
   At Avnet, a Phoenix-based computer components distributor, the
lowest paying, entry-level, non-skilled job _ that of custodian _
pays $7 an hour, said Jan Jurcy, a spokeswoman for Avnet.
</P>
<P>
   The firm is considering pushing that to $9 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Avnet and other companies are finding that they have to pay more
to get and keep workers. The Phoenix area's unemployment rate is
2.6 percent, well below the national 30-year low of 3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fuddruckers starts its hamburger restaurant employees at $5.50
anhour.
</P>
<P>
   `That's just to get a higher caliber person in the door,` said
Glen Lewis, general manager of the chain's eatery at Superstition
Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies still pay minimum wage, but to a smaller
percentage of their workers. Or, they pay minimum wage plus tips.
</P>
<P>
   Tosco, owner of Circle K convenience stores, hires its shelf
stockers at the minimum wage. But only a small percentage of the
firm's more than 3,500 Phoenix area employees are paid that, Tosco
spokeswoman Julie Igo said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Arizona Baseball Club, a private restaurant
at Bank One Ballpark, was looking for part-time food runners and
busers at $6 and $5.25 an hour, respectively. However, those
workers also get tips.
</P>
<P>
   Although minimum-wage boosts typically draw opposition from
businesses worried about profits, Clinton's proposed increase
wouldn't have drastic consequences, most local business owners say.
</P>
<P>
   Fuddruckers, for example, would not have to lay off any of its
workers as a result of an increase, Lewis said. But he may have to
cut employees' hours slightly to maintain profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Stallman is marketing director for the 130 stores at
Superstition Springs Center. He said that with the robust economy,
a $1-per-hour minimum-wage bump likely won't force stores to cut
staff.
</P>
<P>
   `I don't see them hiring fewer workers,` he said. `If they don't
have the sales people, they lose income.`
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Circle K may raise some prices to offset the
wage increase, Igo said. `It is always a possibility that if the
cost of labor goes up, so do prices.` &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Riccardo.Davis(at)Arizona Republic.com or
(602) 444-8894.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 0026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
