<DOCNO> NYT20000604.0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4055 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      06-04 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHERS, MARTYRS AND MEXICANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J.MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - A young mother, much like the young mother of Elian
Gonzalez, gave up her life last week during a brave but foolish
attempt to bring her child into this country, and from the
politicians we hear nothing.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nothing from Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., who issued a congressional
subpoena to block Elian's father from tak ing him back to Cuba
until the matter could be resolved in American courts.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing from Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., who said he was `ashamed of
my government` for not trying to keep Elian in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing from Rep. J.D. Hayworth, R-Ariz., who called on
congressional leaders `to immediately bring up legislation to give
Elian permanent residency status.`
</P>
<P>
   Nothing from Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore or
Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush, each of whom has
said he wants a `family court` to decide whether Elian should stay
or return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   All of these statesmen, and many more, have spoken with misty
affection about how Elian's mother sacrificed her life to provide a
better future for her child.
</P>
<P>
   It's exactly what this other mother did. Still, they say
nothing, because she didn't come from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   She came from Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   According to U.S. and Mex ican officials, 19-year-old Yo landa
Gonzalez of Oaxaca died last Monday in the Ari zona desert after
walking for days in 100-degree heat.
</P>
<P>
   The whole time she carried her 18-month-old daughter, Elizama.
Others on the trip told investigators the mother only had 2 gallons
of water and drank little so her child would have enough.
</P>
<P>
   Yolanda supposedly was entering the United States to search for
her baby's father. Young Elian's mother had a similar story. She
was on her way to America with her boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians ignore such mo tives, however. To them, it's never
about displaced people seeking lost love or fleeing poverty. It's
only about Com munism.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keat ing, who once worked for the FBI and
the Justice Depart ment, said recently of Elian's case, `If a
mother had been shot by an East Berlin border guard and tossed the
child over the wall just before she died, we would never send the
child back.`
</P>
<P>
   Yet, we have no trouble chucking a kid back across the Mexican
border.
</P>
<P>
   Elizama was handed over to the Mexican Consulate and is expected
to be returned to her mother's home in Mexico within a few weeks.
No sub poena. No hearings. No court challenges. No speeches. No
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   We are told the little girl has curly hair and was badly
sunburned, though she is re covering.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the U.S. Border Patrol said it doesn't provide
personal information in cases like this. And for the time being,
the Mexican Con sulate in Tucson doesn't have much to add.
</P>
<P>
   Why should they?
</P>
<P>
   There's been no outcry. Most of the newspapers and TV networks
that spent months covering the little Cuban boy's dilemma have
ignored the plight of the little Mexican girl.
</P>
<P>
   There's no reason to care about Elizama or her dead mother.
There's nothing polit ical to gain from their trag edy. There's no
point in being warm-hearted when you're still fighting a Cold War. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Montini at  &QL; 
Ed.Montini &LR; Arizona Republic.com or (602) 444-8978. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 0027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
