<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4059 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-GONZALEZ-FUNERAL-LADN     06-04 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GONZALEZ-FUNERAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAPD CHIEF'S GRANDDAUGHTER MOURNED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIK NELSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The day before her what would have been her 21st
birthday, more than 1,000 friends, family and public officials
mourned Lori Gonzalez on Saturday, decrying the out-of-control
urban violence that many, including her grandfather, Los Angeles
Police Chief Bernard C. Parks, said her slaying represented.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lori is a symbol of all the victims who have lost their blood
to the violence in our society,'' Bishop Charles E. Blake, said in
his eulogy at the Crenshaw Christian Center funeral service in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Uniformed police officers and a gospel singer stood behind the
beige-and-pink coffin draped with pink-and-white roses and sang
``The Wind Beneath My Wings,'' and ``I Believe I Can Fly'' for her.
Ministers of several faiths praised her and a U.S. senator and the
president sent their condolences.
</P>
<P>
   Later, after laying his 20-year-old granddaughter to rest on a
hilltop overlooking Westchester and the Pacific Ocean, the police
chief recalled the last thing his granddaughter said to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `I love you, Poppy,' and then she got off the phone.
I will always remember that,'' Parks said while surrounded by
members of his family and the family of Joe Gonzalez, Lori's
father.
</P>
<P>
   That conversation took place on May 27, the day before the
Saddleback College student was shot to death in her Chevrolet
Caprice as she pulled out of a fast-food restaurant at La Brea
Avenue and Jefferson Boulevard in the Jefferson Park neighborhood
of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe the intended target was a longtime
acquaintance sitting across from her who ducked out of the path of
the bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Police have named no suspects in the killing, but Parks would
say only that investigators have ``pretty good leads. The issue is
how do we put a case together?''
</P>
<P>
   The chief said that while he has been detached from his job
since the killing, the department has ``some of the best
investigators'' working on the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt in my mind that they will solve this crime,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he has maintained his composure during the ordeal,
Parks briefly let go of the stoic countenance he had worn most of
the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for Bobbie Parks, I could not make it,'' the
chief said of his wife as his voice quavered and he wiped away
tears.
</P>
<P>
   In statements from the slain woman's eulogy to a letter from
President Clinton to Parks' own comments, the death was
characterized as another example of how violence in American cities
- particularly gun violence - has victimized young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``People across America have been shocked and saddened that yet
another one of our young people has lost her life to gun
violence,'' said Clinton in a message read by Los Angeles Mayor
Richard Riordan during the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Blake, in his eulogy, empathized with the grieving family
members by recalling the pain he felt when he learned his son,
Lawrence, had been shot while attending college in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   His son survived, he said, and Gonzalez, too, would live on in
the things she had done and the people she had touched in her
nearly 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   She had helped build homes in Mexico with scrap material she and
members of her Orange County church brought across the border. She
taught Sunday school and when she was in beautician school, helped
convince a young man with scars on his head that he was still
good-looking.
</P>
<P>
   A photograph of the Saddleback College student was printed on
the cover of the funeral service program, and inside was a collage
of more photos, including Gonzalez as a baby, a little girl in a
bunny costume and a graduate in a white cap and gown holding up a
red-bound diploma from Redondo Union High School.
</P>
<P>
   Blake said Gonzalez would live on as a symbol of the destruction
brought by urban violence, which he traced to factors that include
poverty, a lack of education and pervasive violent images on
television, movies and computers.
</P>
<P>
   Parks echoed that sentiment, and said the killing of his
granddaughter reminded him of how much needs to be done to control
and prevent crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times we celebrate the reduction of crime, but we
still fail thousands of times a year,'' the police chief said.
</P>
<P>
   Parks' wife, Bobbie Parks, said she had a message for her
granddaughter's killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping and praying that you find it in your heart to
never do this again,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
