<DOCNO> NYT20000604.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4060 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-LEBRETON-STARS-TE     06-04 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS OPPONENT SEEMS TO BE A DIFFERENT BREED OF DEVIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Little by disarming little, we are getting to know the
New Jersey Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Stars fans would be wise to heed the storm warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, teams have skated into Reunion Arena before, shrugged at the
Slurpee conditions, and slipped away with a one-goal victory over
the Stars. Those hockey teams, fans might smugly point out, were
eventually dispatched. The Stars were always on a mission.
</P>
<P>
   But this visitor is different. The Devils seem both patient and
purposeful. For the defending champs, they are 60 minutes of
matchup problems.
</P>
<P>
   With the Devils' 2-1 triumph last night, they snatched the
home-ice advantage back in their favor in these Stanley Cup Finals.
But that looms as just a subplot.
</P>
<P>
   They are beating the Stars at their own game, and then some.
Game 3 looked a lot like Game 2, which in some ways could have
looked like Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for Stars goaltender Ed Belfour, in other words, the
Devils could have won all three.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are on a mission, all right _ mission survival.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Ken Hitchcock will be criticized for his decision last
night not to match his Mike Modano line against the visitors' line
of Petr Sykora, Patrik Elias and Jason Arnott. But Hitch's
explanation rang with an ominous truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed better advantage,'' Hitchcock said. ``There is no
point in only breaking even.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, breaking even at this stage would almost seem to be a
bold assumption. Arnott and Company continue to generate trouble
with their speed and stickwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been doing this for us all year,'' New Jersey's Scott
Niedermayer said. ``They're a big part of this team's offense, and
they did it again for us tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   After Arnott's goal gave the Devils a 1-all knot and denied the
Stars a chance to break things open early, Sykora's one-timer in
the second period proved to be the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking even? The Modano line's best chances to level the score
were all stopped cold by goalie Martin Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   As palpably unsensational as Brodeur was in the first two games,
he was solid in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what playoff hockey is all about,'' Brodeur said.
``There is no room to breathe out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a few good chances, but not overly. I saw most of the
pucks in that third period, and that makes a big difference when
you're late in the game. If you're able to see the puck, most of
the time you will stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   For eight months, that has been Belfour's credo as well. In his
cold-medicated fog Eddie was awful in Game 1. But he has given his
team a chance to win both of these last two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Eddie played great tonight,'' the Devils' Randy
McKay said. ``I thought we had some phenomenal scoring chances that
he took away.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur, however, was every bit his match, and then some. He was
helped along by the Devils' three penalty kills.
</P>
<P>
   But as coach Larry Robinson said, ``A lot of times your best
penalty killer is the guy between the pipes, and he made huge stops
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with Modano matched against the Devils' Scott Gomez line,
the Stars were never able to cash an opportunity. Which made
Hitchcock's strategy seem for naught.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it was some change from Game 2 but, you know, we
are put out there,'' Modano said. ``The key to our success is our
depth, and if we are scoring one or two goals a game, we still need
that support.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it was last year. We always got key goals from
everybody throughout our lineup, and it made life a lot easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, that was last year. These guys are the Devil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000604.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4061 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-DEVILS-TEX     06-04 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-DEVILS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS GET HOME-SCHOOLED BY DEVILS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Game 3 of the Stanley Cup Finals had to look like a
big, fat juicy fastball to the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   They had stolen a game and home ice from the New Jersey Devils
in Game 2. They were three victories away from repeating as Cup
champions. And the next two games were at Reunion Arena, where they
had lost only once in this year's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say the Stars whiffed on the high, hard one, losing
2-1 in Game 3 last night at Reunion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disappointed,'' Stars forward Joe Nieuwendyk said, summing up
the mood of the room. ``We had an opportunity with a couple of home
games to really do some damage. You really want to win, and,
obviously, we failed in that effort.''
</P>
<P>
   With a national television audience watching in prime time on
ABC, the Stars and Devils provided a surprisingly exciting,
chance-filled game. Unfortunately for the Stars, the Devils No. 1
line of Petr Sykora, Jason Arnott and Patrik Elias were the ones
with most of them.
</P>
<P>
   The line was on the ice for both of their goals. Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock had been playing No. 1 against No. 1, Mike Modano's line
vs. Elias' line, but decided to go away with it because he thought
they ``needed a better advantage. There is no point in only
breaking even.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano didn't seem to understand the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt after Game 2 that that would be a definitive
matchup,'' Modano said. ``Obviously, it was some change from Game
2, but you know, we are put out there. We play against who they
want us to play against.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils' top line helped generate both New Jersey goals, the
first by Arnott to tie the game with 1:54 remaining in the first
period, the second a power-play goal by Sykora at 12:27 of the
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Patrik Elias after the game I was very proud of them,''
New Jersey coach Larry Robinson said. ``I talked to them before,
and I think nobody feels worse than they do that they didn't come
out and have a good game in Game 2.''
</P>
<P>
   They more than made up for it. All the Devils did. Without the
play of Stars goalie Ed Belfour, the score could've been a whole
lot worse. He stopped 29 of the 31 shots he faced, including a
number of point-blank chances to keep Jersey's lead 2-1. But the
Devils' first goal, the one that changed the momentum of the game,
bothered him after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of wish I could have that one back,'' Belfour said.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils called it the turning point. Exactly one minute and
four seconds had passed since the Stars had failed to score on a
power play, including 49 seconds of five-on-three.
</P>
<P>
   Arnott, despite having company in the form of Derian Hatcher and
Dave Manson on both sides of him, managed to get a shot on Belfour.
The puck squeaked through between Belfour's legs. The Stars had
been caught on a change, Manson coming on for Richard Matvichuk,
who lost his stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that late goal there deflated us a little bit,''
Hatcher said. ``And we really weren't able to get it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Until that point, the Stars looked to be in firm control of it.
Thanks in part to a power-play goal by Stars defenseman Sylvain
Cote at 13:08 of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey captain Scott Stevens tried to clear a rebound of a
Jere Lehtinen shot, but his attempt landed on Cote's stick. With
Devils goalie Martin Brodeur out of position and flat on his face,
the goal was open, and Cote took advantage scoring a power play.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils have only allowed four power-play goals on 57 chances
all playoffs, best in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   But what the power play giveth, the power play also taketh away.
</P>
<P>
   With Cote in the box for what he thought was a questionable
elbowing call, the Devils took their first lead since Game 1 when
Sykora scored at 12:27 of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a weird play,'' Cote said. ``I kind of got the
gloves in the face, an elbow. Even the referee was kind of yelling
at him to keep his elbow down. ... Sometimes, they're too slow to
see the first infraction, but they don't miss the second I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the Devils got the lead, they never relinquished it.
They're a lot like the Stars in that respect. When they carry a
lead into the third period, they don't allow much offensively. They
literally choke the offense right out of a team, which they did to
the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas' best chance was a power play in the first minutes, but
the Stars could only muster two shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it negates everything,'' Hatcher said.
``Obviously, we're disappointed we lost, disappointed to be down in
the series. But we'll talk about it \Rtoday\S and bounce back for
Game 4. We have a choice. It's fight on or quit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have said it so many times now that they have to be
sick of their own lack of explanation for why they don't seem to
play really good until their backs are against the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Which is good news for Game 4 tomorrow night. Their backs are
definitely up against it now. If they lose, they go down 3-1 with
Game 5 in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the home team looks to be having trouble holding
serve in this series.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so maybe the whole home-ice advantage thing isn't that big
of a deal anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're right back where we were,'' Devils forward John Madden
said. ``I would sum it up this way: It's like we won two games in
our building, and they won one in theirs. They have to win another
game now.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
