<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALL 9-1-1: DEVILS IN TEXAS LOOKING FOR A CUP TO STEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ There's trouble in Cup City. A better team showed up
last night. It was the other team. This must be the work of the
devil, or Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the results of Game 3, which was all about New Jersey
being much more dominant than a 2-1 victory would indicate, the
Stanley Cup Finals has reached its first crisis point.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are now in a 9-1-1 emergency for tomorrow night.
Either win Game 4 or the Stanley Cup is leaving this town for a
toxic waste dump in East Rutherford. Next question. How do the
Stars win Game 4, based on what was seen last night at Reunion
Arena and has basically been seen through the first three games?
</P>
<P>
   In a very unpleasant surprise for local puck lovers, the Devils
have simply been better in all areas, including for Game 3 that
small piece of real estate between the pipes.
</P>
<P>
   You know the Stars are up against it when Eddie Belfour is
outplayed twice in three games, and it wasn't that Eddie had an
awful evening last night. In fact, the Devils had at least a dozen
prime scoring chances on Belfour, and converted, well, none.
</P>
<P>
   The two goals New Jersey did score were both of a questionable
nature _ in other words, Eddie has been handling those kind of
threats throughout the postseason. To call them ``soft'' goals
would be wrong, however. Then again, ``soft'' is the proper way to
describe the support Belfour got from his skaters.
</P>
<P>
   Coming back with home ice and the series tied was expected to
create a motivational frenzy for the Stars, and through most of the
first period that appeared to be the story. But once a 5-on-3 power
play came up empty late in the period, when there was a chance to
expand a 1-0 lead, the Devils put a pin in that balloon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our penalty killers won the game for us,'' New
Jersey coach Larry Robinson said. Larry is right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was Arnott's \RJason\S goal that caused us to
lose concentration,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. Hitch is
right.
</P>
<P>
   Both those factors late in the first period turned the game to
the Devils. Or actually, the Devils simply took over the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first period,'' added Hitchcock, ``Jersey controlled
the level of play. We're the team that is going to have to pick up
the pace. Yes, there's concern. Our inability to outwork them in
their zone is where we are right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of that is a credit to the way Jersey is playing, but it
still comes down to us not being able to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The shock, of course, is that the Stars didn't use Game 3 as the
jumping off point to take control of the series _ actually, the
Devils did, and their 2-1 series lead looks bigger if you are
willing to admit New Jersey has won all nine periods thus far. OK,
go ahead and call a couple of the periods a draw over the course of
the three games. But it still says the Stars haven't come out and
dominated a period.
</P>
<P>
   Last night appeared to start that way. Scott Stevens' wayward
clearing pass on a Stars' power play was like room service for
Sylvain Cote. He easily beat goalie Martin Brodeur and the Stars
were off and winging. It seemed to get better a minute later when
the Stars went back on the power play, which would become a 5-on-3
for 49 seconds after Claude Lemieux took a stupid penalty.
</P>
<P>
   But the Stars didn't have a major threat with the two-man
advantage, then couldn't connect on the 5-on-4 portion of the
Lemieux penalty.
</P>
<P>
   That left the Reunion masses with an uneasy feeling, and sure
enough, Arnott made the Stars pay with a great play in the final
two minutes of the period. Coming right up Broadway at Belfour,
Arnott fought through a sandwich of Derian Hatcher and Dave Manson,
caught up with a slow-rolling puck, then tucked it between
Belfour's legs. The ol' 5-hole trick tied the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had played a great first period, then we lost energy on
that goal,'' said Hitchcock. ``I thought \RArnott's\S goal set us
back a little bit. I don't think we played with a sense of
desperation until halfway through the third period that we did in
the first period.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils did thoroughly dominate the second period, and after
Belfour had some massive saves on one power play, New Jersey got a
second shot at him with the man advantage. Belfour was under siege
on this one, and his penalty killers couldn't clear the puck, so
they were on the ice too long. But what became the game-winning
goal was an innocent looking blast by Petr Sykora from the point
that Belfour got a glove on, but not enough glove. The puck went
whizzing through his mitt for the 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After that, it was mainly a case of Brodeur being up to every
challenge, including a 6-on-5 bomb from Brett Hull in the final
minute. That one bounced off Brodeur's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   But overall, the victory belonged to the team that deserved it.
And now the crisis in this series belongs to the Stars.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
