<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RANGERS-D'BACKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURTIS FILLS IN NICELY FOR INJURY-PLAGUED RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The trade was made right at the end of the
winter meetings, almost as an afterthought after the Rangers failed
to sign Todd Zeile or make any progress toward signing the
free-agent pitchers still on the market.
</P>
<P>
   On the baseball Richter Scale it barely registered a blip, no
more than one or two lines and a listing in transactions among the
national press. But, from a Rangers standpoint, Chad Curtis from
the Yankees for minor-league pitchers Sam Marsonek and Brandon
Knight is looking pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   In the first of many games without center fielder Ruben Mateo,
Curtis ripped a two-run home run last night that proved to be the
biggest blow in the Rangers' 4-3 victory over the Arizona
Diamondbacks at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Rogers pitched six innings to get the victory, raising his
record to 5-5 with a 4.00 earned-run average. His back stiffened up
in the sixth inning, but Tim Crabtree, Jeff Zimmerman and John
Wetteland pitched three innings of effective relief in steady rain
to hold off the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland has 11 saves in his past 11 appearances, although last
night's was helped considerably by left fielder Rusty Greer, who
ended the game with a diving catch of Bernard Gilkey's high pop in
left-center field to keep speedy Tony Womack from scoring from
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a lot of power,'' Greer said. ``When the ball went
up, I broke back. After that, I was pretty much sold out. With
Womack on first, as fast as he is, he's probably going to score.
When you dive for a ball, it's ... stick your glove out and hope it
goes in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks took a 1-0 lead in the third inning on doubles
by Hanley Frias and Jay Bell. But David Segui's run-scoring single
off Diamondbacks starter Nelson Figueroa tied it in the fourth, and
Curtis followed with a 408-foot homer over the center-field fence
to put the Rangers ahead for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like I had a good rhythm up there,'' Curtis
said. ``I was trying to simplify things, then I got to 3-1, a good
hitter's count, and he laid it in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, who has started 19 of the Rangers' past 21 games and 37
of 54 overall, has seven home runs and 27 runs batted through
exactly one-third the season. He had five home runs and 24 RBI all
last year for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would have thought he would have played as many innings
and had as many at-bats and done what he has done,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said. ``Since day one of spring training he
has been a good fit for us. You feel good when the game is on the
line and he's up there. He knows how the game is supposed to be
played, and he has a good idea of what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis was acquired as a fourth outfielder and a part-time
designated hitter. But the DH part went out when David Segui was
acquired from the Toronto Blue Jays, and the outfield part looked
extremely limited when Greer, Gabe Kapler and Mateo all had
excellent springs.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before all the injuries, the latest being the
broken leg suffered by Mateo on Friday, putting him out for the
season. With the Rangers planning to move Kapler to center field
when he comes off the disabled list later this week, Curtis is the
everyday right fielder for the foreseeable future barring a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said it before, you just stay patient because something
is going to happen,'' Curtis said. ``Each of the guys who were
slated to start have gone on the DL. You don't wish that on anyone,
but it's given me an opportunity.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
