<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERS-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEFFIELD SHOTS SINK ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Dodgers are the road team this
weekend, but for two consecutive games, Edison Field has been
infested with Dodger Blue.
</P>
<P>
   The 34,589 sun-splashed customers Saturday afternoon looked and
sounded like they were split down the middle supporting the
hometown Anaheim Angels and the 5 Freeway caravan from the north.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers faithful had little to celebrate the previous night
in a loss. They waited six at-bats to cheer the first recorded out
of an Angels hitter in a forgettable bottom of the first.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Orange County contingent was forced into the
silent treatment Saturday and didn't have much to holler about in
the Dodgers' 8-3 win to even the interleague series at a game each.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield was the Dodgers' major noise maker, hitting a
three-run homer in the first and a solo shot in third to put the
Angels in a 5-0 deficit that was never overcome.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels made the Dodgers' day - specifically pitcher Chan Ho
Park's day - much easier with errors in each of the first two
innings that scored two unearned runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely man ... I love that,'' Park said of the five early
runs his team scored. That two of the five were unearned made Park
feel even more secure since it affected his counterpart, Angels
starter Brian Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   ``You make a lot of runs early and they make it an easy
outing.''
</P>
<P>
   Park's 5 innings weren't as cozy as he hinted. But Sheffield's
home runs permitted Park (6-4) to get away with allowing eight
hits, walking four, hitting one and throwing two wild pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just hitting that home run and putting us up 3-0 really helps
Chan Ho. He didn't have to go up there and think, `I have to hold
them down,' '' Sheffield said. ``(The Angels) are a good offensive
team and it was big to get those three runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Park's struggles were also alleviated by an Angels lineup that
couldn't capitalize on its opportunities. Anaheim stranded 13
runners, eight in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Park and relievers Terry Adams, Onan Masaoka and Antonio Osuna
limited the Angels to just three hits in 15 at-bats with runners in
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scoring runs hasn't been our problem. Just inconsistency with
pitching,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chan Ho did a good job and I hope it's contagious. Chan Ho had
good stuff. He made a lot of quality pitches and he had a couple of
lapses.''
</P>
<P>
   Park threw 114 pitches, 63 for strikes, a factor in his shortest
outing since he lasted just 3 and was shelled for eight runs by
Arizona five starts ago. When he was giving the Angels chances to
beat him with the walks and wild pitches, he was bouncing back to
get the big outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can have fun on one pitch.'' said Park, who had seven
strikeouts. ``I can make one perfect pitch, but I can not make one
perfect game. Now I'm really learning to make one pitch at a
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper (2-1), the rookie from USC, is quickly absorbing the
finer points of pitching. He's made just eight major-league starts
spanning the last two seasons. But he's gotten through at least six
innings in all three of his outings in 2000 since being recalled
from Triple-A Edmonton on May 22.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his failure to keep Sheffield in the park and that early
5-0 hole he dug, Cooper went deeper into the game than the more
established Park, allowing four earned runs, one walk and eight
hits with five strikeouts in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at his poise, this guy goes and pitches seven
innings after the start he had,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia
said.
</P>
<P>
   The problems Sheffield caused Cooper isn't something National
League pitchers have solved all season. Despite playing with
various injuries, most recently a sprained right ankle, Sheffield
went 3 for 4 with four RBI and three runs scored and has 17 home
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at how selective he is as a hitter, look at how he
uses the whole field, how quick he is with his bat speed,''
Scioscia said. ``He's one of the top five hitters in the National
League, certainly. And out of the teams that we've seen, he'd be
hitting in the middle of the lineup if you put an all-star team
together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 0221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
