r s BC-SOC-GALAXY-METROSTARS     06-04 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-METROSTARS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER MATES BURN GALAXY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ There were former Los Angeles Galaxy players
partying all over their old turf, making the acquisition that
brought Mexican striker Luis Hernandez to the Galaxy look like the
bad deal Galaxy management knew it was - but doesn't talk about
much these days.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis, the young American striker lost in the dispersal draft,
and Roy Myers, gone because of salary cap issues - were sent to New
York so Los Angeles could make room for Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't you know it, both came back to haunt their former team.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis scored in the 48th minute and Roy Myers assisted on
Adolfo Valencia's goal in the 60th minute, leading to a 2-0 victory
Saturday night over the Galaxy before a measly 16,876 at the Rose
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy is 6-2-6 after starting the season 5-0-2. They're
1-2-4 during this recent seven-game skid, with only five goals
during that span.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, New York won for the third straight match since the
Hernandez allocation, improving to 6-6 under former Galaxy coach
Octavio Zambrano, who was forced to watch the game from a luxury
suite after getting tossed last week against the Chicago Fire.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid said the Hernandez trade has disrupted
his team's ability to play good soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to forget it about and move on,'' Schmid said. ``Our
team is using that as an excuse right now. That the league took
these players away and because they're gone we can't play right
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have players that can play, and they need to step
up and play. We need to forget about what the league did to us; I
think everyone can see what the league did to us. If we can put it
behind, we'll be successful, if we live in the past, we won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles was without striker Cobi Jones and defender Greg
Vanney, who were both with the U.S. National team for the U.S. Cup.
Jones, who hasn't scored since April 15 with the Galaxy, had his
best game as a professional Saturday, scoring two left-footed
strikes from long range to go with two assists in a 4-0 rout over
the Republic of South Africa in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Defender Robin Fraser would have been with the U.S. team, but an
injured ankle forced him to the sideline. L.A. was also without
midfield/forward Sebastian Vorbe, who is with Haiti's national team
for a World Cup qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   New York started pressuring in the second half as Mathis burned
his old friends, getting a fortunate bounce off the head of Galaxy
defender Paul Caligiuri. A long cross was sent in the middle for
Mathis, standing at the top of the penalty area. Caligiuri beat
Mathis to the ball, but his header bounced up and behind, leaving
Mathis all alone in front of Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis finished with a hard-low shot to the left-corner, then
ran around in celebration, lifting his MetroStars jersey, rubbing
it in with a T-shirt underneath that read: ``I love New York.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That (shirt) was not to disrespect L.A., I'm just trying to
make fans in New York,'' Mathis said.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis gave his impressions of the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It affected L.A. a lot,'' he said. ``You can bring in the best
player in the world, and I'm not trying to take anything away from
Hernandez, because he's a great player. But to take away three guys
from the starting lineup, that's tough to do for any team. It was
sad how it turned out, I was happy in L.A., but this is just part
of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmid left another partying shot for the MLS after he was asked
about the trade again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe somebody's happy, maybe New York will make it to the
finals, and everyone will be happy,'' he said. ``We'll all have a
party when it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy had its chances in the first half. In the 24th
minute, Hernandez turned on Metros defender Mike Petke, then fired
a left-footed shot from 18 yards straight-away that narrowly missed
the right post.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis blew a good chance to score in the 28th minute. The
sneaky striker slipped between two Galaxy defenders, gathering a
cross from Adolfo Valencia, but he pushed his first touch wide,
allowing Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman to slide in and kick it
away.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez turned on Petke again from the left side, getting a
good look at the Metros goal. He tried bending his shot to the far
netting, but goalkeeper Mike Ammann made a nice one-handed tip
save, leaving the game scoreless at the half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
