<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
Devils want sweep in Dallas, not a split 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ When the Stars faced the Avalanche in the Western
Conference Finals, Colorado players and coaches, not trying to get
too ahead of themselves, admitted their goal in Dallas was to get a
split, thus taking home-ice advantage. They said they would worry
about sweeps at home.
</P>
<P>
   But Devils coach Larry Robinson is more optimistic. Even though
a split would give the Devils home-ice advantage again, Robinson
said yesterday that wasn't his plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Robinson said. ``We are coming here to win both games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils are halfway to their goal after winning Game 3.
\Nsubheds:Still going Many have tried to explain the New Jersey
Devils' playoff success on the road.
</P>
<P>
   No matter the explanation, it's obvious the Devils have a thing
about sticking it to the opposition in that opponent's arena.
</P>
<P>
   With last night's 2-1 victory at Reunion Arena, the Devils are
an NHL-best 8-2 on the road during the playoffs. Their last road
loss came on May 16, in Game 2 of the Eastern Conference Finals at
Philadelphia. Since that loss, New Jersey has won three consecutive
road games, including Games 5 and 7 of the conference finals at
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Road success is nothing new to a winning Devils team. When New
Jersey won the 1995 Stanley Cup, it went 10-1 in other team's
arenas _ the most road playoff victories by any team in NHL
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how you explain it,'' Devils coach Larry Robinson
said. ``Maybe our team tries to keep the game a little bit more
simple. We don't maybe try to do fancy things we do at home. Maybe
we feed off the other team's crowd. I don't really have an
answer.''
\Nsubheds:Still not important New Jersey rookie Scott Gomez had no
interest in the statistic about the success of Game 1 winners in
the Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   After the Stars' Game 2 victory, he was similarly unfazed to
hear that teams winning Game 2 have taken 25 of the past 28 Stanley
Cups.
</P>
<P>
   And most likely he will not care that Game 3 victors have won
the Cup in 44 of 51 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are things you pay attention to when you're not playing
in the series,'' Gomez said.
\Nsubheds:The other guy Everybody knows about the ability of Devils
defenseman and team captain Scott Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   But his defensive mate, Brian Rafalski, isn't too bad either.
New Jersey coach Larry Robinson talked earlier this week about how
well Rafalski was playing in spite of all the attention given to
Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   Rafalski might not go unnoticed much longer after last night. He
threaded a pass to Jason Arnott on the Devils' first goal to get
the assist, then added another assist on the game-winner, a
power-play goal by Petr Sykora.
\Nsubheds:Can't keep a good team down If you think you've got New
Jersey in a hole at any time, you better think again.
</P>
<P>
   The much publicized comeback from a 3-1 deficit against
Philadelphia in the Eastern Conference Finals is only part of the
story when it comes to the Devils' unwillingness to be eliminated.
During the playoffs, New Jersey is 4-2 in games after a loss _
those two defeats occurring during its three consecutive losses to
the Flyers.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
