<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON: LAKERS TO PLAY HARDBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Lakers didn't like the way they
finished Game 6 on Friday, and neither did the Portland Trail
Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Blazers could walk off with the victory, they had to
absorb a few hard fouls (mostly from Shaquille O'Neal and Rick Fox)
and some harsher words (exchanged between Fox and Portland coach
Mike Dunleavy.)
</P>
<P>
   Whether a sign of Lakers frustration or a bit of tone-setting
for today's finale, it didn't sit well with the Blazers. Pippen
accused the Lakers of ``taking cheap shots at guys and trying to
start altercations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I didn't see that in watching the tape,'' said Jackson,
who also argued that O'Neal's third-quarter knockdown of Pippen
should not have been called a flagrant foul.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has been poking at Pippen, his former player with the
Chicago Bulls, since the series began, mostly light-heartedly. But
he issued a warning heading into today's decisive Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Scottie's going to come harder to us, we're going to come
harder to him,'' Jackson said. ``And same with Bonzi Wells and the
rest of them. If they're going to come hard to the basket, we've
got to stop penetration.''
</P>
<P>
   More gamesmanship from Jackson?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's just basketball,'' he said. ``That's what basketball
is about, creating lanes to the basket. We started out with Kobe
(Bryant) being soft on Damon (Stoudamire), and he got five layups
in the first quarter, and I started hammering the point home that
you just can't give up layups. ... You've got to make them shoot
the ball. Eventually, we got the idea, but it wasn't until the
second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's scuffles with Pippen and debate with Dunleavy were left
unexplained. Fox declined to speak to reporters Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Agony of the foot: After playing 48 minutes Friday night, Bryant
said his sprained right foot was ``a little tender'' Saturday but
no worse. But his schedule again called for therapy in lieu of
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just try to get the swelling out, try to get it close to 100
percent for tomorrow,'' he said. ``We have some good trainers here.
They're going to take care of me and get me ready for tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he was limited on defense, Bryant was spectacular on
offense, scoring a game-high 33 points, including four 3-pointers
in the last three minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, things like that happen sometimes when you have an
injury. You tend to find your rhythm,'' he said. ``Your mental
aspect starts to pick up a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bring it on: The Lakers didn't want the series to get this far,
but Bryant sounded enthusiastic about playing an all-or-nothing
Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' he said. ``If you look in the past and look at
all the great teams, everybody's been pushed to the limit before.
Everybody's been pushed to the seventh game. As a kid, watching
those types of games, I used to love them. And being in this type
of situation, even though we'd much rather be preparing for
Indiana, it's kind of cool. We've just got to gut it out, that's
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Safe at home: The Lakers practiced at Staples Center, instead of
at their El Segundo training facility, for the first time in
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've really shot poorly. That's why we're here,''
Jackson said. ``We've only shot once well here in three home games.
We have to come down here and shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have shot 38.5 percent (57 of 148) in their last two
home games, and 24 percent (12 of 50) from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're giving us those 3-point shots that we made (Friday)
night. ... We'd have loved to take them in game number five and
have that kind of success,'' Jackson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
