<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREIG-FILES0605-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Split or shorted. Flat or fitted. Mitered or moire. There's more
than thread count to sheets
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Would the princess have felt the pea if she had
been sleeping on a 732-thread count Egyptian cotton Pratesi king
sheet set for a whopping $2,240, or 183-thread count Ultra Touch
set from Target for a mere $38? From California King to jersey
knit, bed linens have come a long way from sober white to sultry
black satin. The array of fabrics and finishes in today's bedsheets
is mind-boggling.
</P>
<P>
   Bed linens tell a bedtime story.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1800s, the bedroom was open to guests and was often the
site of a sumptuous sweets tray or coffee urn. The choice of linens
gracing the bed was as important and public a selection as the
fabric on the parlor couch.
</P>
<P>
   Today, purchasing new sheets is a relatively inexpensive way to
redecorate a bedroom, quickly make curtains or create a toga. Most
colleges now furnish extra-long twin beds in dorms, requiring a
fall scramble to purchase extra-long twin sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Need help negotiating the trenches of the linen department? Ever
wonder why one makes a bed? Curious about what Wallis and the Duke
slept on? Want to wow your friends with the difference between Pima
and Supima cotton? This edition of the Greig Files cannot guarantee
you a good night's sleep, but it will answer all these questions
and more _ much, much more. WHY DID CAESAR SMELL LIKE A BARN?
</P>
<P>
   Because he slept on a straw mattress. Every evening, Roman
citizens constructed a bed by placing straw in a crude cloth sack.
Every day, the sacks were emptied so the straw could dry.
Therefore, ``new'' beds had to be made every night. This practice,
according to the New York Library's ``Book of Answers,'' continued
until the15th century.
</P>
<P>
   CRUDE CLOTH SACKS TO DESIGNER DENIM SHEETS _ WHAT HAPPENED?
</P>
<P>
   At the turn of the century _ the last century, that is _ bed
linen fabric was sold from a roll, cut and finished to the
specifications of each user. Then along came World War I and the
need for standardized cot sheets and mass production of uniforms.
Rapid urbanization combined with these factors. Bingo! A market and
method to create uniform bed sheets appeared, reports Bob Hamilton,
spokesman for bedding giant PillowTex.
</P>
<P>
   Improvements such as no-iron fabrics (late 1930s) and fitted
sheets (late 1940s) made bed linens more household friendly. In the
mid-1960s, Cannon branded sheets, bringing prints and colors to the
masses.
</P>
<P>
   But the man who moved bed linens upstairs from department store
basements is Yves Saint Laurent, who created the first line of
designer linens. A designer name added cachet, drama and a higher
price tag to the bedsheet.
</P>
<P>
   WHY DO SHEET PRICES VARY SO MUCH?
</P>
<P>
   Fabric, thread count, finish and embellishments determine price.
</P>
<P>
   Linen costs more than muslin, for example. Thread count
indicates the quality and strength of the fabric. Finishes such as
Sanforizing (pre-shrinking) and mercerizing (treating with alkalis
for a characteristic sheen) contribute to the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, embellishments such as embroidery, eyelet trim or
piping chip in to the final price tag. Some of the most interesting
handwork on finer linens today comes from the nimble fingers of
Vietnamese nuns, claims one linen expert. Trained by the French
nuns who established these convents, today these artists work
wonders on fabrics imported from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT IS THREAD COUNT ANYWAY?
</P>
<P>
   The amount of threads woven per square inch. The finer the
threads, the higher the count will be. The higher the thread count,
the lighter and more breathable the fabric becomes and the smoother
it is to the touch. Luxury thread counts begin at approximately 300
per square inch.
</P>
<P>
   WANT TO SLEEP LIKE, WELL . . . A DUCHESS?
</P>
<P>
   Then buy the sheets that Wallis Simpson and the Duke of Windsor
snored on _ Porthault.
</P>
<P>
   This Frenchman and his wife (Daniel and Madeleine) gave the
world the biggest innovation in bedding since the first goose lost
its down: colored and printed sheets. In 1925, the production of
Porthault's signature patterns, violet bouquet and four-leaf
clover, were astonishing to a world awash in all-white linens.
</P>
<P>
   Competition for the high-end linen market comes from the Italian
firm of Frette, founded in 1860. This company is famous for weaving
crests (family, royal and otherwise) into bed linens. A Frette
queen sheet set (350 thread count, 60 percent Egyptian cotton, 40
percent silk) begins at $745.
</P>
<P>
   Over in the Tuscan hills, the house of Pratesi has been
manufacturing beautiful, embroidered linens since founder Remigio
Pratesi first sold his wares to royal patrons. It is common for
these sheet sets to be more than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT IS THE BEST VALUE IN AN ALL-COTTON SHEET?
</P>
<P>
   Many purveyors of luxury linens recommend Charisma by
Fieldcrest/Cannon, the runaway leader in the 300-plus thread count
all-cotton market. The extra long Supima cotton fibers used in this
sheet are fabricated in a twill weave and finished with softeners
that enhance the feel and life of this sheet. Introduced in 1987,
Charisma was the only 310-thread count in a 180-thread count world,
reports PillowTex Vice President Stacie Cronin.
</P>
<P>
   WANT TO DRESS YOUR BED IN LUXURY WITHOUT MORTGAGING THE RANCH?
</P>
<P>
   Contact the new kids on the luxury linen block, John Stoddart
and his wife, Laurie Dusek of Madison Linens. Formerly employed by
New York's chichi linen store, Leron, Stoddart has tapped into the
burgeoning retail market for bedding (more than $8 million in 1998)
with low prices and high service (25 percent to 50 percent less
than other stores vying for the discretionary linen dollar).
</P>
<P>
   Ever need to replicate a painted tile on bath towels or bed
sheets? Match your china pattern on a place mat? Want your coat of
arms on a pillowcase? Madison Linens can make it happen. Traveling
the country by appointment, Madison Linens relies on word of mouth
to bring society mavens to their exquisite wares. Know what you
want _ a hand-hemstitched Frette pillow sham? Need your cipher on a
linen sheet at the ranch? Want to hide your children's initials in
the holiday tablecloth? Just call Madison and order at (888)
420-0668. While the first purchase may be modest (averaging say
$500), satisfied customers usually return with a larger order _
into several thousand dollars, notes Dusek. The first order is a
test.
</P>
<P>
   CAN I CHANGE THE SHEETS ONCE A MONTH, WHETHER THEY NEED THEM OR
NOT?
</P>
<P>
   If the fabric industry has its way, you can.
</P>
<P>
   Think the cotton gin and the Jacquard loom were noted
innovations in the fabric industry? Francital, a French company
specializing in explorer garb, has developed a fabric to absorb
perspiration and odors. The miracle fabric will be tested by North
Pole trekkers who will wear the same pair of underwear and T-shirt
for 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, fabrics that kill dust mites on contact are in the
works, as well as fabrics for bedding and clothing that protect
against fungi and bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S WITH THESE LITTLE PILL BALLS ALL OVER MY BEDSHEETS?
</P>
<P>
   When the fibers of a fabric break or short fibers become tangled
on the surface, those annoying little pills occur. Choose bed
linens with long fibers whenever possible to reduce pill-ness. Turn
pillowcases inside out and select the cycle with the least amount
of agitation when laundering.
</P>
<P>
   WHY DO MY SHEETS MAKE ME SNEEZE?
</P>
<P>
   It is not the sheets, it is the dust mite _ and the little dust
mite droppings they leave in pillows and mattresses. Smaller than a
period, dust mites cannot be seen, and it has been estimated that
nearly 40,000 of these are in a speck of dust (hence the name).
</P>
<P>
   Control mites by cleaning bedding regularly (yes, this means
changing the sheets), washing them in hot water or vacuuming them.
Exposure to direct sunlight (well, airing mattresses on the front
lawn is frowned upon in most neighborhoods) also cuts down on dust
mite problems.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most popular means of control is encasing mattresses
and pillows in an impermeable fabric. Pick up a tightly woven case
made with tricot polyester or pristine (75 percent poly, 25 percent
cotton) fabric.
</P>
<P>
   LINEN LEXICON
</P>
<P>
   _ Combed cotton: Cotton in which the long and short fibers have
been combed or sorted. The longer fibers produce a more uniform,
fine and strong cotton.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cotton: A natural fiber that grows in the seed pod of the
cotton plant. Fibers are typically 1/2 inch to 2 inches long. The
longest staple fibers, longer than 1 1/2 inch, including the Pima
and Egyptian varieties, produce the highest quality fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   _ Damask: A Jacquard woven pattern fabric made of cotton, linen,
silk or blends. Patterns are reversible and flat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Egyptian cotton: Fabric made from cotton grown on the banks of
the Nile River, generally acknowledged as the finest in the world
because of the large percentage of long fibers in the cotton.
</P>
<P>
   _ Linen: A natural fiber made from the woody stem of a flax
plant. One of the oldest textiles, linen fibers are stronger and
more lustrous than cotton fibers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Flannel: A medium-weight, plain or twill weave fabric that is
typically made from cotton, a cotton blend or wool. The fabric is
very soft, brushed on both sides to lift the fiber ends out of the
base fabric and create a soft, fuzzy surface.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jacquard: Woven fabric using a Jacquard attachment on the
loom, which allows for intricate patterns. The Jacquard loom was
invented in 1801 by Joseph-Marie Jacquard.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jersey knit: A fabric with the feel of all cotton without all
the wrinkles. This fabric is smooth but more textured because it is
knitted.
</P>
<P>
   _ Muslin: A plain weave fabric with a thread count usually
between 128 and 180 threads per square inch.
</P>
<P>
   _ Percale: A medium-weight, plain weave, low-to-medium count
(usually 180 to 250 threads per square inch) cottonlike fabric.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pima cotton: A superior medium- to long-staple cotton commonly
grown in the Southwest, named for Pima County, Ariz. Pima cotton is
also grown abroad.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sateen: A fabric made from yarns with low luster, such as
cotton or other staple length fibers. The fabric has a soft, smooth
feel and a gentle, subtle luster.
</P>
<P>
   _ Silk: A natural fiber made from the filaments silkworms use to
make cocoons. Most silk is collected from cultivated worms; Tussah
silk, or wild silk, is a thicker, shorter fiber produced by worms
in their natural habitat. Silk was believed to be discovered by a
Chinese princess.
</P>
<P>
   _ Supima cotton: Long fiber fabric made entirely from Pima
cotton grown in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
