<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4117 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-HOLLOWAY-TV-COLUMN060     06-04 1633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TV-COLUMN0605-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Will we FALL for this?
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ New and different? Nope. More like tried and
true, right down to a crowd of well-known stars.
</P>
<P>
   When the new fall TV season arrives, we'll see more adult dramas
_ a welcome trend that sprang up last season as a backlash to all
the idiotic teen and twentysomething shows.
</P>
<P>
   We'll also see a few more minority faces, a tiny step forward in
the diversity wars. And we'll have two whole nights without
newsmagazines, thanks to cutbacks by ``Dateline NBC'' and ABC's
``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest you think the picture is entirely too rosy, we'll get a
fourth night of ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire'' _ with the threat
of more if ABC's other series stumble out of the starting gate. All
Regis, all the time seems like creative bankruptcy. What happens to
the No. 1 network when people get tired of ``final answers''? We
may find out sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   This is the time of year critics love most. The networks have
announced their fall schedules, but pilots are just beginning to
trickle in (most of which are incomplete and not for review). That
means knee-jerk assessments are the order of the day. Based on
sketchy plot descriptions, casting information and old-fashioned
hunches, astute conclusions are drawn that could be meaningless by
the time the Olympics-delayed fall season rolls around in October.
</P>
<P>
   But hastily drawn conclusions are fun, so why not play the game?
And most things probably won't change all that much.
</P>
<P>
   Even with some last-minute tinkering, 34 new series, along with
three canceled-then-relocated series, will debut on the six
broadcast networks. With the exception of a half-dozen sci-fi shows
(including a rare anthology, Fox's ``Night Visions'') and a
half-hour sketch comedy (WB's ``Hype''), the newcomers are
overwhelmingly traditional. At least they sound traditional at this
stage of the game.
</P>
<P>
   For the second year in a row, there will be more new dramas (18)
than sitcoms (16) on the prime-time schedule. And most of the
dramas star adults. From the sublime (``Freaks &AMP; Geeks'') to the
ridiculous (``Cold Feet''), youth dramas were rejected last year in
favor of mature shows such as ``The West Wing'' and ``Family Law,''
and network programmers paid attention this time around.
</P>
<P>
   Unknown stars were rejected, too. Among the drama stars this
fall are Andre Braugher in the medical series ``Gideon's
Crossing,'' Tim Daly in a remake of ``The Fugitive,'' Ellen Burstyn
in the family drama ``That's Life,'' Craig T. Nelson in the
capital-set cop show ``The District,'' Victoria Principal and
Yasmine Bleeth in the Aaron Spelling sudser ``Titans'' and Fyvush
Finkel in the high school-set (but teacher-focused) drama ``Boston
Public.''
</P>
<P>
   The new comedies have even more famous folks, including the
already heavily promoted Bette Midler as a character closely
resembling herself in CBS's ``The Bette Show,'' Geena Davis and
Peter Horton as a married couple in ``Geena,'' Gabriel Byrne as a
divorced father in ``Madigan Men,'' Christine Baranski as a morning
talk-show host in ``Welcome to New York,'' John Goodman as a gay
dad in ``Don't Ask,'' Katey Sagal as (what else?) an edgy but
matronly aunt in ``Tucker,'' David Alan Grier and Delta Burke as a
Secret Service agent and the First Lady respectively in ``DAG,''
Michael Richards as a Kramer-style, bumbling detective in a
still-untitled comedy for NBC and Steven Weber as a cursed bachelor
in another untitled NBC sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   The old adage that TV shows don't need big stars to succeed
because they make their own stars apparently is out the window.
With the audience splintered by cable and other home entertainment
alternatives, new series have to hit quick to stay on, and
producers feel they have a better shot with a familiar face or two
in the cast.
</P>
<P>
   With producers now casting bankable stars, the networks are
doing the same thing tracking down proven producer-stars. These
power brokers have strong track records, although even the likes of
David E. Kelley can fall flat. (Remember last fall's ``Snoops''?
Neither does anyone else.)
</P>
<P>
   But big wigs like Kelley, who's responsible for ``The Practice''
and ``Ally McBeal,'' attract good actors and the best writers to
new projects. That's why the buzz is already positive for Kelley's
new Fox drama ``Boston Public.'' And that's why this fall's lineup
features even more series from hit makers. Dick Wolf (``Law &AMP;
Order'') has ``Deadline''; Darren Star (``Sex and the City,''
``Beverly Hills, 90210'') has ``The $treet,'' about rich young
turks on Wall Street, and ``Grosse Pointe,'' a spoof of his own
youth melodramas; Paul Attanasio (``Homicide: Life on the Street'')
has ``Gideon's Crossing''; and Aaron Spelling (``Dynasty,''
``Melrose Place'') has ``Titans.''
</P>
<P>
   Howls of protests followed by promises of change headlined last
season's diversity story. A coalition of minority leaders
threatened a boycott when the new series arrived last September
with overwhelmingly white casts. Not to split hairs, but those
leaders failed to notice that NBC's ``Third Watch'' was populated
by the definitive rainbow coalition. Nevertheless, network
executives agreed they could and should do better.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Emmy winner Andre Braugher stars as a crusading
doctor/medical professor in ``Gideon's Crossing,'' with Ruben
Blades among the supporting players. David Alan Grier got his own
sitcom (``DAG'') named with his own initials, Mykelti Williamson
(Bubba from ``Forrest Gump'') plays Lt. Gerard on ``The Fugitive,''
and Rocky Carroll (late of ``Chicago Hope'') co-stars in ``Welcome
to New York.'' Minority players also have substantial roles in
``The District'' (although the chief of police in this primarily
African American city is white), ``Boston Public,'' ``Fearsum,''
``Girlfriends'' and ``Hype.''
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics, woefully underrepresented on network TV, were
understandably miffed that CBS passed on ``American Family,'' a
drama created by filmmaker Gregory Nava and starring Edward James
Olmos. There's a chance CBS will pick it up for midseason _ or ship
it to another network.
</P>
<P>
   After tanking with edgy new series such as ``Action!'' and
``Wonderland'' last year, it's clear the networks are not in the
mood to experiment. The message went out loud and clear when the
only breakaway hit of the season was a representative of a
retro-genre (game shows) from the '50s. Better to be safe, and
possibly bland, than sorry.
</P>
<P>
   OUT ON A LIMB (AND HOLDING A SAW)
</P>
<P>
   Sight unseen, these newcomers have potential. OK, I know I may
look ridiculous if that opinion does an about-face in reviews I
write after seeing the pilots, but that's a risk worth taking.
</P>
<P>
   DRAMAS
</P>
<P>
   ``Gideon's Crossing'' _ I'd watch Andre Braugher read the Yellow
Pages, but here he'll have juicy material from Paul Attanasio, who
wrote many of the actor's best ``Homicide'' episodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fugitive'' _ The original series was great; so was the
Harrison Ford movie. With Tim Daly in the lead, this could be a
winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deadline'' _ Dick Wolf takes on New York newspapers as a
dramatic milieu with Oliver Platt as a hard-charging reporter.
What's not to like?
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston Public'' _ David E. Kelley always surprises, and the
life of teachers in a public high school gives him a rich, fresh
venue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Night Visions'' _ A scary anthology? If it's handled right,
this will give a new twist to the plethora of TV dramas. Aidan
Quinn stars in the first installment. That's a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   COMEDIES
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bette Show'' _ The Divine Miss M pokes fun at herself and
takes us all on a wild ride. I've seen a rough cut of the pilot,
and it's fabulous, dahlings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grosse Pointe'' _ This will either sink or soar, but the
notion of Darren Star satirizing the teen-pout genre he created on
``Beverly Hills, 90210'' is tantalizing.
</P>
<P>
   ``DAG'' _ Unless the writers totally botch this one, it's a slam
dunk. David Alan Grier as a Secret Service agent guarding First
Lady Delta Burke just sounds hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Richards Project'' _ Kramer was often the best
character on ``Seinfeld,'' and Inspector Clouseau was a classic.
This sitcom supposedly combines the two. Chuckle city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steven Weber Project'' _ Funny on ``Wings,'' he'll be funny on
this.
</P>
<P>
   CHANGE OF ADDRESS
</P>
<P>
   ``The P.J.s,'' Eddie Murphy's clay animation comedy about life
in the projects, was axed by Fox but picked up by the WB.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hughleys'' bit the dust when ABC dismantled its TGIF
lineup, so UPN nabbed the family sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sabrina the Teenage Witch,'' another refugee from ABC's TGIF
comedies, moves to the WB.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FI SEASON
</P>
<P>
   Little green men with pitch-black eyes? Nope. Futuristic
creepiness and tales of the para-
</P>
<P>
   normal will seep into prime time, and Fox looks to be the
biggest creep of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dark Angel'' (FOX) _ From Oscar-winner James Cameron
(``Titanic'') comes a future thriller set in post-apocalyptic
America and featuring a genetically-enhanced human prototype and
her cyber-journalist sidekick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fearsum'' (FOX) _ Tales of the supernatural via the Internet,
from the producer of ``The Blair Witch Project.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Night Visions'' (FOX) _ An anthology series with stories
ranging from horror to supernatural to psychological, a la ``The
Twilight Zone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lone Gunmen'' (FOX) _ A spinoff from ``The X-Files''
featuring the nerdy trio of computer-hacking conspiracy theorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freedom'' (UPN) _ Joel Silver, executive producer of ``The
Matrix'' and ``Lethal Weapon,'' created this futuristic war series
that promises to be riddled with violence and special effects.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
