<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-KING-GIMP0605-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fighting spirit puts `Gimp' in league of its own
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The title is your first clue that this is not just
another handicapped-hero story _ that it relies less on sentiment
than a shocking self-awareness to move anyone who watches this
extraordinary documentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``King Gimp'' has you at hello _ from the moment Dan Keplinger,
a 27-year-old artist born with cerebral palsy, spits and concusses
and convulses his opening, subtitled words:
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people think `gimp' means someone with a lame walk. But
`gimp' also means a `fighting spirit.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That spirit shines in small, often poetic ways during the
45-minute film, winner of this year's best documentary short at the
Academy Awards, where Keplinger provided the night's most memorable
moment when he flung himself from his wheelchair and flailed
joyously around the auditorium floor when the Oscar was announced.
</P>
<P>
   The film had a brief, single-screen run to qualify for an Oscar,
so tonight's airing on HBO, which helped produce it, is virtually
its premiere.
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers Susan Hadary and William Whiteford documented
Keplinger's life in Maryland for 13 years, beginning when he was
12. But Keplinger wrote _ or head-butted _ the text, using a head
stick to type on a computer.
</P>
<P>
   So we watch Keplinger as he changes T-shirts; watch as he
removes one shirt and then pulls on another, the whole while
kneeling on the floor, trying to get his arms and head to
cooperate, looking as if he's in a fearsome, minutes-long wrestling
match with . . . himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another day,'' Keplinger writes, ``of crap.''
</P>
<P>
   But Keplinger is largely undaunted by all the crap, and it's his
mother who never lets him fall victim to it. She gave birth to Dan
when she was 18, and her husband left six years later, unable to
cope when she refused to institutionalize their son. She's a saint,
but not a martyr: What she went through to mainstream her son she
did as naturally as she would for any child. The unspoken love
between the two here will kill ya.
</P>
<P>
   There are also teachers _ in high school, then college _ who
accept and help Keplinger when others would rather he go away, and
they remind us of the power of selflessness.
</P>
<P>
   The payoff of it all is Keplinger, now a young man who is often
lonely, often feels scorned, yet whose ``gimp'' spirit keeps him
painting and struggling to be fully human inside a body that makes
many people turn away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has a handicap,'' he says proudly at the end, ``but
only a few are a `true gimp.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Don't miss this one. ``King Gimp'' is just the reality check all
of us smug, boom-economy lightweights need to bring us back to
earth.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
