A4120 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0605-COX     06-04 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0605-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trail of discovery leads 'Holmes' sleuths to remarkable audience
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Occasionally we hear about youngsters who get
pulled down the rabbit hole of fantasy through computers or
role-playing games. Down, down, down they go. The same happens with
the Internet. An interest becomes a fixation that becomes
asphyxiation.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand there are youngsters who, given the
opportunity, go deep, deep, deep into things that elevate.
</P>
<P>
   When Nancy Nixon and Amanda Coody began digging, the channel
they dug delivered them to a wonderland. An academic exercise
became more than pass-fail, A or B or C. It became a Technicolor
ride to always color their lives.
</P>
<P>
   That's the best we can do for young people when we advertise
something called education.
</P>
<P>
   The graduating Waco High seniors were in Phyllis Strother's
independent study humanities class. They chose as a British
literature project Sir Arthur Conan Doyle's creation: Sherlock
Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   When all was said and done, they'd constructed and reconstructed
a crime before a jury. They'd done so before a most unusual jury, a
roomful of strangers who know Sherlock Holmes like nobody else. And
after they made their case to this group, expecting maybe to be
shown the door as impostors, they were made honorary members of _
surely you've heard of it _ the Crew of the Lone Star Barque.
</P>
<P>
   It was an example of how when you have a good notion and you
keep asking around, you can find people who will help make a good
thing better.
</P>
<P>
   After the girls read lots of Sherlock Holmes _ eight books _
they set out to write and present a Holmes-style plot, a mystery
with players from the community. They came to learn one of the
lessons that all students should learn as they search for things
that matter: It never hurts to ask.
</P>
<P>
   That's why when they asked, District Judge Ralph Strother
consented to be in their crime (yes, he's married to the teacher,
but he's also a major Holmes freak). That's why, when they needed
another player and asked, Superintendent Rosanne Stripling put down
what she was doing and picked up a script.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why, to their delight and amazement, when they got on
the Internet and punched in ``Sherlock Holmes,'' they found a North
Texas chapter of the Diogenes Club, an intellectual bunch that eats
and breathes Sherlock Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   After an exchange by e-mail, the club invited the girls to its
lair in Flower Mound to show what they learned.
</P>
<P>
   What they brought was the play: ``The Keys of Truth.'' They had
a crime: the theft of family jewels. They had a culprit, and clues
to test the audience.
</P>
<P>
   HANDCUFFING THE JUDGE
</P>
<P>
   Amanda played Holmes and Nancy played Dr. Watson in this, one of
two performances. The other was before an audience in Waco. In the
Waco performance, Judge Strother, who presides over the county's
juvenile court, played Buff Pemberly, a man who turns out to have
sticky hands.
</P>
<P>
   Long plot cut short, the high schoolers ended up putting Buff in
cuffs. In between, audiences were asked to solve the crime. (Clue:
Follow the cigar ashes.)
</P>
<P>
   So, how did the jury of strangers, devout Sherlockians, react?
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very genuine, very honest,'' said Amanda. And
apparently very approving, bestowing their honorary title. They
were not alone in approval.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor University professor Susan Johnsen, who saw the play in
Waco, invited them to write an article for ``Gifted Child Today''
about their eye-opening experience.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever they study from here on _ Nancy is going to Shriner
College in Kerrville, Amanda to Hollins University in Roanoke, Va.,
_ what they've learned in an exercise like this will benefit them
for life.
</P>
<P>
   You see, beyond the academic skills we all need and subjects we
want to master, what serves you in life is not so much subject
matter in a vacuum. It's what you learn about yourself in applying
what you know to the world around you.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt an appreciation for Sherlock Holmes will make their
lives richer, but that will be a sidelight. To them the real lesson
from this pursuit will be the same as that which rewards a sleuth
for posing the right questions. It's the power of asking.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
