<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4125 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-ARTIFACTS-SIDE0605-CO     06-04 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTIFACTS-SIDE0605-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Battle over the bones rages on
 &HT;    By Lori Cumpston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ The contents of dozens of unmarked
cardboard boxes sitting in a giant warehouse in southwestern
Colorado are at the center of a controversial debate that has
captured the attention of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The non-descript boxes, some stacked two and three high, contain
Native American remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have one of the largest collections of human remains in the
National Park Service,'' says Linda Towle, head of research and
resource management for Mesa Verde National Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Native American Graves Protection and Repatriation Act
passed in 1990 requires that all Native American remains along with
sacred or cultural objects unearthed on federal lands be returned
to tribes for reburial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tribes want these remains reburied close to where they
came from,'' says Towle. ``The park is more than willing to do
that. But there are some issues within the law ... that require
that we identify cultural affiliation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some disagreement among the tribes as to who is
identified as culturally affiliated. We are investigating on how
best to deal with that because the parks want these individuals
reburied and the Native Americans want them reburied. But we have
some legal issues to straighten out in order to make that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The remains, excavated at Mesa Verde during the late 1950s and
early 1960s, have been segregated from the rest of the collection
and are available for reburial once the legal issues are resolved.
The mass burial will not be made public.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over reburial surged to the forefront in the summer
of 1996 after two hydroplane racers stumbled across a
9,000-year-old skeleton near Columbia Park in Kennewick, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   The skeleton, dubbed ``Kennewick Man,'' was discolored and had
soil stuck to it, leading investigators to believe it was not the
body of someone recently deceased.
</P>
<P>
   The Graves Protection Act requires the government to notify
Indian tribes likely to be culturally affiliated with the remains.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, several tribes were notified, including the
Umatilla Tribe, which wanted the remains reburied immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government refused.
</P>
<P>
   In a case that represents the first legal challenge of the
Graves Protection Act, scientists sued, claiming they had a right
to study the remains since there was a question as to the origin.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the federal government, based on the age of
the skeleton, ruled that the remains were Native American.
</P>
<P>
   However, in a stunning decision one month later, the United
States Department of Interior announced it would conduct DNA tests
on the bones.
</P>
<P>
   The decision outraged Armand Minthorn, a religious leader and
trustee of the Confederated Tribes of the Umatilla Indian
Reservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is about respect,'' wrote Minthorn, in an editorial
posted on the Confederated Tribes of the Umatilla Indian
Reservation Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is at issue in this case is not just our desire to
protect one ancestor, but how this case will be applied to every
other Native American skeleton found in the United States. If (the
Graves Protection Act) was intended to return tribes the right to
protect our ancestors from unconsented excavation, removal,
analysis and destruction, then this case has made it painfully
clear that a small group of scientists, with the assistance of the
(Department of Interior), can abrogate that right.''
</P>
<P>
   As the battle over the bones rages on, museum curators like
Carolyn Landes feared the legislation would have another unintended
effect _ empty display cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really afraid that the best stock was going to go away,
even though I knew my culture had done wrong for a very long
time,'' says Landes. ``I am happy to say that is not the way it is
going. A lot of material is going back to where it belongs but
there is still an amazing amount of material that didn't come from
the burial context and doesn't fall under the ... law that can tell
us as much as the grave.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
