<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000604.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4126 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-ARTIFACTS0605-COX     06-04 1910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTIFACTS0605-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Priceless artifacts linger in warehouse awaiting funds for
cultural center
 &HT;    By Lori Cumpston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ A piece of tin roof flaps in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   A spiderweb of silver duct tape does little to camouflage cracks
in the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   The walls lack insulation.
</P>
<P>
   Weeds poke their heads through crevices in the concrete floor.
</P>
<P>
   Mouse traps stand at attention, poised to snap at furry
intruders who dare cross the line.
</P>
<P>
   And in the center of it all sits a priceless collection of 2
million Native American artifacts, some dating back as far as 400
A.D.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't meet legal requirements for maintaining a federal
museum collection,'' says curator Carolyn Landes. ``We are not
alone in that. You go to any underfunded park and you will find the
same situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The warehouse, which is the size of an airplane hangar, is
hidden among yucca plants, juniper shrubs and pinyon pines in
southwestern Colorado. As a security precaution, the exact location
is kept secret, and a Daily Sentinel reporter and photographer were
allowed in recently with the stipulation that the location would
not be published.
</P>
<P>
   The crown jewels stored inside, many excavated from the
Wetherill Mesa Archaeological Project in Mesa Verde National Park
during the late 1950s, tell a story of generations gone by and are
the only records left detailing the history and habits of a lost
civilization.
</P>
<P>
   The Wetherill Brothers, Richard and Al, along with the their
brother-in-law, Charles Mason, are credited with discovering the
cliff dwellings of Mesa Verde while searching for stray cattle in
the winter of 1888.
</P>
<P>
   The find marked the beginning of archaeology in the American
West.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``Anasazi'' is no longer used to describe the ancient
people of the Southwest. The Navajo word means 'ancient enemy.' Out
of respect to the direct descendents of the Anasazi, they are now
referred to as Ancestral Puebloans.
</P>
<P>
   Early Ancestral Puebloans were known as Basketmakers. The
nomadic clan settled in pithouses clustered in small villages built
on mesa tops overlooking the Montezuma Valley sometime around 400
A.D.
</P>
<P>
   As the population grew and the people became more sophisticated,
pithouses were eventually replaced with skillful stone masonry
structures built inside protective cliff alcoves that once
sheltered their ancestors centuries before.
</P>
<P>
   The high level of craftsmanship that went into the cliff
dwellings also carried through to tool-making, weaving, jewelry and
pottery, where dull gray was replaced by snappy black designs
painted on a white background.
</P>
<P>
   By 1300 A.D., the Ancestral Puebloans disappeared, with only the
belongings on their backs, leaving behind a legacy waiting to be
discovered.
</P>
<P>
   The last major archaeological dig at Mesa Verde took place on
Wetherill Mesa in 1959 and unearthed more than a million Native
American artifacts, now stored in sub-standard conditions and
maintained by the National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   Landes punches in a secret security code to gain access to the
main storage area, where the majority of the collection is housed.
A warning sign on the door reads, ``Restricted Access: Area Closed
By Order Of Superintendent.''
</P>
<P>
   The heavy metal door swings back and inside are rows and rows of
gun-metal gray cabinets with numbers posted on the doors.
</P>
<P>
   Landes walks to one somewhere in the middle labeled 435 Site No.
1200, takes off the cover, letting it clank to the floor and pulls
out a tray.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are palettes ... what we would call a paint palette,
where they mixed paint,'' says Landes, pointing to a large rock.
``This one has hematite on it, a mineral they would grind and
that's what made the red paint in the tower at Cliff Palace and any
of the remnants down at Spruce Tree House.''
</P>
<P>
   Another tray reveals blobs of organic material like corn and
yucca leaves that have been chewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are called quids,'' says Landes. ``It's a term
associated with tobacco chewing.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the exact purpose of the quids isn't known, possible
theories are that quids were chewed to keep from getting thirsty in
the bone-dry climate, or they were used to get a buzz similar to a
narcotic.
</P>
<P>
   Drawer after drawer yield treasures and trinkets: sandals styled
from yucca, broken sherds of pottery, a drinking mug with a tiny
pair of black feet painted on the bottom, pieces of woven cotton
clothing, bits of blanket fashioned from turkey feathers and yucca,
farming implements, tools made from bone and intricate beads
crafted out of stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have much of the collection in fairly good storage
conditions,'' says Linda Towle, head of research and resource
management for Mesa Verde National Park, ``but those bowls stacked
on top of each other ... every time we open the drawer there is
that much more opportunity for them to break. They're heavy and
those drawers are not meant to hold that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of the material we have is organic and very sensitive
to changes in humidity and temperature. In a facility like we have
right now where in the winter it gets cold and in the summer it
gets very hot, these materials shrink and contract and they are
going to deteriorate that much faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't even mention the word fire.
</P>
<P>
   Although protected by a sprinkler system, a wildfire near the
Four Corners area in the mid '80s threatened to scorch the
priceless collection, but it was miraculously spared when the wind
shifted.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of fire still looms, however, until the highly
combustible nitrate negatives of the Gustaf Nordenskiold collection
of old photographs can be transferred onto safety film.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a couple of refrigerators in the back where we store
the nitrate,'' says Landes. ``You need to keep them cool. It will
melt down and actually combust.''
</P>
<P>
   Nordenskiold, a young Swede stricken with tuberculosis, heard
about the Wetherill brothers and hired the pair to accompany him to
the cliff dwellings to began photographing the sites and excavating
artifacts, which was legal prior to the Antiquities Act of 1906.
</P>
<P>
   ``His telegrams back and forth to his father are pretty
interesting,'' says Landes. ``They said, 'Lots of trouble but I
think I am going to be OK.'''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Nordenskiold collection is in the National Museum in
Helsinki, Finland.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is the pottery, enough to make a black market
collector salivate.
</P>
<P>
   Graywares, whitewares, redwares: Some sit in neat rows on
makeshift tables while the larger pieces, like ``ollas'' or water
jars, are hidden underneath sheets of protective plastic to shield
them from water damage if the roof leaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some things are every day use,'' says Landes. ``You can see
the soot or the blackening on the grayware. The fact that they
would take the time to make beautiful things when they were just
existing ... their life was so hard and short. It's just amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   To complicate matters, parts of the collection have overflowed
outside of the restricted access area, which is a violation of the
standards set forth to maintain a federal museum collection.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeological finds still sit in brown paper bags, including
one bearing the date of Oct. 23, 1925. The handwriting scrawled on
the front reads, ``From the ruin opposite CT Tower.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have boxes and boxes of this stuff,'' says Towle, referring
to the bags of unprocessed artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our only record and paper bags disintegrate. We really
need to get those artifacts into other containers with that
information transferred onto a permanent record soon because when
they fall apart and everything gets mixed, we have no way to
retrieve the original information.''
</P>
<P>
   More crates of unopened artifacts are warehoused at the
Smithsonian Institution, waiting to be retrieved if a bid for a new
cultural center is successful.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed center will be built on a plot of land next to the
entrance at Mesa Verde National Park.
</P>
<P>
   Famed New York architect Murry Gelberg is designing the center,
which calls for a campus-type facility or a single unit, possibly
modeled after the floorplan of Long House, which is the second
largest cliff dwelling in Mesa Verde National Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we have that in mind, we'll be able to define the square
footage, which will tell us what parts might be for the museum
association, book sales, office space, curation space, research
components, education, exhibits and where we'll do presentations
for programs, whether it's live, slide or video,'' says Larry
Wiese, superintendent of Mesa Verde National Park.
</P>
<P>
   The new cultural center also means Native Americans will have a
more active role in telling the story of their people.
</P>
<P>
   W. Richard West, the founding director of the Smithsonian
Institution's National Museum of the American Indian in Washington,
D.C., has visited Mesa Verde several times to begin training Native
Americans to take part in the interactive exhibits at the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once each tribe has developed the exhibits, we would be able
to put them on display at the center for a month at a time,'' says
Wiese. ``We have 24 affiliated tribes. They'll be able to tell
their story, the past, present and future, however they choose
through storytelling, exhibits, dance or a combination.''
</P>
<P>
   The targeted completion date for the cultural center is 2006 to
coincide with the 100-year anniversary of Mesa Verde National Park.
</P>
<P>
   The estimated price tag is between $20 million and $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa Verde got a much needed boost in May of 1999 when First
Lady Hillary Clinton, armed with a $3.2 million dollar grant,
visited the park in conjunction with the Save America's Treasures
Program. However, much of that money has already been earmarked for
archaeologists to re-evaluate the cliff dwelling sites to determine
whether stabilization is needed to lengthen the life expectancy of
the walls.
</P>
<P>
   That means funding for the cultural center will have to come
from another source, namely big-hearted folks with a desire to see
the past preserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll try and do it through philanthropic means,'' says Wiese.
``We're not going to rely on the federal government. We don't think
the dollars are there. They may be and that would be a pleasant
surprise, but we're anticipating we're going to have to raise that
money outside of the federal government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very expensive proposition,'' adds Towle. ``We have to
have outside support. A dollar here, a dollar there ... it all adds
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Towle says they have been in contact with Sen. Ben Nighthorse
Campbell's office and he is aware of the project. But the
Republican, who holds the distinction of being the only American
Indian in Congress, has shown little interest.
</P>
<P>
   That's a claim Campbell's staff disputes. ``It's ludicrous if
anyone is making the claim that he is not sensitive to the plight
of the Anasazi,'' says James Doyle, communications director for
Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get flooded with requests every year and we grant those
that are deserving. If they are serious about getting money, they
need to make a request.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the money comes from government appropriations or
private donations, one thing is certain: Precious artifacts that
have weathered centuries of time may vanish, just as the Ancestral
Puebloans did more than 700 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
