 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, June 5:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CLINTON (Moscow) _ The American and Russian leaders fail
to bridge differences over missile defense and sign minor
agreements on enhancing early warning systems for a nuclear launch
and disposal of plutonium waste. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CLINTON-ASSESS (Moscow) _ What the Russian-American
agreements, and disagreements, mean. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CLINTON-RADIO (Moscow) _ Clinton takes questions from the
public on a Russian radio program. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SECURITY (Jerusalem) _ Israel's secret service has
tightened security around Prime Minister Ehud Barak as some Jewish
settlers here warn that the domestic climate has the potential to
turn ugly and violent quickly if the Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks, which could result in Israel losing land, move forward. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-VIGIL (Hong Kong) _ Eleven years after China turned its
tanks and troops against student protesters in Tiananmen Square,
tens of thousands of people gathered at a candlelight vigil here
today to remember the doomed democracy movement. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-SEPARATISTS (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ Ignoring stern
warnings from the government in Jakarta, separatists in the
province of West Papua made a declaration of independence today, in
hopes of following the lead of East Timor, which broke away from
Indonesia last year. By Joe Cochrane.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-ROYALS (London) _ Queen Elizabeth II and Camilla Parker
Bowles met this weekend for the first time, setting off speculation
across Britain over a possible marriage for Prince Charles. By
Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   TEX-ESCAPED-PARROTS (Brownsville, Texas) _ A flock of hundreds
of exotic parrots, probably escaped from smugglers, has found a
home in an unusual place: the dusty, bustling city of Brownsville.
Ross Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   DATA-INTERNET (Washington) _ On one side are the Chamber of
Commerce, Consumers Union, research librarians and Charles Schwab.
On the other side are the New York Stock Exchange, real estate
agents and the American Medical Association. These odd alliances of
lobbyists have formed over the question of whether databases _
collections of facts like telephone directories, weather reports,
stock tables and real estate listings _ can be copied, repackaged
and distributed by anyone with an Internet connection. By David E.
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   AMBASSADOR-PROFILE (Washington) _ Profile of John E. Leigh, the
ambassador to Sierra Leone. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded p)
</P>
<P>
   SOFT-MONEY-ADS (Washington) _ Two and a half months ago, flush
with victory in the primaries and eager to be seen as taking the
high road, Vice President Al Gore sent an e-mail message to Gov.
George W. Bush, proposing a ban on ``issue ads'' paid for with
unregulated soft money. Bush, who raised a staggering $70 million
in his primary campaign, dismissed the challenge as a ploy. But
now, with the Democrats dropping hints that they may soon begin a
television advertising campaign on behalf of Gore, Republicans are
eager to hoist the vice president on his own petard. Asserting that
Mr. Gore's message amounted to a solemn promise not to use soft
money, the Republicans are trying to paint Gore as a hypocrite even
before the Democrats' first commercial hits the airwaves. By Peter
Marks.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGES-POLITICS (Undated) _ With touchstone issues like death
penalty challenges, school financing and tort reform hanging in the
balance, contests for state judgeships around the country have
become bruising multimillion dollar political affairs that critics
say are threatening the independence of the nation's state courts
as never before. Millions of dollars in campaign contributions are
flowing into races for top state judgeships this year, while
candidates are testing the limits of rules that forbid them from
signaling how they might vote on cases. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   DEFIANT-JUDGE (Childersburg, Ala.) _ Three years ago, Judge Roy
S. Moore became an icon of the Christian conservative movement by
defying the order of another Alabama judge that he remove the Ten
Commandments from the wall behind his bench and stop opening court
sessions with a prayer. Today, proudly unrepentant, Moore of the
Circuit Court in Gallant is trading on his renown to run for chief
justice of the Alabama Supreme Court, the top judicial post in the
state. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   (Coded k)
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Commentary; subject TK. By William
Safire.
</P>
