<SLUG> BC-SALESFORCE-IBM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM AND SALESFORCE.COM PLAN SMALL-BUSINESS PARTNERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ IBM and the start-up company Salesforce.com plan
to announce a partnership on Monday aimed at helping small
businesses transform themselves into e-businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Salesforce.com, founded last year by Marc Benioff, a former
senior vice president with the Oracle Corp., offers software for
managing sales information like contacts, leads and follow-ups, as
a subscription service from its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, International Business Machines will make
the Salesforce service available to customers of IBM's Small
Business WebConnections, a monthly subscription service that
provides shared Internet access for up to 100 users. IBM and
Salesforce also plan to jointly develop new applications, the
companies said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the deal with IBM was a strong endorsement for
Salesforce.com, particularly because IBM already had a partnership
with Siebel Systems, the leading supplier of traditional sales
management software, commonly known as customer relationship
management. Siebel has a Web offering called Sales.com that
competes with Salesforce.com.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Salesforce.com benefited from a business model
designed to be profitable with only a modest monthly fee, while
Siebel's cost structure was based on traditional enterprise
software pricing of thousands of dollars a user.
</P>
<P>
   The deal ``highlights one of the essential differences between
an enterprise software company selling licenses and the software
services model,'' said Vernon Keenan, an analyst with Keenan
Vision, a San Francisco research firm. Software services,
``basically free the user from the need to hire and staff an I.T.
department,'' said Keenan. ``I.T. staff is a critical issue and
Salesforce.com eliminates that.''
</P>
<P>
   For $99 a month, subscribers to IBM's Small Business
WebConnections, get a local server computer _ the toaster-size
Interjet from IBM's Whistle Communications unit _ 24-hour,
seven-day-a-week technical support, and an Internet connection for
up to 100 users. IBM is offering two free months of WebConnections
as part of the partnership agreement.
</P>
<P>
   On top of the WebConnections subscription, Salesforce.com users
would pay nothing for the first five users, then $50 for each
additional user.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really we're on a mission to make every business an
e-business,'' said Mike Braun, general manager of IBM Global Small
Business. ``Salesforce.com just has an outstanding application that
is right in the sweet spot of the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Salesforce.com will be the first application offered for the
WebConnections service. While small businesses have in the past
made do with simple contact manager software for keeping track of
sales information, Salesforce.com offers a program with the power
of corporate applications like Siebel, but with a simple
Web-browser interface that requires no user training.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the IBM partnership, Salesforce.com said, it had
signed 5,000 customers and was enrolling on average 200 new ones
each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we are now the fastest-growing CRM,'' said Benioff,
Salesforce.com's chairman, using industry shorthand for customer
relationship management. ``For a lot of our customers, who are
small businesses, we can move them into this modern age. IBM will
create a whole host of applications with a single sign-on, and an
appliance to give them access to a full service network,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Braun said the deal did not reflect any weakening of IBM's
relationship with Siebel. ``We have an excellent partnership with
Siebel,'' he said. ``Siebel's offerings are really focused on the
large enterprise. Marc's solution is really focused on the Web for
small businesses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
