<HEADER>
A4168 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PATENTS-NYT &LR;      06-04 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVENTORS DREAM OF A WORLD WHERE EVERY SOCK HAS A MATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The common sock hardly seems in need of taming. Its basic design
has remained unchanged for generations, serving to protect and warm
the foot, and provide a liner between skin and shoe.
</P>
<P>
   As with all clothing, socks are subject to the whims of fashion
and the improvements possible with modern materials. But in the
end, most people own socks that are essentially similar to the
socks their ancestors wore, and just like the socks their friends
and neighbors own.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the nation's patent database proves that there is
always someone who believes the sock can be improved. Inventors
continue to tinker with the sock and to come up with sock
accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, historical trends are apparent. In the 1970s, for
example, there were several attempts to create the dress tube sock,
a dark-colored sock with no defined heel.
</P>
<P>
   More mechanically-minded inventors tend to devote their time to
making the sock perform double duty. In the last 20 years, patents
have been awarded for socks with pockets, heated socks, cushioned
socks, inflatable socks, open-toe socks, half-socks, sock dickies,
socks with hidden shoe horns, tap dance socks, moisturizing socks,
exercise socks, medicated socks and socks with simulated jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   Patents for athletic socks and support socks are so numerous
that many are barely distinguishable from one another, except for
their varying promises to improve performance and strengthen and
support feet, ankles and legs.
</P>
<P>
   After sock enhancements, two fields appear to captivate footwear
inventors: the act of donning socks, and the challenge of keeping
pairs of socks together in the laundry.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassment seems to motivate the inventors of sock sorters.
In their patents, they cite the challenges of owning multiple,
one-size-fits-all socks knitted in similar yarns and colors, or of
living in a household where several people own lots of socks. These
inventors are alarmed by how easy it is to wind up with mismatched
pairs of socks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, the mismatch is discovered when the wearer is in
situations that can cause great embarrassment,'' Wayne Reichle
wrote in his patent for what he called a ``device for sorting
socks.'' Reichle recently won patent 6,067,659 for an invention
that clamps sock mates together. The clamp is color-coordinated to
the sock, with each side bearing an identifying symbol. The clamps
can be attached anywhere on the sock, but Reichle recommends
attaching them to the top edge of the sock so they will be covered
by pant legs.
</P>
<P>
   Grandma might have just tied socks together before tossing them
into the wash, but even in her day, inventors were hoping to add
technology to the process. In 1957, a patent was awarded for a
washable strip of fabric to which pairs of socks could be fastened.
</P>
<P>
   Other inventors have tried to solve the matching problem by
knitting a word or icon into the sock during weaving _ usually in a
place that would be covered by a shoe. One invention added
identifying labels to socks. In 1988, Bruce Anderson won patent
4,734,938 for simply writing the color name on the sock. Rodney
Mazzoli won patent 4,965,902 for a method of joining two socks by
wrapping or tying them together with a strip of material that is
impregnated with fabric softener or anti-cling compound.
</P>
<P>
   In a more recent attempt to solve multiple-sock challenges,
Jonathan Hartzell won patent 5,467,510 for a method of tagging
socks with a four-part, color-coded disc. The color of the disc
indicates the ``fundamental color category to which its sock
belongs,'' he writes in his patent. Another part of the disc
identifies the person who owns the sock. And ``by noticing whether
a sock features a protruding dome-shaped cap or a flat tack disc,
an observer is immediately aware of the inside-out, right side-out
status of that sock.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the sock sorters that use clamps, snaps, tags,
pins, or clasps to hold pairs together in the wash. Joel Hicks won
patent 5,926,925 for magnets that pair socks. Other patents require
holes in the socks to accommodate the pins and tags; others fit
tags over the sock's top edge. The tags often come in pairs bearing
matching colors, letters or numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are not the only ones interested in tracking their
socks. Louise Christy and Frank Saffioti live in New South Wales,
Australia, and won patent 5,579,541 for sock tabs fastened with
hook-and-loop patches like Velcro.
</P>
<P>
   Other inventors have focused on making it easier to put socks
on, since elderly people, handicapped individuals, arthritis
sufferers and pregnant women may all find it difficult to bend over
and pull on socks. Eugene Santamaria, who lives in Crescent City,
Fla., won patent 6,056,171 last month for a long, curved handle
with flexible side wings that expand to stretch the ``opening of a
sock for aiding the insertion of a user's foot into the sock.''
Santamaria writes in his patent that his design is intended for
``users having limited mobility or flexibility to don their socks
on their own and without the aid of others.''
</P>
<P>
   Other devices include frames, handles, shoe horns and
telescoping arms designed to help people put on socks. Ignace
Willemin won patent 5,924,610 for a pair of tongs with jaws. ``The
first gripping jaw keeps the sock open wide enough so that the tip
of the foot can be slipped in and then the heel,'' Willemin writes
in his patent. ``It is then possible to put on the sock and to pull
it up along the calf of the leg without the user having to bend
over. One of the gripping jaws also has a catch element enabling
socks to be removed.''
</P>
<P>
   Other devices are made of horseshoe-shaped plastic over which a
sock is draped or stretched. Often they come with string or rope to
assist in pulling up the sock. Some can be inserted into an empty
shoe, so a person could slip his or her foot into a sock and shoe
at the same time. John and Frank Pettit use a pair of hinged posts
with two attached arms in their patent 4,756,453. An inverted sock
is placed over both arms. ``The user then spreads the posts apart
to stretch the sock open and pushes a foot into the open sock,''
the Pettits' patent says, ``the sock unfolding as it is mounted on
the foot.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Frank Krack's design for a sock that is inherently
easy to pull on. Krack, who won patent 5,575,013, designed a sock
with a pleat down the length of its front. When the pleat is open,
the sock is easy to pull on ``without the pulling, squeezing and
rubbing associated with conventional socks,'' he says. Once the
sock is on, the pleat is closed with a hook-and-loop fastener.
</P>
<P>
   Pleated socks are probably very easy to identify in the wash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 1650EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
