<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4169 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-WAGNER-FEST-815&AMP;ADD-N     06-04 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAGNER-FEST-815&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENOUGH WAGNERIAN CONFLICT FOR AN OPERA 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Passions are not often stirred in Germany, a country
that has learned to mistrust the giddier emotions, but a
long-simmering battle for control of the annual Wagner Festival at
Bayreuth is now coming to a head with an unusual clamor.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is the directorship of the festival, a position held
for the past 49 years by Wolfgang Wagner, 80-year-old grandson of
the composer Richard Wagner. Because Bayreuth, where Richard Wagner
introduced his ``Ring of the Nibelung'' in 1876, occupies such a
central, if contested, place in German culture, the fight is bitter
and widely watched.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner sits Nike Wagner, the niece of the current
director, and his bitter foe, who recently published a stinging
election manifesto in the Frankfurter Allgemeine, calling the
festival old-fashioned, promising a ``trend-setting, contemporary
Wagner'' and blasting a style ``enslaved to 19th-century Wagnerian
mysticism.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposing her is Gudrun Wagner, the second wife of Wolfgang
Wagner and ``the woman he intends to put in his place,'' in the
words of Daniel Barenboim, the director of the Staatsoper in Berlin
and a man who worked for 18 years at Bayreuth. Gudrun Wagner has
been fiercely loyal to her husband through a wave of recent
criticism that has included comparisons of the ``late Wolfgang
era'' to the stagnation of late Brezhnev.
</P>
<P>
   Between them stands a third candidate and a third woman, Eva
Wagner-Pasquier, who is Wolfgang Wagner's daughter by his first
marriage and has worked as an opera manager in Paris and the United
States as well as playing a leading organizational role at the
music festival in Aix-en-Provence, France.
</P>
<P>
   No love is lost among these relatives, who now await the word of
the 24-member board of the Richard Wagner Foundation in Bayreuth.
``The board agreed on May 12 that its decision on a new director
would be taken on June 5,'' said Joachim Oppold, a board spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a catch worthy of Joseph Heller's more twisted
ruminations. While agreeing, at least in principal, that it would
be salutary to find a successor, Wolfgang Wagner has taken the view
that the vote should not constitute any sort of ultimatum, or even
encouragement, for him to step down.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued recently Wolfgang Wagner said, ``The
election of a successor does not mean that the present festival
director is put under pressure to announce a specific point of time
for resigning.''
</P>
<P>
   Because his contract is for life, this position seems legally
solid, if infuriating to Wolfgang Wagner's critics, who have grown
impatient with a festival that remains hugely popular _ demand for
tickets always swamps supply _ but has been described by the
Sueddeutsche Zeitung as treading ``the narrow path between
nostalgia and decay.''
</P>
<P>
   Udo Bernbach, a Wagner scholar, said: ``The legal position is
that Wolfgang Wagner retains his position as long as he wants. He
thought that perhaps he could indicate a successor. But if the
person chosen is not his wife, he will take the view that he is
there for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether he can defend that position is another matter. Pressure
has been growing on Wolfgang Wagner to move on, and the board's
determination to vote on a successor suggests that he may be
vulnerable. The board includes representatives of the German
government, the state of Bavaria, the town of Bayreuth and the
family.
</P>
<P>
   Two factors _ apart from his tenure of almost a half-century _
have accentuated the pressure on Wolfgang Wagner. The first is
musical. Many critics and musicians take the view that the
innovative drive that characterized the festival in the immediate
postwar decades has dried up.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfgang's brother, Wieland, who died in 1966 after running the
festival for 15 years, was the more artistic of the siblings. If
innovation survived his passing _ the postmodern centennial
``Ring'' of 1976 directed by Patrice Chereau and conducted by
Pierre Boulez is widely remembered _ it was generally less evident
in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The second pressure is political. The cult of Bayreuth, and it
is intense, retains ties to the German right. Wolfgang Wagner is
generally seen as having been reluctant to encourage open debate on
the family's links to Hitler, the central role of Wagner's music
under the Third Reich, and the composer's own often scathing
attitude toward the Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bayreuth is Germany's largest single contribution to musical
culture at this moment, but it is unhealthy to have the family in
charge,'' said Karen Painter, an assistant professor of music at
Harvard. ``What has generally been encouraged is the fetish around
the festival and a whitewash on anti-Semitism.''
</P>
<P>
   Because some of the funds for the festival come from the state,
the center-left coalition of Gerhard Schroeder is in a position to
wield some influence. It seems likely that it would push to see the
result of any vote respected quickly.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wolfgang Wagner declined to be interviewed, as did the three
candidates to succeed him. Bavaria is a place of conservative
instincts, and the passions aroused by the succession have already
caused unease. But the long manifesto from Nike Wagner suggested
that she scents blood. Co-signed by Elmar Weingarten, general
manager of the Berlin Philharmonic, it amounted to an unprecedented
reach for power.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no dramaturgy behind the program as it stands
today,'' Nike Wagner said. She called for the repertory to be
extended because ``nothing decreed by Wagner's widow is
sacrosanct.'' So performances of ``Rienzi,'' ``Die Feen'' (``The
Fairies'') and ``Das Liebesverbot'' (``The Love Ban'') should be
added to the ``Ring'' and ``Parsifal.'' The directorship should be
restricted to a 10-year term, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Strong words. But as Barenboim said: ``There is a lot of
pressure to decide what happens when Mr. Wagner goes. But who
defines when he goes? He has a contract for life, and God, as far
as I know, is not on the Richard Wagner Foundation board.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
