<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, June 5, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Unsettled weather will cover much of the East through Tuesday as
a series of low-pressure areas moves from the Midwest to the
northeast coast. Thundershowers surrounding one low-pressure center
will move off the Carolina coast early Monday. The northeast coast
will be mainly dry, but clouds will thicken as onshore breezes
increase.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, showers will occur north of another low as it
moves from the Ohio Valley to the central Appalachians. Over an
inch of rain will be common by Tuesday, especially near the
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Thundershowers will linger Monday in the warm, moist air across
the interior Southeast. Some sunshine will bathe the Gulf Coast,
where scattered thunder will erupt later Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure will keep the Plains dry and mild. The interior
West will be very warm with scattered afternoon thunder in the
southern Rockies
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: TORNADO TALLY
</P>
<P>
   Since records began in 1950, the United States has averaged
about 800 tornadoes annually. During the 1990s, the average was
more than 1,200 twisters a year. A large part of the significant
increase in the number of tornadoes recorded recently can be
attributed to better observation. The building of a national
network of Doppler radar that senses rotating winds in the clouds
has led to the detection of many tornadoes that in the past would
have been unnoticed. Also there are more people in more places with
more cameras watching for twisters.
</P>
</TEXT>
