<SLUG> BC-TV-GIMP-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`KING GIMP': A PAINTER HAPPILY EMERGES FROM A DETERMINED BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: Broadcast notes appear at end of review. Time and channel
are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By JULIE SALAMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was one of those embarrassing, exhilarating spectacles people
hope for when they watch the Oscars. In March, when ``King Gimp''
won the award for best documentary short, the film's writer and
subject sprang out of his wheelchair in a burst of excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night HBO is showing the documentary, which is
exhilarating in its way but far from embarrassing in any way. It
tells the story leading up to that Oscar moment, and how Daniel
Keplinger, the flailing man in the wheelchair, tries to force the
world to see only the man.
</P>
<P>
   His job is not easy because cerebral palsy has set his various
body parts moving to separate rhythms. It is painful to watch him
change shirts. He rolls like a toddler on the floor, struggling to
coerce his uncooperative self into elusive arm and neck holes. So
when he first appears on screen, it is hard to grasp what is going
on with him because this young man with dark shaggy hair does not
stop moving and sputtering. Then subtitles appear to translate
those bursts of noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people think `gimp' means someone with a lame walk,''
says Keplinger. ``But gimp also means a fighting spirit.'' Suddenly
he comes into focus. Keplinger the documentary subject was
discovered at age 12 when Susan Hannah Hadary and William Whiteford
began investigating the lives of children with physical
disabilities. For the next 13 years they periodically checked in
with him.
</P>
<P>
   His progress surprised everyone except perhaps his mother. She
appears to be a calm woman who refused to put her son in an
institution as her husband wanted. He left the family when Dan was
6 and she continued her child-rearing plan. ``I treated him the way
I would have treated any normal baby,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In family photographs he looks normal. The freeze frame of the
still camera stops his perpetual motion, at least for the photo
albums.
</P>
<P>
   After spending a few years at a school for disabled children,
Keplinger was ``mainstreamed.'' His social life was negligible, but
he found solace. Like the cerebral-palsy-stricken Irish writer and
painter Christy Brown (memorialized by Daniel Day-Lewis' bravura
performance in ``My Left Foot''), Keplinger turned to art. Using a
specially designed headpiece to hold a brush, he began to paint and
draw under the guidance of an understanding teacher. Somehow the
contact of the brush and canvas seems to steady him.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Parkville High, an artist was born and the artist was me,''
says Keplinger.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile he did what teen-age boys do: he grew a mustache and a
ponytail and asserted his independence. Before he graduated, he
moved into his own apartment.
</P>
<P>
   At 20 he enrolled in Towson State University in Maryland, where
two teachers would not speak to him and another told him he would
never be an artist. Keplinger thought he might never paint again,
until another teacher took him seriously. So he could make
reasonable suggestions to his student, this teacher tried on
Keplinger's head contraption and tried painting with it.
</P>
<P>
   Keplinger's paintings are fierce, almost defiant, but also
strangely beautiful: or maybe it's impossible not to read them like
this after watching his struggle.
</P>
<P>
   His work can be seen at the Phyllis Kind Gallery in SoHo through
June 30. HBO is simultaneously mounting a virtual exhibit on the
Internet, at hbo.com.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES: &QL; 
`KING GIMP'  &QL; 
At 7 Monday night on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   Directed and photographed by William A. Whiteford; Susan Hannah
Hadary and William A. Whiteford, producers; written by Daniel
Keplinger; music by Michael Bacon; Loye Miller, contributing
editor. For Tapestry International: Nancy Walzog, executive
producer. For HBO: Sheila Nevins, executive producer; Carole Rosen,
senior producer; Lisa Heller, supervising producer; edited by Geof
Bartz.
</P>
</TEXT>
