<DOCNO> NYT20000604.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4184 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-clinton-putin-media-c     06-04 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-clinton-putin-media-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Russian Media Jab Putin, Clinton to Make Point on Free Speech
 &HT;    By Margaret Coker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW - Fed up with the stiff and somber meetings between
President Bill Clinton and Russian President Vladimir Putin, a
popular and controversial Russian television show tried to loose up
the summit atmosphere with a bit of lampooning Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's most popular entertainment show, called Kukly, which
means ``puppets'' in Russian and is best described as a mix between
``Saturday Night Live'' and ``The Simpsons,'' featured Clinton as a
special guest to make a point about the importance of free speech
in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The show and its network, the independent NTV television
station, have come under fire in the past for its irreverence as it
pokes fun at the country's leading politicians. It has repeatedly
skewered Putin, showing skits where his puppet likeness is a pimp
or even God.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin has increased pressure on the television station to
``retire'' the Putin puppet - a threat NTV says it won't bow to.
</P>
<P>
   Russian journalists and intellectuals have been highly critical
of Putin's treatment of the media, and fear the former KGB chief
will reinstate Soviet-era restrictions on the press.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night's Kukly program stressed the importance that a free
press and open style of government can play for a country.
</P>
<P>
   While waiting for Clinton to arrive, the puppet Putin discusses
the possibility of recruiting Clinton as a spy. In a dream
sequence, he practices his pitch to ``Friend Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill,'' says puppet Putin. ``I want us to work together''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, yes,'' replied puppet Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't understand. I want you to work for us,'' Putin says
ominously, as he shows Clinton a thick KGB file filled with the
American's misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   As Putin starts to tick off a list of blackmailable offenses,
including draft dodging and womanizing, Clinton cuts him off.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the American people know all this, who I've been with,
what I've done,'' the Bill puppet says.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can that be?'' asks a perplexed Putin, dismayed because
his tactic appears to have backfired.
</P>
<P>
   The show's irreverence was not one-sided however. It took a
couple of jabs at Clinton, and the shallowness Russians often
perceive in Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get me to agree'' to become a KGB spy, the Bill puppet says
later. ``All you have to do is offer money, lots of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was featured in a Kukly episode two years ago,
speculating about what might have happened if the U.S. president
found himself in Russia at the time of bloody Communist purges of
the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent part of Sunday evening in a scheduled event on
Russia's airwaves, fielding questions in an unprecedented hour-long
radio evening phone-in program on the independent radio station
Ekho Moskvy, owned by the same company that runs NTV.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   For more information: http://www. echo.msk.ru
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
