<DOCNO> NYT20000604.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4185 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-PUTIN-0605-CO     06-04 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PUTIN-0605-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Putin Rejects U.S. Anti-Missile Plan
 &HT;    By Bob Deans
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW President Clinton was unable to overcome Russian leader
Vladimir Putin's objections Sunday to a controversial U.S.
anti-missile program designed to defend America from attacks by a
rogue state or terrorist group.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton warned Putin, though, that continued Russian opposition
to the missile defense shield would make it difficult for the
United States to agree to mutual nuclear weapons reductions Moscow
seeks.
</P>
<P>
   Those cuts, Clinton said, would require a change in top secret
Pentagon plans for responding to a nuclear attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be much better, if we were going to do that, if we
could also know that we were defending ourselves against a new
threat, which we believe is real,'' said Clinton, referring to the
risk of a missile attack from a rogue state such as North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Putin acknowledged the growing risk of such an attack, but he
told Clinton that the United States has exaggerated the threat. He
argued that the missile defense system Clinton is considering could
do more harm than good, by upsetting the strategic balance of
weaponry between the two nuclear powers, perhaps even sparking a
21st Century arms race.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of problems there,'' Putin said through an
interpreter. ``We're against having a cure which is worse than the
disease.''
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders made their remarks during a 25-minute press
conference following a day of intensive talks focused on missile
defense and nuclear arms reductions.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Clinton is scheduled to become the first U.S.
president ever to address the Russian Duma, or parliament. After
that, he flies aboard Air Force One to the Ukrainian capital of
Kiev for a half-day meeting with President Leonid Kuchma, returning
to Washington late Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the open tension over high stakes issues that rekindled
memories of U.S.-Soviet rivalry during the Cold War, both Clinton
and Putin insisted that they had set the stage for working out
their differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really cherish this,'' said Putin. ``We observed not only a
desire to speak, but also to find joint and mutually beneficial
solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back over darker days in U.S.-Russian ties, Putin, a
former KGB officer, said ``One would hope that the very worst in
our relations is far, far behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   In their first summit since Putin was elected president in
March, the two men met for about four hours Sunday in the Kremlin,
roughly the same amount of time as they met the night before.
</P>
<P>
   The two appeared to establish a rapport that was businesslike
and respectful, if not nearly as chummy as the sort of personal
relationship Clinton built over seven years with former President
Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If everyone behaves the way President Clinton has behaved, not
trying to find dead ends and problems, but to seek ways of moving
ahead,'' said Putin, ``I think, between us, in the future our
relations really will be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond congenial atmospherics, the summit bore substantial fruit
on the central goal of reducing the danger of a nuclear exchange
between two countries that together possess more than 80 percent of
the world's nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders committed their countries to disposing of 34 tons,
each, of nuclear weapons fuel plutonium over the next 20 years,
under an agreement that provides for extensive U.S. and
international assistance to help Russia do its part. If it were not
destroyed, the fuel could be used to build thousands of nuclear
warheads or possibly fall into the hands of terrorist groups or
rogue states.
</P>
<P>
   They agreed also to set up a joint office, in Moscow, where U.S.
and Russian military officers could sit side by side at computer
screens and share information on any missile firing that might
appear to threaten either country.
</P>
<P>
   That program, the first permanent military operation ever
between the former Cold War foes, is designed to reduce the risk of
a mistaken alarm that could trigger a counterattack against either
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a milestone in enhancing strategic stability,'' said
Clinton, ``and I welcome it.''
</P>
<P>
   And they agreed to a set of 16 principles to guide them in
continuing negotiations over the core strategic issues of missile
defense and nuclear arms reductions.
</P>
<P>
   Each side cast the principles in different terms, however, and
neither side reported progress on the substance of their
fundamental dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly we haven't eliminated the differences between us,'' on
the subject of missile defense, Deputy Secretary of State Strobe
Talbott told reporters traveling with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the objective case that the United States has
made is very compelling,'' said Talbott. ``But for it to become the
basis of an agreement with the Russians, they need to see that,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials have stressed for weeks that they had no
expectation of resolving the missile defense and arms reductions
differences during this summit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Putin have ordered senior aides to conduct technical
talks on both issues in the weeks ahead, with an eye toward a
second meeting of the two presidents on the margins of the annual
Group of Eight, or G-8, summit in Japan at the end of July.
</P>
<P>
   Time, though, is not on Clinton's side.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from leaving office in January, Clinton is expected to
decide this fall on whether to deploy a proposed national missile
defense (NMD) system.
</P>
<P>
   The NMD system under consideration would consist of a
sophisticated radar station in Alaska and a bevy of 100 missile
launchers, also in Alaska. It's aim would be to detect an incoming
missile fired from across the Pacific Ocean toward the United
States and destroy it en route with defense missiles called
interceptors.
</P>
<P>
   Such a system is not permitted under the Anti Ballistic Missile
(ABM) treaty reached 28 years ago between the United States and the
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proposed amending the ABM treaty to allow for an NMD
system. He contends that such an amendment has been made necessary
by the ability of North Korea, presumed by the U.S. intelligence
community to have several nuclear weapons, to deploy a long-range
ballistic missile.
</P>
<P>
   Putin rejects that argument.
</P>
<P>
   Putin fears, also, that a limited NMD system would be the first
step toward a far more sophisticated missile shield that, over
time, would undercut the strategic balance of power between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia believes that NMD will undermine strategic stability,
threaten Russia's strategic deterrent and provoke a new arms
race,'' said Talbott, the administration's long term point man on
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton claims that the NMD system would pose no threat to
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The two countries are in the initial stages, moreover, of
negotiating further reductions in their nuclear arsenals.
</P>
<P>
   The countries, combined, have more than 14,000 nuclear warheads
deployed on long range bombers and missiles. They have agreed to
try to reduce that total to 5,000 under a third Strategic Arms
Reduction Treaty (START), now in the early stages of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, though, is seeking further reductions, down to a
combined total of 3,000. Russia's nuclear arsenal is rapidly
deteriorating and economic woes are making it increasingly
difficult for the country to safely maintain a large nuclear force.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Sunday that both sets of negotiations must proceed
in tandem, and he made clear that progress in one area would be
largely pegged to progress in another.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans' e-mail address is BobDeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
