<SLUG> BC-TV-DAUGHTER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE HEADLINES, A NOMINEE FACES HER MEDIA CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Production notes at end of review.) 
 BY JULIE SALAMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``An American Daughter,'' Christine Lahti plays Lyssa Dent
Hughes, a prominent Washington doctor who has been nominated to be
surgeon general. During what is supposed to be a friendly
television interview, Lyssa's husband mentions the time his busy
wife failed to respond to a jury summons. The interview transforms
Lyssa into a celebrity of sorts, a media target. Everything about
her _ her hair, her manner, the things she has said about her
mother _ become ammunition to be used against her.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Wasserstein, who wrote the script, based on her Broadway
play, was inspired by real events: the failure of Zoe Baird's
nomination for attorney general, because she didn't pay taxes on
her nanny's salary; Kimba M. Wood's stymied nomination for the job,
also because of nanny problems; even Lani Guinier, whose nomination
for assistant attorney general was beset by politics, not personal
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was interested in what happens to the best and brightest
people in this country and why they don't go into public office,''
Wasserstein said in a publicity handout. ``What's more important:
that they're good at public relations or that they're good at their
jobs?''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds meaty. So it is curious, at least in this Lifetime
production, which will be broadcast Monday night at 9, that Lyssa
appears almost entirely as mother, wife, friend _ oh, yes, and
beleaguered nominee. She is always taking something out of the
refrigerator or putting something in or cleaning up or shopping at
Safeway. She doesn't even seem to have domestic help, though she
and her family live in a huge Georgetown home that is unnaturally
tidy.
</P>
<P>
   It's a relief, near the end, when she finally shows up at the
hospital she is supposed to be running and dons a white doctor's
coat (or maybe it's a relief because the setting recalls better
television moments for Lahti, when she was a regular on ``Chicago
Hope.'')
</P>
<P>
   The characters are cartoonish. Lyssa's nemesis is Quincy Quince
(Blake Lindsley), a sleek young postfeminist writer of the Naomi
Wolf school. Lyssa's best friend is Dr. Judith Kaufman (Lynne
Thigpen), a Jewish oncologist (and, it seems, Wasserstein's alter
ego, except for being black): Judith is always dieting, feeling
like a failure despite her success, a single woman in her 40s
pursuing fertility options. Lyssa's husband (Tom Skerritt) is a
sociology professor who has given many private tutorials to his
female students (including slinky Quincy).
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Wasserstein knows how to write a funny scene, but the
speechifying overwhelms the satire. ``You think my wife is one of
those 1970s good girls who came into prominence in the 1990s and
schedules a half-hour a day for spontaneity?'' asks husband Walter,
thematically.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as a subtle, feminist gesture Wasserstein has handed the
philandering husband more than his share of doozies. ``We're really
smart people, Lyssa,'' he says. ``We deserve to get everything out
of life the really smart ones get.'' But Lyssa doesn't have the
sense to look at him and say: ``Do any of us deserve anything,
Walter?'' She doesn't say this _ or anything like it _ because
Wasserstein seems to believe that privilege should beget privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Lahti rises to the occasion when she is given one. Though
Wasserstein wants us to empathize with Lyssa's plight, she does not
really seem to like her own creation very much. When Lyssa finally
decides to defend herself on television, she ends up whining.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman from good schools and a good family,'' Lyssa tells the
women of America archly. ``That woman has to be made to publicly
suffer so we know she's real.'' She continues, ``If she refuses to
compensate for her achievements, then she deserves to be hung out
to dry.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that's a talk-back-to-the-television moment. ``Clam up,
Lyssa,'' you might feel compelled to say. It isn't that poor little
rich girls can't be sympathetic. But they can't be self-righteous
at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Production notes:
</P>
<P>
   AN AMERICAN DAUGHTER
</P>
<P>
   Lifetime, Monday at 9 p.m. ET
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Wasserstein, Abby Adams, Robert Schwartz, Chad S. Hoffman,
executive producers; teleplay by Wasserstein, based on her stage
play; directed by Sheldon Larry. Produced by Gleneagle Productions
in association with Hearst Entertainment for Lifetime Television.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Christine Lahti (Lyssa Dent Hughes), Tom Skerritt (Walter
Abrahamson), Jay Thomas (Timber Tucker), Mark Feuerstein (Morrow
McCarthy), Lynn Thigpen (Judith Kaufman); Stanley Anderson (Sen.
Alan Hughes) and Blake Lindsley (Quincy Quince). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
