<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-ROYALS-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE QUEEN BREAKS THE ICE WITH CAMILLA PARKER BOWLES 
</HEADLINE>
   By WARREN HOGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In a noteworthy and unexpected warming of the coldest
shoulder in the realm, Queen Elizabeth II this past weekend met
Camilla Parker Bowles, mistress to her son Charles, the prince of
Wales, for the first time since their affair began.
</P>
<P>
   The get-together was at a 60th birthday party on Saturday for
the exiled King Constantine of Greece at Charles' Highgrove estate
in Gloucestershire. It ended an extended royal snub that had
irritated and dismayed the prince and complicated the choreographed
efforts by his staff to gain gradual public acceptance of Parker
Bowles as his consort and possible queen.
</P>
<P>
   Parker Bowles, who last saw the queen two decades ago, was
reported by other diners to have made a low, formal curtsy. The two
women then chatted briefly before the 100 guests tucked into a
barbecue lunch. They were seated at different tables.
</P>
<P>
   For years the queen had let it be known that she disapproved of
the liaison between the 51-year-old heir to the throne and the
52-year-old divorcee whom Diana, princess of Wales, blamed for
wrecking her marriage to Charles. The prince's staff had made
gaining the queen's tolerance of the relationship their No. 1
public relations priority.
</P>
<P>
   For royal watchers, birthday-party attendance has become an
important measure of whether the sovereign's thumb is up or down.
Parker Bowles was not invited to a grand party planned this summer
for Queen Elizabeth the queen mother, who turns 100 on Aug. 4. In
November 1998 the queen pointedly did not attend the Highgrove
party marking Charles' 50th birthday, because the hostess was
Parker Bowles.
</P>
<P>
   Next up for the guest-list scrutinizers is the 18th birthday of
Prince William next month.
</P>
<P>
   Buckingham Palace let it be known that the queen accepted the
invitation for Saturday's party knowing full well who had been
invited. A palace spokesman commented tersely Saturday night, ``The
queen attended a birthday party for King Constantine given by the
prince of Wales at Highgrove this lunchtime, and Mrs. Parker Bowles
was among the guests.''
</P>
<P>
   A constitutional expert, Lord St. John of Fawsley, said the
meeting was a necessary healing of a long-running quarrel but did
not mean that a marriage between the prince and Parker Bowles was
likely. ``It is essentially a private meeting, but the queen is
very well aware of the significance which will be attached to it,''
he told The Press Association, Britain's domestic news agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The queen is cool in her judgment and she would have assessed
the whole issue,'' said Lord St. John, whose name, following
British tradition, is pronounced ``SIN-jun.'' ``She has clearly
concluded that the time has come for them to end what has been a
point of contention.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I welcome the fact that it has happened. There are
so many problems which afflict families today that it is a very
good thing that this potential rift between her majesty and the
prince of Wales has been healed.'' But he went on, ``It is a long
step from that to concluding that a marriage will take place
between Mrs. Parker Bowles and the prince _ but that is really a
matter for them.''
</P>
<P>
   While there is plenty of evidence that Charles wants to step out
in public with Parker Bowles, there is little to suggest that he
wants to walk her down the aisle. Members of his staff point to his
statement at the time of his divorce that he would not remarry.
They also assert that Parker Bowles, to whom they refer privately
as ``Mrs. P.B.,'' has no interest in becoming queen.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Brooks-Baker, publishing director of Burke's Peerage,
said he believed there would be a royal wedding and speculated that
the Church of England would soon change its rules to allow
remarriage for divorced men or women whose former spouses are still
alive. This is the barrier blocking Parker Bowles.
</P>
<P>
   There is little likelihood that she will be able to assume any
official functions, but there may now be a place for her at private
family occasions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Charles and Camilla Shand, as she was then, first met at a
London nightclub in 1972, where she is said to have told the prince
that her great-grandmother was his great-great-grandfather's
mistress, and then said, ``So how about it?'' She was referring to
Alice Keppel, who had been the lover of King Edward VII.
</P>
<P>
   Their friendship bloomed into what he later described as a
``blissful, peaceful, and mutually happy relationship.'' Then he
went to sea as a junior officer in the Royal Navy and she married
Maj. Andrew Parker Bowles, a cavalry officer. During the 1980s,
they resumed a sexual relationship, and Diana famously complained
in a television interview that ``there were three of us in this
marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the public emergence of Charles and Camilla were well
under way when Diana's death in a car crash in Paris in August 1997
put an end to any thought of it.
</P>
<P>
   The effort resumed on a night in January 1999, when
photographers were alerted that Charles and Camilla would be
emerging together from the Ritz Hotel after a 50th birthday party
for her sister Annabel Elliott. The burst of flashbulbs turned
Piccadilly into daylight during their 20-second passage from
doorway to limousine.
</P>
<P>
   Details of Parker Bowles' meetings with William and Harry, his
younger brother, now 15, were leaked to improve her image among
people who were unforgiving of her role during Charles' marriage to
the boys' mother. The couple were filmed together on a Greek island
cruise last summer, and Parker Bowles made a highly publicized trip
to New York, where she was photographed with society figures.
</P>
<P>
   In the days in which she was accused of sinking the royal
marriage, buns were thrown at her by angry shoppers in a food store
and her looks were compared unfavorably with those of a horse on
the front page of a tabloid newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   But opinion polls now indicate that most Britons are not opposed
to the relationship, or even to their marriage, though there
remains general opposition to the notion of her becoming queen. And
now the most difficult convert has yielded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
