<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-KLM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH AIR AND KLM SAID TO BE IN EARLY MERGER DISCUSSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Amid renewed pressure in the airline industry to
consolidate, British Airways has held informal merger discussions
with KLM Royal Dutch Airlines, executives close to both companies
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   While the executives emphasized that the discussions are in the
most preliminary stage _ one executive called them talks about
talks _ it underscores a sense of urgency among airline operators
to seek partners, in the hope of increasing profit in an industry
where many companies, particularly in Europe, have seen margins
erode.
</P>
<P>
   The informal discussions take place amid the proposed
acquisition of US Airways by UAL, parent of United Airlines, for
$4.3 billion and overtures from AMR, American Airlines' parent, to
Northwest Airlines about combining their businesses. Those talks
have adjourned, executives said. Northwest has made it clear that
it would expect a high price, with the value of the UAL-US Airways
deal as a starting point. The initial offer by AMR, which is said
to be considering its next move, was considered too low.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the state of discussions, the airline industry is on
the verge of more consolidation, analysts say, as a few big
carriers move to get still bigger, carving out big chunks of the
flight routes.
</P>
<P>
   Already, airlines in the United States and Europe have entered
into a hodgepodge of alliances that allow passengers to book
flights on member airlines and share frequent-flier programs. In
fact, if British Airways were to merge with KLM, it would put
several alliances into question. British Airways is a member of the
Oneworld alliance with American, and KLM has an alliance with
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   British Airways tried to merge many of its functions with
American in 1996, but regulators have blocked the proposed deal.
KLM broke off its alliance with Alitalia in April. If British
Airways were to merge with KLM, it might also take on KLM's
alliance with Northwest. However, some analysts think that the
combined company's relationship with Northwest would have to be
severed to gain regulatory approval because the group would control
too many trans-Atlantic flights.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some analysts think that a deal between British Airways
and KLM would gain approval from regulators. British Airways has
reported poor financial results in recent periods, with its 1999
earnings the worst since the airline was privatized. ``We believe
British Airlines accepts that its European operations will destroy
shareholder value until, and unless, European consolidation
happens,'' Peter Hyde, an analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston,
wrote in a note to investors.
</P>
<P>
   European airlines that rely on traffic on the Continent have
been especially hard hit. Low-cost carriers, mimicking the success
of Southwest Airlines in the United States, have forced down profit
margins, undercutting intercity prices by the big carriers that
have run markedly higher than on similar-length routes in the
United States. Hoping to avoid being left out of the low-cost
segment, British Airways and KLM have created their own low-cost
carriers. British Air spawned an airline called Go, and KLM created
a discount carrier called Buzz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
