<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4219 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CNN-MEDIA-2TAKES(830)     06-04 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-MEDIA-2TAKES(830)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT CROSSROADS, CNN RETHINKS ITS APPROACH TO THE NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  By JIM RUTENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CNN celebrated its 20th anniversary in Atlanta on Thursday night
with fireworks and video clips of the news organization's proudest
moments: the Persian Gulf War, the Space Shuttle Challenger
disaster, the Olympic Park bombing in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But another scene perhaps better reflected the current mood at
the CNN Center: reporters chasing the network's founder, Ted
Turner, through hallways, up escalators and even into a public
bathroom as he tried to avoid their questions.
</P>
<P>
   That Turner was avoiding journalists on one of his proudest
days, the celebration of a major milestone for his news network,
underscored the many uncertainties facing CNN as it reaches young
adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   For all of its accomplishments, CNN is currently garnering its
lowest monthly ratings in nine years, a fact that has prompted its
top executives to reevaluate the way the network approaches news.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, CNN is expected to come under the ownership of
a new company this fall, when its parent corporation, Time Warner,
is scheduled to merge officially with America Online. Anticipation
of that merger is creating both anxiety and hope among CNN
executives.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, it is believed that AOL, the largest Internet
service provider, with 22 million subscribers, can help bring CNN
back to a dominant position among news organizations. On the other,
the new company will have a new management structure and, possibly,
new ideas about how to do things, especially when ratings are low.
</P>
<P>
   And, despite all declarations of harmony at the anniversary
celebration, one fact is inescapable: Under the new company's flow
chart, Turner, CNN's most ardent protector and champion, will still
hold the title of vice chairman and senior adviser _ but he will no
longer have direct operating control of the cable properties he
amassed over three decades. That role would go to AOL's president,
Robert W. Pittman.
</P>
<P>
   Just days before the festivities in Atlanta began, The Los
Angeles Times reported that Turner, Time Warner's largest
individual stock holder _ who will own 4 percent of AOL-Time Warner
_ was displeased about his new role and associates were warning
that he could disrupt the merger. That threat was emerging just as
the companies were sending voting materials to their shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Executives within the two companies confirmed last week that
Turner was angry, but not necessarily so much about his new role.
Rather, they said, he felt he was not properly consulted as the
flow chart was drafted and was caught off guard upon its release a
month ago.
</P>
<P>
   With all of this in mind, Steve Case, the AOL chairman, and
Gerald M. Levin, the Time Warner chairman, went out of their way to
declare publicly last week that Turner would play a large role in
the new company and in CNN.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, Turner had apparently changed his tune.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happy _ I'm happy!,'' he told a reporter. He added, ``You can
be unhappy one week and happy another one, right?'' Then three
public relations executives approached and the conversation ceased.
</P>
<P>
   Still, given these apparent corporate mood swings, it should
come as no surprise that top executives at CNN are an uneasy lot
these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever there is change, there is uncertainty and anxiety,''
said Tom Johnson, the CNN chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said his most fundamental concern was whether AOL would
try to meddle with the network's journalism. He said CNN executives
had similar concerns in 1996, when Time Warner merged with Turner
Broadcasting. Time Warner, however, took the same hands-off
approach that Turner did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very, very smooth transition because journalism is at
the core of Time Warner,'' Johnson said, referring to its
publications like Time. ``And up until this most recent
announcement, we have really felt quite confident about the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he and others have received reassurances on two key
issues from Case and Pittman: that AOL will not pressure CNN to
pursue racier, tabloid stories and production values that might do
better in the ratings than the standard international and political
news, and that it will allow CNN to cover the news impartially
regardless of its affiliation to AOL. On the bright side, CNN is
hoping for the exposure that AOL can give it.
</P>
<P>
   But, in the wake of the recent ratings declines, Johnson said
there had even been discussions inside CNN about changing editorial
direction.
</P>
<P>
   CNN has been consistently dogged by one major problem that is
almost inherent to its mission: Viewers will go to it in droves
when major news breaks, but tend to go elsewhere when the news
cycle is slow. With an average of 225,000 households tuning in each
day in May, CNN's ratings are down 33 percent compared with those
of May 1999 and are at their lowest monthly level since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The network also is facing new competition from cable news
competitors like the Fox News Channel, which is growing
considerably, and NBC's offerings, MSNBC and CNBC.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The ratings situation is said to be, at times, of pressing
concern to Turner. Johnson said that Turner was extremely concerned
in midwinter, when CNBC's early evening business show, ``Business
Center,'' for the first time beat CNN's ``Moneyline'' in the
monthly ratings. Turner then began conversations with Lou Dobbs,
the former ``Moneyline'' anchor and CNNfn president who is well
respected by Wall Street but left CNN last year in a messy public
scene when Time Warner executives tried to limit his ownership of
space.com, the space Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted was disappointed,'' Johnson said. ``Ted wanted to bring
Lou back and he initiated conversations with Lou, first by phone
and then in person.''
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs left CNN last June amid boiling tensions with CNN's U.S.
president, Rick Kaplan, that made any collaboration between the two
difficult, if not impossible, and it was believed within the
organization that his return would bring those tensions to the
surface once again. Johnson said that he vehemently opposed the
move, but that he did so on the grounds that Dobbs would still have
an ownership stake in space.com, hindering his impartiality as a
journalist. The idea was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Of that move, Turner would only say in an interview, ``That was
a long time ago.'' And, he said of the current ratings situation:
``I'm not the kind to panic. It's not so precarious as when we
started,'' a reference to the earliest days at CNN when on-air
personalities had to contend with dropping ceiling panels, low-rent
equipment and absolutely negligible ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the reassurances he has received from AOL, Johnson said
concern was high enough within CNN that debate continued about
whether to produce sexier programming. But, Johnson said, he and
other executives concluded that the organization should resist such
temptation.
</P>
<P>
   Case said he agreed, and that he was not concerned by the
current ratings. ``I think some of these things are cyclical,'' he
said. He and Levin said that Johnson and Kaplan would continue to
have their full support in their positions.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, CNN executives said that the strategy was to bolster
the news network's international coverage with more foreign
bureaus.
</P>
<P>
   But, most important, they said, they hope to strengthen CNN's
overall presence by promoting it well on the AOL Internet and
interactive TV services and by making it more available on wireless
devices. Specific plans, they said, are in embryonic stages, but,
ultimately it is their intention to make CNN's headlines available
anywhere at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan said he believes that sort of ubiquity in distribution
would make the current concerns about ratings seem quaint. In
anticipation, Turner advertising sales executives have held
discussions with Nielsen Media Research, the television ratings
service, about broadening the way it will measure CNN's audience to
account for viewers who may get its headlines on their cellular
phones and computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to have a broader view at AOL-Time Warner
about what advertising really means,'' Levin said, adding that
CNN's advertising revenues are up considerably despite ratings
declines.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of broad advertising sales approach is a main reason
why, executives said, Turner's operational duties are being taken
over by Pittman, the AOL executive who is to oversee all pay
services of AOL-Time Warner. The task will demand close attention
to the merging of old and new media, two areas where Pittman, a
founder of Viacom's MTV, has considerable experience.
</P>
<P>
   Levin said that Turner would exert as much influence as ever.
``It doesn't make any difference what our prosaic reporting lines
are,'' he said. ``What really matters is that he is there and that
he is a transcendent figure.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with the merger pending, and Turner's prior
displeasure now out in the open, it is in the interest of top AOL
and Time Warner executives to avoid controversy and keep Turner's
spirits up.
</P>
<P>
   That could explain why, in the minutes leading up to their big
celebration on Thursday night in Turner's Philips Arena, CNN
assigned a publicity executive to each reporter covering the event
for other organizations.
</P>
<P>
   But it turned out that they really did not have much to fear.
</P>
<P>
   As a reporter approached him at one point, Turner grabbed Case
by the neck and pulled him close. ``See: I'm happy!'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
