<P>
   LIFESTYLES
</P>
<P>
   ARTIFACTS - GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ A piece of tin roof flaps in
the wind. A spiderweb of silver duct tape does little to camouflage
cracks in the ceiling. The walls lack insulation. Weeds poke their
heads through crevices in the concrete floor. Mouse traps stand at
attention, poised to snap at furry intruders who dare cross the
line. And in the center of it all sits a priceless collection of 2
million Native American artifacts, some dating back as far as 400
A.D.''We don't meet legal requirements for maintaining a federal
museum collection,'' says curator Carolyn Landes. ``We are not
alone in that. You go to any underfunded park and you will find the
same situation.'' The warehouse, which is the size of an airplane
hangar, is hidden among yucca plants, juniper shrubs and pinyon
pines in southwestern Colorado. As a security precaution, the exact
location is kept secret, and a Daily Sentinel reporter and
photographer were allowed in recently with the stipulation that the
location would not be published. PHOTOS. (Cumpston, Grand Junction
Daily Sentinel). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ARTIFACTS-SIDE _ GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Mesa Verde has one of
the largest collections of Native American human remains in the
National Park Service. But legalities set forth in the Native
American Graves Protection and Repatriation Act of 1990 have
prevented them from returning them to the tribes for reburial.
(Cumpston, Grand Junction Daily Sentinel) WITH PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PIANO-MAN _ Talk about your two-fisted talents: Athens resident
Joey Freeman, 49, has not only been accepted into the Van Cliburn
Foundation's International Piano Competition for Outstanding
Amateurs, he's a licensed massage therapist who feels that his
vocations feed off each other.''I almost by accident discovered
that I was getting better at massages when I was playing the piano
a good bit,'' says Freeman, who holds master's degrees in piano
performance, musicology and business administration from the
University of Georgia. He combines his loves by giving clients who
want it both a 30-minute performance and a 1 1/2-hour massage. It's
usually a woman, getting a birthday present from her husband. We
spent an afternoon with him in Athens, watching the maestro at
work. The Cliburn competition is June 5-10 in Fort Worth, Texas.
(Brock, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GREIG-FILES _ Need help negotiating the trenches of the linen
department? Ever wonder why one makes a bed? Curious about what
Wallis and the Duke slept on? Want to wow your friends with the
difference between Pima and Supima cotton? This edition of the
Greig Files cannot guarantee you a good night's sleep, but it will
answer all these questions and more _ much, much more. (Greig,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
