<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; WHAT BABA WAWA LEARNED FROM THE LINDBERGH CASE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The tricks of TV journalists, soulfully gazing into the cameras
whether they're questioning heads of state or flattering megawatt
celebrities, are based on lessons 70 years old, says a new
documentary, ``Legacy of a Kidnapping: Lindbergh and the Triumph of
the Tabloids.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, written and narrated by Harper's editor  &UR; Lewis &LR; 
 &UR; Lapham &LR; , will be broadcast on a PBS station in Long Island on
Monday. The New York Observer describes its claims that ``squeamish
and sensitive anchorpersons''  &UR; Peter Jennings &LR; ,  &UR; Diane &LR; 
 &UR; Sawyer &LR;  and  &UR; Barbara Walters &LR;  are ``the well-groomed stepchildren
of tabloid journalism godfather  &UR; William Randolph Hearst &LR; ,'' the
heirs of  &UR; Damon Runyon &LR; ,  &UR; Walter Winchell &LR;  and  &UR; Adela Rogers St. &LR; 
 &UR; John &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The voices of the people covering the kidnapping trial of
 &UR; Bruno Hauptmann &LR;  were ``not unlike'' those of Jennings and Walters
after the death of  &UR; Princess Diana &LR; , says Lapham, ``who
periodically interrupted their sucking on the bones of wonderful,
wonderful Diana to rebuke with an air of condescension and disgust
those awful paparazzi.'' The ``Sob Sisters'' Hearst assigned to
follow Hauptmann's wife during his trial were ``as skilled as Diane
Sawyer in the application of false sentiment.''
</P>
<P>
   Lapham decided to focus on ABC's stars after watching the Di
coverage. ``They were really unctuous to a degree that's hard to
imagine. ... I could have just as easily used  &UR; Dan Rather &LR;  or  &UR; Tom &LR; 
 &UR; Brokaw &LR;  or someone from CNN. I think the networks are all the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Postcard from London:  &UR; Bob Cullinan &LR;  saw the stage version of
``The Graduate,'' preceded by the civilized announcement: ``We
remind you that this production is set in the year 1963, before the
invention of the cellular telephone.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Rick Robinson &LR;  of Laney College sends word on apparent
downsizing: Assistant Dean  &UR; Eugene Short &LR; , who retired in December,
has been replaced by  &UR; Sharon Short &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   - With issue No. 2 due on the stands in a couple of weeks,
 &UR; Ellen Kunes &LR; , editor of O, the Oprah Magazine, has resigned.
Despite rumors of friction between editors and  &UR; Oprah Winfrey &LR; , she
said she was leaving because of personal ``work /family issues.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Arthur Laurents &LR;  reveals in his new autobiography ``Original
Story By'' (Knopf; $30) _ mined for Personals by  &UR; Chris &LR; 
 &UR; Jehle &LR;  _ that  &UR; James Mason &LR;  always ``wore a false torso beneath his
shirt. ... Mason was completely unself-conscious about the falsie''
and didn't mind being seen being  &LR; strapped into it on movie sets.
</P>
<P>
   - In a probing Movieline feature, 10 celebrities tell the
magazine the biggest misconception about them. ``Well, people think
I was born in San Francisco,'' reveals  &UR; Josh Hartnett &LR; , ``which is
not accurate. I don't know where that comes from. I might have said
something near that at some point. Like my mom lived in San
Francisco, but I wasn't born there.'' A check of imdb.com, a movie
database, proves him right; it says he was born in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   - Looking for a good read?  &UR; Stephen Hochheiser &LR;  forwards a
Publishers Weekly review of ``The Secret,'' a posthumously
published  &UR; Harold Robbins &LR;  novel: ``Subplots explore sweatshop
conditions, trade relations with China and technology millionaires,
but all roads lead to nipple clips and crotchless panties.''
</P>
<P>
   - Ad Age reports that Coca-Cola is doing its best to squelch a
rumor in Egypt that if you hold the soft drink's logo to a mirror,
it reads in Arabic, ``La Mohammed, La Mecca,'' which is said to be
a denial of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   - Wrinkle-zapping  &UR; Seth Matarasso &LR; , maestro of botox and
collagen _ poison 'n' plump _ confirms a Vogue magazine story that
a San Francisco client had him make a house call to Rio _ three
days, first-class tickets _ where she was vacationing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Old clothes should now only be worn by young people, and young
clothes (skinny trousers, bat sleeves, boyish suits, slinky
dresses) will look best on the not-so-young. ... It means not
dressing your age _ unless you happen to be 35. ... It's this
obsession with median adulthood, with possessing the glamour and
power of a woman with a past and a future, that drives the new
bourgeois chic (among the young) and, conversely, the new
spunkiness (among the older crowd).''
</P>
<P>
   -  &LR;   &LR; Got that? Vogue recommends trying to be young if you're
old, and old if you're young. And if you're 35, just sit there.
</P>
