A4227 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT &LR;      06-04 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS FROM THE MEDIA BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   `MILLIONAIRE' WILL FACE `SURVIVOR,' AGAIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There will be a Round 2, after all.
</P>
<P>
   After uncertainty about the possible consequences, ABC will
again pit the hottest show of the television season, ``Who Wants to
Be a Millionaire,'' against CBS's much discussed and highly
promising newcomer ``Survivor'' on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Against all expectations, CBS scored a coup last week when
``Survivor,'' its summer series about social interaction and
survival skills on a remote island, did some real damage to
``Millionaire,'' ABC's most valuable property. In a stealth move,
ABC had scheduled ``Millionaire'' on that Wednesday night just to
derail the new series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' did remarkably well with young viewers, the
audience ABC usually courts. ``Millionaire,'' which was already
being denigrated by some competitors for starting to skew old in
its appeal, looked extremely top-heavy with older viewers when
matched against ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   That is certainly not the message ABC wants to send this summer
just before it moves from a three night-a-week to a four-night
schedule of ``Millionaire'' in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   If ABC had wanted to avoid making a decision about a second
showdown with ``Survivor,'' it got no help from the New Jersey
Devils. Only a sweep in the Stanley Cup hockey finals, being
carried by ABC in prime time, would have eliminated the need for
ABC to think about having Regis Philbin square off again against
those folks dodging rats and snakes on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   But the Devils lost Game 2 to the Dallas Stars, and ABC knew the
hockey series would last at least five games, pre-empting this
Thursday's showing of ``Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   With an extra ``Millionaire'' on its hands, ABC could have
chosen to play it on Wednesday at 8 to challenge the second episode
of ``Survivor'' _ or it could have slid it to the safety of, say,
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But after weighing the risks involved if ``Millionaire'' fared
even worse this week against ``Survivor,'' ABC still opted to meet
the new enemy head on again.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago it was CBS that was most concerned about the outcome;
now the pressure has shifted to ABC. As an executive at a competing
network noted, any drop in the powerhouse status of ``Millionaire''
could have serious financial implications for ABC, which has
charged advertisers huge prices for the show.
</P>
<P>
   ABC executives profess no more concern about the future of
``Millionaire'' than they did before ``Survivor'' arrived. At least
one interested party expressed nothing but warmth for the new
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Burnett, the executive producer of ``Survivor,'' said he
received one especially welcome call amid many of congratulations.
Michael Davies, the executive producer of ``Millionaire'' called to
say, as Burnett put it, ``welcome to the hit club.''
</P>
<P>
   --BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   A DEATH IS NOTED IN THE META-MEDIA FAMILY
</P>
<P>
   In the expanding world of meta-media (translation: journalists
writing about journalists) the Web site NewsWatch.org has been a
relatively tiny boutique.
</P>
<P>
   Its offerings were limited, tailored to those interested in what
was written, not who was doing the writing. Last week, it became
the first casualty among the current generation of meta-media
sites, as its one financial backer backed off.
</P>
<P>
   As Paul Mongerson, a former engineer and executive who
originally offered $1 million to underwrite the site, explained on
Friday, his original idea was to point out examples of distortion
by the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't to educate people or philosophize,'' he said. ``It
was to say, `This is what is said, and it's not the case.' The
purpose was to bring ordinary news consumers into the debate over
media distortion that currently takes place among elites.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, he said, the audience of about 25,000 unique
visitors each month turned out to be not the news consumers that
Mongerson had put up $1 million to reach, but the same old elites.
You know, the ones who hop from Jim Romenesko's MediaNews site
(www.poynter.org/medianews/index.cfm) to Kurt Andersen's Inside.com
to the Online Journalism Review ojr.usc.edu _ all sites that were
quick to note the death in the neighborhood last week.
</P>
<P>
   Trevor Butterworth, the editor of the two-year-old site, said
the decision came as a shock when he heard about it last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought our success in creating an audience and winning
plaudits on a minor scale,'' he said, was something Mongerson would
appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he had a different vision,'' Butterworth added, ``and what
we managed to do did not please him so he pulled the plug.''
</P>
<P>
   S. Robert Lichter, president of the Center for Media and Public
Affairs, the organization that runs NewsWatch, said on Friday that
he had some hope of finding new financing. But when he spoke of the
site, it was in the past tense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed what you can do as a mom-and-pop organization,'' he
said, ``but we also showed the limits of that.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Felicity Barringer
</P>
<P>
   PUBLISHING EXECUTIVE TO BE NAMED
</P>
<P>
   American Express Publishing is expected to announce Monday that
its new president and chief executive will be Ed Kelly, the
publisher of the company's Travel &AMP; Leisure group.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, whose group publishes Travel &AMP; Leisure and its spinoffs,
T&AMP;L Golf and Travel &AMP; Leisure Family, will succeed Daniel B.
Brewster, who resigned two weeks ago to become the chief executive
of Gruner &AMP; Jahr, a unit of Bertelsmann AG.
</P>
<P>
   American Express Publishing, which is a partnership between the
Time Inc. unit of Time Warner and the American Express Co.,
publishes four consumer magazines, including Food &AMP; Wine and Travel
&AMP; Leisure and specialty publications for American Express
customers, like Departures magazine. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
