<HEADER>
A4229 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NEW-ECON-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-04 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-ECON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW ECONOMY: NOT ALL TECHNOLOGY ACQUISITIONS SUCCESSFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In no sector of the technology business have more companies with
less revenue been acquired for richer sums than in communications
equipment. It is almost routine for obscure start-ups with little
or no revenue to be acquired for hundreds of millions, or even
billions, of dollars in stock by industry giants unable to keep up
with all the changes in communications technology.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, for instance, Lucent Technologies Inc. agreed to
pay $4.5 billion in stock for Chromatis Networks, which is
developing technology to enhance the capacity and capabilities of
fiber optic networks within cities.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, many of these deals look good for everyone, and
they often are. The buyers can move into new areas. The
entrepreneurs become rich, as do the venture capitalists who buy
into the target company. But not every deal can be a success, and
as the pace of acquisitions grows, so may the number of bad deals _
like the examples below, all of which offer lessons on the risks of
the get-bigger-by-buying strategy.
</P>
<P>
   CIENA-OMNIA, $429 MILLION, MARCH '99: Ciena Corp. is a leader in
optical communications equipment. But when Ciena agreed to buy
Omnia Communications Inc. last spring, it was trying to move into a
new market: data networking. Omnia was developing products using a
technology called asynchronous transfer mode, which uses optical
networks but is not itself an optical system.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Omnia has generated essentially zero revenue for Ciena,
and few analysts foresee any such revenue any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Ciena says that customers simply do not want to buy Omnia's sort
of product. That means either that Ciena badly misgauged the market
or that its sales force, tailored to optical gear, has not figured
out how to sell Omnia's technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect significant revenue this year from that
product, so that's a disappointment to us,'' said Denny Bilter, a
Ciena spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Be careful when expanding beyond your core market and
make sure your sales force can distribute the new product.
</P>
<P>
   SIEMENS-ARGON, $240 MILLION, MARCH '99: When Siemens of Germany
decided to become serious about data networking last year, it
bought three start-ups in the United States _ Redstone
Communications Inc., Castle Networks Inc. and Argon Networks Inc. _
and put them into a new division called Unisphere. Redstone, which
makes gear that pools data traffic at the edge of big networks, has
been a big success. Castle, which wants to develop the
next-generation of voice telephone switches, seems to be making
headway. And then there is Argon.
</P>
<P>
   When Siemens agreed to acquire it, Argon wanted to make an
ultrahigh-capacity switch for the core of big networks using both
asynchronous transfer mode and Internet protocol formats. That was
pretty much the last anyone heard about Argon.
</P>
<P>
   One problem was that Argon's technology did not mesh smoothly
with Redstone's. Unisphere is trying to work out the kinks.
</P>
<P>
   Siemens might be faulted for not recognizing this problem before
spending hundreds of millions of its shareholders' dollars on
Argon. But at the time, other European communications giants like
Alcatel and Ericsson were rushing into the data communications
market, and Siemens apparently did not want to be left behind.
Unisphere executives declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Even if the competition is making noise, take the time
to do technical due diligence research. Moving recklessly can cost
a lot of time and money later.
</P>
<P>
   TELLABS-NETCORE, $575 MILLION, JUNE '99: In a move somewhat
similar to the Ciena-Omnia deal, Tellabs Inc., a leader in optical
transmission, tried to move into a new market by acquiring NetCore
Systems Inc., a company that wanted to build high-capacity routers
using asynchronous transfer mode and Internet protocol formats for
the core of big networks.
</P>
<P>
   But NetCore's technology did not work as well as Tellabs had
anticipated, and it is not clear when the deal may start paying
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``In NetCore's case you have a combination of a
less-than-elegant integration of the company into Tellabs, probably
a product that was not as mature as Tellabs' management thought it
was, and a marketplace that got pretty competitive,'' said Steven
D. Levy, chief communications equipment analyst for Lehman
Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Investors judge older companies like Tellabs mainly on the
growth of their per-share earnings. With a market value of only $27
billion, Tellabs cannot throw its stock around as aggressively as
bigger companies can, without risking dilution of its earnings.
That has led some experts to believe that Tellabs is simply afraid
to pony up the money necessary to acquire private companies with
the best technology. Tellabs declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Be careful expanding into new markets but also remember
that spending too little may yield little in results.
</P>
<P>
   CISCO-MONTEREY, $500 MILLION, AUGUST '99: Cisco Systems Inc.'s
acquisition of Monterey Networks Inc., which makes gear that links
optical communications networks at high speeds, appears set to
become much more successful than the Omnia, Argon and NetCore
deals. But it is not a home run just yet.
</P>
<P>
   And home runs, or at least doubles, are what the market has come
to expect from Cisco, almost surely the most successful corporate
acquirer in the past decade. On the day the Monterey deal was
announced, Cisco also said it was buying Cerent, a different sort
of optical networking company, for about $6.9 billion. That deal
has definitely been a home run: Cerent may well generate $1 billion
in revenue for Cisco this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the Monterey deal has just about fallen off the radar
screen. People close to Cisco have said the company's original
internal target of moving Monterey's products into the market this
spring was a result of unwarranted optimism within the Monterey
team.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco still has not announced any sales of Monterey's systems,
though people close to the company said last week that they
expected announcements of some tests with major communications
carriers shortly.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: Even acquisition champs like Cisco can have an off day.
That is one reason Cisco, using a portfolio approach, does so many
deals.
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT-NEXABIT, $900 MILLION, JUNE '99:
</P>
<P>
   In this deal, Lucent did not seem to get what it thought it was
buying. But at least it got something of value, and even the
original vision may finally be coming into focus.
</P>
<P>
   Nexabit Networks Inc. was supposed to catapult Lucent to
immediate leadership in the market for ultrahigh-capacity Internet
routers, devices that help direct data traffic. According to many
communications experts, it turns out that Nexabit's technology is
actually better-suited for transmitting information in a format
known as frame relay rather than the conventional Internet protocol
format.
</P>
<P>
   The Nexabit deal could still work. This week, Lucent plans to
announce that VCities, a small communications carrier based in
Dallas, has agreed to buy the Internet protocol version of the
Nexabit product.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson: The lesson from Lucent and all these companies is that
nothing can replace thorough research before a deal and
nose-to-the-grindstone execution afterward. With the pace of
acquisitions accelerating, it is only getting easier to make bad
deals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000604.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
