<HEADLINE>
RADICALS' RESENTMENT MAKES BARAK TIGHTEN SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT4 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israel's secret service has tightened security
around Prime Minister Ehud Barak, news reports say, as some Jewish
settlers warn that the domestic climate could turn ugly and violent
quickly if the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks move forward.
</P>
<P>
   The alarm bells began ringing here last week, when the leader of
a young, radical settlers' group issued a disturbing assessment of
the feelings in his community, which were aroused by the prospect
that some settlers would be evacuated as the result of a peace
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, when I see Barak's plans and I hear the voices around
me,'' said Shimon Riklin, leader of the Next Generation settlers'
organization, ``I say that if, God forbid, he carries out this
dangerous plan, his days could be numbered.''
</P>
<P>
   To Israelis, who are only now coming to grips with the traumatic
assassination of Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin in 1995, this kind of
language is profoundly unsettling. The country is in a far
different place now, having absorbed the initial shock of what
concessions the peace effort entails and the aftershocks of Rabin's
assassination.
</P>
<P>
   But among the political leadership and the security
establishment, the fear of being caught unawares or unprepared _
much less of reliving such a trauma _ is strong. So as the threats
continued over the weekend with more inflammatory statements by an
extremist settler and two rabbis, Barak's close associates seemed
eager to take them at their word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear friends, there will be a murder,'' Benjamin Ben-Eliezer,
the communications minister, said Sunday on Israeli radio. ``I am
warning the security services and everyone: Don't put your heads in
the sand.''
</P>
<P>
   The director-general of the Settlers Council, the umbrella
organization that has a relatively moderate leadership, said Sunday
he did not believe that Barak faced any danger from his community.
The organization repeatedly on Sunday condemned the use of
violence, although it declined to condemn any of the statements
that others considered inflammatory.
</P>
<P>
   And the Settlers Council's spokesman, Yeshoshua Mor Yosef, even
said in an interview that he thought the prime minister's bureau
was fabricating information about supposed threats on Barak's life
in order to manipulate public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, an evening newscast cited unidentified
security sources as saying it would be impossible to tighten
security around the prime minister since his security was already
supposedly airtight. Barak's office would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   After Barak addressed the issue of incitement during his
closed-door Cabinet meeting, his bureau made some of his remarks
public. As he habitually does, he expressed deep respect for ``the
settlement enterprise,'' which has sought over several decades to
reclaim the West Bank from the Palestinians, seeing it as the
biblical Land of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   But the prime minister also delivered a warning of his own
against any attempt to use violence, or the threat of violence, to
derail his peacemaking plans _ which he sees as a continuation of
the work of his mentor, Rabin. It is futile, he said, to try to
block a ``historical process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The murder of Yitzhak Rabin was a human and national tragedy,
but it could not stop the peace process,'' Barak told his Cabinet,
a statement released by his office said. ``This is a flawed grasp
of reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The repercussions of any political assassination would
boomerang against those fighting for the Greater Land of Israel,''
he said. ``If there is anything that deviates from the legitimacy
of the settlers' struggle, it is acts such as these.''
</P>
<P>
   Yigal Amir, an ultranationalist Jew who was convicted of
murdering Rabin, said he had acted to thwart plans to transfer land
to the Palestinians. The assassination took place against the
backdrop of increasingly vicious personal attacks on Rabin, and
many here believe that an atmosphere of incitement, including some
by rabbis, encouraged Amir and other extremists.
</P>
<P>
   As the settlers' movement gears up to battle Barak, some here
worry that protest rallies could once again get out of hand as
verbal hostility increases. A settler rabbi, for instance,
published an article this weekend accusing the government of
``treason'' and ``crimes against the Jewish people.''
</P>
<P>
   As if transported back in time, many Israelis rushed to say what
some wished they had said five years ago. Among them was Carmi
Gilon, who was director of the General Security Services at the
time of the assassination and resigned afterward. In an interview
on Israeli radio, he said, ``It behooves the rabbis to understand
the weight of responsibility they bear and to be cautious in their
statements.''
</P>
<P>
   In a similar vein, David Levy, the foreign minister, said:
``Rabbis, I call to you, be careful with your words. You are
spiritual leaders, and dangerous expressions could, God forbid,
bring about another blow that we won't be able to withstand.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The secret service also has stepped up its monitoring of extreme
right-wing organizations, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   To many Palestinian officials, the idea of such anxiety rippling
through Israel seems a bit premature. Although President Clinton
sounded a note of optimism last week when he said a peace accord
was ``within view,'' Palestinian and Israeli officials have been
exchanging barbs about what they call each other's recalcitrance,
and both sides say the talks on substantive issues are at an early
stage.
</P>
<P>
   Saeb Erekat, a senior Palestinian negotiator, on Sunday
described the talks as ``in crisis,'' although this is something he
often says, reflecting his long frustration with the effort.
</P>
<P>
   And Barak continued to break character and to criticize the
Palestinians publicly, as he did last week for the first time. He
described the way they are conducting themselves in the talks as
``a regression.'' With a September deadline for a final accord
looming, he said the Palestinians were postponing discussions ``on
various pretexts'' and generally dragging their feet. The
Palestinians issued the same charge in the opposite direction.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, briefly sparred
Sunday on the contentious issue of Jerusalem. Barak said he had
instructed his negotiators to put the subject aside for the moment,
while Arafat angrily retorted that Jerusalem must be on the table,
``and whoever doesn't like it can go drink from the sea.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians are pushing for the next land transfer, which
is supposed to take place this month. Associates of Arafat say he
is determined to obtain as much land as possible from the Israelis
in case the negotiations break down; that land will be the sole
basis for a Palestinian state if he unilaterally declares one in
September, as he has warned that he will do if talks do not
progress.
</P>
<P>
   But in Israel, as opposed to the Palestinian side, where there
is far deeper skepticism, the general presumption is that the peace
talks are marching forward. Thus the settlers' anxiety is
increasing.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech on Friday to his Labor Party, Barak said he aspired
to keep 80 percent of the settlers under Israeli sovereignty in the
``final status'' accord. He declared that this would be an
``unusual historic achievement'' and that the settler movement
would have achieved its goal of permanence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak urges us to see the cup as half full,'' Shimon Shiffer
wrote Sunday morning in the newspaper Yediot Ahronot.
</P>
<P>
   But the settlers were not buying it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
