<SLUG> BC-CORSAIR-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN BALLET'S `LE CORSAIRE' PLEASING ROMP WITH PIRATES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Yes, the plot is nutty. And yes, the music thumps
along with absolutely no subtlety. But when American Ballet Theater
presented ``Le Corsaire'' on Saturday afternoon at the Metropolitan
Opera House, that swashbuckling 19th-century Russian story ballet
kept a theater full of children entranced and had the adult
balletomanes among them cheering. And that is no small feat.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to see ``Le Corsaire,'' which Ballet Theater will
perform again Monday night, is to go with the flow and not allow
oneself to get lost in the crowds of fierce pirates and nubile
slave women and other local color at the Turkish bazaar, gardens
and pirate cave where much of the action takes place. What is
important about the production, based on versions by Marius Petipa
and Konstantin Sergeyev and staged for Ballet Theater by Anna-Marie
Holmes, is the opportunities it offers for unabashedly lovely and
pyrotechnical dancing that, for once, grows out of, and furthers,
the plot.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Jaffe and Jose Manuel Carreno epitomized the contrasting
delicacy and prowling sensuality that make the ballet's most famous
excerpt, the ``Corsair Pas de Deux,'' more than just ballet
razzle-dazzle danced by two lead characters, Medora and the slave
Ali.
</P>
<P>
   Marcelo Gomes' pirate Conrad, a role debut, was a man of simple
passions communicated through easy, expansive classical dancing
that contrasted enjoyably with the terrier-like intensity and
whirligig travel of Joaquin De Luz, an endearingly villainous
Birbanto. The clarity and amplitude of Maxim Belotserkovsky's
dancing, a high point of the afternoon, made the slave dealer
Lankendem unusually likable.
</P>
<P>
   Ekaterina Shelkanova, new as Gulnare, hovered between tragedy
and mischief in an unsubtly danced performance. Ethan Brown was a
charming Pasha, whose dream of an animated garden leads to one of
the ballet's most exquisite sequences. That kind of beauty was also
communicated in the dancing of Yan Chen, Michele Wiles and Anna
Liceica in the Odalisque trio.
</P>
<P>
   The lead cast was completed by Eleena Melamed as the do-or-die
head pirate woman and Carlos Molina as the Pasha's sweetly bumbling
sidekick. Ermanno Florio conducted the score, a stew of music by
Drigo, Delibes and three other composers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
