<HEADER>
A4236 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-EVERGLADES0605-COX     06-04 2046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES0605-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Can the Everglades be saved?By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Speeding fast enough for the wind to stop your breath,
Tom Shirley's airboat roars over ankle-deep water through a maze of
reedy grasses. And the creatures of the marsh spring to life.
</P>
<P>
   Alligators roll and dive, roiling the cola-colored water seconds
before the boat glides overhead. Egrets and white ibises take off
in the distance, fluttering like tattered handkerchiefs across a
horizon marked by scattered clumps of willow. Awkward as always,
great blue herons lumber into the air.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, at least 25 miles west of the strip malls of Broward
County, Shirley stops for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   His destination is a gray, clapboard cabin along a canal lined
by dwarf cypress trees, snake-necked anhingas that plunge for their
food, and rainbow-hued birds called gallinules that stalk across
the lily pads. A sign warns, ``Beware of Attack Frog.''
</P>
<P>
   Out here in the sparse, watery wilderness called the Everglades,
a tourist could imagine that the Real Florida still exists as the
first European explorers encountered it: the land of mosquitoes and
water moccasins, panthers and wood storks, untouched by the asphalt
and stucco suburbs swarming in from the coasts.
</P>
<P>
   The tourist would be wrong, however _ a fact that's leading
Florida and the nation to embark on a great experiment: Can $7.8
billion, four decades of bulldozing and drilling and digging, and
the assembled wisdom of scientists and engineers save this
ecological treasure? At the same time, can South Florida keep its
farming economy and double its population to 12 million people?
</P>
<P>
   Shirley, for one, is worried about the answer. The Fort
Lauderdale man has a scrapbook of memories here a half-century old,
with photos to back them up, and they tell him how much of the
Everglades has already vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Stout hardwood trees toppled by floods, their islands
disintegrated. Bird flocks and once-abundant snakes, shrunk to bare
remnants of their selves. An emaciated gator. The skulls and
skeletons of drowned white-tailed deer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all sorts of barometers telling us something is
wrong,'' says Shirley, his arms as creased as a gator's hide.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley first ventured into the Everglades in the 1940s, and
later spent 30 years as a state wildlife officer. At 68 _ 15 years
older than Everglades National Park, some distance to the south _
he still makes his living here operating airboat tours. But not
happily.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I come out here today,'' he says, ``it breaks my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   NO QUICK FIX
</P>
<P>
   After spending a combined $3.5 billion trying to treat the
Everglades' ills, state and federal taxpayers are on the verge of
trying for an all-out cure _ if Congress approves it in the next
two months.
</P>
<P>
   No more tinkering with problems in one part of the region, only
to worsen them someplace else. No more pitting people against
nature. No more putting nature last.
</P>
<P>
   That's the promise, at least.
</P>
<P>
   The $7.8 billion restoration plan is the creation of dozens of
agencies, led by the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers and the South
Florida Water Management District. It's already won support from
Gov. Jeb Bush, the state legislature, the White House and key
congressmen from both parties.
</P>
<P>
   But the ecological disaster was more than a century in the
making. Reversing it won't be quick.
</P>
<P>
   With drainage projects beginning in the 1880s, Florida _ and
later the feds _ shrank the historic Everglades by half, turning
the rest to cities and farms. When the corps finished the job after
World War II, the remaining marsh was hemmed in by dikes,
crisscrossed by 1,600 miles of canals, and subjected to a ruinous
cycle of dryness and floods.
</P>
<P>
   The results:
</P>
<P>
   The Everglades lost more than 90 percent of its wading birds,
and its central marshes lost more than 60 percent of their
tree-covered islands. Florida Bay and Lake Okeechobee flirted with
ecological collapse. More than 600 of the region's species are
considered rare or imperiled. Fish in most of the Everglades became
off-limits to eating because of toxic mercury contamination.
Meanwhile, the same drainage system that has damaged the Everglades
dumps so much wasted water out to sea _ roughly 600 billion gallons
a year _ that serious shortages loom in coming decades. In coastal
estuaries such as the St. Lucie River and the Lake Worth Lagoon,
canals routinely dump pollution and wreck the ecological balance
that fish and sea grass require.
</P>
<P>
   Reverse course, the plan's supporters say, and you not only
rescue the nation's largest freshwater marsh, you also safeguard
the water supply for future residents.
</P>
<P>
   The experts who wrote the plan acknowledge that much remains
unclear about how the Everglades used to flow, and about how that
flow supported its old abundance. The result is a plan that skimps
on a lot of details, leaving them to be filled in as knowledge
improves.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters say it's critical to begin the years of tests,
pilot projects, and early earthwork as soon as possible _ including
getting Congress to approve the plan this year. Most likely, that
means getting an initial vote in the House and Senate before
members break for their August recess.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves scant few weeks to answer some critical questions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Who will set the rules for the restoration _ federal
bureaucrats or the state?
</P>
<P>
   _ Will Congress provide enough money for the plan? And will
Florida's promise to pay its own share, codified in a law Bush
signed last month, prove to be enough?
</P>
<P>
   _ How much leeway should the corps have to carry out the plan
without lawmakers scrutinizing every one of its 68 planned
projects?
</P>
<P>
   _ Perhaps most fundamentally, will the plan really help the
Everglades, or will it become a giant water-supply subsidy for
farmers and developers? And should Congress guarantee that the
Everglades gets its water before anyone else?
</P>
<P>
   Then there are myriad other disputes that could undermine the
restoration even if it wins Congress' OK: Struggles between
environmentalists and the sugar industry over the fate of a planned
reservoir in western Palm Beach County. Arguments between
environmentalists and the Miccosukee Indian tribe over which
federal agency they mistrust the least _ the Corps of Engineers or
the Interior Department. The fate of a proposed international
airport next to the Everglades in Homestead.
</P>
<P>
   And don't discount the effect of this year's presidential
election, which pits Vice President Al Gore against the governor's
brother, George W. Bush. Gore and Jeb Bush have already traded some
jabs over the Everglades, along with some carefully calibrated
praise.
</P>
<P>
   Even identifying the plan's main goal has caused a food fight on
Capitol Hill. The White House's legislative language says the
plan's ``primary and overarching purpose'' is to restore the
Everglades _ irking farmers and utility managers who insist that
water supply and flood control should get equal footing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a bumpy ride,'' said Tom Adams, a National
Audubon Society lobbyist in Washington. He said he's optimistic the
bill will pass, but it could be the last thing Congress does this
year.
</P>
<P>
   If the plan fails this year, supporters fear, they'll never get
another chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``What choice do we have but to move forward?'' asked Shannon
Estenoz, co-chairwoman of the Everglades Coalition. ``We've got an
almost dead lake. We've got an almost dead (St. Lucie) estuary. . .
. It's unconscionable that we would wait one day longer than we'd
have to.''
</P>
<P>
   AGREEING ON A PLAN
</P>
<P>
   But even the environmentalists are far from united. Some groups
say a bad restoration plan is worse than none at all _ and this
one, they argue, is fatally compromised by concessions to sugar and
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be accused of being great naysayers and
totally negative, yadda yadda yadda,'' said Juanita Greene,
conservation chairwoman of the group Friends of the Everglades. But
she said the plan ``doesn't seem to be emphasizing Everglades
restoration. Unless it's revised, we will oppose what's in it.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan still has the backing of almost all of the largest
state and national environmental groups, including the Audubon
Society, the World Wildlife Fund, the National Wildlife Federation
and the Everglades Coalition, a 42-group alliance.
</P>
<P>
   But some smaller groups call it a plan only an engineer could
love.
</P>
<P>
   True to the no-compromise spirit of its founder, the late
Marjory Stoneman Douglas, Greene's group wants a plan that
eventually would buy all 500,000 acres of sugar cane south Lake
Okeechobee. That land would go back to its original function:
storing water and letting it flow in an unbroken sheet to the
Everglades, replenishing the marsh and filtering pollution. It
would actually expand the remaining Everglades, not just make do
within its existing borders.
</P>
<P>
   The engineers say the buy-it-and-let-it-flow idea sounds great,
but it couldn't work in the drained, shrunken and sunken Everglades
that remain. Corps restoration chief Stu Appelbaum has likened the
Everglades to a comatose patient who must remain on the respirator.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the plan calls for storing hundreds of billions of
gallons of water along the margins of the Everglades, then creating
pumps to move it around the marshes in ways that are supposed to
mimic nature's historic patterns.
</P>
<P>
   The storage would include 60,000 acres of reservoirs in the
sugar region, leaving the rest to farming, and nearly 200,000 acres
east of the Everglades and around Lake Okeechobee.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also would store billions of gallons underground in
more than 330 storage wells, a technology never before used on such
a huge scale. Some scientists worry about whether the injected
water would pollute existing ground water _ or whether it would
seep away before it could be used.
</P>
<P>
   Another controversial part, costing $1 billion, would create
reservoirs on 15 square miles of limestone quarries that miners
already plan to dig in wetlands next to the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   The engineers refer to the quarry reservoirs as a ``Lake Belt,''
but they'd resemble no natural lakes ever seen in South Florida: up
to 36 feet deep with ruler-straight banks. Such deep water would be
an impossible place for wading birds to feed, or for sunlight to
nourish plants on the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call this restoration _ this square hole in the ground,''
scoffed Sierra Club activist Barbara Lange. In a letter to the
corps about the miners' plans last year, Interior Department
scientists criticized the proposed quarries as ``non-natural
habitat of little or no value to the Everglades ecosystem.''
</P>
<P>
   The department is still waiting to see whether the corps will
soothe its criticisms with a revised version of the quarry plan.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Shirley and other outdoorsmen complain that the plan
would drown, not save, tree islands in the central Everglades. They
say the plan, aimed at replenishing long-deprived sections of
Everglades National Park and Florida Bay, calls for keeping water
too deep north of the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have their way, this place will be under water,''
Shirley says.
</P>
<P>
   In a packet of documents that outdoor groups have sent to
members of Congress, Shirley stands in a photo next to a tree
toppled last year by flooding from Hurricane Irene. The caption:
``Everglades restoration at work.''
</P>
<P>
   Not true, said the corps' Appelbaum. He said his agency will
look at any evidence the outdoorsmen have collected about what
water depths the tree islands can withstand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the same goals they do,'' Appelbaum said. ``We're
trying to restore the entire system.''
</P>
<P>
   The corps' and water managers' assumptions also will face
scrutiny from a panel of experts appointed by the National Academy
of Sciences, which could release a report early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The plan's ultimate leap of faith is that ``getting the water
right,'' as the engineers put it, will reap benefits for the plants
and animals. Until they try it, they can't know for sure that it
will.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan's supporters say they know one thing: The system as
it exists doesn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
