<HEADLINE>
11 YEARS AFTER TIANAMEN SQUARE MASSACRE, MEMORIAL EBBING 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Eleven years after China turned its tanks and troops
against student protesters in Beijing's Tiananmen Square, tens of
thousands people gathered at a candlelight vigil here Sunday to
remember the doomed democracy movement.
</P>
<P>
   This year's ceremony drew far fewer people than last year's,
when a crowd of 70,000 packed Victoria Park to mark the 10th
anniversary of the massacre. Three years after Hong Kong's
reversion to Chinese sovereignty, Tiananmen Square is no longer the
emotional touchstone it once was. But as the only public
commemoration on Chinese soil, the vigil is still remarkable for
seeming so routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eleven years ago, the Chinese government was corrupt,'' said
Ang Chi-peng, who works in a trading firm. ``Eleven years later,
the Chinese government is still corrupt. We have to keep coming out
and saying that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ang, 51, has attended the vigil every year since 1989, when more
than 1 million people poured into the streets of Hong Kong to
protest the violent crackdown in Beijing on the night of June 3-4.
This year, he brought his 12-year-old daughter to witness Hong
Kong's annual assertion of free expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hong Kong is a political display window for China,'' Ang said.
``They allow things to happen here, but not anywhere else in
China.''
</P>
<P>
   The police presence was light on this stifling evening as the
crowd sang songs and waved softly flickering candles under a
crescent moon. Giant screens at either end of the park replayed
images of tanks rolling through Tiananmen Square as the sound of
machine-gun fire echoed from loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in China, security forces fanned out to ensure that
the anniversary passed without notice. In Beijing, police arrested
a pro-democracy activist in Tiananmen Square as he tried to scatter
banners commemorating the crackdown. The man, Shen Zhidao, was
arrested in the square last year as well, when he opened an
umbrella covered with anti-government slogans.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, the police broke up memorial services for the
victims of the massacre in Beijing and Xian, said the Information
Center of Human Rights and Democracy, a Hong Kong-based civil
rights group. The group also said that 50 dissidents in four cities
had begun a 24-hour hunger strike to honor the victims and demand
that the Chinese government reassess the crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong, however, the anger toward Beijing has clearly
ebbed. An annual survey released by the University of Hong Kong
indicated that public support for the group that organizes the
vigil had fallen to a record low _ 49 percent of those polled. In
last year's survey, 56 percent of people polled said they supported
the group, the Alliance in Support of Patriotic and Democratic
Movement in China.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the alliance said, ``Under heavy political
pressure, some people have quietly withdrawn, some people's hot
blood has run cold, and some people have even betrayed their
conscience by defending the massacre.''
</P>
<P>
   To compensate for the fading memory of Tiananmen Square, the
vigil's organizers concentrated their efforts on young people. The
theme was ``passing the torch of democracy'' to a new generation.
</P>
<P>
   Among adults here Sunday, the subject of China's economic ties
with other nations came up repeatedly. T.C. Leung, who works in a
hotel, said that China's campaign to join the World Trade
Organization and establish normal trade relations with the United
States would foster a new democratic movement in the country.
</P>
<P>
   A 44-year-old teacher standing nearby agreed. ``China wants to
be accepted into the global economy, so it will unconsciously
accept the rules of the game,'' said the woman, who would gave her
name only as Au. ``The rules are set by democratic countries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
