<HEADER>
A4238 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-AMBASSADOR-PROFILE-AR     06-04 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMBASSADOR-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIERRA LEONE'S AMBASSADOR CONFRONTS TERROR AND INDIFFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Many of the worst photographs are kept in a red
paper folder on the coffee table in the ambassador's office.
</P>
<P>
   As some diplomats might want to share photographs of a
sun-dappled tourist resort or a new business development in their
homelands, Ambassador John E. Leigh asks visitors to the Sierra
Leone Embassy to inspect the evidence of the nightmare that has
descended on his West African nation.
</P>
<P>
   He takes the first photograph from the pile. ``Here, what has
she done to deserve this?'' he asks of the child in the photo, a
girl not more than 3 or 4 years old. Her belly is covered with
scars from blade cuts. Most of her right arm is missing, removed
from above the elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just put your arm on the ground and chop it off,'' he
says of the grotesque tactics of the rebels who have mutilated
whole villages of people, including infants, by hacking off their
limbs, in an undeniably successful effort to spread terror. A
second photograph shows a pretty young woman, perhaps 20, with two
stumps where her hands had been.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of other civilians have been killed outright in almost
a decade of fighting in Sierra Leone, a diamond-rich nation of 5
million people whose history is bound up with the United States.
Much of the population, including Leigh, is descended from American
slaves who fought their way off Southern plantations and returned
to Africa. English remains the official language.
</P>
<P>
   The ambassador, an American-educated businessman and lawyer
turned diplomat who has run the embassy here since 1996, said he
did not believe the first reports of the mutilations when they
began to trickle back to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stunned by it; I thought it was a made-up story,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But quickly enough, the evidence became overwhelming. ``When
they chop off people's hands, they will say to the victims, `Let's
see how you're going to vote now,''' Leigh explained. ``In Sierra
Leone, people are in a state of shock. Nobody thought that fellow
Africans could be this vicious.''
</P>
<P>
   The extreme violence, he said, is explained by the diamonds,
which the rebels _ who have received support from Libya and
neighboring Liberia _ seek to control. ``The greedier you are, the
more violent you are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the scale of atrocities, he said, it has been difficult
to get Americans to listen and care, including officials of the
Clinton administration. ``It's just not important to them,'' he
said. ``Sierra Leone is small, the economy is tiny.'' As for the
State Department, he said, ``They listen to me but they do
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Leigh said a possibly racist double standard became clear last
year, when Sierra Leone continued its descent into chaos as the
United States began its multibillion-dollar military and
humanitarian aid campaign in Kosovo. ``Here is a white nation
getting all of these goodies, and here is Sierra Leone, where they
are cutting off the arms of women and children, and they are not
paying any attention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps worse, he said, the United States joined with other
Western powers last year in pressuring the Sierra Leone government
to negotiate with the rebels, producing a cease-fire agreement in
which the government pardoned the guerrillas who had been
mutilating civilians. After the deal was signed, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright traveled to Sierra Leone and met with the rebel
leader, Foday Sankoh. The agreement has collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were forced into it,'' Leigh said. ``The United States went
in and pushed it on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Leigh is unpopular across town at the State
Department. ``They give me dirty looks,'' he said with a throaty
chuckle. ``They don't like me there because I speak out.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for the administration's response, a State Department
official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that the United
States had provided more than $300 million in humanitarian aid in
Sierra Leone over the last decade. Washington was the principal
financial backer of an international peacekeeping force there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion that we haven't done very much is certainly
erroneous,'' the official said, adding that the United States had
not pressed the peace agreement on Sierra Leone but had instead
been an honest broker at the request of the government there.
``That is absolutely false, and I think Ambassador Leigh knows
that.''
</P>
<P>
   To the 61-year-old ambassador, the anger that he arouses among
American diplomats is simply proof that he is doing his job. The
Sierra Leone government asked Leigh to take over the embassy here
in the hope that after spending most of his adult life in the
United States, he would know how to make his voice heard in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   His roots to the United States go back to the 18th century, when
his ancestors escaped from Southern plantations and, according to
family accounts, fled to Nova Scotia and eventually to Sierra
Leone. ``Sierra Leone was a place for the guys who were
rebellious,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh grew up in Freetown, the capital, and was educated at
American- and British-run missionary schools. His father worked for
what was then the British colonial government. Like many from elite
families, he went to college in the West. He received a bachelor's
degree and an MBA from New York University, and a law degree from
Suffolk University.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, he has married an American, had three children,
all of them American citizens, and worked for the Chase Manhattan
Bank, Squibb Pharmaceuticals and Xerox. When he was tapped to
become ambassador, he was a lawyer in private practice in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But he says he has no desire for American citizenship. An
American passport, he said, would dishonor the memory of relatives
who had to risk their lives centuries ago to escape the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   `'My wife has been on my case to become an American,'' he said.
`'But I didn't feel right doing that. My ancestors fought their way
out of America's slave population. I didn't want to negate that
heritage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000604.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4239 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MARATHON-THEATER-REVI     06-04 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARATHON-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT WILL HAPPEN TO THE BABY? AMONG OTHER COSMIC, ONE-ACT
QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Leslie Caputo's ``Birth Marks,'' which closes the
first half of the third and final installment of Marathon 2000, the
Ensemble Studio Theater's annual festival of new plays, has enough
situational complexity to make you want a second act. As it opens,
a young woman named Terry _ she's maybe 18 or 20 _ has just given
birth to a baby in a hospital on the Lower East Side. Played by
Jenna Lamia, she's blonde, lovely, Irish Catholic and alone. Her
husband, who is Hispanic, hasn't shown up at the hospital, and he
never will.
</P>
<P>
   Instead she is visited by her disapproving, bigoted and
spineless father (Martin Shakar), who brings letters from his wife
to read to her, letters that begin, ``To my disgraced daughter.''
She is also visited by her husband's sister, Yvonne (Nicole Gomez),
who is both a spitfire party girl and a genuinely concerned friend,
and by her husband's brother, Luis (Ramon de Ocampo), a dopey kid
who has been dispatched to find the missing spouse and failed his
mission in spectacularly dunderheaded fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The plot issue is what will happen to the baby, and the play
could stand expansion to more fully simmer the emotional stew that
is cooked up in a mere 40 minutes. But the pungency of this small
play is in its rendering of the cross-cultural and
cross-generational conflicts in a working-class pocket of the city.
</P>
<P>
   From the opening conversation, in which Terry's father speaks to
his daughter with an Irish accent and Terry responds in New Yawkese
_ ``her'' is pronounced ``huh'' _ the ingrained obstacles to every
relationship in this play are painfully and realistically evident.
</P>
<P>
   The dialogue is written with a sure ear, no mean feat
considering the vernacular variety, and all the actors, but
particularly Lamia and Gomez, give their characters the sense that
for all their will to connect, they're speaking in separate
tongues. By the end, an entire neighborhood, its ethnic mix thrown
together by economics and circumscribed by limited dreams, has been
evoked by four people in a hospital room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Birth Marks'' is the highlight among the five bite-size plays
that make up the program, which runs through June 11. The others
are less ambitious, though each has its moments to recommend.
</P>
<P>
   Even ``Proof,'' by Jeff Reich, the play that closes the evening
by running bizarrely off the track of its initially comic premise,
does have a great beginning. In it a professor of neuroscience at
an undistinguished college takes out the frustration of a life of
academic obscurity on a classroom full of first-year students. The
scene takes the form of his opening lecture, and it is hilariously,
farcically bitter, complete with a slide show in which all the
slides are upside down. (You wouldn't think an upside-down goldfish
would look so weirdly funny, but it does.)
</P>
<P>
   The professor, Nathan Simpson, is played with a delicious comic
sense of self-loathing distress by Brad Bellamy. But alas the play
doesn't know what to make of the situation it has wrought; it
devolves into a windy confrontation between Simpson and his pompous
mentor (Forest Compton).
</P>
<P>
   The other plays include ``The Final Interrogation of Ceausescu's
Dog,'' by Warren Leight, the playwright's first work on a New York
stage since his ``Side Man'' won the Tony Award for best play last
year. An amusing trifle, it depicts the canine companion of the
deposed Romanian dictator being questioned by a suddenly liberated
citizen. His efforts to crack the dog's smugly privileged demeanor
cause him no end of frustration, which Ean Sheehy does a nice job
of letting bubble up until he cracks.
</P>
<P>
   Sheehy has the thankless role, here, however: as the dog,
Alexander R. Scott, dressed in a houndstooth jacket and speaking in
an Eastern European-accented pidgin English, is the star of the
show. ``I am simple dog,'' he says, whenever he's unmoved to
respond, an anthropomorphism that makes you giggle every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alien Boy,'' by Will Scheffer, is a monologue about a
13-year-old coming to recognize his homosexuality. It has a vivid
central anecdote _ the confused boy writes to a psychiatrist,
picked out of the phone book, pleading for treatment _ and the
performance, by David Greenspan, is an idiosyncratic one, well
thought out both physically and verbally. But the play itself has
too many familiar signposts _ mother issues, ``The Boys in the
Band'' _ not to feel a bit shopworn.
</P>
<P>
   The play that opens the evening, ``Cannibals'' by Heather
Dundas, is a comic reverie about Jane, a suburban mother who
wonders how she got that way. ``Here's what I don't understand,''
she says, stepping out from behind the wheel of her car, in which
she's driving her clamorous two children and their friends to
school. ``Ten years ago I was a bisexual living in New Orleans.''
</P>
<P>
   In scenes that flip back and forth between Jane's stressed
daydreams and the reality of her stressed morning, she persuasively
reveals the understandable conflict between what her life might
have been and what it is. The script is detailed enough to make
Jane a real character, and in the lead role, Diana LaMar is
singular enough to rouse a potentially hackneyed circumstance to
the level of a sympathetic predicament.
</P>
<P>
   The switchbacks are directed with comic efficiency by India
Cooper, even if the final image, Jane drawing a line down the front
of her face with lipstick, is on the heavy-handed side. The main
difficulty with the play is in its use of full-grown actors as
7-year-olds and a 3-year-old. Despite their ardent efforts here,
the actors come across as such ill-assigned performers generally
do, not as children but mentally deficient adults.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   MARATHON 2000 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 23rd annual festival of new one-act plays.
</P>
<P>
   `SERIES C' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Associate producers, Sarah Elkashef and Tom Cavanaugh; Marathon
literary manager, Eileen Myers; production manager, Timothy L.
Gallagher; technical director, Carlo Adinolfi; production stage
manager, Jim Ring. Lighting by Greg MacPherson; sets by Adinolfi;
costumes by Bruce Goodrich; sound by Robert Gould; assistant to the
lighting designer, Matt Staniec. Presented by the Ensemble Studio
Theater, Curt Dempster, artistic director; M. Edgar Rosenblum,
executive director; Jamie Richards, executive producer. At 549 West
52nd Street, Clinton. &QL;
</P>
