<SLUG> BC-RAC-PEGASUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUSAICHI PEGASUS TO MISS BELMONT AFTER INJURING HOOF IN BARN 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the first time in 30 years, the third jewel in
horse racing's Triple Crown will not have the Kentucky Derby winner
or the Preakness winner in the starting gate. Trainer Neil Drysdale
announced Sunday that Fusaichi Pegasus injured his right hoof and
will not race in the Belmont Stakes on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The injury occurred Saturday at 2 p.m. when a blacksmith working
on another horse in Barn 1 at Aqueduct dropped a tool and startled
Fusaichi Pegasus, who was asleep in the back of his stall. The
Derby winner jumped forward, lost his footing, slid into the door
and sustained a cut about the size of a dime in his right front
hoof wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was immediately treated and bandaged and there is no
soreness,'' Drysdale said. ``He'll be fine in five or six days, but
if we trained him for the Belmont it could lead to a larger crack
in his hoof wall. You have to do what is right for the horse.''
</P>
<P>
   The mishap occurred seven days after Frank Stronach and Joe
Orseno _ the owner and trainer of Red Bullet _ decided that their
lightly-raced colt needed to rest after beating Fusaichi Pegasus by
four lengths on a wet and taxing track in the Preakness on May 20.
</P>
<P>
   With no stirring rematch and no inherent drama of a horse trying
to capture the Triple Crown as it had the past three years, the
focus for the Belmont was on the $4 million horse with a penchant
for rodeo-style bucking in the morning and often-displayed
effortless and overpowering speed in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Grade 1 $1 million Belmont is a wide-open race with a
different kind of significance. Silver Charm, Real Quiet and
Charismatic each failed in their bids to become only the 12th horse
in 123 years to sweep the grueling series, which demands the
3-year-old horses to prevail over the varying distances of a mile
and a quarter, a mile and three-sixteenths and the Belmont's mile
and a half in a span of five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But not since 1970, when Dust Commander followed his victory in
the Derby with a ninth-place finish behind the Preakness winner
Personality, has the Belmont been without the winner of either
race. Dust Commander skipped the Belmont and Personality scratched
the day before the race because of injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were intending to run no matter who showed up,'' said Todd
Pletcher, who trains Impeachment, the third-place finisher in both
the Kentucky Derby and Preakness. ``This shows you how tough it is
for horses to run these races. It just makes the Belmont that much
more wide open.''
</P>
<P>
   If Impeachment indeed makes it to the starting gate, he will be
the only one of 19 Derby starters to run in all three Triple Crown
races. So far there are nine probable starters for the Belmont,
though with the loss of the formidable Fusaichi Pegasus as well as
Red Bullet that number may grow, perhaps to as many as 14.
</P>
<P>
   The likely favorite now is the Derby runner-up Aptitude who
skipped the Preakness as did other contenders such as the
fifth-place Derby finisher Wheelaway and the seventh-placed Curule.
The trainer of Aptitude, Bobby Frankel, acknowledged his colt can
run himself into contention for winning year end honors with a
victory in the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Fusaichi Pegasus not running, there's a potential for
more uncertainty about the 3-year-old championship,'' Frankel said.
``Obviously, we would like to make a run for that. But right now,
we're taking things one race at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Triple Crown faces include the Peter Pan winner
Postponed, Globalize, Tahkoda Hills, Appearing Now and Chief
Seattle. It is likely that Commendable, who finished 17th in the
Derby and Hugh Hefner, the sixth-place finisher in the Preakness,
will move from the possible to the probable list, along with
perhaps the Peter Pan runner up Unshaded and anyone else who
believes their horse can go the distance for a rich purse in a
significant race.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: For the first time since 1996 when
Grindstone won the Derby, Louis Quatorze won the Preakness and
Editor's Note won the Belmont, three different horses will have a
victory in the spring's classic races.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale said the owner of Fusaichi Pegasus, Fusao Sekiguchi,
was disappointed by the development but agreed that they hold him
out of the Belmont and point the colt to the Breeders' Cup Classic
in November at Churchill Downs, where he first prompted talk of a
super horse with his impressive victory in the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   The trainer, however, did not seem too shaken Sunday. He will be
inducted into thoroughbred racing's Hall of Fame at Saratoga and is
admired for his cautious and conservative approach to handling
horses. In 1992, he scratched A.P. Indy from the Derby on the
morning of the race when the colt came up with a far more serious
hoof injury. A.P. Indy returned to win the Belmont, as well as the
Breeders' Cup and was named horse of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale acknowledged the first two legs of the Triple Crown had
taken a lot out of Fusaichi Pegasus and was waiting on a workout
scheduled for yesterday before committing the colt to the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this is a blessing in disguise,'' he said. ``The
decision whether or not to run him hadn't been made. Well, he made
the decision himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
