<P>
   RUSSIA-CLINTON (Moscow) _ President Clinton and President
Vladimir Putin of Russia concluded two days of intense talks today
without narrowing their differences on an American proposal to
amend the 28-year-old Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty to allow the
United States to build a new national missile defense system. By
Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-IMMIGRANTS (Miami) _ Before they left Cuba for America in
1994 Joel Ruiz, who is black, and Achmed Valdes, who is white, were
the best of friends. Today, in Miami, the two men live only four
miles apart, not even 15 minutes by car. Yet they are separated by
a far greater distance, one they say they never envisioned back in
Cuba. In ways that are obvious to the black man but far less so to
the white one, they have grown apart in the U.S. because of race.
For the first time, they inhabit a place where the color of their
skin defines the outlines of their lives _ where they live, the
friends they make, how they speak, what they wear, even what they
eat. By Mirta Ojito.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGES-POLITICS (Undated) _ With touchstone issues like death
penalty challenges, school financing and tort reform hanging in the
balance, contests for state judgeships around the country have
become bruising multimillion dollar political affairs that critics
say are threatening the independence of the nation's state courts
as never before. Millions of dollars in campaign contributions are
flowing into races for top state judgeships this year, while
candidates are testing the limits of rules that forbid them from
signaling how they might vote on cases. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
