<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE WINNIE PALMER AWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arnold Palmer had never had such a terrible first round at the
Masters. America's golfer, a four-time winner at Augusta National,
had opened the 1985 Masters with an embarrassing 83, and now, as he
was about to tee off in the second round, somebody asked Winnie
Palmer if her famous husband had considered withdrawing.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she said, ``he considered shooting a 67.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not shoot 67 that day, but he did shoot a smooth par 72
while his wife was shooting down anybody who made the mistake of
even wondering if he might have thought about withdrawing.
</P>
<P>
   That was Winifred Walzer Palmer, the woman behind the man who
put ``charge'' into the golf vocabulary, the woman who died last
Nov. 20 of abdominal cancer at age 65.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arnold has had his share of good fortune in life,'' his lawyer
and agent, Mark McCormack, has said, ``and the best fortune of all
was marrying Winnie. From the beginning, she brought to Arnold an
ability to cope with the kind of problems he never knew existed.
She was astute, discerning and a realist.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years she was wife and secretary and business consultant.
She handled the family finances. She balanced the books, paid the
bills, made the travel arrangements, mailed the entry blanks and
devoted her entire attention to one goal: making sure that her
husband's mind was free to concentrate on his golf.''
</P>
<P>
   She also devoted herself to the Arnold Palmer Hospital for Women
and Children in Orlando, Fla., and to their hometown Latrobe, Pa.,
hospital, library and St. Vincent's College.
</P>
<P>
   In her memory, the Metropolitan Golf Writers Association
instituted the Winnie Palmer Award for ``an individual in golf who
has consistently given their time, energy and enthusiasm to those
less fortunate.'' At its national awards dinner Monday night at the
Westchester Marriott, the first recipient of the bronze sculpture
will be Barbara Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbara and Jack have been our close friends for many years,''
Arnold Palmer said. ``Winnie would be as pleased as I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Nicklaus has raised more than $10 million for various
charities, including the Children's Hospital of Columbus (Ohio),
the American Cancer Society, the Fellowship of Christian Athletes
and the Chi Chi Rodriguez Youth Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winnie would be embarrassed by the award,'' said Donald
``Doc'' Giffin, the longtime aide-de-camp to Arnold Palmer, ``but
she would be delighted that Barbara's getting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Marty Walzer, Winnie's brother, remembered the Saturday morning
in 1954 he noticed his parents and 19-year-old sister talking
quietly in their Coopersburg, Pa., home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 13,'' he said, ``old enough to know that just from the
way they were talking, it was serious. The previous Tuesday night,
Arnold, who had just won the U.S. Amateur, had met Winnie at a
party for a golf tournament at Shawnee-on-Delaware, and now she was
telling my mother and father that on Friday night Arnold had
proposed to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, just before Thanksgiving, they eloped. They
were married in Falls Church, Va., near the home of Arnold's
sister, Cheech.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother was all for it,'' Marty Walzer said, ``but Dad had
reservations. He came around eventually, but after Winnie and
Arnold had their two daughters, Peggy and Amy, I remember Dad
telling Arnold, `You wait and see, you'll feel the same way I
did.'''
</P>
<P>
   In Arnold's rookie year on the PGA Tour, he and Winnie traveled
from tournament to tournament with a trailer hitched to his coral
pink Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the Masters,'' Marty Walzer said, ``the trailer park was
next to a drive-in movie. I sat outside the trailer and watched the
movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after that, Palmer's charisma put him centerstage as a
golfer. Then he developed into a multimillion-dollar golf
conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winnie never lost her perspective; the money never changed
her,'' Marty Walzer, who owns the Pine Barn Inn in Danville, Pa.,
said. ``She was as comfortable with Mamie Eisenhower and Barbara
Bush as she was with my baker. She was so accommodating to
everyone, so genuine. I don't think she had an enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Winnie also knew how to surprise her husband.
</P>
<P>
   On his 37th birthday, the doorbell rang in their Latrobe home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Answer it, Arn,'' she said. ``It's the TV repairman.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Arnold opened the door, he saw a golf pal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could you put up an old friend for the night?'' Dwight D.
Eisenhower asked.
</P>
<P>
   Winnie Palmer had arranged for Arnold's jet to pick up the
former president at his Gettsyburg, Pa., farm as well as taking
care of most of the other details of her famous husband's birthday
party.
</P>
<P>
   That, too, was Winnie Palmer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 1855EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
