<DOCNO> NYT20000604.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4270 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-NYT &LR;      06-04 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAFELNIKOV AND SANCHEZ-VICARIO RALLY TO ADVANCE IN FRENCH OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Sunday was a day for proving points while winning them
at the French Open.
</P>
<P>
   Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario made it clear that, despite all the red
clay that has passed under her quick feet, she is still not to be
taken lightly. Venus Williams, Monica Seles and Chanda Rubin showed
that, despite injuries and occasional bouts of self-doubt, they
still belong in the second week of a Grand Slam event. And Yevgeny
Kafelnikov, despite a visit from the trainer, proved that foot
blisters do not always result in an upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's normal, normal circumstances for the professional tennis
player when you have blisters on your feet, and it's a matter of
treatment I think,'' said the fourth-seeded Kafelnikov
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Andre Agassi faded meekly away after developing the
same condition against Karol Kucera in the second round. But
Sunday, Kafelnikov kept plugging and sliding away in the fourth
round, coming 2 points from defeat before finding a way to overcome
Fernando Vicente, 5-7, 6-3, 5-7, 7-6 (4), 8-6.
</P>
<P>
   The day's finest comeback, however, belonged to Sanchez-Vicario,
the indefatigable Spanish veteran who trailed Austrian baseliner
Barbara Schett by 0-6, 1-4 before rallying for a 0-6, 6-4, 6-2
victory and reaching the 13th French Open quarterfinal of her
career. She has won the title here three times and, despite the
fact that a few French fans earned her wrath last week for booing
her for drop-shotting too often, this remains her favorite event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still a very competitive woman; I still know that you have
to play much better than me to beat me,'' said the 28-year-old
Sanchez-Vicario.
</P>
<P>
   For her efforts, Sanchez-Vicario earned a date in Tuesday's
quarterfinals with Williams, who flirted with trouble late in the
opening set against Anke Huber before taking firm control and
winning, 7-6 (4), 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling 80 percent now, and before I was about 50
percent,'' said Williams, who missed the first four months of the
season because of tendinitis in both wrists. ``I'm still making too
many errors for my taste, still inconsistent, but it's better every
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The other women's quarterfinals, to be played on Tuesday, will
match top-seeded Martina Hingis against Rubin; the third-seeded
Seles against No. 6 Mary Pierce, and the No. 5 Conchita Martinez
against Marta Marrero, a fellow Spaniard.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis had to shake off a disastrous second set to defeat
Ruxandra Dragomir, 6-3, 0-6, 6-1. Rubin, a Lousianan who was ranked
in the top 10 in 1996 before a serious hand injury knocked her
back, defeated Natasha Zvereva, 6-4, 7-5. Seles, suffering from
sinus problems and bronchitis but not from a lack of power or
confidence, defeated Amelie Mauresmo of France 7-5, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce overwhelmed Asa Carlsson, 6-4, 6-0. Martinez beat Ai
Sugiyama, 5-7, 6-3, 6-4, and Marrero, a 17-year-old qualifier
playing in her first Grand Slam event, beat Rossana De los Rios,
4-6, 6-0, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when qualifiers had no place in the women's
game, but the depth and suspense is clearly increasing. A year ago,
Barbara Schwartz became the first women's qualifier to reach the
quarterfinals here. At last year's Wimbledon, a record three
qualifiers reached the fourth round. The 108th-ranked Marrero and
151st-ranked De los Rios reached the fourth round here this year,
but while De los Rios walked off the court an exhausted loser, she
could also be proud. In 1994, the Paraguayan took a five-year break
from the game to get married and have a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to play tennis again because one fine morning, I
woke up feeling like I wanted to do it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune has not often been Seles' friend in recent years. But
she arrived at this French Open in a fine frame of mind and,
despite her sinus problems that are requiring her to take
antibiotics, in very respectable shape. She needed to be against
Mauresmo's probing groundstrokes, but though Seles double-faulted
on her first match point, she got the benefit of a net cord on her
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really for me today the main thing was just to stay mentally
strong out there, because I had to fight so many things,'' Seles
said of facing the popular Mauresmo. ``It wasn't just like a
regular tennis match.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd may not be quite so partisan when she faces Pierce,
who represents France but now spends most of her time in the United
States. Pierce beat Seles, 6-1, 6-1, on her way to the title in
Hilton Head in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just see if I can rise up to the occasion; it's going to
be up to me,'' said Seles, who missed five months of action and
this year's Australian Open because of a stress fracture in her
foot.
</P>
<P>
   A tiny stress fracture in Rubin's right hand changed the course
of her career. In 1996, she reached the semifinals in Australia
and, at just 21, was considered the next great American player. But
she played little the rest of the year while doctors tried to
diagnose her problem. She had not been back in the quarterfinals of
a Slam again until now.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knows fear now,'' said her coach, Benny Sims. ``From age
12 to 21, she didn't know any. What was there to fear? She was
black, pretty, a millionaire. I see her getting her feet back under
her now.''
</P>
<P>
   Spaniards generally have little difficulty with their footing on
clay. Along with the three women who reached the quarterfinals
Sunday, two Spanish men, Alex Corretja and Juan Carlos Ferrero also
made it to the final eight. Corretja, the No. 10 seed, defeated the
Swiss teen-ager Roger Federer in straight sets. Ferrero, seeded
16th in his first French Open, eliminated Mark Philippoussis, 6-2,
6-2, 3-6, 6-3. The two Davis Cup teammates, who will face the
United States on clay in the semifinal in Santander in July, will
face each other next.
</P>
<P>
   Kafelnikov will face No. 5 Gustavo Kuerten, who defeated
11th-seeded Nicolas Lapentti, 6-3, 6-4, 7-6 (4).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
