<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MOST BRAVES JUST WANT RELIEF FROM ROCKER 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In their quest for serenity and maturity, the Atlanta
Braves do not permit music to be blared in their clubhouse. The
Braves are one of the classy organizations in sports, and plan to
remain so.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a chemistry problem on this club, they've always
been able to cut out the cancer,'' said Chipper Jones, choosing his
words calmly and precisely.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday afternoon, throughout this elite locker room, there was
the silent scream of the Turner Field Men's Chorus, probably close
to 24 inner voices shouting in unison: Get this guy out of here!
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker probably blew his career in Atlanta Sunday in
spectacularly oafish fashion. It is hard to imagine he will be on
the Braves' roster when they travel to Shea Stadium for games from
June 30 to July 2.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are the Braves sick of having to discuss his antics,
they also see him as a threat to their safety. Kevin Millwood, hit
by a flying object from an assassin-fan in Los Angeles, does not
want to stand near Rocker anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth, neither do I,'' Chipper Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   They give the impression they do not want to dress near him
either. Sunday, before playing their dominators from New York, the
Braves had to deal with another outburst from the troubled man.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, who got himself in trouble from a vicious stream of bile
against gays, people with AIDS, welfare mothers, people who speak
foreign languages in the U.S., minorities and other urban types,
spotted Jeff Pearlman, the reporter from Sports Illustrated who
wrote the article quoting him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't over between us,'' Pearlman quoted Rocker as
saying. ``Do you know what I could do to you?''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker then demanded that two stadium security agents not allow
Pearlman into the clubhouse. The episode took no more than two
minutes, and nobody was hurt, but there was the stunning
realization that Rocker has even less control of himself in person
than on the mound _ 25 walks in 18 innings, including Sunday's
shaky inning in the 7-6 loss to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   John Schuerholz, the Braves' executive vice president and
general manager, released a statement that said, ``We immediately
began to address the matter internally and are continuing to do
so,'' adding, ``We will do everything in our power to insure that
similar incidents do not occur in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   There is only one way to guarantee that. Tom Glavine, who has
been here the longest, said he is not a psychiatrist, which tells a
lot about what the players are thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Major League Baseball accomplished nothing with the
15-game suspension to start the season. The commissioner's office
merely told Rocker to stay away from work but never got through to
his heart and soul. His parents, who are said to be good people,
have not been able to affect his hair-trigger impulses.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Rocker gets plenty of support. What kind of a
signal is it that management permits the display of the Georgia
flag with the Confederate emblem directly in front of the Braves'
dugout while the National Anthem is being played?
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Yankees were stunned to see the vast majority of
Braves' fans roar when Rocker came running in from the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's home,'' said Brian Jordan, an African-American, a college
man, a leader in the clubhouse, either meaning Rocker plays for the
home team, or appeals to a nasty strain of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Rocker does not seem to have many fans left in his
own clubhouse. If the players thought this was some news-media
invention, they had the chance to scream at the reporters Sunday.
Instead, they sighed when asked why the leaders have not warned
Rocker to keep quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been done already,'' Millwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the Braves _ ``white, black, Hispanic''_ had given
Rocker a second chance. Alluding to his own history of domestic
problems, Jones said, ``I've provided some distractions myself from
time to time, and I'm not going to throw stones at John for saying
things that may have been politically incorrect.''
</P>
<P>
   That view is reasonably pragmatic, but then Jones admitted:
``Yeah, it's a pain in the butt for 24 other guys. It's something
we don't want to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones heard about Rocker's confrontation and said: ``He may feel
he was misrepresented. The professional thing would have been to
walk away. I haven't seen John do that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   One locker over, Jordan said: ``He's going to have to give this
up sooner or later. The Braves will make do, with or without John
Rocker. The general manager is too good. Bobby Cox is too good a
manager. This is something John is going to have to deal with. I'm
sure it will be soon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made his bed, now he's going to have to lie in it,''
Jordan said. ``Geez, you only get nine lives. He's using them up
pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves gave every impression they wanted John Rocker's life
with the Braves to be over in less than four weeks _ before they go
to New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
