<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4280 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-YANKS-BRAVES-NYT &LR;      06-04 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES' RIVERA SAVES GAME WON BY BELLINGER'S PINCH-HIT HOME RUN 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After seven innings Sunday, the Yankees' lead over the
Braves was one run and Manager Joe Torre was absolutely determined
to hold it, having seen the Yankees blow three leads on Saturday.
There would be no middlemen, no finessing of the bullpen, no
manipulation of matchups. Six outs remained and Torre summoned
Mariano Rivera to get them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it very badly,'' Torre said later, cheerfully, after
Rivera navigated through the final two innings, with difficulty,
clinging to a 7-6 victory. Clay Bellinger gave the Yankees the lead
with a pinch-hit home run in the top of the seventh in his first
at-bat since May 27.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees (30-22) took two of three games from the team with
the best record in baseball and left with the self-respect that had
been stripped during Saturday's miserable defeat. Torre berated his
players in a meeting immediately following that game, angry over
their play.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of his rant might be construed as that of a venting
manager, but some players thought Torre's outburst was more
calculated than that. He singled out a handful of perceived
offenders who occupy different sectors of the roster: Roger
Clemens, a pitcher destined for the Hall of Fame; Jason Grimsley, a
middle reliever; and Bernie Williams, the cleanup hitter, center
fielder and highest-paid Yankee. If Clemens and Williams were being
chastised, others perceived, then everybody has to be accountable,
and Williams and Clemens seemed to understand what Torre was trying
to accomplish. ``We're all family,'' Torre said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   What Torre was trying to convey, his extended family understood,
was that they were not meeting their own standards; they were not
playing to their own capabilities, having lost 14 of 23 games.
``We're better than that,'' Torre told his players.
</P>
<P>
   They responded with intense desperation Sunday, Chuck Knoblauch
forcing a 10-pitch walk to open the game and ignite a three-run
burst, Tino Martinez driving in the last run with the first of his
two doubles. The Yankees scored again in the third, the fourth and
the fifth, though Paul O'Neill and Jorge Posada were out of the
lineup. And Torre thought that Andy Pettitte was pushing himself.
</P>
<P>
   But Pettitte's arm was not responding, and he could not command
the flight of the ball. The Yankees led, 4-0, in the third and
Pettitte surrendered two runs in the third. The Yankees scored a
run in the fourth; the Braves did, too. Scott Brosius slugged a
homer in the top of the fifth, Atlanta matched that in the bottom
of the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Javy Lopez and Reggie Sanders bashed back-to-back homers in the
bottom of the sixth inning, tying the game at 6-6. It felt like
Saturday all over again, the blown leads, the inability to contain
the Atlanta offense. Torre felt his team had fought, battled. He
wanted this game, badly.
</P>
<P>
   Bellinger batted for Pettitte with two outs in the seventh, just
hoping to reach base. There was no reason to anticipate a home run;
Bellinger rarely plays, and no Yankee had hit a pinch-hit homer
since May 29, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Mulholland threw a fastball, a strike. He threw another
fastball, same speed, same spot, and Bellinger slammed it, knowing
on contact it would clear the left-field fence. He jogged around
the bases, head down, stifling his smile until he reached the
dugout, where teammates gave him high fives and hit him on the
helmet.
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley pitched the bottom of the seventh, striking out Brian
Jordan. Two innings remained. Torre turned to the pitching coach,
Mel Stottlemyre. ``What about Mo for two?'' Torre asked, using
Rivera's nickname. Stottlemyre smiled slightly when speaking.
``It's very tempting,'' he replied to Torre.
</P>
<P>
   What Stottlemyre did not say was no, and with that, Torre's
decision was made. He wanted his closer, right then, one inning
earlier than normal. ``We fought hard,'' Torre said. ``I didn't
want it to slip away.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera retired the first two batters in the eighth easily. Bobby
Bonilla, a switch-hitter, batted for Walt Weiss _ right-handed,
against the right-handed Rivera, figuring it would be easier to
combat Rivera's cut fastball that way. He drove the ball to the
right-field corner, and catcher Chris Turner and Torre and others
thought it would land safely.
</P>
<P>
   But Shane Spencer motored in pursuit, extended his glove, caught
the ball and took two more steps before bouncing off the fence.
Rivera and others waited in front of the dugout to congratulate
him.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera got two easy outs in the ninth. Then Andruw Jones
singled. Rivera jammed Chipper Jones with a cutter, but Jones
looped the ball over Brosius' head. Andruw Jones reached third and
Chipper Jones stopped at first, ensuring that Rivera would have to
pitch to the next hitter, Andres Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if jeopardy transformed into adrenaline in Rivera's
fastball: Turner could feel the velocity increase. Galarraga took a
big swing, fouling the ball straight back: 96 miles per hour, radar
guns flashed. Another fastball, another foul, straight back: 97
mph. Rivera threw a ball outside. Turner called for a four-seam
fastball, a high fastball. Galarraga swung and missed the 97-mph
pitch, and the Yankees spilled out of their dugout to congratulate
their closer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 1942EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
