<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4281 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-SPERIGLIO-NYT &LR;      06-04 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SPERIGLIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILO SPERIGLIO, 62, NOTED SHAMUS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Milo A. Speriglio, a tireless private detective with an
unquenchable thirst for publicity and an obsession with the death
of Marilyn Monroe, died April 30 at his home in Encino, Calif. He
was 62.
</P>
<P>
   He died of lung cancer, his wife, Patricia, said.
</P>
<P>
   Speriglio, the director of Nick Harris Detectives Inc. of Van
Nuys, Calif., unabashedly modeled himself on the fictional gumshoes
Sam Spade and Philip Marlowe and was inspired to become a private
eye by the television series ``Peter Gunn,'' which ran from 1958 to
1961. He wore gold chains, cracked wise, smoked cigarettes and had
a penchant for turning up at murder sites where television crews
might be expected, notably that of Nicole Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Speriglio necessarily came across as some sort of
outsize Runyonesque character. ``Milo is half the size of Cannon,
not nearly as handsome as Mannix and a lot smarter than Barnaby
Jones,'' The Los Angeles Times reported in 1976. ``He's a quiet,
soft-spoken guy, on the small side with glasses. He could pass for
a bank clerk. But he's handled more cases than all the television
sleuths combined, about 35,000 over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of a 20-year investigation he undertook on his
own beginning in 1972, Speriglio wrote three books about Marilyn
Monroe, whom he asserted was murdered in 1962 by the Mafia, at the
behest of President John F. Kennedy and his father, Joseph Kennedy
Sr. His accusations led to the opening of police files on her death
and calls for a grand jury investigation.
</P>
<P>
   After a censored version of the FBI's file on the case was
turned over to the Los Angeles County district attorney's office in
1982, prosecutors endorsed the original conclusion: that the
actress committed suicide. They said there was no need for further
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the evidence available to us,'' District Attorney
John Van de Kamp said at the time, ``it appears that her death
could have been a suicide or a result of an accidental drug
overdose.''
</P>
<P>
   But Speriglio continued the hunt. He wrote two more books about
Monroe's death, which he insisted added more evidence to support
his controversial contentions. He said his last book on the
subject, ``Crypt 33: The Saga of Marilyn Monroe _ The Final Word,''
which was written with Adela Gregory and published by Birch Lane
Press in 1993, should have silenced his critics and led to arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing left to tell,'' he said in a review he wrote
of his own book for the Amazon.com Web site in September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Though most of Speriglio's cases over 41 years involved normal
investigative fare, like spying on unfaithful spouses, he also
handled several other famous cases. One involved the death in 1959
of George Reeves, who played Superman in the 1950s television
series.
</P>
<P>
   The actor's mother disputed the official verdict of suicide.
Speriglio concluded that the bullets that killed Reeves were fired
from at least 16 inches away, and his opinion became a significant
part of a debate that still continues. The case, however, was never
reopened.
</P>
<P>
   Speriglio was born in Greenwich, Conn., and moved to California
when he was 3. He once told a reporter that his first case involved
a hunt for a missing panther when he was 16. A picture of him armed
with a baseball bat appeared in the local newspaper, and other high
school students began calling him Panther Boy.
</P>
<P>
   He briefly worked as a rock 'n' roll disc jockey, calling
himself Mad Milo. He then held other jobs and took criminology
courses before, his wife said, he ``burst'' onto the investigative
scene.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by his daughters,
Janelle Speriglio of San Diego, and Holly Skodis of Burbank, and a
sister, Amelia Speriglio of Torrance, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Speriglio's genius for getting publicity was demonstrated when a
telephone company in 1975 assigned a dial-a-Santa service a number
just one digit different from the detective agency's. A few
children called the agency by mistake, and word got out that the
private eyes were more fun than the ``real'' Santa. Thousands more
children called after the story became news.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times described the Christmas scene: ``For a
famous detective, Speriglio cut a bit of a mousy figure in build,
curly hair, a gold bracelet on his wrist and an almost bashful
smile on his lips. He wore a short-sleeved red shirt and a
cone-shaped Santa's cap with a cotton ball dangling over one ear.''
</P>
<P>
   Speriglio, who believed all publicity with the correct spelling
of one's name was good publicity, explained, ``If you're going to
go undercover and play the role of someone, you have to dress the
part.''
</P>
<P>
   Speriglio's agency kept the nearly-Santa number for years.
</P>
<P>
   Another scheme by Speriglio that got a lot of holiday publicity
was the Finder of Lost Loves Reunion, which promised in the late
1980s to reunite three people with their lost loves _ by Christmas,
of course.
</P>
<P>
   As Speriglio told it, you could almost hear the ping of the
heartstrings. ``A widower in his 60s here in town asked us to find
his childhood sweetheart _ he knew only her maiden name,'' he said.
``It turned out they lived a few blocks apart. She was a widow and
they fell in love again and were married, and I was the best man.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also the time Speriglio promised to find Nicole
Simpson's killer, for whom O.J. Simpson's defense team was
incidentally offering a $500,000 reward.
</P>
<P>
   ``If only I knew some voodoo that would make those trees talk,''
he said as he cruised the leafy streets of the Simpsons'
neighborhood with a Washington Post reporter. ``I do not believe
O.J. did it. Whoever did it deserves to hang. I cannot let this
woman down.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was Speriglio's two-decade interest in Marilyn Monroe's
death that received the most attention. His offer of $10,000 for
her lost red diary was widely noted, if unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Always, he kept his main focus and was hardly shy about saying
so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a fan of Marilyn's,'' he pronounced on a book
promotion tour. ``I haven't seen her movies. And I don't read books
about her unless they mention me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 1950EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
