u s BC-TV-SPORTS-PARALYMPICS     06-04 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-PARALYMPICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET TV COVERAGE OF PARALYMPICS IS PLANNED 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the Summer Olympics in Sydney, NBC Sports will
carry 161 hours and MSNBC and CNBC will telecast 276{ more hours on
cable.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, also from Sydney, Wemedia.com will Webcast at least
100 hours of the Paralympics, which are contested by disabled
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   This is not prime-time television, but Wemedia Corp., which owns
the Internet site and publishes We, a slick magazine for disabled
people from its downtown Manhattan office, is capitalizing on
advances in streaming video to bring the Paralympics to computers
from Oct. 18-29. After the Paralympics, the company plans to
Webcast two events a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to create access and mobility to watch the games
for people nobody have cared about, and make it free to the
world,'' Cary Fields, Wemedia's president, said. ``The computer
makes the disabilities disappear. It's the ultimate enabler.''
</P>
<P>
   Wemedia's plans for the 18-sport Paralympics are ambitious:
three separate daily feeds of 12 hours of live events, feature and
studio coverage, from 7:30 p.m. to 7:30 a.m. Eastern, which would
be repeated for the next 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Track and field and swimming and velodrome cycling could all
be starting at once and you can go to one for two or three hours
then switch to another,'' said Rick Gentile, the executive producer
of Wemedia Sports, who served in the same position at CBS Sports.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to shifting between three video feeds, there will be
a second screen offering a continuous flow of accompanying
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a blank slate _ an entire network to program,'' said
Gentile, who was a top programming or production executive during
CBS's telecasts of the 1992, 1994 and 1998 Winter Olympics. ``And
with three feeds, we'd better be good. A lot will depend on our Web
site boys to synchronize it all together.''
</P>
<P>
   Wemedia tested its technology in April at the Paralympic sailing
trials and plans more tests next month at the track and field and
swimming trials. The quality of the Webcast depends on the
capabilities of the computers receiving it as well as on the
equipment Wemedia uses to transmit the video. Nonetheless, the
quality of streaming video in general seems to improve on an almost
daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few weeks ago, I would have said TV is TV, but this is
different,'' Gentile said. ``What works on TV doesn't necessarily
work on the Web. Pictures and graphics are smaller. But on a
laptop, where you'll have one box with a moving pictures, we can
synchronize graphics in a way that makes this unique.''
</P>
<P>
   Wemedia's primary goal is to expand the presence of the
underexposed Paralympics _ and bring new members to its web site,
which will add a much larger sports news and information component
today. But it also intends to spread the gospel about the
extraordinary skills of the thousands of athletes who are blind,
paraplegic, amputees, mentally retarded or have cerebral palsy.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Huebner, executive director of the United States
Association of Blind Athletes, doubted the Wemedia would face a
shortage of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 300 to 400 local, regional and national events within
our own organization,'' he said. ``Wemedia is helping parents and
kids find out what events are out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Pincus, the vice president of content for Wemedia Sports,
added: ``There are basketball tournaments, rugby, tennis
tournaments, sailing regattas, skiing and expedition-adventure
events. There's no question we'll have enough to do two events a
month.''
</P>
<P>
   Olympic viewers are accustomed to network features about
athletes that often strain to find the obstacles, family tragedies
or melodramatic woes that formed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here every story smacks you in the face,'' Gentile said.
``They're all remarkable. At the dock where the athletes get on the
boats, many have to be picked up or hoisted into the boats. Then
you see 30 empty wheelchairs and prosthetic arms and legs on the
dock.''
</P>
<P>
   To advocates of the disabled, Wemedia's sports strategy fills a
long overdue void and will provide broad recognition for their
athleticism .
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy to think only disabled people will watch disabled
events,'' said Deborah Bonsack, executive director of America's
Athletes with Disabilities, which promoted 190 disabled sports
events last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to think of disabled sports as sports played by
people with different physical compositions.''
</P>
<P>
   If Wemedia finds viewer success in Webcasting the Paralympics
and other events, she said: ``Folks will have a shift in opinion.
You'll hear people stop and say, `How does that amputee swimmer do
that?'''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Imparato, president of the American Association of People
with Disabilities, said: ``Too often, the public view of people
with disabilities is a charity model, that we need to raise money
for them. But the Paralympics and Special Olympics show disabled
people achieving well beyond what people with disabilities are
supposed to be able to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He cautioned that many disabled people _ as well as those who
are able-bodied _ cannot afford a computer and cannot view the
Webcast of the Paralympics.
</P>
<P>
   But with the U.S. television rights, on top of its world Web
rights deal, Wemedia has a TV strategy. It is seeking a cable
partner to for daily reports, and a broadcaster for a
post-Paralympics special.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the Webcast to enhance the broadcasts,'' said Jay
Rosenstein, the vice president of programming for Wemedia Sports,
``and the broadcasts to make the public aware of the Webcast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
