<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4284 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DEFIANT-JUDGE-NYT &LR;      06-04 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEFIANT-JUDGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICON OF RELIGIOUS RIGHT ATTEMPTS TO TRADE IN ON HIS RENOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (With JUDGES-POLITICS) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHILDERSBURG, Ala. _ Three years ago, Judge Roy S. Moore became
an icon of the Christian conservative movement by defying the order
of another Alabama judge that he remove the Ten Commandments from
the wall behind his bench and stop opening court sessions with a
prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Today, proudly unrepentant, Moore of the Circuit Court in
Gadsden is trading on his renown to run for chief justice of the
Alabama Supreme Court, the top judicial post in the state. And days
before the Republican primary on Tuesday, leading political
observers in Alabama said he just might win.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's campaign against three Republican opponents is the
latest battle for party supremacy between the religious right and
the business community in Alabama. Last October, Christian
conservatives scored a major success by voting down the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more significantly, a win by Moore would provide strong
confirmation that there are places in the country, and Alabama has
been the epicenter, where voters are simply fed up with the breadth
of the separation between church and state.
</P>
<P>
   Moore taps into that discontent by arguing that many Americans,
and activist judges in particular, have misinterpreted the founding
fathers' intent. He contends that the removal of God from public
life has contributed to school shootings, an expansion of gay
rights and other examples of what he sees as moral decay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've forgotten that judges shouldn't be running around trying
to form society into something they think it should be,'' he told
members of the Kiwanis Club here last Thursday. ``They've taken
something away from us that is the most valuable thing that our
forefathers held dear, the freedom to worship God, publicly,
privately, in the manner we choose.''
</P>
<P>
   But Moore, 53, does not stop at promoting himself as a strict
constructionist. Man's law, he insists, is deeply rooted in God's
law as revealed by the Holy Scriptures. Furthermore, he says, his
study of Washington, Jefferson and Madison has convinced him that
the United States is a Christian nation that was founded on
Christian principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not say it's a Christian nation by establishment,''
he said in an interview. ``In other words, you do not have to
worship God as a Christian. But that did not mean that our
principles, our foundation, our business organizations, our
fraternal and civic organizations, were not founded by Christian
principles and that Christian principles did not govern the laws of
our land.''
</P>
<P>
   Such assertions appall those who believe the First Amendment
provides absolute protection for religious minorities against the
potential tyranny of the majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judge Moore, if he's elected, must understand that it's the
Constitution and not the Bible that governs Alabama,'' said Barry
W. Lynn, executive director of Americans United for Separation of
Church and State, which is based in Washington. ``His understanding
of the Constitution can only be described as bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   It is telling, however, that none of Moore's Republican
opponents have tried to depict him as extreme. Indeed, Associate
Justice Harold See of the state Supreme Court, who is also trying
to move to the chief justice's chair, has used television
advertisements to promote his own work, while a law professor, in
researching Moore's defense in the Ten Commandments case.
</P>
<P>
   Both public and private polls have consistently shown Moore with
a lead but falling below the majority needed to avoid a runoff. In
addition to See, his opponents are Judge Wayne Thorn of the Circuit
Court in Birmingham and Judge Pam Baschab of the Court of Criminal
Appeals in Montgomery. The winner will face the Democratic
candidate, Sharon Yates, in November.
</P>
<P>
   Judicial elections in Alabama are highly partisan, often pitting
business-minded Republicans who favor restrictions on tort claims
against consumer-minded Democrats who have the backing of trial
lawyers. Republicans currently hold a 5-4 majority on the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   See is the clear choice of the state's Republican political and
business leadership. He received $150,000 from the Business Council
of Alabama last month, the largest of his $1.14 million in
contributions, and has made heavy purchases of television
advertising. Moore has raised $260,000, enough to run a few
advertisements on cable television.
</P>
<P>
   Moore has received a boost, however, from Thorn, who hopes to
squeeze into a runoff by attacking See for abandoning his seat in
order to run for chief justice. If See wins, Thorn points out, the
state's Democratic governor, Donald Siegelman, would appoint a
successor, presumably a Democrat who could reverse the partisan
majority on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Flynt, a historian at Auburn University, said he expected
Moore to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``An awful lot of the Republicans in Alabama,'' Flynt said,
``are George Wallace Democrats who crossed over in the culture wars
_ women need to stay in their place, we need a restoration of
morality in schools _ and Roy Moore really resonates with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some of See's supporters said this week that they expected
Moore to finish first on Tuesday, though not with a majority.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's primary political assets are his name recognition and
his reputation as a man of conviction. In 1995, the American Civil
Liberties Union sued him in an effort to remove the Ten
Commandments and end his courtroom prayers. It took nearly three
years, but by 1998 both a federal judge and the state Supreme Court
had thrown out the lawsuit on technical grounds without resolving
the underlying issues.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, a circuit court judge had ordered Moore to
remove the tablets and cease the prayers. Moore refused, becoming a
hero to thousands of Alabamians who held rallies in his defense. At
one point, Fob James Jr., then the governor, threatened to call out
the National Guard to defend the Ten Commandments against
court-ordered removal.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's admirers clearly like his principles and the ramrod
style he developed as a West Point cadet, a military policeman in
Vietnam and a local prosecutor. He footnotes his speeches, and his
casual conversations, with memorized recitations of historical
tracts _ letters from Madison, writings by John Locke _ almost
always to support his proposition that the founders recognized
government's subordination to God.
</P>
<P>
   In his appearances last week, Moore did not hesitate to
criticize the courts for legalizing abortion and for pushing
Vermont lawmakers to allow gay unions. Without a moral and legal
standard based on Scripture, he said, the logical extension will be
laws allowing unions between ``two men and four women,'' or between
``a sheep and a man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me ask you this,'' he said. ``Are you going to pay your
tax money to support a man and a sheep on welfare? Hmmm?''
</P>
<P>
   Moore is also something of a poet. ``While truth and law were
founded upon the God of all creation, man through law now denies
him and calls it separation,'' he said, closing his Kiwanis speech.
``Children are told they can't pray in school and they teach them
evolution. Why can't they see the fear of God is the only true
solution?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
