<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A CALAMITY HURTS INTERLEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This may be viewed some day as the game that killed
interleague play. Oh, it will be tough to commit that deed, as
justifiable and as merciful as it might be, as long as Bud Selig is
commissioner. On the other hand, if Selig had been at Shea Stadium
Sunday and watched the Mets be humiliated, 15-5, by the worst team
in the major leagues, he might have different thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the potential excitement of a Mets-Yankees series,
there is a game like the one at Shea, where 43,610 fans, including
many innocent, impressionable youngsters, were subjected to a
horror show that in movie theaters would have been rated R, if not
NC-17, and on television would have carried a warning for viewers
to watch at their discretion.
</P>
<P>
   The only surprise was that the team creating most of the
viewer-discretion material was the one that is supposed to be good,
not the team they played, the one with the worst record in Major
League Baseball, the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby J. Jones, perhaps the most critical member of the Mets'
starting rotation, was the primary perpetrator, but he had help, a
lot of it, from his friends, though with friends like these, who
needs enemies?
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, Jones gave up home runs on consecutive
pitches to two players who had not previously hit a home run this
season. One, in fact, Esteban Yan, the Devil Rays' starting
pitcher, had never batted in 10 years as a professional and hit his
home run on the first pitch he had ever seen at that end of the 60
feet 6 inches between the mound and home plate.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning, Jones walked two batters in loading the
bases and setting the stage for his departure and a five-run flurry
that turned the game in the Devil Rays' favor.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning, Kurt Abbott and Robin Ventura, the men who
man the left side of the Mets' infield, squandered opportunities to
get double plays, adding agony to the five-run flurry.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth inning, Rich Rodriguez hit two batters sandwiched
around an Abbott error, loading the bases and leading to another
five-run outburst, Bubba Trammell delivering the coup de grace with
a pinch-hit three-run home run against Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Now the defending World Series champion Yankees and the
perennial National League champion Atlanta Braves did not play two
sparklers Saturday and Sunday, and teams have inflicted any number
of awful intraleague games on the paying public. But if the
commissioner and his cohorts are going to try to sell interleague
games other than the obvious matchups, they are going to have to
come up with something better than Sunday's game at Shea.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Mets are going to wind up in playoff games in
October, they are going to have to come up with someone better than
Jones for their starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since he's been back, he's had some real strong innings,''
Manager Bobby Valentine said, grasping for something positive to
say about Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Since he returned from a monthlong stay on the disabled list
with a strained calf muscle, Jones has started four games, emerging
with one victory, one loss, two no-decisions and a 7.59 earned run
average. That ERA beats the 16.20 he concocted in his three
pre-injury starts, but it is nothing to boast about.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the Devil Rays said Jones had nothing Sunday, noting
that he struggled to get on top of the ball and suggesting that the
right-hander will have little chance for success if he continues
pitching that way. He said Jones looked like he was pitching hurt.
Valentine said that with 100 or so games left, Jones has time to
get it together. ``I'm confident he'll get it back,'' the manager
said.
</P>
<P>
   But consider the record of the pitcher in whom the Mets have
placed their faith. Three years ago almost to the day, Jones gained
his 10th victory in his 12th start of the 1997 season, reaching a
double-digit victory total faster than any Mets pitcher before him,
faster than Tom Seaver, faster than Dwight Gooden, faster than
Jerry Koosman, David Cone, Frank Viola. Since then, however, Jones
has compiled an 18-21 record.
</P>
<P>
   Warming up Sunday, Jones said, he had ``probably the best
fastball I've had this year.'' In the second inning, he threw a
fastball on a 1-2 count to Felix Martinez, and the Devil Rays' new
shortstop hit the ball over the right-field fence for two runs.
Jones threw a fastball on his next pitch, too, and the opposing
pitcher, in his maiden stance at the plate, hit the ball over the
left-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martinez's home run was missed location,'' Jones said. ``I
tried to go fastball in and left it out over the plate. The pitch
to Yan, he hadn't had a bat before. You try to make a good pitch.
Anyone with a bat in their hands is dangerous. I knew when he hit
it that it was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The day only deteriorated from there.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball officials have not completed next season's schedule.
They can still change their minds and abandon interleague play.
Sure, the Mets and the Yankees create anticipation and excitement,
but if the Mets are going to play like they did Sunday, let the
National League's woeful members, the Phillies, for example,
benefit. Charity begins at home. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
