<HEADER>
A4287 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WIRELESS-TRADES-NYT &LR;      06-04 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIRELESS-TRADES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHWAB PLANS WIRELESS LINK ON THE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hoping to catch the wireless Internet wave, Charles Schwab the
leading discount brokerage firm, plans to let its online customers
cut the cord and do their online trading from cars, commuter trains
or even the beach, using wireless devices.
</P>
<P>
   The move, which Schwab plans to announce Monday, comes more than
a year and a half after one of its main competitors, Fidelity
Investments, introduced wireless access. But so far, wireless
brokerage services have remained such a small market niche that
Schwab does not consider itself late to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not the first, but we're early,'' said Dawn Lepore,
Schwab's chief information officer. ``This is a marathon, and it's
just beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Schwab plans to introduce a service called PocketBroker that
will enable its customers to maintain constant contact with their
brokerage accounts while they are away from their homes or offices.
Through two models of hand-held digital organizers made by Palm
Inc., and eventually through pagers and mobile phones that can
connect with the Internet, customers will be able to make trades
and receive messages from Schwab about stocks they track and trades
they have ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab, based in San Francisco, burnished its image as a
pacesetter in the brokerage business in the last four years, when
it encouraged most of its customers to switch to trading online at
a time when investors were largely conducting business over the
phone or in person. But many competitors beat Schwab to market with
wireless trading services _ most notably the brokerage arm of
Fidelity Investments, the Boston-based mutual funds giant, which
began offering such a feature in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, while Fidelity has aggressively promoted wireless trading
and is the undisputed leader in wireless brokerage services, those
activities still account for only a sliver of the company's
brokerage business. More than 65,000 Fidelity customers have signed
up for wireless access to their accounts, but that is less than 2
percent of Fidelity's brokerage customers.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Ferra, who heads Fidelity's wireless operations, said the
Fidelity Web site was visited 4 million times by Palm VII users in
May. But only a tiny part of that activity involved stock trades,
for which Fidelity collects commissions of $15 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts see those figures as evidence that, until now, the
demand for stock quotes, news and information about the financial
markets has overshadowed demand for trading stocks using a wireless
device.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, however, a confluence of activity by wireless
equipment and network companies, Internet service providers and
publishers of news and information have given momentum to various
sorts of wireless Internet applications. And so the online
brokerage industry is stepping up its efforts. Besides Fidelity, an
FMR Corp. unit, the online brokerage services TD Waterhouse,
ETrade, Ameritrade and DLJdirect have been busy linking up with
Palm, pager makers and mobile phone service providers. The AT&AMP;T
Wireless Group, for example, is promoting the ties between its new
PocketNet wireless Internet service and Waterhouse, ETrade and
DLJdirect. Wireless access to Fidelity and Ameritrade is a featured
service of the Sprint PCS Wireless Web.
</P>
<P>
   Ferra, the Fidelity executive, said that locking up those
relationships now, as the service providers promoted their
offerings, would be critical to success as wireless catches on with
users. Fidelity, for instance, has nailed down a potentially
valuable deal with Palm, which loads wireless connection software
on every one of its Palm VII's, that company's only model so far
with a built-in wireless modem.
</P>
<P>
   When Fidelity introduced wireless access, Ferra said, it
expected only the most active traders to want it, and so it offered
the wireless service only to those with account balances of at
least $100,000. Now, anyone with a Fidelity brokerage account can
register a wireless device. Fidelity also provides delayed stock
quotes and other data free to users of certain wireless devices and
services who are not Fidelity customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The firms who get out here early and create a superior product
will win this space,'' said Ferra, who calls wireless the ``second
coming of the Internet.'' He said that about 70 percent of
participants in a recent focus group indicated that they might
switch brokers if their current broker did not provide wireless
access soon.
</P>
<P>
   The brokerage houses have been waging an expensive fight for
bigger shares of the fast-growing market for online investing. If
wireless access will get customers to open accounts and move
assets, firms will gladly offer it _ in the same way that
traditional Wall Street firms like Merrill Lynch and Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter came around last year and began offering low-commission
online trading. Morgan Stanley introduced wireless access to online
accounts earlier this year, and Merrill has said it will follow
suit before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   By then, ETrade hopes to have made its brand synonymous with
mobile trading, said Jim Safka, general manager of ETrade's
wireless effort. The company, based in Palo Alto, Calif., wants to
strike deals as quickly as it can with all of the major device
makers and service providers and plans to use a big marketing
budget to heavily promote wireless, starting in the fall, Safka
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not focusing so much on it being a pure trading
device,'' he continued. Whether an investor has a use or a need for
wireless access to his brokerage firm, Safka said, ``has more to do
with someone's lifestyle than it does with their trading
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   ETrade's 3 million customers make, on average, two trades a
month, Safka said. But he predicted that within four years ETrade
customers would increasingly be making connections using wireless
devices rather than stationary personal computers. ``This market is
going to take off like wildfire in the next six to 12 months,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Safka, Lepore of Schwab contends that no brokerage company
has yet gained a lasting competitive edge, because the market for
wireless financial services is only now developing in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brokerage business isn't on wireless yet,'' Lepore said.
``I don't think in five years we will look back and say that in May
2000 the die was already cast. Wireless will really take off when
more of the products are phone-based.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Schwab's PocketBroker service will not be accessible
through mobile phones. At first, it will be available for $55 a
month to users of two devices, the Palm IIIx and Palm Vx, to which
modems must be added for use with wireless services. But Schwab
said it planned soon to extend the service to two-way pagers made
by Research in Motion and later to mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with this country, the more immediate business
opportunity through mobile phones is in Europe and Asia, Lepore
said. Through an alliance with the Swedish cellular phone giant
Ericsson, Schwab is developing mobile Internet applications for use
in Britain, Japan and Hong Kong _ areas in which wireless phones
are already in wide use as portable data terminals.
</P>
<P>
   Lepore said Schwab planned to introduce wireless brokerage
service for mobile phones this fall in Hong Kong, where many
investors do all their stock trading through wireless connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This truly is a global play,'' Lepore said. ``And right now,
it's very, very early in the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
