<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN-AGE PITCHER HOMERING IN FIRST AT-BAT STARTS ROUT OF METS 
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To lose to the Tampa Bay Devil Rays Sunday, the Mets
had to summon up demons that had been chased away long ago in the
Bobby Valentine regime.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays tormented the Mets in a 15-5 victory _ the
highest score against the Mets this season, and equaling Tampa
Bay's record.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine yielding a home run to a pitcher who had never been to
the plate in his professional career _ on the first pitch he saw.
</P>
<P>
   Or imagine seeing the Gold Glove third baseman Robin Ventura,
distracted by a broken bat that arrived at the same time as a
ground ball, throwing the ball away to start a five-run sixth
inning that broke open the game.
</P>
<P>
   Later that inning, Ventura, as well as shortstop Kurt Abbott,
bobbled balls that could have resulted in inning-saving double
plays.
</P>
<P>
   And to top it off, the Devil Rays scored an additional five
unearned runs two innings later after loading the bases on two hit
batsmen and an error.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets, who captured the first two games of the weekend
series, get another chance Monday night against another weak
American League team when the Baltimore Orioles come to Shea for a
three-game series. And then there is the annual interborough soap
opera against the Yankees next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had started this series with baseball's second-best
record (30-21) in the history of interleague play. They also have
been a very successful home team this season, winning almost twice
as often as their opposition. And the Devil Rays? One of baseball's
worst teams, quite simply, a team that won only once in every three
games on the road.
</P>
<P>
   But the Devil Rays unveiled some surprises, including a hitter
named Estaban Yan. He was also the starting pitcher, though he had
never had an at-bat in a professional game. Not even in the minors,
and certainly not in his previous 132 games in the major leagues.
Sure, he said in a charming accent, he had at-bats before ``in
school in the Dominican.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Valentine was assessing Yan as a hitter. After
all, what did the Mets know about this 25-year-old who had never
been to the plate?
</P>
<P>
   ``We suspect the guy today isn't a hitter,'' Valentine said.
``He's never done the National League thing and he's a young
hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   So in the second inning, the Mets starter Bobby J. Jones could
be forgiven if he thought he had an easy out, especially after
Felix Martinez had launched a two-run home run (on a 1-2 pitch) to
propel the visitors to a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Up stepped Yan, oblivious to the fact that only 11 pitchers in
the history of baseball had ever homered in their first at-bat, and
none had done it in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to myself, `I got a chance,''' Yan said. ``I feel
comfortable. I feel I want to swing at the first pitch. He try to
throw a strike. He figures I'm an easy out.''
</P>
<P>
   And so on the first pitch he had seen in an at-bat in a game
since his teen-age years, and after seven seasons of pro ball, Yan
swung at the first pitch, a fastball. He drilled it almost 370 feet
over the left-center field wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't trying to throw a fastball down the middle by any
means,'' Jones said. ``Anyone with a bat in his hands is
dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   That 3-0 edge, though, does not mean much for a team that
struggles as much as the Devil Rays do. Jones recovered to pitch
three straight scoreless innings, and the Mets scored four times to
take a 4-3 lead into the sixth. Mike Piazza, in his second game
back after being sidelined with a concussion, knocked home two of
the runs.
</P>
<P>
   But then came the Devil Rays' five-run assault in the sixth.
They knocked out Jones, the eventual loser, even though he said he
had felt better about his fastball and slider Sunday than he had
previously this season.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Pat Mahomes, who followed Jones, was lifted for a
pinch-hitter in the seventh. And then his relief, Rich Rodriguez,
was the victim of his own and his teammates' sloppiness in the
crushing eight inning.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez hit two players. Abbott threw a ball away. That set
the stage for the five unearned runs, including Bubba Trammell's
third pinch-hit homer of the season, a three-run blast.
</P>
<P>
   Yan, who got the victory for his five-inning stint, was
magnanimous.
</P>
<P>
   Told about Valentine's assessment, the pitcher said, ``He may be
right. Maybe I got lucky this time. I'm very excited.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
