<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4296 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-STANLEY-CUP0605-C     06-04 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STANLEY-CUP0605-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Where Lemieux goes, Cups follow
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ During the Eastern Conference finals, the Philadelphia
Flyers made the fatal mistake of poking fun at Claude Lemieux's
spelling. They should have known better. You don't agitate the
NHL's No. 1 agitator.
</P>
<P>
   Early in New Jersey's series with the Flyers, Lemieux tried to
get under the skin of Philadelphia captain Eric Desjardins by
saying, ``What's the `C' stand for? Selfish.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, Lemieux can spell in French a whole lot better than he can
in English. But when it comes to Lemieux, C' stands for only one
thing _ Cup. That's Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux has already played on three Cup winners. This could be
his fourth. The Devils lead the Stanley Cup finals 2-1 going into
tonight's Game 4 at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   If New Jersey captures its second championship in six years,
Lemieux will become the first player to win a Cup, get traded to a
team that wins another, then return to the old team and win again.
</P>
<P>
   Confusing? Perhaps. But Lemieux has always been at his best in
the postseason, when the games mean the most.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux, 34, broke in by winning a Stanley Cup as a rookie with
Montreal in 1986, scoring 10 playoff goals. Then he was the Conn
Smythe Trophy winner as postseason MVP in 1995 when he scored 13
goals and New Jersey swept Detroit in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just incredible my name will be on it,'' Lemieux said at
the time. ``To be the most hated man in hockey and have your name
on the Conn Smythe Trophy is really special.''
</P>
<P>
   But before the next season, Lemieux was traded to Colorado after
a falling-out with general manager Lou Lamoriello. What did the
Avalanche do? Win the Cup in Lemieux's first season, beating
Florida. A year later, when Colorado lost in the Western Conference
finals, Lemieux had 13 playoff goals.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux wore out his welcome in Colorado, too. But after
watching his team bomb in the playoffs since 1995, Lamoriello
decided the Devils needed Lemieux back. The deal was made early
this season, with the postseason in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux, who is an unrestricted free agent after the season,
ranks sixth in the NHL in career playoff games (218) and eighth in
goals (80). His 19 game-winning goals trail only Wayne Gretzky (24)
and Brett Hull (21).
</P>
<P>
   After four goals and five assists in the first three rounds,
Lemieux has been quiet in the Stanley Cup finals. Quiet in scoring,
that is. He is never quiet on the ice. Or angelic. If ever a player
belonged on a team called the Devils, it's Lemieux.
</P>
<P>
   He is nicknamed ``Pepe'' _ as in Pepe LePew, the cartoon world's
most famous skunk.
</P>
<P>
   Here is Hockey 101, according to Pepe Lemieux:
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to hit somebody as hard as you can. If he's shaken up,
or if he's going to miss a shift or two, or he's worrying he's
going to get hammered again, then you've done your job. You'll
whack somebody sometimes, maybe just give a guy a slash, maybe 15
seconds of little shooting pain. That takes him off his game.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
