<SLUG> BC-GEN-CYBER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT'S THE TICKET, WITH NO SLEAZY GIFTS NECESSARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Online ticket orders for events at the 2002 Winter
Olympics in Salt Lake City won't be taken until October, but
registration on the organization's official site
(www.SaltLake2002.com) is the first step toward getting them.
</P>
<P>
   More than 730,000 tickets will be made available to the public,
but 20 percent of those will be reserved for Utah residents.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket prices range from $20 for short track speed skating to
$425 for the gold-medal hockey game. Opening and closing ceremonies
are going for $885.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Sept. 6, tickets for such high-demand events as opening
and closing ceremonies will be sold to the highest bidders in an
Internet auction, the SLOC said.
</P>
<P>
   --Sotheby's has an auction (www.sothebys.amazon.com) timed to
coincide with the NBA Finals that includes some amazing items.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 things that once belonged to Wilt Chamberlain -
including his custom-made sports car called ``The Searcher'' and a
signed pair of the high-topped canvas Converse he wore when he
scored 100 points in 1962 - are included.
</P>
<P>
   Also, 40 pieces of the old 264-panel parquet floor from the
Boston Garden are being sold. Included is a piece determined to be
the spot where the Lakers' Magic Johnson made his famous hook shot
to beat the Celtics for the 1985 NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   The auction, co-sponsored by Amazon.com, starts today and
continues through June 14. Proceeds go to a variety of charities.
</P>
<P>
   --Suits, jackets and other promotional campaign materials that
Michael Jordan wore and signed for a clothing company called Bigsby
&AMP; Kruthers will go up for auction starting Tuesday on a site
(www.air23.com) launched by Sports Investments International. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
