<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4298 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-ROCKER0605-COX     06-04 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ROCKER0605-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocker rants at reporter
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nearly 5 1/2 months after the fact, John Rocker
finally made his editorial response to Sports Illustrated. It was
no love sonnet.
</P>
<P>
   In a chance encounter outside the Atlanta clubhouse Sunday
morning, Rocker dressed down SI writer Jeff Pearlman, accusing him
of portraying the Braves closer in the worst possible light and
making a veiled threat that the issue is not settled.
</P>
<P>
   Spotting Pearlman in the tunnel outside the Braves clubhouse at
around 11 a.m., Rocker quickly turned his cap around to get it out
of the way, then positioned himself inches from the writer's face.
For the next two minutes and 45 seconds, Rocker backed Pearlman
across the walkway with a steady stream of invective.
</P>
<P>
   The incident was witnessed by three newspaper reporters and a
Yankees broadcaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'It's not over with you and me,' `` said Pearlman,
who had been in town all weekend covering the Yankees-Braves
series.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first Turner Field visit this year for Pearlman, who
wrote the December story that portrayed Rocker as an angry young
man with disparaging views on race and foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Several times, Rocker poked a finger at the tip of Pearlman's
nose, grazing him the last time before storming off to the
clubhouse. He returned moments later with a security guard, whom he
instructed to keep Pearlman from entering.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had a choice,'' Rocker said. ``and you chose to f--- me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Rocker's second heated exchange with a media member since
returning from his suspension. The first, an April on-field
encounter with WAGA sportscaster Jeff Hullinger, almost came to
blows.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to comment afterward, Rocker declined, saying, ``Do I
ever?''
</P>
<P>
   Braves general manager John Schuerholz also declined to discuss
the incident but issued a statement that said, ``We will do
everything in our power to ensure similar incidents do not occur in
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   But happening as it did, with a New York press crops in town,
the Braves were again left to explain their puzzling pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pain in the butt for the 24 other guys,'' said third
baseman Chipper Jones, ``and it's not something we like to deal
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
