<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4304 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CLINTON-ASSESS     06-04 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CLINTON-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: CLINTON'S PROSPECTS FOR AN ARMS DEAL WITH PUTIN AS DIM AS
EVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (With RUSSIA-CLINTON, RUSSIA-CLINTON-RADIO) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Seeking to lower expectations Clinton administration
officials had insisted this should not be viewed as an arms control
summit. But it was.
</P>
<P>
   The main purpose of the two days of meetings with President
Vladimir Putin was to soften the Kremlin's resistance to American
plans for a limited missile defense, and to pave the way for a new
arms control framework by the end of the Clinton presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Two days of meetings, however, failed to produce progress on
either count, and the prospects for a breakthrough on Clinton's
watch seem as dim as ever.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons why the Clinton administration
approached the summit with a sense of urgency. Unlike the Reagan or
Bush administrations, the Clinton administration has yet to
negotiate a landmark accord on strategic arms and it is eager to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure also comes from the Clinton administration's
schedule for deploying an anti-missile system. The administration's
goal is to install 20 interceptors and build a large
battle-management radar in Alaska by 2005, a defense system the
White House insists is needed against a potential North Korean
threat.
</P>
<P>
   To meet that deadline Clinton needs to give the go-ahead for at
least some of the work by the end of year. And unless the Russians
drop their objections and agree to modify the 1972 Antiballistic
Missile Treaty to allow a limited defense, Clinton will have to
consider withdrawing from the accord.
</P>
<P>
   That would not only create a confrontation with Moscow, it would
also seriously aggravate Washington's relations with its allies in
Western Europe, who are nervous that the American missile-defense
program will undermine the existing arms agreements and spark a new
arms race with Russia and China, and perhaps even with new nuclear
states like India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some modest shifts in the Russian positions, however,
the fundamental disagreements remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Putin made absolutely clear to President Clinton
that Russia continues to oppose changes to the ABM treaty that the
United States has proposed,'' Strobe Talbott, the deputy secretary
of state, acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that the two sides made no headway on arms
control. They agreed on a set of guidelines, grandly called the
``principles of strategic stability,'' for future talks.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines take note of the emerging missile threat and
allude to the possibility of amending the accord, steps American
officials billed as an indication that Moscow is beginning to take
account of Washington's worries about the potential missile
capabilities of North Korea and Iran, even if the Kremlin believes
those fears are exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Russia also signed two secondary, but
noteworthy agreements. One requires each side to dispose of 34 tons
of weapons-grade plutonium over the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   While 34 tons is enough to make thousands of warheads, it
represents one-fourth of Russia's military stockpile. The disposal
will also not take place unless industrialized nations underwrite
the $1.75 billion that it will cost to carry out the program in
Russia, a contribution that has yet to be arranged.
</P>
<P>
   Another accord would also set up a Moscow-based center where the
United States and Russia would exchange information on missile
launches. The purpose is to help the Russians compensate for their
gaps in the frayed system of early warning radars and reduce the
chance that Moscow might launch its nuclear arsenal based on a
false alert.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton and Putin signed the accords with great fanfare,
that did not mask their deeper dispute over missile defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials are still holding out the hope
that they may bring Putin around by the end of the year. And some
observers have speculated the solution might be a grand bargain in
which the United States would move forward on missile defense in
return for the arms cuts sought by Russia.
</P>
<P>
   There are, however, several reasons why the Clinton
administration is unlikely to succeed. For one thing, the Clinton
administration does not appear to have pursued the grand bargain
with any real enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   Driven by budgetary pressures, for example, Moscow has urged
that the two sides agree to slash their strategic arms to 1,500
warheads as part of a START-III treaty. That would be substantially
less than the level of 2,000 to 2,500 warheads the United States
has insisted on.
</P>
<P>
   In his press conference Sunday, Clinton did not rule out the
deeper cuts. But administration officials said later that such
reductions probably could not be considered until after a START-III
treaty was concluded.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that the Pentagon is opposed to such deep cuts and
the White House does not want to pick a fight with the military
during an election-year. The Clinton administration also has not
yet conducted the sort of wide-ranging review of its nuclear war
plans and targeting policy that would be required to properly
assess such a significant reduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have previously agreed to a range of 2,000 to 2,500 on
START-III,'' Clinton said. ``If we were to come down below it, it
would require us to change our strategic plan, and we believe it
would be much better, if we were going to do that, if we could also
know that we were defending ourselves against a new threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason why a breakthrough does not seem near is that
Russian officials know missile defense is a campaign issue. Even if
they agree to Clinton's proposal, they may end up negotiating again
with George W. Bush, the Republican candidate, who is promoting a
far grander plan.
</P>
<P>
   The more fundamental reason, however, is that Putin and his
generals are still deeply concerned that a missile defense will
unleash a competition in defensive technology that the cash-poor
Russian state is bound to lose. Even if the United States builds a
limited defense, the Russians say, it is likely to be just the
first phase in a more ambitious system that will give the United
States a strategic edge over Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the summit meeting was to ease these anxieties.
And while administration officials sought to put the best face on
the meeting, they acknowledged there was still considerable work to
do.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, Talbott added, still believes that an American missile
defense ``will undermine strategic stability, threaten Russia's
strategic deterrent and provoke an arms race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
