<SLUG> BC-TEX-ESCAPED-PARROTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODD FLOCK OF MEXICAN PARROTS SETTLE IN TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 10th graf to correct spelling of Zachary Taylor)  By ROSS E. MILLOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas _ Just as the blazing afternoon sun softens
and begins to set, the parrots start to arrive, squawking and
keening as they wheel high overhead in the blue sky and drop into
the upper fronds of palm trees growing along the Rio Grande River.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do that every night,'' says Jessie Moreno, a cashier at
the Fort Brown Hotel, who likes to watch the birds roosting on the
hotel grounds. ``They come swooping back here when it starts to get
dark and spend the night up in those palm trees. In the morning
they'll take off again and fly out over the city looking for
food.''
</P>
<P>
   The birds call to each other as they dart from tree to tree,
brightly colored slashes of green, yellow and blue, and when a
truck backfires nearby they howl and take to the air as one,
screaming wildly as they swirl overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry,'' Moreno says, ``they'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   But the flock of parrots, more than 300 of a species known
scientifically as Amazona viridigenalis, are not really supposed to
be here in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Wild parrots in an urban environment like this dusty, bustling
border city seem unusual enough, but this flock is also odd for
other reasons, local experts say.
</P>
<P>
   They are at least a hundred miles from their typical roosting
grounds deep in Mexico, and a third of the parrots are birds
released by or escaped from smugglers trying to slip them illegally
into the country, said Steve Walker, a staff member at the
University of Texas at Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said a devastating freeze in 1982, coinciding with an
agrarian overhaul that deforested large sections of Northern
Mexico, combined to draw the birds into the Brownsville area.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that freeze we started seeing large numbers of
free-range parrots here,'' Walker said. ``Our conjecture is that a
flock of old veterans, who had made the trip before, decided to
come up out of Mexico into this area to forage. These birds can
live to be 60 to 70 years old and sometimes longer than that.''
</P>
<P>
   There is anecdotal evidence from old military diaries, Walker
said, of sightings of parrots even farther north, along the Nueces
River area, at a time when Gen. Zachary Taylor's troops were
quartered there in the Mexican War in 1847.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was in November, in the pecan season, and these parrots
just love pecans,'' he said. ``So they must have flown at least 200
miles even further north to look for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brownsville flock now contains more than 160 nesting pairs
of three types of parrots: yellow-cheek parrots, also known as
red-lored, red-crowned parrots, and, the most colorful of the local
flock, yellow-head parrots, Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think most, if not all, of the yellow-heads are escaped or
released birds,'' he said. ``But the red-crowns have just wandered
into the area to feed and ended up staying.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the escaped or released birds would have been trapped
along the Rio Corona or Rio Soto La Marina in southern Tamaulipas,
Mexico, Walker said, and the red-crowned parrots would have come
from still further south. It is illegal to bring any of the parrots
into the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see that some members of the flock still have their
wings clipped as a bird smuggler would do; those are released or
escaped birds,'' Walker said, adding that they were easy to spot:
``They have to beat their wings twice as fast to go half as far.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker, who became interested in the birds when he hosted a
local wildlife show on television, says the birds eat palm dates,
citrus from the vast commercial groves that surround Brownsville,
and mosquitoes that swarm over the city's many ``resacas,'' a kind
of catchment pond for rain.
</P>
<P>
   Up until two years ago, there was a Catch-22 in protecting
parrots from hunters or trappers, says Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't supposed to be here so they weren't really
covered by state laws,'' he said. But Walker and other local
wildlife enthusiasts worked with the Texas Birding Association to
have the local parrots designated as a native population in 1998,
making them a protected species.
</P>
<P>
   Walker also led a successful effort to have the parrot
designated as the official city bird of Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   The birds are monogamous for life, keep their families together
for a long time, and have what Walker calls `shared intelligence.'
``That means they like to talk to each other,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The parrots are also amazingly adaptive creatures, Walker said.
The same freeze that drew the birds here in the early 1980s killed
many local palm trees, and the rotted trunks make perfect homes for
the parrots.
</P>
<P>
   To build their nests, the parrots find holes made by woodpeckers
seeking insects in bark. The parrots then patiently peck and claw
at the woodpecker holes until they have made a large enough cavity
for nesting.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the hotel grounds, Moreno slapped the base of one of
those palm trees with bare her hand several times and two small
yellow parrot heads popped inquisitively from a hole halfway up the
tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two have a nest in there, so we'll be seeing some more
babies soon,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
