<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4320 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-SOFT-MONEY-ADS-NYT &LR;      06-04 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFT-MONEY-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFT MONEY ADS BREWING AS ISSUE; BUSH, GORE BOTH LIKELY TARGETS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two and a half months ago, flush with victory in
the primaries and eager to be seen as taking the high road, Vice
President Al Gore sent an e-mail message to Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, proposing a ban on ``issue ads'' paid for with unregulated
soft money.
</P>
<P>
   Bush dismissed the challenge as a ploy. But now, with Democrats
dropping hints that they may soon begin a television advertising
campaign on behalf of Gore, Republicans are eager to hoist the vice
president on his own petard.
</P>
<P>
   Asserting that Gore's message amounted to a promise not to use
soft money, the Republicans are trying to paint Gore as a hypocrite
even before the Democrats' first commercial hits the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   In a June 1 letter to Ed Rendell, general chairman of the
Democratic National Committee, Jim Nicholson, the Republican
national chairman, suggested that Democrats were poised to renege
on the promise because Bush has been running ahead of Gore in some
polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd ask you to tell the truth: Al Gore meant to keep his
pledge only so long as it was beneficial to him politically,''
Nicholson wrote. ``That's why he's changed his mind now that he's
fallen in the polls. That's why the DNC is looking for any excuse,
any loophole, any fine print to serve as justification for his
clear intention to violate another pledge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans made Nicholson's letter available to reporters
before it was sent. And to some who monitor the gamesmanship
between the parties, it appeared that the Republicans were seeking
to enlist on the side of the angels on a confusing and complex
issue in which neither party could claim purity.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Democratic officials said, obscure groups with ties to
the Republican Party are already running commercials in California
and Washington, D.C., that are intended to tar Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line here is that both the Bush campaign and the
Gore campaign are planning to spend tens of millions of dollars on
these illicit soft money ads in this election,'' said Fred
Wertheimer, president of Democracy 21, a Washington group that
advocates campaign finance reform. ``I don't know that voters
should care about this game of `got you,' but they should deeply
care about the huge amounts of six-figure campaign contributions
that in the end are going to be spent.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Gore, though, who set the game in motion with his e-mail
message to Bush on March 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I challenge you to accept my proposal that we both reject the
use of soft money to run issue ads,'' Gore wrote. ``I will take the
first step by requesting the Democratic National Committee not to
run any issue ads paid for by soft money unless and until the
Republican Party uses money for advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans remember the 1996 campaign, when the Democrats ran a
pre-emptive series of issue advertisements on behalf of President
Clinton well before the conventions that did substantial damage to
Bob Dole's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a period when Dole was low on cash,'' said Nelson Warfield,
a Republican consultant who served as press secretary for the Dole
campaign, ``the Clinton-Gore team was able to define him as an
extremist when in fact Dole was a mainstream Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the large-scale use of party-sponsored commercials
has yet to occur. But the memory of 1996 lingers, and Republican
officials are trying to hold Gore accountable for his offer, saying
that in the e-mail message, and in some statements on TV news
programs, Gore has pledged not to use soft money.
</P>
<P>
   But aides to Gore said that just as in the case of a challenge
to former Sen. Bill Bradley to forgo commercials during the
Democratic primaries, Gore's proposal was contingent on an
agreement with his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who saw Bush's response to the Gore challenge knows the
Bush campaign has not taken it seriously from Day 1,'' said Chris
Lehane, press secretary for the Gore campaign. ``I think for Jim
Nicholson to suddenly be trying to get on the moral high ground is
laughable.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last four years, issue advertising _ ostensibly intended
to promote a cause rather than a person _ has become a tool in
congressional and presidential races. The advertisements are often
echoes of the commercials that the candidates run, but they avoid
terms like ``vote for'' or ``defeat.'' These words, the courts have
found, constitute electioneering, and would make the ads subject to
the strictures of the Federal Election Commission. Issue
advertisements paid for with soft money have no financial
disclosure requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans clearly want Gore to pay a political price should
the Democratic National Committee begin a blitz of issue
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``From Gore's standpoint,'' Wertheimer said, ``this is not a
pledge he should have made, and obviously, it was made to score
points. Now Bush is trying to use it to score points of his own.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials contend that Bush and his allies long ago
violated the spirit of Gore's overture. They say that over the last
several weeks, the Republicans have made clear that their
general-election television strategy will be to have the Bush
campaign run upbeat commercials while leaving the attack
advertising in the hands of little-known interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, organizations like the Sierra Club and the National
Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League are running ads
attacking Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats point to a recent $1.5 million anti-Gore campaign on
television in California by Shape the Debate, a group formed by
associates of Pete Wilson, the former Republican governor, and to a
more recent series of commercials being run on cable television in
Washington. Sponsored by an organization called the Coalition to
Protect Americans Now, the latest 30-second commercial, unveiled
this week, criticizes the Clinton administration's handling of
America's nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Backus, a Democratic National Committee spokesman, said
the commercials were part of a ``stealth campaign'' by Republicans
to attack Gore without having to reveal the source of the money
used to pay for the advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Gaffney, head of the advisory board for the Coalition to
Protection Americans Now, said the group was formed four months ago
to invigorate discussion on security issues, not to derail a
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organization is in no way connected to the Bush
campaign,'' Gaffney said. ``People that I am very close to and have
worked with are advising Bush. But that is in no way translated
into any kind of coordination.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 2055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
