<DOCNO> NYT20000604.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4322 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CLINTON-RADIO-     06-04 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CLINTON-RADIO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON RUSSIAN RADIO, CLINTON RAISES CONCERNS ABOUT SQUASHING OF
DISSENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Hours before he flew to Moscow on Friday, President
Clinton pointedly observed in a speech in Berlin that Westerners
``do not yet know if Russia's hard-won democratic freedoms will
endure.'' Sunday, with a few muted gestures, the White House
illustrated what he meant.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday morning, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright visited
Radio Liberty, the United States-financed broadcaster whose blunt
coverage of the war in Chechnya last winter led to the Russians'
detention of a top reporter, Andrei Babitsky.
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday evening, Clinton gave an hourlong interview to Echo
Moskvy radio, an all-news station that is part of Russia's
Media-MOST empire. Long known for critical reports on the Kremlin,
Media-MOST was raided last month by armed federal tax police,
curiously clad in camouflage and ski masks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Kremlin's denials, the raid was widely seen here as
a warning that opponents criticize this government at their peril.
</P>
<P>
   The two appearances underscored the sub-theme _ to the White
House, at least _ of this arms-control meeting: the shaky state of
Russia's democratic freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton raised those concerns Sunday in meetings with President
Vladimir Putin. Putin was said to have reassured the president that
building a civil and democratic society was one of his priorities.
</P>
<P>
   But some political experts here, both Russian and foreign, are
less sanguine. Putin's rise has brought an increasingly open effort
to bring the press, religious leaders and other potential opponents
to heel.
</P>
<P>
   That view was highlighted in recent confrontations involving
government authorities that left the distinct odor, if not the
reality, of a Kremlin crackdown on civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, customs officers searched the bags of an Amnesty
International employee arriving in Moscow and confiscated pamphlets
alleging human-rights violations by Russian troops in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Customs officials said the employee lacked required documents
certifying that the pamphlets were legal. Amnesty International
called the seizure ``a dangerous precedent that brings back
memories of the Soviet Union.''
</P>
<P>
   In another case, potentially more serious, leaders of Russia's
Jewish minority charged on Thursday that the Kremlin was plotting
to undermine and divide them, apparently to dilute complaints about
Russian assistance to Iranian military programs. By those accounts,
a Kremlin official pressured Russia's chief rabbi, Adolf Shayevich,
to resign last week in favor of a Jewish leader who enjoys
government support. Rabbi Shayevich refused and wrote a letter of
complaint to Putin.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin has offered support to an independent religious
group, the Federation of Jewish Communities, which was founded in
Moscow late last year.
</P>
<P>
   International Jewish groups condemned the Kremlin overture.
</P>
<P>
   The chief Moscow rabbi, Pinchus Goldschmidt, quoted American
officials Sunday night as saying that Clinton had raised the
incident with Putin and received a positive response. ``I can only
hope that his response will be not only in words, but in deeds,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's paper commitment to civil and human rights is
impeccable. In his guiding statement of principles, he wrote that
``the main threat to human rights and freedoms, to democracy as
such, emanates from the executive authority.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why I, personally, am paying priority attention to
building partner relations between the executive authority and
civil society.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the early going, Putin's passion for the strong center he
says Russians need seems to have trumped other concerns. He has
seeded the top ranks of his administration with former military and
KGB officials. And some of his farthest-reaching policies, such as
a plan to tighten the Kremlin's grip on Russia's 89 regions, have
come from strategists on his military-oriented security council.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until President Yeltsin's resignation'' _ the deft move that
virtually assured Putin's election victory last March _ ``it was
almost evident that Putin was playing a role written by someone
else,'' Nikolai Petrov, a senior analyst with the Moscow Center of
the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, said in a recent
interview. ``When he replaced this team of former Yeltsin advisers
with former KGB guys, he looked more or less independent. But I'm
not sure he still is.''
</P>
<P>
   By far the most visible suggestion of a Kremlin clampdown
centers on the news media, which exist under the watchful eye of
their own government ministry, beefed up by Putin last year. Since
then, the ministry has pulled the license of one television station
and threatened to auction the licenses of two others. One, Moscow's
TV Center, is controlled by Yuri M. Luzhkov, a Kremlin rival and
the mayor of Moscow. The other is ORT, a state-owned, avidly
pro-Putin network controlled by the financier Boris A. Berezovsky.
The two were accused of slanting election coverage.
</P>
<P>
   To no one's surprise, ORT easily recaptured its license in a
one-sided auction last month. Luzhkov's TV Center, on the other
hand, appears to face at least one serious bidder. It is fighting
its license revocation in court.
</P>
<P>
   The ministry also has demanded that the news media ban
interviews with or other quotations from Chechen guerrillas or
opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terrorists are waging a media war'' against the government,
said Vladimir V. Grigoriev, the deputy press minister. ``We are
insisting that electronic and printed media not give a chance to
the terrorists to address and lie to the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how a newspaper might be punished for violating the ban,
he replied: ``That's the main problem. The mass media is probably
the most democratic institution. There could be no real penalty _
probably a reprimand.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Federal law provides, however, that a newspaper can be shut down
by court order after two government reprimands. And the case of the
most rebellious and powerful of the Kremlin's press critics _ the
Media-MOST empire run by Vladimir V. Gusinsky _ suggests that a
powerful journalistic critic of the Kremlin risks an unusual run of
bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   The company runs not just Echo Moskvy, but the newspaper
Sevodnya, the newsmagazine Itogi and the NTV television network _
the only network with a reach even approaching the coast-to-coast
coverage of state-owned ORT. When his empire began attacking the
war in Chechnya and refused to endorse Putin, Gusinsky said
recently, retribution was swift.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, the government-controlled gas monopoly Gazprom
decided to call due a $211 million loan to the company. The
Media-MOST headquarters were raided last month in what the Kremlin
says was an inquiry into illegal surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   Days later, the Central Bank stepped in to prevent the sale of
the insolvent MOST Bank, once controlled by Gusinsky. He charges
that the action was taken to prevent Media-MOST from profiting from
the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   In his radio interview Sunday night, Clinton was asked by a
Russian journalist whether he ever had an urge to throttle a
reporter or to sic his tax police on an unruly critic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fair to say that in the history of our country,
nobody has had more negative press coverage than myself,'' he said.
``But if the approach is balanced, then you have a chance to give
an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   As for wielding the police against his enemies, Clinton said:
``I have never done anything like that. It's illegal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
