<SLUG> BC-BRAZILL-ATTORNEY0605-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Father chooses high profile attorney for his son
 &HT;    By Susan Spencer-Wendel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Attorney Bob Udell has handled at least
70 murder cases, gotten death sentences overturned, defended the
most reviled of killers, and gotten outright acquittals.
</P>
<P>
   But Udell says the main reason Nate Brazill's father put him on
his son's case was the fact Udell has a 13-year-old son too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to figure them out is a crapshoot,'' Udell said of
13-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   But Udell, 51, has been tapped to try. He contacted the family
late last week about representing Nate Brazill, the teenager
accused of shooting Barry Grunow, a language arts teacher at Lake
Worth Community Middle School. Udell met the teen for the first
time Sunday at the Juvenile Detention Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the child everybody hopes for: thoughtful, bright,
sensitive,'' Udell said. ``He just did a very stupid thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to accept responsibility. Nathaniel pulled the
trigger. We know that,'' Udell said. ``But his state of mind at the
time. . . that's what we'll have to litigate.''
</P>
<P>
   Udell wouldn't comment about what Brazill told him was the
reason he took the gun to school except to say: ``Nobody planned or
intended to kill anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   A grand jury is scheduled to decide next week whether to indict
the 13-year-old on murder charges and try him as an adult. Udell
said he will consider the rare and risky move of having his client
testify before the grand jurors. The risk is that anything Brazill
says at the hearing could be used against him later in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Udell, a small, wiry man who has captivated courtrooms with his
high-strung energy, will be assisted by another Stuart attorney,
Lance Richard. Richard has limited criminal defense experience.
</P>
<P>
   The public defender initially appointed to represent Brazill
said Sunday that the news was disappointing, but not surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked promising for Nathaniel,'' said Assistant Public
Defender Randy Berman. ``A junk gun with a hair trigger, no
animosity for the teacher, a good kid _ it looked promising.''
</P>
<P>
   Udell would not comment on whether he has taken on the case for
free or the family is paying. ``We'll work that out later,'' he
said. Brazill's mother works in food service and his father is a
postal worker.
</P>
<P>
   A family member who answered at the Brazill home Sunday night
declined to comment on the decision to switch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
