<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4328 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-DALL-NIEUWENDYK-N     06-04 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DALL-NIEUWENDYK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WING'S RETURN A BOOST FOR STARS' NIEUWENDYK  

</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Dallas forward Jamie Langenbrunner is expected to play
for the first time in these Stanley Cup finals when the Stars meet
the Devils on Monday night in Game 4. With the Stars trailing, two
games to one, nobody should be happier than Dallas center Joe
Nieuwendyk to see Langenbrunner back on his left wing.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk won the Conn Smythe Trophy last season as the most
valuable player of the playoffs, in which the Stars took their
first Stanley Cup. In the finals this year, however, Langenbrunner
has had a knee injury and Nieuwendyk has been a ghost.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Stars had a potent second line featuring
Nieuwendyk and Langenbrunner to complement Mike Modano and Brett
Hull on their top line. Nieuwendyk led all playoff scorers with 11
goals last year and tied the National Hockey League record for most
game-winning goals in one playoff year with six. He and
Langenbrunner combined for 21 playoff goals last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have lacked that second-line punch this season.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Coach Ken Hitchcock went so far as to change his strategy
from Games 1 and 2 and shy away from playing Modano's line against
Jason Arnott's. ``We have to try and break even against Arnott,''
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   But Arnott's line dominated an older, slower line centered by
the Stars' Guy Carbonneau in Game 3, which the Devils won, 2-1;
Arnott's line accounted for both goals. For the second time in
three games, Arnott's line played the more decisive role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's any secret right now that we've got one
line that is obviously concerning Jersey,'' Hitchcock said. ``We
need more from more players to win this series.''
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner has been out since Game 5 of the Western
Conference finals with a sprained knee. Nieuwendyk has no goals or
assists in the five games Langenbrunner has missed.
</P>
<P>
   Two questions put to Hitchcock Sunday were: How much has
Nieuwendyk missed Langenbrunner? And is it a valid excuse?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Hitchcock said. ``This is a game about
adjustments. We have learned how to play without people all year. I
think it is less about that and more going into the critical areas
to score. I think that all of us, Joe included, but also Mike and
Brett _ you are not going to score from a distance against this
team. You are going to have to get into gritty areas to score, and
that's really the bottom line. And Joe knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   He just had not been able to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the thing we'd like to see more from Joe is that he
doesn't play to score, he plays the game,'' Hitchcock said. ``What
we'd like to see is when you look at Nieuwendyk at the end of the
game, he is front and center. He's gotten his chances. He's been
one of the best players on the ice. We'd like to see him dictate
that tempo early. He has done that at critical stages in series
past. But sometimes in those series, these games haven't happened
until Game 5 or sometimes even Game 6. This is Game 4 tomorrow, and
we need it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk, 33, has complained lately that he has not had a good
scoring wing to play with since Langenbrunner was injured. But he
was not available to speak to reporters Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   So the questions about Nieuwendyk's lack of production were put
to Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe is like any other scorer,'' Hitchcock said. ``He is a lot,
in our case, like Brett Hull. When you are a scorer and you are
scoring, it seems that every part of your game is energized. Joe is
a perfect example. He is a streaky player. And if he scores early,
like he did at times during the last two series, then he is a very
effective player for that game and for the next few games.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you don't score, you start thinking too much. I find
that with great offensive players and great scorers, when they
start thinking, that is when they are at their worst.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk scored just 15 goals this season, the lowest total of
his 13-year NHL career. He played 48 regular-season games, missing
21 with a separated right shoulder. Hitchcock noted that Nieuwendyk
and his regular linemates, Langenbrunner and Scott Thornton, were
together for about 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a very good line for us,'' Hitchcock said, ``but
they haven't played together very much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
