<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4334 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-LAPOINTE-COLUMN-N     06-04 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LAPOINTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PUT SOME ICE INTO THE STANLEY CUP  

</HEADLINE>
   By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ As the Stanley Cup finals continue in a state that
borders Mexico, the players fret about bad ice inside Reunion Arena
and everyone else notices the warm and humid conditions outside in
June.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ice is so bad,'' Martin Brodeur, the Devils' goalie, said
Sunday. He tried to leave his net a few times to play the puck
Saturday night against the Stars but thought better of it. ``I
couldn't get to the puck because I missed the first two, three
steps because of the ice,'' Brodeur said.
</P>
<P>
   Most players seem to agree that the best ice, any time of year,
any place in the National Hockey League, is in Edmonton, where the
best teams used to be found when Glen Sather's Oilers won the cup
five times from 1984 through 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Would it make everyone happy for the NHL to do it the way the
National Football League does? The NFL plays the Super Bowl at a
warm-weather or domed site every January. Why not play the hockey
finals every June in Edmonton, a neutral site? They love hockey
there. And the late-spring weather is still cold enough to play
hockey on outdoor ice.
</P>
<P>
   (Just kidding on that last one, Canadian friends. Been there in
June. Know about the pleasant temperatures and the late-evening sun
so far north. Also remember the late-May snowstorm during one
finals there back when playoffs used to end before training camp
began.)
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to think about Edmonton these days because so many
former Oilers are front and center. Wayne Gretzky, the former
Edmonton star, bought into the Phoenix team last week. Sather, the
former Edmonton general manager, took over as boss of the Rangers.
And Jason Arnott of the Devils, a former Edmonton prospect, scored
a dynamic goal Saturday night to help his team gain a 2-1 victory
over the Dallas Stars and a two-games-to-one lead in the
four-of-seven-game championship round, which resumes here Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Arnott leads the Devils in playoff points with 19. According to
Ken Daneyko, New Jersey's veteran defenseman, Arnott has really
started to take on a leadership role. ``He wants to be the go-to
guy,'' Daneyko said. ``To be an elite hockey player in this league,
you have to have that cocky attitude in a good way.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnott was a rarity in the last decade of Sather's Edmonton
regime: A good pick on the first round of the entry draft. Sather,
also a cocky guy, is an angle-player who last week scored a good
deal for himself in New York. Critics who cite Sather's poor draft
record in Edmonton in the 1990s might also consider his trading
record.
</P>
<P>
   He sent Arnott and Bryan Muir to the Devils in 1998 in a deal
for Bill Guerin and Valery Zelepukin. Lou Lamoriello, the Devils'
boss, got the best of that one. Like Sather of recent weeks,
Lamoriello will soon be a free agent. Unlike Sather, Lamoriello
will not take over the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   While Lamoriello gets credit for building this Devils team, much
applause is directed toward Larry Robinson, the coach who replaced
Robbie Ftorek with eight games left in the regular season. For now,
Robinson is on a motivational roll. When he threatened to bench
Scott Gomez in the Toronto series, Gomez perked up. When Robinson
screamed at the team in the Philadelphia series, the team responded
well.
</P>
<P>
   When Robinson publicly chastised the careless play of Petr
Sykora and Patrik Elias after Game 2 of the finals, Arnott's Czech
wings helped him dominate Game 3. Sykora scored the winning goal
Saturday and that line had 13 shots. Here's to you, Robinson. And
Sunday, Elias was not afraid to respond to his coach, in an oblique
sort of way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it is the right approach to just blame
individuals for a loss because this is a team,'' Elias said. But he
was smiling through the news conference, he and Sykora, up there
like two wild and crazy guys, joshing with teammates in the back of
the room and off to the sides.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the mood with these chatty Devils, so many smiles as
they mingled with the news media. On the Dallas side, things are
glum. Stars supporters fear that the defending champions are too
old, too tired, too injured, too slow. But a Dallas victory Monday
night would change everyone's tune. And tunes are so much a part of
the atmosphere in funky Reunion, a barn only two decades old that
feels antiquated.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to hold heat and humidity. Flying insects were cruising
the press box Saturday night _ without credentials. The players may
hate to skate here and the cramped quarters give the league
logistical problems. But the fans are enthusiastic and friendly and
the music adds to the ambience. Unlike most NHL arenas, they employ
a disk jockey who refuses to assault the senses and sensibilities
of the customers by continuously blaring strip-joint rock.
</P>
<P>
   When the gates opened Saturday, and the fans climbed the steep
stairs to their dark, green seats, he softly played ``Sympathy for
the Devil,'' in deference to the visiting team. The lights were
still dim and the effect was wonderfully creepy. After an icing
whistle on the bad ice, the speakers softly emitted ``Ice, Ice,
Baby.'' It almost makes a neutral observer pull for a Stars victory
Monday night to guarantee Game 6 here Saturday. All things
considered, hockey in Dallas is pretty cool. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
