<DOCNO> NYT20000604.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4339 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-DEVILS-PENALTYKIL     06-04 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-PENALTYKILLERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS TAKE AN ADVANTAGE IN KILLING PENALTIES  

</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Goaltending and special teams are the basic ingredients
for success in the playoffs, a claim made over the years by coaches
and players with several championship rings. That was the first
thing cited by Devils Coach Larry Robinson, who has seven
championship rings as a player and coach, before this postseason.
His Devils are justifying his claim in the Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to their special teams, the Devils took a
two-games-to-one lead over the Dallas Stars with a 2-1 victory in
Game 3 here Saturday night. The Devils killed three of the Stars'
four power plays, including a five-on-three situation for 49
seconds at a critical time in the first period. They also killed a
delay-of-game penalty on Martin Brodeur with 4 minutes 15 seconds
left in the game, which many considered the goaltender's best
performance in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our penalty-killers won the game for us,'' said Petr Sykora,
whose power-play goal with 7:33 left in the second period _ a
blistering shot from the slot off a pass from Jason Arnott, who
scored the Devils' first goal _ was his third game-winner in the
playoffs. It was the 12th power-play goal in 62 attempts in the
playoffs for the Devils and the ninth for Sykora.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson attributed the success of killing Dallas' two-man
advantage to the strategy of keeping the puck out of their zone.
With Scott Stevens, Scott Niedermayer and John Madden leading the
way, the penalty-killers shut down Brett Hull and Mike Modano, two
of the game's most deadly snipers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any shot from the outside, it's Marty's,'' said Madden, the
best penalty-killer among the Devils' forwards. ``You want a shot
your goalie can see,'' he said, referring to Brodeur. ``You don't
want a shot from the middle because it can be tipped or
deflected.''
</P>
<P>
   Niedermayer, who is usually the third defenseman on the
penalty-killing unit after Stevens and Ken Daneyko, said of killing
the penalty to Brodeur: ``That's a huge part of the game when
you're up a goal and they have a two-minute power play. Our PK has
done a great job for us in the playoffs and all year long.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as in the regular season, the Devils' penalty-killers have
been the best in the playoffs. They killed 13 of Florida's 14 power
plays in the first round, and all 20 of Toronto's power plays in
the second round. When they reached the Eastern Conference finals
against Philadelphia, the Devils thwarted 15 of the Flyers' 17
power plays to reach the finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils are two victories from their second Stanley Cup for
other reasons, too: Stevens' crunching hits and brilliant play by
several forwards. Throw in a tirade by Robinson at precisely the
right time _ after three straight losses to the Flyers in the
conference finals _ and the Devils are threatening to dethrone the
defending champions.
</P>
<P>
   History is now on the side of the Devils, who have been the
better team in this series. In the 21 times the Stanley Cup finals
were tied at 1-1 after the first two games, the winner of Game 3
captured the trophy on all but three occasions.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils' hope that youth and exuberance would prevail over
experience is starting to materialize. The Stars had difficulty
keeping up with the Devils' speed on Saturday night, when their age
showed for the first time in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can use being tired as an excuse,'' said Kirk
Muller of the Stars, who, like the Devils, went through a grueling
seven-game series in the conference finals. ``You are fighting for
every inch out there, and there is no space. But I think we still
have enough left in the tank.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day Robinson kept his players off the ice, more than half a
dozen players refused to admit this afternoon that they had the
edge over the Stars in the four-of-seven-game finals, not even
after they handed the Stars only their second loss in 11 playoff
games at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot think you're better and get comfortable,'' said
Bobby Holik, whose team is 8-2 on the road. ``You cannot for a
moment think that, because they can come at you on the next shift.
They have a lot of experience and have responded to pressure
before.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
