<HEADER>
A4346 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LAD     06-04 1332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUELAS' HEAVY BAG OF BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If Oscar De La Hoya and Shane Mosley don't know
what to do with the millions they'll make for their June 17 fight
at Staples Center, they might want to see Rafael Ruelas.
</P>
<P>
   Ruelas the fighter? Nope, Ruelas the personal financial planner.
Same guy, new career.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Ruelas isn't your typical ex-fighter. (Yep, he's
retired.)
</P>
<P>
   Inside the ring, he made the absolute most of limited natural
ability through unwavering determination and exhaustive
preparation. In other words, he truly realized his potential - and
then some.
</P>
<P>
   He got up from two first-round knockdowns to beat Fred Pendleton
and win the IBF lightweight title, his one and only world
championship. That's the kind of fighter Ruelas was and the man he
remains.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the ring, he was always a go-getter. As a teen-ager,
only a few years after he and his brother Gabriel moved here from
Mexico, he made a few bucks by using his bilingual skills to help
immigrants file amnesty papers.
</P>
<P>
   And as early as 1995, the year he lost his title to De La Hoya,
he began to dabble in the business world. Now, after taking UCLA
extension classes, he's a certified tax preparer and has been hired
by Paine Webber.
</P>
<P>
   He's training as a personal financial planner but must pass a
grueling six-hour test next month to become licensed. Anyone who
knows him will be surprised if he doesn't pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like winning a big fight,'' Ruelas said of his
post-boxing accomplishments. ``But I have a big fight (the exam)
ahead of me and I'm getting ready for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been under pressure before and I know good things are
hard to attain. It takes a lot of dedication. I think of this
(pre-exam period) as a studying camp instead of a training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like I'm preparing for a big fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruelas will have some advantages if he passes the test.
</P>
<P>
   One, he knows quite a few wealthy people. De La Hoya and Mosely,
for example. He fought them both in the amateur ranks and De La
Hoya as a professional.
</P>
<P>
   And, two, De La Hoya, Mosley and others in the boxing business
who have money to invest know that Ruelas would fight for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fact I'm known will help me,'' he said. ``People
know I'm a hard-working individual and that I'm not out to screw
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``In boxing, I was always happy that people wanted me to win and
I didn't want to let people down. I was always prepared to win and
that's what I'm doing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruelas has had something of a rivalry with De La Hoya, which
peaked when De La Hoya knocked him out in two rounds to win the IBF
title in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ruelas said De La Hoya shouldn't be surprised if he
makes a business proposition one day. A few minutes later,
realizing he'd left something out, he added: ``The same goes for
Shane. I know them both and they're both good guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruelas already is talking like a businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone: Gabriel Ruelas, who'll be 30 in July, also
has his hands full at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   The also-retired former junior lightweight champ is involved in
a variety of projects for Santa Clarita Valley-based Valencia
Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   He's co-producing a feature film about his life; is a featured
athlete on Valencia's Internet and documentary outreach program,
``Hangin' with the Boyz''; will travel to Australia for the Sydney
Olympics to interview other featured athletes; and he's negotiating
for a Spanish-language television show, possibly as a game-show
host.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, he works several days a week as a representative
for Castaic Brick, one of his longtime sponsors, and runs a boxing
gym for kids in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Film production on his story is in the early stages. The script
for the film is almost finished, which is a feat in itself: There's
plenty to write about.
</P>
<P>
   Ruelas almost died as a baby, immigrated from Mexico to the U.S.
with his brother as a child, discovered boxing here, broke his arm
in a pro fight, won a world championship in spite of it and
delivered the blows that killed Jimmy Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Could be an interesting film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really amazing,'' Ruelas said. ``You never know what will
happen (whether the film will actually be made) because you know
how Hollywood is. I think it'll happen, though. And, right now, it
feels like winning the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about things.''
</P>
<P>
   Change in schedule: The five fight cards scheduled around the De
La Hoya-Mosley fight are now four. A June 18 card scheduled to be
televised by ABC has been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves a June 15 card at the Universal Amphitheater
featuring Laila Ali and Oba Carr in separate fights; a June 16 card
at Fantasy Springs Casino in Indio with Antonio Diaz facing
Demetrio Ceballos; an afternoon card on June 17 at the Bicycle Club
in Bell Gardens featuring Stevie Johnston on ABC; and the principal
card at Staples on the 17th.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: Shades of the old Mike Tyson?
</P>
<P>
   David Tua took out capable but apparently frightened Obed
Sullivan in 51 seconds Saturday, a dramatic conclusion that will
help sell a prospective bout with champion Lennox Lewis in
November.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what fans want, someone who goes out there and
destroys his opponent,'' Tua's promoter, Dan Goossen, told the
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, also seeking a bout with Lewis, hopes he gets to the
Briton before Tua does.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's angry, mean and hungry,'' Tyson said recently of Tua.
``He's got that look in his eye, like he's ready to kill someone. I
hope it's not Lewis, because I want to end Lewis.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Robert Garcia fought too boldly toward the end of his bout with
Ben Tackie on the Tua-Sullivan undercard and lost a fight he was
winning easily.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, an Oxnard resident and former junior lightweight champ,
was caught with a left hook and stopped in the 10th round.
</P>
<P>
   ``My corner told me to come out and box and fight smart,''
Garcia said of the final round. ``But I'm a warrior. I made a
mistake, but things happen like that in boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   That's two consecutive knockout losses for Garcia. It'll be
tough for him to climb back to the top. ...
</P>
<P>
   Acelino Freitas of Brazil, one of the hottest prospects in
boxing at 25-0 with 25 KOs, faces Lemuel Nelson in a 12-round
junior lightweight bout Saturday on HBO. ...
</P>
<P>
   Arizona made the right decision when it granted Julio Cesar
Chavez a boxing license.
</P>
<P>
   Of course the 37-year-old former champion will get crushed by
WBC super lightweight champ Kostya Tszyu on July 29. Chavez's loss
to journeyman Willy Wise in October seemed to indicate that he's
nothing like the fighter he once was.
</P>
<P>
   However, if anyone has earned the right to give it one last
shot, it's him. He's one of the greatest fighters of all time and
remains as good as many contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be my last fight,'' he said. ``Let me go out with
dignity and honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's just hope he goes out healthy. ...
</P>
<P>
   Colorado has established a boxing commission, which sets the
stage for a fight between native son Stevie Johnston, the WBC
featherweight champ, and former titleholder Jesse James Leija in
September. ...
</P>
<P>
   Evander Holyfield said he has fought - and lost - with injuries
or illness, in Riddick Bowe III (illness), Lennox Lewis I (illness)
and against Michael Moorer (sore shoulder).
</P>
<P>
   And he wasn't about to do it again against John Ruiz. Their bout
was pushed back until at least August after Holyfield tore a muscle
below his ribs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to embarrass myself the way I did when I fought
Lennox Lewis the first time,'' said Holyfield, 37. ``I'm just not
going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield's advisor, Jim Thomas, said his client's injury has
nothing to do with his age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' he said. ``It's a simple athletic injury. It
has nothing to do with age or deterioration. This could happen to
an 18-year old.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
