<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR0605-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stewart gets back on track
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOVER, Del. _ The trophy and six-figure check were appreciated.
But more than anything, Tony Stewart was satisfied with the
reaction from the crowd after winning the MBNA Platinum 400 on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the best thing about this win,'' Stewart said in a
quiet voice. ``Having those people supporting me like that . . . I
haven't had that for a while now.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart has been the subject of controversy in the Winston Cup
Series for more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   Some of it was his own fault. Frustrated after the race at
Richmond, he sped through the garage area and endangered the safety
of spectators and other teams' crew members. After he climbed out
of the No. 20 Pontiac, he was rushed by reporters and kicked a
cameraman.
</P>
<P>
   At The Winston all-star race a week later in Charlotte, Stewart
was criticized by Ward and Jeff Burton for rough driving.
</P>
<P>
   The image of Stewart was severely damaged even more a few days
later when a magazine quoted him as saying he was fed up with many
aspects of the circuit, including being hounded by
autograph-seeking fans and the loss of his privacy as a result of
his sudden rise to stardom last season.
</P>
<P>
   He did not realize the impact of the magazine article until he
was booed by the crowd during the week in Charlotte. Stewart later
apologized for his comments, saying they were taken out of context.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, however, the tide finally appeared to be turning for
the young star, who is sponsored by Atlanta-based Home Depot.
Stewart was a popular figure throughout the weekend at Dover Downs
International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing those fans all around there cheering . . . I wish I had
the words to express (how much it meant to me),'' Stewart said.
``Because the last two weeks have literally been heck for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a nice feeling seeing all those people (cheering) again.
Hopefully that will start building our fan base back up.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart dominated the 400-lap event around ``The Monster Mile,''
leading 242 laps. His only threat came at lap 387 when rookie Matt
Kenseth tried and failed to pass on the inside of the third turn.
Stewart took his first checkered flag of the season, becoming the
12th different driver to win in 13 races this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out of the (chase for the Winston Cup championship)
by any means,'' said Stewart, who moved to ninth in the points
standings. ``I don't think you ever count yourself out with so many
races to go because you never know what can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth finished second. Bobby Labonte finished third and
expanded his lead in the points standings to 82 over Ward Burton,
who finished two laps down and in eighth place.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
