<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HUMANITARIAN-AID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: INEFFECTIVE HUMANITARIAN AID  
 DRUG LAWS THAT MISFIRED  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, June 5:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Humanitarian disasters have emerged as the most complex
challenges facing American foreign policy. There has been strenuous
debate over whether America should get involved when there is
famine in Somalia or Sudan, genocide in Rwanda, mass killings in
East Timor or a refugee exodus in Kosovo. What gets less attention
is the question of how to take effective action when we do get
involved. An internal State Department report provides an unusually
frank assessment of why American action has sometimes been slow or
ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   The study was directed by Morton Halperin, head of the policy
planning staff at the State Department, and James Michel, counselor
to the Agency for International Development. It examines how
Washington responded to three man-made humanitarian disasters _
stemming from armed conflicts in Kosovo, Afghanistan and Sudan _
and one natural disaster, Hurricane Mitch in Central America.
Although the report finds much to applaud, it is also a tale of
poor coordination, missions being duplicated or falling through the
cracks, and confusion inside the administration and the private
humanitarian groups that sometimes cannot be sure with which agency
to work. Confusion over which part of the government was leading
the response to Hurricane Mitch, for example, led to delays in
assessing the damage and getting aid to Central America. Most
important, at many times when American policy was made, no one was
present to remind officials of the humanitarian consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The report can be read as a plea for establishing a single
office to coordinate humanitarian assistance, with a chief who
would participate in high-level meetings the next time we are faced
with a Kosovo or Sudan. This is an eminently sensible
recommendation for the next administration, which is sure to find
itself wrestling with new famines, hurricanes and wars.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of this unclassified assessment have stirred
grumbling inside the State Department for their public bluntness,
especially because their criticisms have received most of the
attention. But they could have hoped for little impact if they had
kept their views classified, and the issue is one that deserves
airing. Halperin and Michel have performed a service by identifying
the shortcomings in America's humanitarian programs, and by
allowing the public to know.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 2136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000604.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4355 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-CAMPAIGN-79     06-04 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-CAMPAIGN-790&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON GETS MIXED REACTION AT SALUTE TO ISRAEL PARADE 
</HEADLINE>
  By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton and Rep. Rick Lazio shook
hands and stood side by side Sunday, both vowing to support the
political and economic stability of Israel. But along the Fifth
Avenue route of the annual Salute to Israel Parade, the intense,
even angry, division among Jews over the two U.S. Senate candidates
was starkly on display.
</P>
<P>
   The parade, like so many others in New York, typically draws a
healthy contingent of vote-seeking politicians.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, the political jockeying was so pervasive and the
crowd seemed so politically engaged that even some organizers said
that campaigning was overshadowing the purpose of the event, to
celebrate the 52nd year of Israeli statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio marched with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, just ahead of the New
York City Police Department marching band. Clinton lined up behind
them, beside Sen. Charles Schumer and a collection of leaders of
Jewish groups.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady proved to be the biggest media attraction,
drawing such a large pack of television cameras and photographers
that her security team stretched out a rope to corral them. But she
also inspired the most vociferous reaction from the crowd, with
spectators sporadically booing, screaming and sometimes even
crudely insulting her as she passed.
</P>
<P>
   Also along the 22-block parade route, in addition to the groups
of school children, religious clubs and community associations,
were three likely future candidates for mayor _ City Comptroller
Alan Hevesi, Public Advocate Mark Green and City Council Speaker
Peter Vallone _ as well as many other state and local officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary brings out passions in people,'' said Green, who
described the crowd as perhaps the most intense he had seen in his
decade of marching in parades in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio and Clinton went to great lengths throughout the day to
try to demonstrate their devotion to Israel, as both candidates, in
what has quickly become a competitive race, clearly recognize the
importance of the large number of Jewish voters in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   But despite their competition for votes, they were quite cordial
with each other. They shook hands and chatted briefly about Lazio's
two daughters during a break in the parade while they stood at a
reviewing stand on Fifth Avenue at 69th Street.
</P>
<P>
   It was Lazio's and Clinton's first joint appearance since
Giuliani dropped out of the nation's highest profile Senate race
last month and Lazio replaced him as the Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio repeatedly spoke Sunday about his support for moving the
U.S. embassy in Israel from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem, to recognize the
city that Israel claims as its capital.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who also supports such a move, spoke more generally
about what she called her longstanding respect for the country and
its people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States has been and will be always there for
Israel,'' she said, drawing applause from crowd, including the
mayor and Lazio. ``And we will always support the Israeli
government and Israeli people as they struggle to find a safe and
secure peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates stayed away from more controversial topics,
such as whether there should be an independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton angered many Jewish voters last year with when she
voiced support for such a state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to take the lead of the state of Israel on this,''
Lazio said Sunday when asked by a reporter about the topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some serious questions about whether or not a
Palestinian state is sustainable, considering the security concerns
of the state of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   But the animosity felt by some in the crowd toward Clinton was
evident on nearly every block, with some holding signs recalling
her embrace last year of Yasser Arafat's wife, Suha, while others
shouted ``Go back to Arkansas,'' mocking her move last year to New
York state.
</P>
<P>
   Mira Hakak, a Queens statistician, held a torn up Clinton
campaign sign in her hands, just above an Israeli flag that was
propped up in her pocketbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``She did not do anything in her life and now she wants to be
our senator,'' said Hakak. ``If she wants to be in Washington, she
should get a job as a lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Emotions ran so high that brief scuffles at times broke out
between the two camps, such as when one backer of Clinton had her
campaign sign pulled out of her hands and torn up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was just a lot of hate,'' said Resi Cooper, 29, of Long
Island, a supporter of Clinton, who said she was nearly knocked
over by Lazio supporters at one point during the parade.
</P>
<P>
   Asked later about being booed at the Parade, Clinton responded:
``I had a great time. I mean, that's democracy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Also amid the crowd were many undecided voters, like Lisa
Rosenzweig, 39, a lawyer from Brooklyn, who said she generally
votes for Democrats, but has not made up her mind in the Senate
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``How's your lip?'' she yelled to Lazio, whose lip was still
swollen from a fall he took in a Memorial Day parade last week on
Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   She later told a reporter that she considered Lazio a worthy
candidate and would not likely decide on her vote until November.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who was campaigning for his second time with Lazio, at
times seemed to attract more attention than the Long Island
congressman, with spectators chanting his name and some even
holding his old Senate campaign signs.
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor appeared to make an effort to let Lazio take the
lead, allowing him to decide when to break away from the parade and
greet supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Both Lazio and Clinton dashed from the end of the Salute to
Israel Parade to the smaller Philippine Day Parade on Madison
Avenue in Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton received a much warmer welcome from this crowd, some of
her supporters so excited that they tried to climb over police
officers to reach her.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
