A4357 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-TV-GOODY-SEX-AZR &LR;      06-04 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-SEX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SEX AND CITY' OUT-CHICKS
 `CHICK TV'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 BY BILL GOODYKOONTZ 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  Remember `Ghost?` You know, the Demi
Moore-Patrick Swayze weeper about true love, short bangs and making
clay pots while a ghost hugs you?
<TEXT>
<P>
   That movie pretty much defines the term ``chick flick.'' It
combined all the elements: the sappy plot, the tear-jerking
emotions, the, you know, romance.
</P>
<P>
   Television has its own version of the chick flick, naturally.
The elements are the same - watch any episode of ``Once and Again''
and before Sela Ward's teenage daughter sheds her first weekly
tear, you'll have the idea - only they're repeated week after week.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't to say real men don't watch ``Once and Again,'' or
didn't hide tears in a darkened theater when ``Unchained Melody''
swelled during ``Ghost.'' Variety, spice of life, like that. But
like prime-time ice skating, this sort of entertainment clearly is
aimed at women.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, TV for chicks that serves as an antidote to
chick TV. And it returns tonight - ``Sex In the City,'' the HBO
series starring Sarah Jessica Parker as Carrie, a New York sex
columnist (based on the ``New York Observer'' writings of the
genuine item, Candace Bushnell).
</P>
<P>
   If you've never seen the program, its title is stunningly
accurate. This is a show about sex, pure and simple. Actually,
that's not true - the sex in ``Sex and the City'' is rarely pure
but is complicated enough to send Dr. Ruth into a screaming fit
(but then, what sex isn't?).
</P>
<P>
   This season, the show's third, is no different. In the first two
episodes, Parker's character dates a politician. So there is some
talk of politics - which leads directly to talk about sex. It also
leads to sex, sort of, sex that by the second episode is so kinky
it would not only be unfair for me to spoil the surprise, but
should it worm past a snoozing editor would also probably cost me
my job for trying.
</P>
<P>
   There is more sex, lots of sex, hotter sex. How much hotter sex
is there than sex leaning against a fire truck?
</P>
<P>
   There is also utterly profane lan guage from the mouths of the
babes, if you'll forgive a sexist term, who hang out with Carrie -
another series trademark.
</P>
<P>
   While we're at it, let's just go ahead and say it: The language
is shocking. And the only reason I can figure why is because you
don't expect beautiful women to talk that way. Or about that kind
of thing (including more terms for the male sex organ than you'll
hear in a junior-high locker room).
</P>
<P>
   Yet the same kind of talk about the same type of subject doesn't
even raise an eyebrow when I hear it on, say, ``The Sopranos,''
because that's how I expect a bunch of mobsters to talk. Guy
mobsters, at that.
</P>
<P>
   Is that fair? Of course not. Yet I don't feel bad for responding
that way, because an underlying premise of ``Sex and the City'' is
that the series is showing me how women really talk, and what they
really talk about - a universe normally off-lim its to guys.
</P>
<P>
   If that's all there was to the show, it would be an interesting
lark, nothing more. What makes ``Sex and the City'' something
better is the occa sional nugget sandwiched in between all the sex
talk and sex action that puts the sometimes desperate antics into
perspective. One of Carrie's friends, for instance, blurts out her
belief that `women really just want to be rescued.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not just something men don't know. According to Carrie,
it's some thing single women in their 30s don't even want to admit
to themselves. Thus we learn another secret women keep.
</P>
<P>
   The real question, of course, is whether it's true - all of it
or any of it, the ambitious sex, the frank sex talk and the
vulnerability that lies just beneath.
</P>
<P>
   You're asking a guy? I don't know. But to its credit, ``Sex and
the City'' does make it seem so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 2139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
