<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4358 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-CONVENTIONS-AZR &LR;      06-04 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVENTIONS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVENTION COVERAGE GROWS ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (MOVING in ``A'' and ``K'' categories)  
 By JON KAMMAN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Move over, TV networks and gavel-to-gavel cable broadcasters.
The Internet is coming to the 2000 political conventions in a big
way.
</P>
<P>
   What one convention official calls an ``astronomical'' growth of
online news will provide a dimension of coverage scarcely imagined
just four years ago, when the first convention Webcasting took
place.
</P>
<P>
   The shift comes as commercial television networks pare back live
coverage of what they increasingly see as a ``canned'' four-day
show that can't sustain the interest of most viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Local stations, too, are showing less and less commitment to
staffing the events. For example, about 30 stations affiliated with
or owned by ABC covered the 1996 convention, but only about half
that many will be going this year, said Michael Huitt, executive
producer of the network's convention coverage.
</P>
<P>
   In the Phoenix area, three of the six largest commercial
television stations will have a presence at the conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Schedules aren't yet firm, but the mainstream networks are
expected to air as little as an hour a day of convention reportage.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves non-stop coverage to be supplied by cable
broadcasters CNN and C-SPAN, by the non-commercial PBS net work
and, increasingly, by online providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see an explosion from all quarters in the
amount of information on the Internet about the convention,'' said
Tim Fitzpatrick, press secretary for the Republican National
Convention, which opens July 31 in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   No one is certain how many of the 15,000 members of the media
covering each convention will represent e-media.
</P>
<P>
   The count is difficult because many holding accreditation will
file video, sound and text both to the traditional print and
electronic outlets and to those organizations' relatively new World
Wide Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, will work exclusively in cyberspace, their
material disseminated by outlets as large as America Online, with
more than 20 million members, and as specialized as a pair of
minority-oriented Web sites, politicallyblack.com and, for Latinos,
www.hola.com.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Internet offers unlimited space and time for both
live and archived online stories, it can fulfill the information
needs of small niche groups and insatiable political junkies alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see it as a way to let Americans personalize, rather than
just localize, the news they receive,'' Fitzpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, (Thomas) P. ``Tip'' O'Neill (the late Democratic
House speaker from Boston) was famous for the adage that all
politics is local. We view it now as all politics is PERSONAL, with
the power of the Internet,'' Fitzpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties are gearing up to Webcast their own coverage. They
also promise opportunities for interactive participation during the
conventions, although for now they won't reveal more than
generalities about possible chat rooms, polling and direct
messaging of officials.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP convention's Web site won't be operating until next
month, Fitzpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, at www.dems2000.com, already are accepting
worldwide input for the party platform that will be adopted at the
Aug. 14-17 convention in Los Angeles, spokesman David Dam said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This convention will make history as the most technologically
sophisticated event ever,'' said Lydia Camarillo, chief executive
for the Democrats' gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Whether all the newfound availability of information will
translate into interest and utilization is open to question,
however.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this year's conventions, using the Internet is still
enough of a novelty and a low-tech experience _ watching 20,000
cheering politicos on a one-inch picture _ that it will be more
like watching the Mars landing a couple of years ago,'' said Steve
Doig, who specializes in computer-assisted journalism as Knight
Professor of Journalism at Arizona State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It offers some wonderful opportunities for many organizations
to very cheaply present their viewpoints,'' Doig said, and it
allows people to view as much as they want whenever they want it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're probably a convention away from what it can be
someday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, although convention Webcasts attracted millions of
visits a day, ``there weren't a lot of Americans who had computers
powerful enough to watch live programming,'' Fitzpatrick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Internet Alley,'' a few out-of-the-way media spaces with
computer connections provided in 1996, will be practically a
boulevard this year, with 55 booths assigned, he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 2147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
