<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COCKFIGHT-RAID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
190 ARRESTED AS POLICE RAID COCKFIGHTING RING IN THE BRONX 
</HEADLINE>
   By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police raided a rundown movie house in the Bronx and
broke up a professional cockfighting ring just as a night of
gambling and bloody fighting was getting started, the authorities
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six people suspected of organizing the spectacle were
arrested. Another 154 people were issued summonses for observing
animal fights.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses and the police said the raid, conducted by about 75
officers who surrounded the building and burst through two
entrances with a battering ram, caught the gamblers by surprise
before the scene turned to bedlam and a chase ensued across the
theater's roof, where some bettors tried to escape by scrambling
down a ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Spectators paid $25 to sit under low-hanging fluorescent lights
in a squalid auditorium while the roosters sliced each other open
and bettors howled with glee or frustration. The 36 people
suspected of organizing the event were each charged with one count
of animal fighting, a felony under state agriculture law.
</P>
<P>
   The theater was the scene of a similar raid in March 1995, when
the police stopped what they said was a national championship
cockfight. Nearly 300 people were arrested or ticketed that night.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Inspector Michael Brooks, commanding officer of the Vice
Enforcement Division, said that during the latest raid, which began
late Saturday and continued into Sunday morning, roosters and men
ran through the building with the police in pursuit. The floors
were soiled with dog feces, blood and feathers. The odor was rank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was horrible,'' he said. ``The place was a real dump.''
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the raid, fire marshals ordered the building
closed.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said the police were still trying to determine who owned
the building and who had promoted the cockfights.
</P>
<P>
   Residents in the area said Sunday that cockfighting returned to
the building last year, as meticulously organized as before.
</P>
<P>
   Bettors wagered $200 to $500 on the roosters of their fancy,
neighbors said. Each fight lasted until one rooster collapsed and
refused to fight on, a condition that often meant death.
</P>
<P>
   The police said they stopped the fights within an hour. Eight
roosters were already dead.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said an undercover detective began attending fights
months ago to gather information on the bird handlers, guards and
money collectors. The authorities said the detective's work enabled
the police to pick out the organizers from the spectators after the
raid.
</P>
<P>
   The police said $14,000 was confiscated and 33 fighting cocks
were taken to the Center for Animal Care and Control in East
Harlem, where they would be humanely killed. Two pit bulls were
also seized. Brooks said the dogs would probably be killed as well.
</P>
<P>
   Cockfighting roosters, which are bred for ferocity, swiftness
and stamina, are too evil-tempered to be adopted as pets and too
tough to eat. Many are also injected with steroids to make them
meaner in a fight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000604.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4363 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-GUNS-CHECKS-NYT &LR;      06-04 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-CHECKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN SALE REJECTION RATE LEVEL AT 2.4% 
</HEADLINE>
   By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ About 204,000 gun sales were rejected after
background checks of the buyers in 1999, the Justice Department
said in a report issued over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   That was a rejection rate of 2.4 percent of the 8.6 million gun
sale applications submitted under federal, state and local laws.
The laws bar the sale of firearms to people with records of felony
conviction or indictment, fugitive status, court restraining
orders, mental illness and misdemeanor domestic violence
convictions.
</P>
<P>
   The report, issued by the department's Bureau of Justice
Statistics, found that the rejection rate was higher at the state
and local level than at the federal level. The reason, it said, was
that the state and local police departments ``have access to more
detailed criminal history records than the FBI.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six states, which encompass more than two-thirds of the
country's population, perform their own background checks. The
other states rely on the FBI to perform the checks. Of the 8.6
million checks last year, the FBI conducted 4.5 million checks, and
state and local agencies performed 4.1 million checks.
</P>
<P>
   The rejection rate for the state and local background checks was
3 percent, compared with a rejection rate of 1.8 percent for
federal checks. The Clinton administration has argued that the
states are better equipped than the FBI to perform background
checks, but some states contend funding constraints preclude paying
for the checks.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Holder, the deputy attorney general, said the gun sale
rejections were part the federal Brady Law effort to keep guns out
of the hands of ``felons, fugitives, domestic abusers and other
persons not legally allowed to have a gun.'' The law is named for
James Brady, the press secretary to President Ronald Reagan who was
wounded an assassination attempt on Reagan in 1981 by a man later
determined to be mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite our success,'' Holder said, ``we must not become
complacent. There are still 89 Americans, including 12 young
people, dying every day from gunshot wounds. We must continue our
efforts to prevent crime and gun violence and our tough enforcement
strategies at the federal, state and local level.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 123,000 gun sales rejected by state and local authorities
last year, 73 percent were prompted by prospective buyers having
records of felony convictions or indictments and 11 percent by
domestic violence convictions or restraining orders.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department said that background checks had resulted
in the rejection of 536,000 gun sales, out of 22.2 million
applications, since the Brady law was passed in 1994 through the
end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The national rejection rate has remained 2.4 percent since 1994,
despite the Nov. 30, 1998, switch to computerized instant checks
and the addition of checks on long-gun purchasers. Only handgun
buyers were checked before.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, a Democrat from New York who began
advocating gun control after her husband was killed and her son
severely wounded in the Long Island Rail Road shooting in 1993,
said Sunday that more money should be provided for the background
checks of prospective gun buyers. ``This is another reason that we
should close the gun show loophole,'' McCarthy said, referring to
the fact that background checks are not required for buyers at gun
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of gun control have blocked efforts to enlarge the
background checks to include purchases at gun shows. With Vice
President Al Gore casting the tie-breaking vote, the Senate voted
in 1999 to include gun shows, but the House of Representatives
deleted the requirement.
</P>
<P>
   A symbolic measure, a resolution that does not have the force of
law, was approved by the Senate last month in a 50-to-49 vote,
urging that all sellers at gun shows be required to conduct checks
on buyers.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy said that the 2.4 percent rejection rate showed that
``ordinary, law-abiding citizens can get a gun'' and that the rate
would be no different at gun shows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000604.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4365 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PUENTE-WAKE-NYT &LR;      06-04 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUENTE-WAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK FANS SAY THEIR FINAL GOODBYES TO TITO PUENTE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUAN FORERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hundreds of people, from world-famous musicians to
retired taxi drivers, came together at a Manhattan funeral chapel
Sunday to say goodbye to the Mambo King.
</P>
<P>
   Tito Puente, the legendary band leader and percussionist, died
Wednesday after half a century of delighting crowds the world over
with his Latin jazz and frenetic salsa. And Sunday, faithful fans
and loyal friends waited for hours for the brief chance to spend a
quiet moment beside hise white coffin.
</P>
<P>
   Mourners started arriving at the Riverside Memorial Chapel on
the Upper West Side as early as 10 a.m., and hours later hundreds
of people remained, waiting in a line that stretched nearly a block
along West 76th Street from the corner of Amsterdam Avenue. For
many, it was an emotional farewell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tearfully saw him, left him a kiss and said goodbye,''
said Michael Terrace, 74, a former professional dancer who often
performed at the old Palladium in Midtown where the Tito Puente
Orchestra solidified its reputation in the 1950s. ``It hurts. It
really hurts. You have to say: `Tito, I enjoyed working with you. I
loved you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Puente, who died at age 77 after suffering complications from
open-heart surgery, will be buried Tuesday after a private funeral
in Nanuet, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   So it was Sunday's seven-hour wake _ along with another wake
Monday between 11 a.m. and 7 p.m. at the chapel _ that gave fans a
chance to bid farewell to El Rey.
</P>
<P>
   Public officials like Peter F. Vallone, the City Council
speaker, and Rep.Jose E. Serrano of the Bronx attended. Latin music
fans penned in behind police sawhorses, meanwhile, reveled in the
collection of young and old Latin musicians who came together to
pay their respects to a man who shaped their music, including Ruben
Blades, the Panamanian singer and actor; Cheo Feliciano, the
baritone; and Tito Nieves, the salsa star.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen musicians that I hadn't seen since I was a little
girl,'' said Cindy Rodriguez, the daughter of the late band leader
Tito Rodriguez, who, with Puente and Machito, are credited with
driving the mambo craze. ``You know, you're not going to see these
people in one place again.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who spent hours in line waiting to get into the chapel
were rewarded with a walk up a short flight of stairs to a chapel
where Puente's body, clad in a white suit and white tie, lay in a
coffin surrounded by white orchids. Eight pictures of Puente, one
of him in a Navy uniform during World War II and the others showing
him banging on his timbales with delight, were placed around the
coffin.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, the mourners passed the coffin, many saying a brief
prayer or kissing the plastic glass that covered the open coffin.
</P>
<P>
   Esperanza Rengifo of Queens carried four of Puente's 118 albums,
clutching them to her chest as she recalled how important his music
had been to her. ``I've been here since 8 a.m.,'' said Rengifo, 73,
as she neared the entrance to the chapel at 1 p.m. ``I missed Mass
to be here, so I asked God for forgiveness. I said `I'll have to
miss Mass because I need to see Tito Puente.'''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who came, it seemed, had a personal memory of the
band leader: salseros who danced to his music in the Palladium half
a century ago, friends who laughed and joked with a man famous for
his sense of humor, musicians who performed with him in smoky
neighborhood joints and world-class music halls.
</P>
<P>
   Luz Pagan said being so close to Puente reminded her of the days
when she paid $1.50 to get into the Palladium to dance for hours to
his music. ``Imagine, how great it was,'' she said. ``To hear those
timbales. You would feel it in your blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Others carried Puerto Rican flags in honor of one of the
island's most famous sons, who was born in 1923 in East Harlem to
Puerto Rican migrants and is credited with spreading the island's
music to far corners of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of people wore T-shirts or buttons featuring the
musician's famed pudgy cheeks and irascible grin that they had
bought from vendors near the chapel. Some parked their cars nearby
and cranked up their stereos, playing ``Oye Como Va'' and other
famous songs composed by Puente.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had to come here,'' said Pedro Aguilar, a dancer
known as Cuban Pete, who first met Puente in 1949. ``I just
couldn't miss this. I wanted to say my goodbyes properly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
