<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' DRAFT GURU SAYS TALENT POOL WEAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Major League Baseball's 2000 First-Year
Player Draft begins today, and five of the first 64 selections
belong to the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, that might not be the boon it would appear to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there were quality in the draft pool and depth, it would be
a much more comforting feeling,'' said Chuck McMichael, the
Rangers' director of scouting. ``But it's not that good of a draft,
in my opinion. I've sat in 20 draft rooms now, and it's one of the
weakest I've seen. Now, that's not to say we're not going to get
good players.''
</P>
<P>
   Signing that amateur talent, though, will be a costly endeavor
regardless.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have one selection in the first round (No. 25), two
supplemental first-round choices (Nos. 35 and 39) and two during
the second round (Nos. 56 and 64).
</P>
<P>
   The five players chosen with those selections during the 1999
draft received signing bonuses totaling $4.19 million, and that
figure could exceed $5 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have the draft picks, you're probably paying that
money to free agents,'' Rangers general manager Doug Melvin said.
``Yet, they're unproven, and that's the risk you run. The draft
does get very expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers lost their first-round selection to the St. Louis
Cardinals for signing left-hander Darren Oliver as a free agent,
but the organization received the New York Mets' first-round choice
as compensation for losing third baseman Todd Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the Rangers received supplemental first-round selections
for Zeile and right-hander Aaron Sele, whom the Seattle Mariners
signed as a free agent. The Rangers also received the Mariners'
second-round selection as compensation for Sele's departure.
</P>
<P>
   So, what will the Rangers do with their first five selections?
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, McMichael would prefer two power arms, a power bat, a
pure hitter and a middle infielder/center fielder with speed and
the potential to become a leadoff hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, McMichael cannot predict with any degree of certainty who
will be available when he makes the 25th pick. On Friday evening,
McMichael estimated that he spent 12 of the previous 24 hours on
the telephone attempting to gain a sense of who would be chosen
before the Rangers' first selection.
</P>
<P>
   McMichael's efforts produced 63 possibilities, leaving him
little idea of who will be available at No. 25.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
