<HEADLINE>
GLYNN GETS START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers will recall right-handed pitcher
Ryan Glynn from Triple-A Oklahoma and start him tonight against the
Los Angeles Dodgers, manager Johnny Oates said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn will be replacing left-hander Darren Oliver, who
complained of a ``dead arm'' after each of his past two starts.
Oates, though, expects Oliver to return to the rotation and start
Sunday against the Colorado Rockies in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Glynn went 3-1 with a 3.17 earned-run average in 11 appearances
(10 starts) for the RedHawks this season, but he missed his
previous scheduled start with a finger blister.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers plan to option outfielder Scott Podsednik to
Double-A Tulsa to make room for Glynn on the 25-man roster. The
Rangers purchased Podsednik's contract Saturday from Tulsa.  &QL; 
Kapler on schedule
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers expect outfielder Gabe Kapler to return to the
lineup as their center fielder Friday against the Rockies, manager
Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler will begin his second medical rehabilitation assignment
with Double-A Tulsa and play five innings tonight, seven innings
tomorrow and nine innings Wednesday before rejoining the Rangers,
Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler went on the 15-day disabled list May 4 after suffering a
partial tear to his right quadriceps muscle. The Rangers plan for
Kapler to replace Ruben Mateo (fracture, right femur) as their
center fielder after the latter suffered a season-ending injury
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve outfielders Scarborough Green and Jason McDonald will
share playing time in center field until Kapler's return, Oates
said.  &QL; 
Sheldon plays
</P>
<P>
   Reserve infielder Scott Sheldon logged his first start this
season at third base for Mike Lamb, who strained the trapezius
muscle in his right shoulder Saturday during a 4-3 loss to the
Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The injury did not prevent Lamb from playing, but Oates chose to
give the left-handed hitter the evening off against Arizona
left-hander Omar Daal. Lamb strained the muscle swinging the bat
during his final plate appearance Saturday.  &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Reserve infielder Frank Catalanotto likely will make his first
start defensively since May 18 tonight against the Dodgers, Johnny
Oates said. Catalanotto likely will spell second baseman Luis
Alicea.
</P>
<P>
   The first-inning home runs by catcher Ivan Rodriguez and first
baseman Rafael Palmeiro marked the second time this season the
Rangers hit back-to-back homers.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's Craig Counsell snapped a 210 at-bat homerless streak
with his second-inning solo shot off right-hander Esteban Loaiza.
It was Counsell's first home run since hitting one off of
Philadelphia's Wayne Gomes on July 24, 1998. / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
