<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ENID NEMY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   I was looking for an old fan in the attic and found instead a
48-star flag and the sleek and slender wedding dress I wore 50
years ago when I, too, was sleek and slender. And a scrapbook from
the years 1943-1948 with the contents pure New York nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   1943: City of New York transit pass, 5 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Menu: Ed Winston's tropical bar in Greenwich Village, gin and
tonic, 53 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Date: Henry Grunwald.
</P>
<P>
   1944: Philharmonic ticket, Carnegie Hall, $3.60.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket: First airplane ride, Washington to New York, $11.65.
</P>
<P>
   1945: Newspaper clipping, Brooklyn residents offer drinks from
first-floor windows to celebrate end of war in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Pin: V-J Day.
</P>
<P>
   1946: Dance, American Veterans Committee, $1.50.
</P>
<P>
   Playbill: ``Harvey,'' 48th Street Theater, Frank Fay.
</P>
<P>
   No fan.
</P>
<P>
   _ BARBARA COLE FEIDEN
</P>
<P>
   Thomas E. Healy and his wife, Jane, both outdoor enthusiasts who
live in Vail, Colo., were visiting their children and grandchildren
in Manhattan last month and enjoying an afternoon in Central Park.
Near their picnic spot, a 40-ish father was playing, quite
raucously, with his son. He eventually climbed quite far up a
small, budding tree to demonstrate either his enthusiasm for the
day or perhaps his retained prowess.
</P>
<P>
   As he reached a level of about 15 feet, shouting all the way, he
grabbed a branch that was apparently covered with some unpleasant
natural residue. Healy, much amused, reported the reaction _ ``With
much surprise, this obvious city dweller exclaimed: `Can you
believe it? There have been birds in this tree!'''
</P>
<P>
   SUBWAY
</P>
<P>
   I stand and wait at the platform gate
</P>
<P>
   this morning I'm running a little late
</P>
<P>
   the train is nowhere to be found
</P>
<P>
   the tunnel is not making a sound.
</P>
<P>
   I stand and shuffle my feet back and forth
</P>
<P>
   this is a daily occurrence, of course
</P>
<P>
   people are gathering, they are close at hand
</P>
<P>
   we are all huddled in this subterranean land.
</P>
<P>
   I stand and lean myself against a pole
</P>
<P>
   now I begin to fidget and stroll
</P>
<P>
   cursing to myself when will it come
</P>
<P>
   for I'm part of this frenzy and have succumbed.
</P>
<P>
   _ JEFF BURGESS
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   I have lived for the last 30 years in a building housing people
in the arts, have developed a nodding acquaintance with some
tenants and am friendlier with others in varying degrees. The other
day, I got into an elevator with two other original tenants, an
actor I've seen on screen but whose name I don't know, and a woman
I know by name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, Sheila,'' I greeted her. She nodded and smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is your name Sheila?'' the actor asked. She nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he said, ``I've been calling you Lillian for years and
you never corrected me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she replied, ``and you never heard me answer you,
either, did you?''
</P>
<P>
   _ DOLORES DU BOIS
</P>
<P>
   One of the homework tasks that Susan Mayerowitz gave her
second-grade class was to name three bodies of water. One child, no
slouch at keeping up with current trends, wrote: ``Pellegrino, Deer
Park and Evian.''
</P>
<P>
   When it isn't used for transit information, the message board
inside the token booth at the 71st/Continental Avenue subway
station in Forest Hills, Queens, carries inspirational quotes put
up by the staff. Donald Singer particularly liked this one: ``It is
only with the heart that one can see rightly. What is essential is
invisible to the eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Elaine Sloan was walking up Fifth Avenue when she saw a homeless
man with a pit bull by his side and a pushcart loaded with
paraphernalia. She asked if he would be willing to give up the dog
if she could find it a home. When he replied in the affirmative,
she said she would need some time to work on it and asked how she
could connect with him again.
</P>
<P>
   In an instant, he pulled out a cell phone. ``Let me give you my
number,'' he said. She gave him her office number and the two
exchanged calls for a couple of weeks, but Sloan had no luck
placing the dog. Both man and dog have since disappeared. The cell
phone still rings, but there's no answer.
</P>
<P>
   A CITY GIRL'S LAMENT
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there's beauty out here in the country
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of flowers and trees.
</P>
<P>
   And as I rejoice in the bounties of nature,
</P>
<P>
   I sneeze and I sneeze and I sneeze.
</P>
<P>
   _ ELEANOR BESEN
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   It happened on a crowded 86th Street crosstown bus, one of those
double-size buses with accordion pleats. At Central Park West,
there were a number of people waiting to get on and off, and I was
pleased when the driver finally closed the door, waiting for the
light to change. As it was, I was going to be late for an
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a woman from the back came forth holding something and
called out: ``He dropped his wallet. Can you catch him?''
</P>
<P>
   The driver asked, ``Do you know which one it was?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I'm sure,'' the woman said. ``He was a heavy-set man who
just got off.''
</P>
<P>
   The driver opened the door and honked vigorously, but no one
turned around.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, the driver said: ``Go find him. He must be just
around the corner. I'll wait for you.''
</P>
<P>
   When the woman hesitated, looking down at the small child she
was with, several people said: ``Don't worry, we'll take care of
the child. Go.''
</P>
<P>
   Off she ran, rounded a corner and came back in a minute or two,
smiling, triumphant and empty-handed. She had found him. He was
flabbergasted and, of course, very grateful.
</P>
<P>
   As she climbed back onto the bus, we all cheered, and it was
almost as if we had all participated in this good deed. All that
day, I glowed with the memory, and every time I think of it, it
makes me proud to be a New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   _ JANE S. GOULD
</P>
<P>
   Louise Weiss depressingly relates the following tale of a
telephone call to Citibank customer service.
</P>
<P>
   L.W.: ``I'd like to know the location of ATMs in Norway that
will accept my Citicard.''
</P>
<P>
   Citibank: ``Is that in ... which state?''
</P>
<P>
   L.W.: ``It's in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Citibank: ``Oh, Europe.'' Long silence. ``Exactly where is
Norway located? In which country?''
</P>
<P>
   L.W.: ``Norway is a country.''
</P>
<P>
   Citibank then gave her another number where, after listening to
Barber's Adagio for Strings, she got a mechanical voice that
started with Andorra and eventually informed her that there are 740
ATMs in Norway. The country. In Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
