<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ERSTAD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD HAS TURNED IT AROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ It's three hours before the first pitch of the
day as the sweltering sun of a late spring afternoon bakes the
baseball diamond at Edison International Field.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the air conditioned confines of the Angels clubhouse,
left fielder Darin Erstad is busy studying videotape of Dodger
pitchers as he and his teammates begin this year's round of
Interleague play.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad, who turned 26 Sunday, is in the midst of a ritual that
has made him one of the American League's most dangerous hitters
this season. Through Friday night Erstad possessed the league's
second best average of .372. His plate presence has helped keep the
Angels the chase for the American League Western Division title.
That's a far cry from 1999 when Erstad finished the year batting a
dismal .253 on a franchise that was among baseball's all-time
worst.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Erstad was named the American League Player of the
Week. In the course of six games he hit .481, with 13 hits in 27
at-bats -- including a triple and four home runs. His slugging
percentage of 1.000 lead the league.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the difference?
</P>
<P>
   ``This year the hits are falling,'' Erstad explained. ``Last
year they weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   It might be as simple as that, but there's more to the science
of hitting than dumb luck. It takes hard work and dedication, two
qualities that Angels' manager Mike Scioscia claims Erstad has in
abundance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darin's an All-Star caliber player,'' Scioscia said. ``And I
think he's rebounded from an off year last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the leadoff hitter he's really in a swing position where
you have to drive in runs and set the table for other hitters and
he's done both magnificently and become one of the premeir hitters
in our league this year.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for Erstad's comeback might e the fact that he's
played without injury this season. Still another might be the fact
that he hasn't had to bounce around from position to position in
the outfield or from spot to spot in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, he's committed to the team, Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it would faze him to do anything that would help
us win,'' Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Troy Glaus agreed with Scioscia noting that Erstad is
as responsible for the Angels success this season as anyone on the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you get a leadoff hitter hitting .370, that helps
everyone out,'' Glaus said. ``I mean Mo Vaughn has 40-something
RBIs and a lot of them are (Erstad).
</P>
<P>
   ``So what he's doing this year helps everybody out,'' Glaus
added. ``The more he gets on base, the more chances we have to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad's teammates all say his daily ritual before a game plays
a key role in Erstad's performance on the field. While the ritual
varies slightly from day to day there is also some consistency to
the routine.
</P>
<P>
   After watching videotape Friday, Erstad spent 10 minutes
preparing his by rubbing and scraping the shaft with pine tar
wrapped in a rag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to get a bat ready for play so this is just something I
do,' Erstad explained. ``Sometimes there's a glossiness on a bat
and by doing this you get a rough edge feel to it. I just like to
get it so there's that rough stuff on there.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the Angels take batting practice about two hours
before the opening pitch. Erstad is the first one on the field and
while he waiting his turn, he hits balls off a tee.
</P>
<P>
   Batting practice begins with two bunts, a grounder, then long
flies to the outfield. On Friday, Erstad took the fifth batting
practice pitch he saw and effortlessly ripped it into the right
field stands.
</P>
<P>
   After that Erstad retreats to the clubhouse to finish preparing
for the game. The hard work all pays off. In his first at bat
Friday night, Erstad cranked a hit to right. Before the night had
ended, Erstad was 2-for-5 at the plate with an RBI as his team
defeated the Dodgers 12-5.
</P>
<P>
   As the first half of the 2000 season draws to a close, the
Angels hope that Erstad will contine to perform with the
consistency he has shown this far. For his part, Erstad said he
will do his best.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the leadoff hitter that's my job and that's all I'm
concentrating on is getting on base,'' he said. ``I want to get on
base so that guys like Mo Vaughn and Tim Salmon can do their jobs.
``If I can do that, then the offense and the team is going to be in
a lot better shape than it was last year. That's what I'm working
for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
