<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLSON NEWS ISN'T PROMISING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Already miffed by home-plate umpire Chris
Guccione's strike zone and Todd Hollandsworth's sore hamstring, Los
Angeles Dodgers manager Davey Johnson wasn't ready for a Gregg
Olson update after such a frustrating loss.
</P>
<P>
   Olson's scheduled rehabilitation outing for Single-A San
Bernardino was scrapped Sunday when the reliever experienced more
pain in his arm while warming up in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Olson, disabled since April 11 with a right forearm strain,
played catch before heading to the bullpen. After throwing three
warm-up pitches, he was shut down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeez. That's amazing,'' a flabbergasted Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Olson's setback was disappointing considering the 33-year-old
was optimistic about returning soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just need to prove to everybody else that I'm pain-free and
I'm throwing the way I'm supposed to,'' Olson said Friday. ``The
bullpen was throwing so well early on. I'd like to be off (the
disabled list) right now and be able to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Herges and Antonio Osuna struggled Sunday, Herges blowing a
7-5 lead in the eighth and Osuna issuing three walks and hitting a
batter to allow the winning run in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' concern of finding healthy and effective relievers
makes Hollandsworth's updated condition even more difficult to
stomach.
</P>
<P>
   The center fielder pulled up lame chasing a fly ball Saturday
and suffered a pulled right hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth's status is technically day-to-day, but Johnson
calls that diagnosis just that: technical.
</P>
<P>
   ``How bad it is, you're looking at day-to-day, but
(Hollandsworth is out) at least a week,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had already lost one outfielder over the weekend
when Geronimo Berroa was placed on the disabled list with a bone
bruise on his left foot.
</P>
<P>
   Makeup game: The Dodgers' April 17 home rainout against the
Houston Astros will be made up Thursday at 6:10 p.m. at Dodger
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   That open date in the schedule was one of just two off days for
the Dodgers in June and is sandwiched between interleague series
with Texas and Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   For the record: Eric Karros' first-inning, three-run homer
Sunday was the first baseman's 227th career home run with the
Dodgers, leaving him one shy of tying Ron Cey's Los Angeles record
of 228.
</P>
<P>
   Karros ranks fifth combining the Brooklyn/L.A. years. Duke
Snider (389), Gil Hodges (361), Roy Campanella (242) and Cey hold
the top four spots.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Shortstop Mark Grudzielanek went 0 for 4 Sunday
and snapped a streak of 21 consecutive games reaching base safely
(via a base hit, walk or hit by pitch). Right fielder Shawn Green
had two hits and has reached safely in 50 of 53 games played in
2000. ... The Dodgers have the 17th pick in today's free-agent
draft. Baseball America's mock draft has the Dodgers choosing Miami
prep shortstop David Espinosa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
