<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000604.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4373 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-LANGUAGE-AZR &LR;      06-04 1578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-LANGUAGE-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    E-MAIL IS HELPING TO RESHAPE THE LANGUAGE(a) 
 &HT;    (Duplication warning: MOVING IN ``A'' AND ``L'' CATEGORIES) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BARBARA YOST (a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AFAIK, I'll BRB, FWIW. Until then, I'll TTYL. Time flies,
IYKWIMAITYD.
</P>
<P>
   YWIA.
</P>
<P>
   Sanskrit? Hieroglyphics? Osco-Umbrian?
</P>
<P>
   If this looks like some indecipherable ancient language, rest
assured you won't need the Rosetta Stone to translate it, just a
working knowledge of e-mail jargon, a dialect that compresses
English into as many acronyms as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: As far as I know, I'll be right back, for what it's
worth. Until then, I'll talk to you later. Time flies, if you know
what I mean, and I think you do.
</P>
<P>
   Are e-mail and the Internet changing the English language?
</P>
<P>
   Of course they are. Everything changes language, especially
time, technology and politics.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the epic poem (beginitalic)Beowulf,(enditalic) written
more than 1,000 years ago in Old English. For modern readers, it's
almost incomprehensible, resembling a cross between Norse and
Latin:
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic) Oft Scyld Scefing(enditalic)
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic) monegum maegbum(enditalic)
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic) egsode eorl,(enditalic)
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic) feascaft funden;(enditalic)
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic) weox under wolcnum (enditalic){hellip}
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward to the 14th century and try to read Geoffrey
Chaucer's (beginitalic)Canterbury Tales.(enditalic) The text is a
little easier than (beginitalic)Beowulf (enditalic)but still
something of a stumper without a glossary: ``Whan that Aprill, with
his shoures soote, the droghte of March hath perced to the roote
{hellip} ``
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare's plays, written in the late 1500s and early 1600s,
are easier still, but no one would confuse them with Arthur Miller:
``Romeo, Romeo, wherefore art thou Romeo?''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Internet arrives with its own brand of poetry: ``Forget
600 megahertz, this baby is running at a gigahertz through a RAM
bus big enough to download twice the information.''
</P>
<P>
   To the uninitiated, it might as well be a line from Chaucer.
</P>
<P>
   Language experts are not alarmed. They neither condemn nor
condone the evolution but simply watch with interest as technology
plays a hand in how we communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing you can do about it,'' says Alleen Pace
Nilsen, linguist and English professor at Arizona State University.
``That's like saying is rain all right. {hellip} It's just where we
happen to be right now.''
</P>
<P>
   More formal writing, Nilsen says, probably won't be affected by
acronyms and the casual structure of computer language (spelling
and punctuation are lax, subjects are often omitted: ``Hope to see
you soon'').
</P>
<P>
   And don't despair that e-mailspeak will change English so much
that some of us will be tempted to leap off the Tower of Babble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's self-regulating,'' says Elly Van Gelderen, ASU linguist
and associate professor of English. ``If you don't understand
someone anymore, you go back to what's slightly more standard.''
</P>
<P>
   What's standard?
</P>
<P>
   That question could not have been answered 300 years ago. Until
English was codified around 1700, when the printing press was well
established, spellings and grammar were inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   Pronunciation, while difficult to determine before recorded
speech, was also subject to the whims of time. Between the eras of
Chaucer and Shakespeare came the Great Vowel Shift, where English
vowels played a game of musical chairs. In Chaucer's time, the word
``meat'' was pronounced ``mate.'' ``House'' was pronounced
``hoos.''
</P>
<P>
   Over succeeding centuries, those pronunciations changed, though
linguists are at a loss to explain exactly why.
</P>
<P>
   War can change language when conquering armies bring in their
own vocabularies. When William I of Normandy invaded Saxon England
in 1066, the English language was enriched with French influences
and became the most important language in the world.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Creativity can change language. People invent new words.
Shakespeare was the first to use such terms as pedant,
assassination, obscene and frugal, though all have roots in Latin
or Greek.
</P>
<P>
   The invention of words often involves combining ``morphemes,''
the smallest meaningful units of language, such as prefixes and
suffixes. Your children know about morphemes. They're the basis of
the names for Pokeman characters, which have the ring of
familiarity: Squirtle, Wartortle, Blastoise, Bulbasaur, Charlizard,
Charmeleon.
</P>
<P>
   Some words are created because they sound like the objects they
describe, a device called onomatopoeia. But not every ear hears
these sounds the same.
</P>
<P>
   Consider ``Snap! Crackle! Pop!'' the sound Rice Krispies make.
Sounds logical? Think again.
</P>
<P>
   In Austria the cereal says, ``Piff! Paff! Poff!'' In South
America, it's ``Pim! Pum! Pam!'' And in Japan, ``Pitchie! Patchi!
Putchi!''
</P>
<P>
   Invention can be the mother of language. When scientists began
to genetically engineer foodstuffs, someone dubbed it
``frankenfood,'' but the term never quite caught on. The life span
of a new word depends on who invents it, who uses it and how
relevant it is.
</P>
<P>
   With the arrival of the automobile at the turn of the century
came a new vocabulary to name new parts. Who can forget the fabled
Dynaflow, a transmission developed by Chrysler?
</P>
<P>
   We borrow words from old technology to describe new technology.
The word ``car'' comes from the previous mode of transportation,
the carriage. The word ``carriage'' had come from ``chariot.''
</P>
<P>
   And we still ``roll up'' our car windows even though most are
power-driven these days and simply rise with the flip of a switch
instead of a crank.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the Internet to see how software writers are giving us
familiar terms for cyberspace functions. We ``bookmark'' favorite
Web sites. We store material in ``folders.'' We use ``yellow
pages'' and ``channels.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are also new words, and technology has always expanded
our vocabulary. Since the earliest times, objects have needed
names.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy who invented the wheel had to come up with a word to
describe it,'' notes James W. Ney, ASU professor emeritus of
linguistics.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout history, subsets of society have invented their own
vocabulary. American miners in the late 19th and early 20th
centuries developed a language called Bootlink. In the 1950s and
'60s, Blacks introduced such terms as ``jazz me, baby,'' ``let it
all hang out,'' ``beat to his socks'' (which evolved into the White
term, the ``Beat Generation'') and ``funky.''
</P>
<P>
   Teenagers are notorious for creating their own slang - from
``twenty-three skiddoo'' in the 1920s to ``tubular'' and ``grody to
the max'' in the 1990s. Slang is popular because it forges unity
within a group, what Van Gelderen calls an ``identity marker.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's appealing because it's forbidden,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Awesome.
</P>
<P>
   When slang is unique to a particular field or industry it's
called jargon. Newspaper jargon uses such words as ``obit,''
``graf,'' ``lede,'' ``typo.''
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officers talk about ``jumpers,'' ``901H'' (dead
body), ``m.o.'' (modus operandi, or motive).
</P>
<P>
   In computers, technogeeks toss around words like ``gigabyte,''
``terabyte,'' ``RAM bus,'' ``serial port.''
</P>
<P>
   While acronyms have become popular in computer language, they
are not a new device. The German language has always been full of
acronyms, Van Gelderen says. In America, they enjoyed great
popularity in the 1940s, when divers Jacques Cousteau and Emile
Gagnan invented scuba equipment, or Self-Contained Underwater
Breathing Apparatus, and the American military gave us the snafu
(Situation Normal, All Fouled Up).
</P>
<P>
   Today, the word is ``fubar'' - Fouled Up Beyond All Recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Language is identity and power. Ruling forces try to exert their
authority by crushing language. As waves of immigrants arrived in
America in the 19th century, many were forbidden to speak their
native languages, and bilingualism remains controversial.
</P>
<P>
   Language separates people by class. In George Bernard Shaw's
play (beginitalic)Pygmalion(enditalic) aristocrat Henry Higgins
elevates the social standing of Eliza Doolittle by teaching her
proper English.
</P>
<P>
   Today it is not so much a particular class that embraces
computer language as it is a generation. But while young
entrepreneurs created the Internet, they are now aging and bringing
with them the power to shape the vocabulary, Nilsen says.
</P>
<P>
   Invention takes power and money, traditionally vested in the
hands of adults.
</P>
<P>
   While not all Internet and e-mail influences will be permanent,
some will remain, Nilsen predicts the creativity to invent words,
informal spelling and punctuation and the trend toward
``bicapitalization'' - HarperCollins, DreamWorks, PlayStation.
</P>
<P>
   For those who fear English might change too rapidly, Ney points
to forces that stabilize language. In the 15th century, the
invention of the printing press began the move toward
standardization of spelling. Today, broadcast networks standardize
speech.
</P>
<P>
   But computer communication is democratic. With the proliferation
of personal Web sites, anyone can forge a new lexicon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GMTA.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Great minds think alike.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; G/G now.
</P>
<P>
   (Gotta go.)
</P>
<P>
   Or is it too archaic to sign off with, ``Catch you on the flip
side''?
</P>
<P>
   We thought so.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at Barbara.Yost(a)Arizona Republic.com or
(602)444-7936.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
