<HEADLINE>
LIVE! NUDE! AND LEGAL! ARTIST GETS HIS NAKED PHOTO
</HEADLINE>
  By SHAILA K. DEWAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the moment Sunday morning when the flat, pink glow
of dawn gave way to yellow sunlight and shadow, Spencer Tunick
announced that his photo shoot was complete.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred-fifty-two naked models, who had been lying on an
empty stretch of Delancey Street in Manhattan, under the
Williamsburg Bridge, sprang to their feet and applauded.
</P>
<P>
   The moment was triumphant, or at least worry-free, for Tunick,
who is known for his photographs of nudes in public places, and for
being arrested for taking them. On Saturday, the U.S. Supreme Court
said the city could not stop him from staging such pictures, and
Tunick said he hopes the decision will end a long First Amendment
battle.
</P>
<P>
   With a handful of police officers looking on, Tunick said he was
thankful that he could work without the fear of being arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a victory for the body as an art object, not a sexual
object or a recreational object,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Finney, a frequent model for Tunick, said the photographs,
which often show bodies arranged in abstract forms, emphasized
people's similarities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like when you watch those shows on the Discovery Channel
and you see a herd of antelope,'' Finney said. ``This is like a
herd of naked people. We're so used to looking at the clothes to
define a person.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the shoot was over, on went hooded sweatshirts, silk
skirts, bike shorts and jeans. Many of the models, all volunteers,
headed to Ratner's restaurant, a few blocks away, for a celebratory
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   There, Tunick, 33, moved from table to table, jittery from the
morning's high-speed logistics. A district court judge had granted
him 15 minutes for the shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Tunick began shooting nudes in public in 1992, when he posed a
naked man in front of Independence Hall in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found that people paid more attention to my backgrounds when
I placed a nude person in front of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tunick has been arrested several times on charges that vary from
unlawful assembly to exposure of a person, but the charges against
him have always been dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   When Tunick began to find police waiting for him at the
appointed time and place of his photography shoots, he said he
decided in 1999 to sue New York City in federal court, seeking,
among other things, an injunction to prevent his future arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hess, the city's corporation counsel, said the city had
received no complaints about the shoots. But, he contrasted
Tunick's photography in public to theater productions that viewers
choose to see: ``People who do not choose to watch it are being
exposed to it.'' He .
</P>
<P>
   Tunick said he knew that shooting nude people en masse- was not
always appropriate: ``I don't think I could do this in the middle
of the day in front of Macy's.''.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
