<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4379 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-COL-SENATE-RACE-NY     06-04 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-SENATE-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: CANDIDATES WHO AGREE TO DISAGREE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOYCE PURNICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Say what you will about the shake-up in New York's
Senate race _ and there is so much to say that we'll be reading
about it in the history books _ Rudolph Giuliani's withdrawal has
given the public a choice.
</P>
<P>
   We had one before, but on personality much more than on
substance, because Hillary Rodham Clinton and the mayor agreed on
most major issues. Not so Clinton and Rick Lazio, Giuliani's
successor as the Republican candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady and the congressman from Long Island do share
some of the same positions and give themselves similar labels: He
calls himself ``mainstream'' and she calls herself a ``centrist.''
But you get the impression that these two candidates would often
vote differently in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Well, he is ``mainstream'' enough to get the support of the
Conservative Party, which rejected Giuliani as too moderate. And
Clinton is ``centrist'' enough to win support from the Liberal
Party, which is mainly in business to pursue patronage jobs, not an
ideology. But this time the old label fits.
</P>
<P>
   Except for her support for the death penalty and lukewarm
embrace of welfare reform, it is difficult to find an issue on
which the first lady is not liberal _ which she cannot acknowledge,
because her opponents use the ``l'' word as a synonym for
``extremist.''
</P>
<P>
   The Conservatives line up for patronage, too, but the
Conservative Party also embraces a strong eponymous ideology,
marked by opposition to abortion, to gay rights and to affirmative
action.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio does not agree with the Conservatives on every issue, but
if he wins it is logical for voters to at least expect the party to
have access to him and a claim on loyalty, just as liberals would
to Clinton. And he does support the party's position on an issue of
the greatest concern to the party and its leader Michael Long _
opposition to what critics of the procedure call partial-birth
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio supports both fundamental abortion rights and many curbs
on abortion. For instance, he voted for a ban on Medicaid coverage
for abortions, against abortions for women in federal prisons,
against allowing military women to get privately financed abortions
in military hospitals overseas, against human embryo research.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio strongly objects to so-called partial-birth abortions,
often inaccurately described as dealing only with a rare,
gruesome-sounding procedure used in late-term abortions. Critics
want the procedure banned; supporters argue that congressional
legislation is so vaguely written that it could prohibit common
procedures early in a pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has no voting record, of course, but says she supports
abortion rights without restrictions, and she won the endorsement
of the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League. On
the other issue where the two candidates differ most starkly, gun
control, Clinton backs comprehensive gun-control measures, and
Lazio supports some regulations but not others.
</P>
<P>
   He voted for the Brady Bill, which put a five-day waiting period
on the purchase of guns, and for a ban on the sale of assault
weapons. But he also has reservations about gun licensing and
registration, which he calls ``speculative.''
</P>
<P>
   This is interesting because his congressional district is in
Suffolk County, which has some of the strongest registration and
licensing regulations in the country. Suffolk requires anybody
purchasing a handgun to register with the county Police Department
or the sheriff, and to undergo an initial background check and
another to renew every five years.
</P>
<P>
   County officials say that there are 30,900 licensed gun owners
in Suffolk and that the regulations work well.
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control advocates say that national registration would help
cut down on gun trafficking _ critical to states like New York,
where most crimes, including the recent massacre at Wendy's in
Queens, are committed with guns originally sold out of state. There
seems little doubt that the issue will be going before the next
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative future of the abortion debate is more
complicated, related to a pending Supreme Court decision on
abortion, to who wins the presidency and to whom he might nominate
to fill Supreme Court vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe _ in fact, probably _ New Yorkers will vote less on
ideology than on intangibles, like temperament. But at least for
the purists, Lazio and Clinton will be able to debate those
positions on which they disagree. From the perspectives of
mainstream centrists, that is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
