<P>
   (NYT6) BOISE, Idaho -- June 4, 2000 -- JUDGES-POLITICS --
Contests for state judgeships around the country have become
bruising multimillion dollar political affairs that critics say are
threatening the independence of the nation's state courts. Cathy
Silak lost re-election to the Idaho Supreme Court in May in a
campaign that questioned her views on abortion and same-sex
marriage. ``You now have the active involvement of political
parties and special interest groups and individuals with special
axes to grind,'' says Silak. (Glenn Oakley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- June 4, 2000 -- NY-NUDE-PHOTO-SHOOT -- A mass
of bodies evoking a hilly landscape shaded in the tones of human
flesh on Delancey Street in Manhattan near the Williamsburg Bridge
shortly after sunrise, Sunday. The mass disrobing by the East River
was for a photo session viewed by many as a symbol of artistic
freedom, especially photographer Spencer Tunick. Tunick says the
photos depict ``a living organism of hundreds of bodies forming a
landscape, the relationship between the anonymity of public space
and the human body.'' (Richard Perry/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) JERUSALEM -- June 4, 2000 -- ISRAEL-SECURITY -- Israel's
secret service has tightened security around Prime Minister Ehud
Barak, news reports say, as some Jewish settlers warn that the
domestic climate could turn ugly and violent quickly if the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks move forward. To Israelis, who are
only now coming to grips with the traumatic assassination of Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin in 1995, the fear of being caught unawares
or unprepared, much less of reliving such a trauma, is strong.
Prime Minister Ehud Barak surrounded by a security detail in late
May. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- June 4, 2000 -- AMBASSADOR-PROFILE -- John
E. Leigh, Sierra Leone's ambassador to the United States. Leigh an
American-educated businessman and lawyer turned diplomat who has
run the embassy in Washington since 1996 grew up in Freetown, the
capital of Sierra Leone, and was educated at American and
British-run missionary schools. His father worked for what was then
the British colonial government. (Justin Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CHICAGO, Ill. -- June 4, 2000 -- BOOKSELLERS-MEDIA --
Roxanne Coady of the R.J. Julia bookstore, at the BookExpo America
2000 convention. The bookstore will be participating in two new Web
sites designed to promote independent booksellers. The sites hope
to showcase the independents as stores run by booksellers with
personalities as unique and marketable as their books. (Steve
Kagan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PALO ALTO, Calif. -- June 4, 2000 -- ETHERNET --
Technology industry analysts and executives say the rapid
improvements in Ethernet could bring a frenzied pace of change to
the telecommunications world similar to the microprocessor chip's
revolutionary impact on the computer industry in the 1980s. Brian
Lemoff, left, and Lisa Buckman are part of a team at Agilent
Technologies that has produced a device, based on a technology
developed 27 years ago, that is capable of shuttling data at a rate
of 10 billion bits a second. (Thor Swfit/The New York Times)
</P>
