<DOCNO> NYT20000604.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4390 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-R-NY-NUDE-PHOTOS-ART-     06-04 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NY-NUDE-PHOTOS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVE! NUDE! AND LEGAL! ARTIST GETS HIS NAKED PHOTO
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By SHAILA K. DEWAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the moment Sunday morning when the flat, pink glow
of dawn gave way to yellow sunlight and shadow, Spencer Tunick
announced that his photo shoot was complete.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred-fifty-two naked models, who had been lying on an
empty stretch of Delancey Street in Manhattan, under the
Williamsburg Bridge, sprang to their feet and applauded.
</P>
<P>
   The moment was triumphant, or at least worry-free, for Tunick,
who is known for his photographs of nudes in public places, and for
being arrested for taking them. On Saturday, the U.S. Supreme Court
said the city could not stop him from staging such pictures, and
Tunick said he hopes the decision will end a long First Amendment
battle.
</P>
<P>
   With a handful of police officers looking on, Tunick said he was
thankful that he could work without the fear of being arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a victory for the body as an art object, not a sexual
object or a recreational object,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Finney, a frequent model for Tunick, said the photographs,
which often show bodies arranged in abstract forms, emphasized
people's similarities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like when you watch those shows on the Discovery Channel
and you see a herd of antelope,'' Finney said. ``This is like a
herd of naked people. We're so used to looking at the clothes to
define a person.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the shoot was over, on went hooded sweatshirts, silk
skirts, bike shorts and jeans. Many of the models, all volunteers,
headed to Ratner's restaurant, a few blocks away, for a celebratory
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   There, Tunick, 33, moved from table to table, jittery from the
morning's high-speed logistics. A district court judge had granted
him 15 minutes for the shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Tunick began shooting nudes in public in 1992, when he posed a
naked man in front of Independence Hall in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found that people paid more attention to my backgrounds when
I placed a nude person in front of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tunick has been arrested several times on charges that vary from
unlawful assembly to exposure of a person, but the charges against
him have always been dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   When Tunick began to find police waiting for him at the
appointed time and place of his photography shoots, he said he
decided in 1999 to sue New York City in federal court, seeking,
among other things, an injunction to prevent his future arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hess, the city's corporation counsel, said the city had
received no complaints about the shoots. But, he contrasted
Tunick's photography in public to theater productions that viewers
choose to see: ``People who do not choose to watch it are being
exposed to it.'' He .
</P>
<P>
   Tunick said he knew that shooting nude people en masse- was not
always appropriate: ``I don't think I could do this in the middle
of the day in front of Macy's.''.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000604.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4391 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-TRAILBLAZERS-LAKE     06-04 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-TRAILBLAZERS-LAKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS SAVE THEIR BEST FOR LAST TO ELIMINATE TRAIL BLAZERS  

</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant were about to
suffer the most devastating playoff collapse of their careers, a
loss so agonizing it would take only a National Basketball
Association title to live it down.
</P>
<P>
   But something miraculous happened at the Staples Center on
Sunday night, something neither their fed-up legions nor the
Portland Trail Blazers ever expected after controlling Game 7 of
the Western Conference finals for nearly four quarters.
</P>
<P>
   They grew up. O'Neal, Bryant and the Los Angeles Lakers played
like champions, somehow coming back from a 16-point deficit and
rallying to defeat the Blazers, 89-84. The Lakers outscored
Portland, 31-13, including a run of 25-2, in the fourth quarter
after trailing by 71-58.
</P>
<P>
   The end came so suddenly for Portland, the two young stars
showing more resilience than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Leading by 4 points with 45 seconds left, Bryant drove the
middle of the lane and at the last possible second lofted an
alley-oop pass for O'Neal, his 7-foot-1-inch, 330-pound teammate.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who had disappeared for long stretches of the game,
caught the ball with his right hand, cocked it back and dunked it
maliciously, a basket that made the score 85-79 with 41.3 seconds
left and turned the arena into a state of extended delirium.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal finished with 18 points and 9 rebounds and Bryant had 25
points and 11 rebounds. Portland was led by Rasheed Wallace's 30
points.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers face the Indiana Pacers in Game 1 of the National
Basketball Association finals beginning Wednesday night here. They
came close to losing a 3-1 series lead.
</P>
<P>
   A devastating 15-0 run helped their cause. Brian Shaw made two
pivotal 3-pointers during the run, including a bomb from the left
wing with 4:02 remaining that severely damaged Portland's
confidence. That shot tied the score at 75-75 and sent the building
into a tizzy, 20,000 people rising from their seats in yellow
T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice completed a 3-point play with less than six and a half
minutes remaining. He went hard to the goal, laid it in, drew a
foul and made the free throw to give the Lakers their first lead _
49-48 _ since it was 9-8.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith scored the next 7 points on long jumpers, including
one from beyond the top of the arc. When Portland led, 57-51, it
appeared to be in tremendous shape.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers played an awful first half and several times seemed
on the verge of being blown out.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal picked up his third foul with 6:18 left in the second
quarter, swinging his elbows as he tried to create space for
himself around Arvydas Sabonis. Rather than frustrate him, though,
it made him focus and play more effectively.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by 10, the Lakers drew to 3 points after consecutive
baskets by O'Neal inside and a 3-pointer by Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant played with fire, too, making Bonzi Wells and Steve Smith
take impossible shots and making plays on offense. He played 48
minutes on a sprained right foot in Game 6 on Friday. Rather than
practice on Saturday, he underwent therapy for the injury.
</P>
<P>
   If he was sore, the Lakers were hurting worse. They were
struggling badly, and needed Bryant to be superhuman.
</P>
<P>
   He was not, but his 12 points, his defense (3 blocked shots) and
his rebounding (6) were enough to keep the Lakers in the game. He
sent the Lakers to the locker room with momentum by taking a
give-and-go from Ron Harper and dunking underneath to cut
Portland's margin to 42-39.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal had taken only four shots. Wallace was in a groove,
connecting on 6 of 11 attempts, and Pippen was providing all the
intangibles.
</P>
<P>
   An L.A.-Indiana series _ the only matchup that could save the
league from a small-market finals and perhaps the worst televised
ratings in basketball's modern era _ did not look promising.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers were seeking to become only the seventh team in
league annals to overcome a 3-1 deficit in a four-of-seven-game
series and the first Western Conference team to accomplish the
feat. The Larry Bird-led Boston Celtics were the last team to
succeed, stunning Julius Erving and Philadelphia in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   After Game 4 in Portland _ the Lakers' second victory on
Portland's home court _ Coach Phil Jackson described the Blazers as
being ``at death's door.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, no one was home.
</P>
<P>
   All the mental tweaking Jackson attempted backfired and became
used as fodder for Pippen, his former pupil. After victories in
Games 5 and 6, the Blazers suddenly had Jackson and his team on a
psychological ledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know they're a little bit of a fragile team,'' Pippen said
before Sunday's game. ``They don't have the experience. They don't
truly believe in the triangle system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you catch guys like that, you tend to think things are
working in your favor.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was so flustered by recent developments, he eruptedwhen
asked about Sabonis, his counterpart in the key, who helped to
limit the league's leading scorer to 17 points and 7 rebounds in
Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't done anything,'' O'Neal said on Saturday. ``He has
three players helping him. I don't give him any credit at all.
None. Don't ask me about a one-on-one matchup. No one will ever
play me one on one. I've got four players on me. I'm angry because
you asked me about Sabonis. He can't play.''
</P>
<P>
   If the pressure was on anyone, it was on O'Neal to deliver in
only the second Game 7 he ever played. He and Anfernee Hardaway
sent the Orlando Magic to the 1995 finals with a memorable
performance against the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   He became the central theme of the national news media, all of
whom implored the NBA's most valuable player to perform like the
best player in basketball when it mattered most. The lead sports
column in The Los Angeles Times bellowed, ``Superman, where are
you?''
</P>
<P>
   Even Magic Johnson, who directed the Lakers to their last title,
in 1988, and serves as a team vice president and part owner, sensed
the feeling building. ``He needs this so people don't look at him
as a loser,'' Johnson said. ``This is his time. Everyone knows
it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal came late to that realization. He finally dived for a
loose ball with less than nine minutes left in the third quarter,
tumbling into the second row as the Superman theme was cued up over
the public-address system.
</P>
<P>
   Among his litany of self-proclaimed nicknames _ the Big
Aristotle being the most recent _ O'Neal earlier this season called
himself Shaq Kent. But there are no phone booths inside the Staples
Center, no supermen to save the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Only fallible human beings who play basketball for a living. And
against a remarkably resilient team from Portland, they were just
enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
