<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PHONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA PHONE COMPANY CHANGES PLANS FOR NEW NETWORK 
</HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ China's second telephone carrier, China
Unicom, has confirmed that it has abandoned plans to use current
wireless telephone standards known as CDMA, developed by U.S.-based
Qualcomm Inc.
</P>
<P>
   China Unicom, which is preparing to list its shares in Hong Kong
soon, said it still plans to build a network using later-generation
CDMA technology, the official China Daily Business Weekly said on
Sunday. But it said it cannot risk investing in current CDMA
technology that might soon be obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing of construction of a narrow-band CDMA system has
become unfavorable, so we plan to build a wide-band CDMA network,''
an unidentified China Unicom official told the newspaper. ``CDMA''
stands for ``code division multiple access,'' and Qualcomm's
current CDMA technology is a narrow-band technology.
</P>
<P>
   The report is the latest in a wild ride for CDMA's fortunes in
China and Qualcomm's fortunes back home. Talk that China would
scrap its CDMA plans has plagued Qualcomm for over a year. Last
week China Unicom gave conflicting signals on its CDMA stance,
hammering Qualcomm's share price.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm's stock is trading at less than half its January high,
largely because of the uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Given the size of China's potential market, the country's
backing could cement CDMA as a technology standard for the future.
China Unicom had been expected to build a CDMA network capable of
serving 10 million subscribers by the end of this year. And the
company signed a royalty agreement with Qualcomm in February.
</P>
<P>
   But telecommunications analysts have long argued that it made
little sense for China to invest billions of dollars in a new
standard when the country is already largely served by competing
GSM technology and when technology standards are changing quickly
in any case.
</P>
<P>
   China's support of the technology became a political issue
during negotiations over the country's entry to the World Trade
Organization. The United States lobbied heavily for China to open
its markets to CDMA technology and CDMA proponents claimed China
had agreed to back the technology last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's newspaper report said the February agreement with
Qualcomm ``could be canceled.'' Now Qualcomm can only hope to
benefit from Unicom's use of more advanced CDMA technology in the
future, it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
