A4393 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-VICTIM-FIGHTSBACK-LAD     06-04 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VICTIM-FIGHTSBACK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANDING UP TO GANGSTERS COSTS MAN HIS FINGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LISA VAN PROYEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ Despite his fear ofgangs, a 46-year-old man
somehow summoned the courage to turn away a group of drunken thugs
when they tried to get into his apartment complex.
</P>
<P>
   It cost him dearly: The gangsters got inside and used a shotgun
to blast away the machinist's livelihood along with his fingers.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, he underwent surgery, while his wife wondered where
they and their 1-year-old son will live now, and how he will
support them if he can't return to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been back. I want to move,'' said the woman, who
asked not to be identified for fear of retaliation. ``With his
injury, he is going to be disabled.''
</P>
<P>
   Through tears, she called on city officials to take more action
against gangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city government should be more concerned about the people,
and apartment managers should do more thorough background checks on
people,'' she said. ``Whatever happened to my husband I don't want
to happen to anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they believe they know who was behind this
vicious shooting and vowed to deploy extra officers to find the six
to eight gang members.
</P>
<P>
   ``When innocent people and their families are victimized, I
think we need to spend some time on this,'' said Detective Bruno
Pabon of the &UR;  &LR; Los Angeles Police Department's West Valley Division.
</P>
<P>
   The gang members' attack Tuesday _ and the man's refusal to
submit to them _ reflects a growing frustration among residents and
police with gangs in the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   It is a particularly acute problem in the west end of the
valley, historically a placid area of the city, where violent gang
crime rose 12 percent in the first quarter of the year, as compared
with the same period last year. Two people were shot last month on
the handball courts at Canoga Park High School in what police
suspect was a gang-related shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Yet according to LAPD statistics, for the first three months of
this year, violent gang crimes in the valley have decreased, as
compared with the same time period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the complex where Thursday's shotgun attack
occurred said the gangs seem to operate without concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody's worried about what's happening here. It
doesn't make any sense,'' said one neighbor, Jose Barajas.
</P>
<P>
   This incident occurred when at least a half-dozen gang members
peered through the gate of the complex where the machinist lives
Tuesday night and asked him to let them in.
</P>
<P>
   He refused.
</P>
<P>
   They broke the glass next to the gate, got into the complex and
chased the man to his apartment while his wife and baby watched in
horror. First, they threw beer bottles at his apartment, and they
shot into the apartment with a shotgun, hitting the man in his left
hand and chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran into the apartment frightened that they were following
him,'' said his wife. ``The gang was telling him to open the door.
I was terrified.''
</P>
<P>
   When confronted by the shotgun, the man instinctively raised his
left hand to shield his body, so the shot blasted off his pinkie
and ring fingers.
</P>
<P>
   He was in fair condition Friday, but his boss is unsure whether
he will be able to return to work at the Canoga Park machine shop
where he had been providing a good living for his family. There, he
specialized in deburring parts, a skill that requires dexterity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be difficult. We'll have to see what movement he has to
the hand,'' said Ralph De La Cruz, the shop foreman. ``It really
upsets me. He's a good worker and very dependable.''
</P>
<P>
   A co-worker, Denver Rhodes, called for a crackdown on gangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The track record of our court system is written on the streets
of our city, where criminals run free and law-abiding, hard-working
citizens have to lock themselves behind bars at night,'' Rhodes
said.
</P>
<P>
   When the man and his family moved to the area in the 21800 block
of Lanark Street about eight months ago, they were aware of the
gang problems, but the rent was cheap and within a reasonable
distance to ride to work by bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor said this group of gang members has long intimidated
residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hated that they were always outside his apartment building.
He was frightened for his life because he would have to pass by
them when going home,'' the neighbor said.
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
