<SLUG> BC-POOLS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALERT FOR WATER SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JUDI VILLA  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Virginia Geffre worried about the play pool in the
front yard a couple doors down.
</P>
<P>
   A child could easily fall in, and no one might see.
</P>
<P>
   She couldn't bear the thought of little lungs filling with
water. So last week Geffre joined a growing num ber of Phoenix
residents who are calling the Fire Department to report unsafe
pools on their own streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to see a kid drown. I don't care whose kid it
is,'' Geffre said. ``Kids are precious, and people need to protect
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week alone, seven people called on Phoenix firefighters to
check a pool that posed a hazard to children. There have been 83
such calls to the Fire Department this year and 144 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the calls involve breaches in fences at community pools.
Others are about open or unlocked gates that provide easy access to
a backyard pool. Several, like Geffre's, deal with blowup pools
left out front, filled with three to four feet of water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't people get the picture?'' asked Geffre, a
grandmother of seven. ``People need to be aware that kids can drown
in a bucket. To open yourself to something like that is
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials attribute the calls to heightened awareness about
pool safety, and they speculate that people don't know their
neighbors well enough anymore to approach them with such a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not trying to turn in their neighbors,'' Deputy Chief
Bob Khan said. ``They're saying, `Hey, the kids could get hurt.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Firefighter Karee Lansbery recently was called to a Phoenix home
where a family left a 15-foot-long blowup pool filled but unused in
the front yard.
</P>
<P>
   `They just don't think about it,'' Lansbery said. ``Maybe
they've gone inside but they're going to come back out and swim
some more. They forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Lansbery said many people view play pools simply as a toy for
their kids and don't realize they can be just as dangerous as
in-ground pools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you put water in the (play) pool, you're creating a
danger to everybody,'' Lansbery said. ``A little kid could run down
the street, see it and fall in and drown.''
</P>
<P>
   Penelope Pugh said she appreciated the call she got from the
Fire Department about her backyard pool. Pugh was having some yard
work done, and someone apparently forgot to secure the gate. She
has no kids and no pets, so her pool isn't fenced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It heightens my awareness now to check on it every day and at
night and whenever I leave,'' Pugh said. ``It's important that
people are aware and alert because it is such a tragedy that
children fall into the pools and die.''
</P>
<P>
   Six children have drowned in Phoenix this year, one more than
all of last year. Twenty-two children have nearly drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials warn the numbers are bound to get worse. June is
typically the month when the most water incidents occur each year.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors keeping an eye on each other could make a difference,
Khan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just Mom and Dad anymore,'' he said. ``It's all of
us, and if we all work together, then the number of kids that die
and end up in wheelchairs will go down.'' &QL; 
2
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 2309EDT &QL; 
