<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANGELS-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS RALLY TO BEAT DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT MAGOLOFF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Sunday's battle for baseball supremacy in
Southern California was probably what Major League Baseball had in
mind when it introduced interleague play in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The players, managers and coaches for the Los Angeles Dodgers
and Anaheim Angels consistently shifted focus away from the
turf-war theme of the three-game series at Edison Field. But they
still gave the fans - whose offsetting ``Dodgers'' and ``Angels''
chants suggested much greater fan interest - an exciting finish.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels trailed by two runs after seven innings but exploited
Los Angeles' troublesome bullpen for a come-from-behind 8-7 victory
to claim the first series of the season 2-1. The teams meet for
another three games at Dodger Stadium on July 13-15.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's newest player, shortstop Kevin Stocker, scored the
game-winning run when reserve outfielder Orlando Palmeiro was
walked by Antonio Osuna (0-2) with the bases loaded in the bottom
of the ninth inning and two outs. Osuna issued four walks and hit
Tim Salmon with a pitch. He lost the game without allowing a hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (the count) got to (2-0), that's when I started taking,''
Palmeiro said. ``I saw him walk (Troy Glaus before me), and I
wanted to make him throw it over the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   But Osuna never found home-plate umpire Chris Guccione's strike
zone, walking Palmeiro on four pitches. The result: Eleven of the
Angels' last 18 victories have now been by one run and 16 have been
by three runs or less.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' inability to get a hit off Osuna led the Dodgers' to
believe Guccione's strike zone shrunk throughout the game,
culminating with a miniscule window by the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those pitches were close,'' Osuna said. ``I threw a lot of
strikes. For me, I think, I don't know. (The problem) was behind
home plate, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson was a little more straightforward
about the rookie umpire, who was making his major-league debut
behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a real small strike zone to begin with,'' he said.
``Then it got wide a little bit, and then at the end it got a
little smaller. It's a tough way to lose a game, when it's
questionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the take on the strike zone, Anaheim's bullpen got the
job done while the Dodgers' didn't. After starter Jarrod Washburn
allowed seven runs on eight hits and five walks through 5 innings,
Mike Fyhrie and Troy Percival (3-2) combined for 3 innings of
shutout relief. They gave up a combined three hits and struck out
five of the 12 batters they faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to have days when your guys are going to come out
and do the job,'' Angels manager Mike Scioscia said. ``Our bullpen
gave us the opportunity to come back today. Both of our offenses
are very potent, and they did the job when they had to.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers reliever Matt Herges gave up the game-tying runs in the
eighth on an RBI single by Bengie Molina and a run-scoring
fielder's choice for Adam Kennedy (Cal State Northridge). Tim
Salmon (2 for 2) reached base in all five of his at-bats and hit
his 13th homer of the year. Darin Erstad (2 for 5) had his third
consecutive multiple-hit game and leads the American League in that
category with 30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
