<HEADER>
A4502 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-LIBRARY-PARAPSYCHO     06-04 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LIBRARY-PARAPSYCHOLOGY-(1250)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELIEF AND SKEPTICISM MINGLE AT THE PARAPSYCHOLOGY FOUNDATION  

</HEADLINE>
   By LYNDA RICHARDSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A die-hard group of regulars settled into black
folding chairs in the library of an elegant brownstone on the Upper
East Side. They come every month to hear about any and all things
pertaining to the realm of parapsychology.
</P>
<P>
   Once, the lecture was about surviving death. Other times, it had
been on out-of-body experiences, seances, channeling and remote
viewing, a form of clairvoyance.
</P>
<P>
   On this particular night, the audience leaned close to hear
whether Harry Houdini, the magician and escape artist, communicated
a secret message from beyond the grave in 1929 to his widow,
Beatrice, through a man described as a trance medium. The question
has long been pondered among Houdini aficionados.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker, William Rauscher, a retired Episcopal priest and
psychic researcher, did not keep the audience in suspense for long.
He said that it was all a hoax and that the medium, Arthur Ford,
had conspired with Houdini's widow. Rauscher told the audience that
he believed Ford did have psychic abilities, just not in this
instance.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some in the audience wanted the real goods. An intense
little man with coal-black hair raised his hand and asked why
Houdini failed to communicate from the grave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he was dead,'' said Rauscher, as muffled cackles rose
from here and there in the packed library. ``It just didn't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it was the other night at the Eileen J. Garrett Library
of the Parapsychology Foundation. The library is stocked with more
than 10,000 volumes on matters ranging from ghosts and
poltergeists, psychic spies and healing research, to spiritualism.
</P>
<P>
   It is a place where just about any assumption might be
contemplated, and where psychic phenomena are accorded the respect
that they have yet to receive in the material world beyond the
tastefully appointed brownstone on East 71st Street.
</P>
<P>
   The other night, the foundation's executive director, Lisette
Coly, was standing in the hallway, watching the audience watch the
lecturer. Her diminutive 84-year-old mother, Eileen Coly, sat near
the carpeted staircase leading to the second floor. Upstairs is
home to an audiovisual lab, a periodicals room and a rare books
collection, which includes a pigskin-bound volume in Latin that
dates from the 1500s. A taffy-colored cat named Sushi, which lives
in the brownstone, lorded over the front reception desk.
</P>
<P>
   The library has one of the world's largest collections of
parapsychology books, according to Coly. The foundation was
established in 1951 by her maternal grandmother, Eileen Garrett, a
writer and a so-called trance medium who died in 1970. It was
endowed by Garrett's close friend Frances Payne Bolton, a wealthy
Ohio Republican who served in the House of Representatives from
1940 to 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett accepted her psychic abilities as a fact of life, her
granddaughter said, though she also was known for her skepticism.
Coly recalled her as saying: ``Monday, Wednesday and Friday, I
believe in the paranormal. Tuesday, Thursday and Saturday, I don't.
Sunday, I don't give a damn.''
</P>
<P>
   Coly shares her grandmother's ambivalence, though she does not
claim any psychic ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of things that cross my desk that I cannot
understand,'' said Coly, 50. ``I see stuff that is very provocative
and very suggestive of a psychic explanation, and yet I see people
who are harmed by charlatans every day.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Wednesday, Coly was introducing that night's
lecturer, Rauscher, and welcoming the two dozen or so people who
were taking their seats. She wants to raise awareness about
parapsychology by holding more lectures at the library, which is
free to the public. ``Parapsychology wants to look at all this
murky seance stuff in the bright light of day with scientific
methodology.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Coly, a good-humored woman with shoulder-length blond
hair, admits that it can be tough sometimes. When she meets people
for the first time, especially at PTA meetings _ she has two
school-age children _ she plays it safe, saying only that she is
the executive director of a nonprofit foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parapsychology elicits a very strong response, and I don't
want to open that can of worms,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For many of the people attending the lecture, it is precisely
their concern about being ostracized that makes the library such a
comforting place. A middle-aged man, whose business card indicated
that he was a physician and cancer researcher in New York City,
asked to remain anonymous. He said his belief in psychic phenomena
could jeopardize his high-level hospital position.
</P>
<P>
   (The physician is convinced that two of his patients had
out-of-body experiences, with one elderly, comatose woman floating
to the hospital ceiling and watching her own death before she was
resuscitated.)
</P>
<P>
   ``For some people, thinking there is communication from the
other world is very weird,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people would burn us at the stake,'' his female companion
added.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At the library that night, some who gathered had spent much of
their lives contemplating psychic issues. Among them was Dr. Hans
Holzer, an elderly author of dozens of books who describes himself
as a scientific investigator of the paranormal but is more commonly
known as a ghost hunter. His most recent books include ``Hans
Holzer's Travel Guide to Haunted Houses'' and ``Psychic: True
Paranormal Experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Holzer likes to catch up with old friends and hear about new
interpretations of psychic phenomena at the monthly forums. The
other evening, he leaned over to chat with his longtime friend
Martin Ebon. Ebon, 83, has written ``Psychic Warfare: Threat or
Illusion?,'' about Russian military research into the paranormal,
among other books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find the atmosphere is one of openness,'' Holzer said. ``By
and large, there is a nucleus of people like me there every
month.''
</P>
<P>
   Holzer later said he was unmoved by the Houdini lecture. (He is
convinced that a secret code was relayed by Houdini to his wife.)
Holzer pointedly noted that Rauscher has a background as a
magician. ( Rauscher was introduced as belonging to England's Magic
Circle and the International Brotherhood of Magicians.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a waste of time; it had nothing to do with
parapsychology,'' Holzer said sternly of Rauscher's lecture. ``Let
me put it this way: I never trust a magician fully. Magicians
believe firmly that psychic phenomena are all fake.''
</P>
<P>
   Rauscher, the author of a new book, ``The Houdini Code
Mystery,'' insists he is not a psychic debunker. He believes in
extrasensory perception and the mystical experience, but says he
cannot be tricked easily.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Ann Drucker, who teaches in the English department at
Nassau Community College, was also expecting to hear something else
from Rauscher, but because he is a man of the cloth: ``I thought
that he would not find reasons to disbelieve what Arthur Ford had
been saying through his mediumship.''
</P>
<P>
   Drucker, an author who specializes in children's psychic
experiences, has become a regular at the Wednesday night lectures.
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, Drucker and eight other people went to an
Upper East Side restaurant, where they chewed over details of that
night and the world of parapsychology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every night, it's different,'' Drucker said. ``A lot of these
people have been in the field for a long time and have published in
it. It's sort of like a way of having a little community
get-together in the field of parapsychology in New York City. We
catch up with who is doing what, where. It's a small world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 2313EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000604.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
