<SLUG> BC-NY-INMATE-ADVOCATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK BARS PRISONER ADVOCATE, ALLEGING COMPLICITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By NINA SIEGAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An advocate for prisoners in New York has been barred from
visiting state prisons because officials contend she encouraged a
systemwide inmate strike, which was supposed to begin Jan. 1 but
was averted.
</P>
<P>
   The advocate, Alice Green, executive director of the Center for
Law and Justice, has visited state prisons for 20 years as an
liaison between inmates, their families and the state. As an
employee of the New York Civil Liberties Union in the 1970s, Green
said she helped prisoners prepare for their release with job
training and advice on their transition to life outside.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 10 years, Green's Albany-based group, the Center
for Law and Justice, has organized an annual meeting between
prisoner advocates and state lawmakers. Green said she typically
visits state prisons about once a month to plan for the conference
and meet with inmates for other reasons.
</P>
<P>
   But for more than a year, Green said, she has been denied entry
to every prison she has sought to visit. About a month ago, she
said she began calling the State Department of Correctional
Services each day to find out if she was, in fact, being banned.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, she said she received a letter dated May 9 from Glenn
S. Goord, the commissioner of the department, which stated: ``You
are correct. Pursuant to the authority vested in me by law, I have
directed each superintendent to deny all visitation access by you
and any member of your organization.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason, wrote Goord, was that Green posed ``a clear threat
to the safety and security'' of inmates and prison employees. The
letter accused Green's organization of ``encouraging an illegal
systemwide inmate action on Jan.1.''
</P>
<P>
   But Green said she had not ben permitted to enter the prisons
since last spring, months before the inmate action was scheduled.
She said she thought she had been barred because of an incident in
January 1999 in which she unfurled a banner that read ``No More
Prisons'' behind Gov. George E. Pataki while he was giving a
speech. She was arrested but acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, I got an invitation from prisoners at Attica and I
was approved to go in, but then, at the last minute, I was told I
couldn't come in,'' Green said. ``I was told I was a radical,
opposed to prisons, and that was the reason for not letting me
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Green said she did not help foment a prison strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly brought it to the attention of people outside but
I in no way encouraged that strike,'' Green said. ``I had not even
been in the prisons for at least a year, and I've worked in the
prisons for 20 years without incident.''
</P>
<P>
   James B. Flateau, a spokesman for the New York Department of
Correctional Services, said there was no connection between Green's
action at the Pataki rally and the corrections department denying
her prison access. He said members of Green's group were allowed
into the prisons until late last fall, but he declined to comment
further on any role she might have had in a strike.
</P>
<P>
   To avert a strike, many inmates were transferred, two prisons
were placed under lockdown and guards were added.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, no member of the public is allowed into state
prisons without permission from Goord's office.
</P>
<P>
   Green said it will be almost impossible to plan the prison
legislative conference this year without visiting inmates, and her
advocacy on behalf of inmates will be hurt by the ban.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara J. Olshansky, assistant legal director for the Center
for Constitutional Rights in New York, has been following Green's
case. She said she was worried that the ban against Green would
squelch advocacy by other prisoner support organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to be very concerned about saying anything they
believe in, whether inside or outside the prison, because they're
going to be afraid that they will be exiled as well,'' she said.
``Then everyone's First Amendment rights get squashed, both inside
and outside the prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Flateau disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work her group ostensibly is doing is carried on by a
number of groups, and we don't expect there to be any noticeable
impact on the inmate population because she's not there,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
