<HEADLINE>
COPPELL SLUGGER A PRIME PROSPECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK HERRIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COPPELL, Texas _ Most of the tales are true. They may sound a
bit far-fetched, but they happened.
</P>
<P>
   Really.
</P>
<P>
   There are witnesses. More come to see if they will have
something to tell. Jason Stokes, Coppell High School's
super-slugging first baseman, carries with him stories of
gargantuan hits. The kind that prompt the question, ``Did that kid
just do that?''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5, 230-pound Stokes, who hit a state-record 25 home
runs this season, has sent fans buzzing and coaches scrambling for
measuring devices. The recently awarded Gatorade National High
School Player of the Year has what some call ``major-league
power.'' That raw power is expected to land him in the first round
of the Major League Baseball first-year player draft, which begins
today.
</P>
<P>
   The Stokes stories are extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer with the Connie Mack League Dallas Mustangs, Stokes
hit a 525-foot home run at Dallas Jefferson. Over the left-field
fence, over the street, and over the first row of homes. Several
players, including Stokes, later measured the hit.
</P>
<P>
   At Carroll this year, Stokes launched a 500-foot blast over the
left-field scoreboard that hit the school's tennis courts, 145 feet
past the outfield wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got out and measured it,'' Carroll coach Larry Hughes. ``I
had never seen a ball hit like that.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also the estimated 500-foot-plus shot at Trinity
Christian Academy in Addison, over an apartment complex off
hard-throwing David Purcey, also a heavily watched prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball America'' has projected Stokes to go in the first
round. The magazine's predraft projection had Stokes going as high
as No. 4 to the Kansas City Royals. The Royals are one of two
teams, San Diego being the other with the ninth pick, Stokes said
has shown the most interest. ``Baseball America's'' latest
projection has Stokes being selected at No. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Stokes, Jason's father, said he has been told his son
could slip in today's first round _ possibly out of the top 10 _
because small-market teams at the top of the draft are showing
reluctance to pay Stokes the money high picks can command.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason is a top-five pick,'' Bobby Stokes said, ``but they
don't want to pay him as a top-five pick.''
</P>
<P>
   If ``Baseball America's'' predraft projection does materialize,
however, Stokes will be the fourth Fort Worth-Dallas area high
school player to go in the first five picks since 1994. The last
was Arlington Bowie outfielder Vernon Wells, who went No. 5 to the
Toronto Blue Jays in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons of Stokes, though, are geared toward another local
hitting phenom, Ben Grieve, the No. 2 pick overall out of Martin in
the 1994 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to pitch to Grieve,'' said Keller coach Rob Stramp,
who coached against Grieve at Irving Nimitz. ``He'd miss every once
in a while, but with Stokes, he just constantly rockets the ball.
He's the best power hitter in high school I've ever seen. Pitching
to him wasn't worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   As a senior, Stokes' vaunted bat demolished school records. He
touted a .536 average with 62 runs batted in with a 1.330 slugging
percentage. Stokes powered Coppell's 32-3 season that ended in the
Class 4A Region II semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets ``real'' quiet when he's up,'' said Daniel Raudabaugh,
a 13-year-old Coppell fan. ``Everyone wants to see what he's going
to do next.''
</P>
<P>
   Stokes, 18, is regarded as the top power hitter available, and
he is expecting a first-round selection and quick signing. Despite
signing a scholarship with the University of Texas, he doesn't feel
that hinders his signability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to sign as quick as possible and get out and start
playing,'' said Stokes, in his down-home drawl. ``I'm just looking
somewhere in the first round, and I'll be more than happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Before high school, Stokes looked far from a future first-round
draft pick. He was once a 5-10, 245-pound chubby middle school kid
with little athletic ability. Then Stokes hit his growth spurt and
the weights. He grew taller, stronger and got thinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we really considered Jason to be an athlete
until his sophomore year,'' Coppell coach Dave Curliss said. ``Not
until he started to lose some of the baby fat.''
</P>
<P>
   As Stokes grew, so did his reputation. He hit eight home runs as
a sophomore and 13 as a junior. Then he followed with 32 more that
summer with the Mustangs.
</P>
<P>
   His bat speed and his hand strength are what sets him apart.
</P>
<P>
   Curliss said Stokes' bat speed has been clocked as high as 103
mph. That compares with his teammates' average in the 70- to 80-mph
range. Curliss said one scout, who tested Stokes' hands, said his
score was second only to Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very strong human being,'' said one major-league
scout. ``He has tremendous hand strength, which relates to bat
speed, which relates to power.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the power stroke. He hits them where they don't have
any defensive players.''
</P>
<P>
   While scouts rave about his power, he's hardly one-dimensional
at the plate or in the field. Stokes showed running ability by
stealing 12 bases in 13 attempts. He showed contact hitting ability
by striking out only 12 times in 112 at-bats. And he showed arm
strength, which could project him as an outfielder, while playing
some at third base.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Stokes' compact and laser-quick power stroke that make
him a soon-to-be professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a pure hitter and has major-league power, and he's proven
it,'' said Dave Acton, a part-time Toronto Blue Jays area scout.
``The best thing about Stokes is he produced under the amount of
pressure he had.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
