<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-LEHTINEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE-MINDED LEHTINEN CREATING OFFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The day-to-day status reports of Jere Lehtinen's
certain return had become so day-to-day misleading, it seemed his
only use in the playoffs would be as a decoy.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed those reports were to make Edmonton, San Jose and
Colorado think the league's top defensive forward might play at any
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Through two series, despite Stars coach Ken Hitchcock's
insistence on several occasions that Lehtinen would return,
Lehtinen remained a scratch. His recovering fractured right ankle
was still causing him fits. By the end of the second round, perhaps
only his teammates and coaches believed Lehtinen would truly grind
in the corners before the season ended. But the Stars knew.
</P>
<P>
   `` somebody else, maybe ,'' Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor said.
]''Everybody knows Jere is probably working twice as hard off the
ice as we are on the ice,'' Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor said.
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen, who won the Selke Trophy the past two seasons as the
NHL's top defensive forward, finally made his grand return for Game
1 of the Western Conference Finals. Ten games into his comeback and
three games deep into the Stanley Cup Finals, Lehtinen's tenacious
two-way play shows no signs of missing 65 regular-season games and
10 playoff games. He has one goal and four assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have loved to have had a full year together, playing
healthy, playing together,'' Stars center Mike Modano said. ``It's
scary to think what we could have accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   Or not have accomplished if the ankle had sidelined him against
Colorado. His return gave the Stars a fallback when rookie Brenden
Morrow, who had replaced Lehtinen at left wing on the Stars' first
line, went down with his own ankle injury in Game 1 against
Colorado. Lehtinen also was used on the second line in Game 2 of
the Stanley Cup Finals in an attempt to ignite Joe Nieuwendyk, who
hasn't scored in five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We use Lehtinen as a catalyst,'' Hitchcock said. ``When
anybody is not going well, we just put him with Lehtinen. So, if I
am having a bad day, Lehtinen comes for coffee with me. If we need
Nieuwendyk to get rolling, then that is where we put Jere.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock hinted yesterday that Morrow is playing well enough to
jump from the fourth line and rejoin Modano and Brett Hull, which
would allow Lehtinen to play on the second line. Those plans also
hinge on the impending return of Jamie Langenbrunner, who Hitchcock
said he expects to rejoin the lineup today for Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the line is going to be, but it doesn't
matter where everybody goes,'' Lehtinen said. ``We have to get more
shots and get going.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen had the assist on Hull's game-winner in Game 2 against
New Jersey. And, immediately after Hitchcock moved Lehtinen
alongside Nieuwendyk and Jon Sim later in that game, the line
generated scoring chances but couldn't cash in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jere just adds a little different aspect to that
line,'' said winger Scott Thornton, whom Lehtinen replaced. ``He's
obviously a great defensive hockey player, but he can create a lot
of offense in the zone. He's confident with the puck, and he's
poised in the corners, and he is not afraid to go battling and get
his nose dirty.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
