<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS DON'T WANT HISTORY TO REPEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the resident Civil War buff, Ken Hitchcock was asked
yesterday if the Stanley Cup Finals reminded him of anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it isn't Pickett's Charge that we're running here,''
the general of the Stars said.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1863, history tells us, the combined Confederate forces
of Maj. Gen. George E. Pickett advanced on Union troops at
Gettysburg. Results were disastrous. A total of 6,240 Confederate
soldiers lay dead, wounded or missing after the battle.
</P>
<P>
   The Union's great advantage was better firepower.
</P>
<P>
   Feel free, therefore, to draw your own Stanley Cup Finals
analogies here.
</P>
<P>
   Do the Stars, down two games to one heading into tonight Game 4
at Reunion Arena, have the firepower to overcome the New Jersey
Devils? Or are they walking into a disaster?
</P>
<P>
   Like a Zamboni driver on prescription cold medication, the Stars
have careened up and down the ice in this series.
</P>
<P>
   At times, they have appeared groggy, and at times inspired. For
brief spells, they have fought like bulldogs _ for others, they've
simply played like Chihuahuas.
</P>
<P>
   With each downhill plunge of the roller coaster, the knee-jerk
reaction has been to forecast the Stars' imminent demise. But the
defending champs have always rallied to prove otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me it's 2-1,'' Hitchcock said. ``We win tomorrow, and all
you people are telling us how great we are.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars seem to know the drill as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of experience in the dressing room,'' defenseman
Darryl Sydor said yesterday. ``I think that obviously you couldn't
like what happened the night before. But the next day is a new day,
and we realize what we have to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we just play a little bit more desperate, a little bit
more under control, and keep it simple. Keep it simplified and get
things done.''
</P>
<P>
   History, not unlike Hitchcock's Civil War reference, is not on
the Stars' side. In the Cup finals, the team that won Game 3 to
take a 2-1 lead has gone on to win the championship 18 of the past
21 times. The Stars will be trying to do something that has only
been accomplished twice in the past 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   Do they have enough firepower?
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing opinion is that that is largely up to Joe
Nieuwendyk, who, history also reminds us, won the Conn Smythe
Trophy as the playoffs' Most Valuable Player last year.
</P>
<P>
   Getting injured winger Jamie Langenbrunner back should help.
Langenbrunner has a high intensity style that forces the other team
to pay attention. If his wounded knee allows him, he should provide
instant energy to whatever line he plays on.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars need him. They need contributors, not watchers.
</P>
<P>
   Are they a tired team, as some have suggested?
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't make sense. If anything, after eight months, they
can finally see the carrot at the end of the stick. They know the
satisfaction that is finally within their grasps.
</P>
<P>
   When asked yesterday, Hitchcock turned the question around on
the writers who wrote it.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, they're probably tired of covering this,'' he said. ``They
want to get on with the Cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   A frustrated team does tend to look like a tentative team, and a
tentative team can appear to be tired.
</P>
<P>
   But as Hitchcock said, ``I thought the qualities of New Jersey
came out after they scored their first goal, and it frustrated us.
I think both teams have been able to control the other's
frustration level.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were prepared to play patient and strong defensive
hockey, even though the game was 1-1, and we were trying to push
the issue too much and got burned because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for tonight, he conceded, is to see that the
frustration doesn't set in again.
</P>
<P>
   The roller-coaster season suggests that the Stars will rebound
and knot the best-of-seven series. But Finals history warns that
the defending champs might be waging a losing battle.
</P>
<P>
   Firepower wins, no matter how many times the general yells
charge.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
