<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETMUSIC-MP3-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DIVING INTO THE MP3 MOSH PIT  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Kick.com's new storefront on a rough but
redeveloping block in downtown San Francisco looks more like a
nondescript employment office than the high-tech home of yet
another Net music startup.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the Mission Street site is the perfect symbol of the
challenges awaiting a company jumping into the Internet's latest
fad, online music.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of companies like Kick.com are setting up shop on every
virtual street corner at a dizzying pace, each hoping to stand out
from the crowd with technology that will capitalize on the
popularity of MP3s and Napster's maverick song-swapping program.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco and Silicon Valley have become hotbeds for Net
music startups, each hyping new technology that promises to
``revolutionize'' Internet music and the music industry, giving
consumers a less complicated and more legal way to find, review and
enjoy digital songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are excited about music,'' said Kick.com's Matthew
Skyrm, chief executive and co-founder of the 20-employee startup.
``That's one reason you see a lot of the best people at companies
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Kick.com, ArtistOne.com and MuBu.com in San Francisco, along
with Gigabeat Inc. in Sunnyvale, Calif., are just some of the local
companies that have just launched or are close to launching their
Web sites and products.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just a local phenomenon. A company called
eMikolo.com, based in New York and Israel, last week unveiled the
eMikolo Entertainment System that lets users legally download
digital music, videos, books and other content.
</P>
<P>
   They are all trying to rise above the din already created by
only slightly older Audio Alley players like Listen.com, Liquid
Audio, Emusic.com, Vitaminic.com and, of course, the wildly
popular, legally embattled Napster.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are excited about this, not just about MP3 piracy, but
they see the market is interesting,'' said Manish Vij, CEO of
Pointera, a Palo Alto, Calif., company that will launch today,
offering its own new ``legitimate file sharing'' program that
allows users to share all types of files, not just music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, Napster has hit a nerve. Now (the question is) how do
we make money on this?'' said Vij, who is launching Pointera as a
new division of his year-old Internet music and video sharing site,
Spinfrenzy Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Field Already Glutted
</P>
<P>
   Analysts, though, say many of the Net music startups won't be
around to hear the answer because the field already may be too
crowded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not all of them are going to make it,'' said Malcolm
Maclachlan, media analyst for International Data Corp. ``There's
going to be a real contraction in the number of viable music
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, the online music world was sparsely populated by
about a dozen companies straining to be heard in the wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   That was only about three years ago, when the MP3 music
compression format was gaining popularity among college students
but was not even on the radar screens of the $40 billion-a-year
recording industry.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with MP3 firmly planted in the pop-culture lexicon, there
are hundreds of such companies around the country, said Ric Dube, a
senior analyst at Internet and entertainment research firm Webnoize
Research of Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Habits Hard to Change
</P>
<P>
   Fading fads like online health and online pet supplies were like
the tail wagging the dog, Dube said. They hoped to convince
consumers to abandon old habits and get their health tips or pet
supplies in a new way, through the Web.
</P>
<P>
   But online music has been an easier sell _ many consumers have
adopted the technology with ease, which is causing the music
industry to change its pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking example so far has come from San Mateo,
Calif.'s Napster Inc., the 1-year-old company behind a freely
distributed software program that allows users to find and swap MP3
files easily among themselves via an Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   The Napster program first spread like wildfire across college
campuses, but it's no longer unusual to find older Napster-ites
with a thousand songs stored on their computer hard drives.
</P>
<P>
   The program gained notoriety as some college campuses banned it
for taking up too much Internet bandwidth.
</P>
<P>
   And the Recording Industry Association of America, representing
the biggest record companies, and individual artists Metallica and
Dr. Dre, have sued Napster, saying the shared songs violated the
nation's copyright laws. And Napster was also the subject of a
congressional committee hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The controversies have landed Napster in national headlines in
major publications, including the cover story of this week's
Newsweek.
</P>
<P>
   A new report by Web research firm Jupiter Communications Inc.
said Napster users, who were posting a vast library of 55 million
music files, were a demonstration of ``the music industry's failure
thus far to satisfy online consumer demands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Napster is popular because that's where the content is,'' Dube
said. ``Our economy is based on supply and demand. That's `demand,'
not `pretty please.' ''
</P>
<P>
   More and More Believers
</P>
<P>
   The new bumper crop of startups believes that demand points to a
lucrative market ripe for companies that can make Net music easier
for consumers to use, while at the same time generate new profits
that will keep entertainment companies and artists happy.
</P>
<P>
   The Jupiter report projected that, by 2003, downloadable songs
will account for only 5.7 percent, or $146.6 million, of overall
online sales of music, including CD sales. But the report also said
Napster's success hints that a subscription-based model could boost
downloadable song revenues much higher.
</P>
<P>
   And since music itself strikes a chord across every demographic
slice of the population, executives at the new startups believe
that making money from online music is only a matter of finding the
right formula.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's such an explosion of demand for music online,'' said
Erin Turner, one of three recent Stanford University business
graduates who formed Gigabeat.com, which launched last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``With so many niche sites, it's becoming a marketplace of mass
confusion for the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Gigabeat bills itself as a ``one-stop online gateway for music
fans,'' with Web-based programs to find downloadable music files
and Internet radio stations. A ``GigaSpiral'' tool allows users to
discover new songs and artists similar to the singers and music
they already like.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said she and her co-founders, Wilburt Labio and Narayanan
Shivakumar, understand their audience. She said the three met while
they were students at Stanford, and just like the audience they are
trying to reach, they were ``all music fanatics as well as Web
geeks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're part of the first generation that grew up with the
Internet as part of our daily lives, from school to work to play,''
Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   John Adams, founder of Imagine Radio, said his new company,
MuBu, has the edge over other new Net music companies because it is
steered by veterans of technology and the entertainment businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those smart MBA graduates don't respect the fact that there's
actually more to it than writing a business plan,'' said Adams,
whose company is shooting for a formal launch of its online music
technology later this month. ``We're not just one of those
Internet.com kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Kick.com's Matthew Skyrm believes his company knows what the
recording industry wants. On May 10, the company launched a beta of
its Kick.com Music Companion, a Web-based technology that will
allow music companies to deliver ``personalized'' news and
information directly to fans.
</P>
<P>
   Offering More Information
</P>
<P>
   The technology, for example, will recognize a music fan is
listening to a Smashing Pumpkins CD and automatically find upcoming
band concert dates, a discount on band sweatshirts or breaking news
on band members.
</P>
<P>
   ArtistOne.com, housed in an office in San Francisco's
tech-centric South Park area, launched its site May 15. It hopes to
give new and emerging musicians the chance to use downloadable
music to build their careers, which is a similar mission embraced
by other firms, like Garageband.com and Riffage.com.
</P>
<P>
   ArtistOne, which gives artists a 70 percent cut of sponsorship
revenues, is already up to about 500,000 unique users, CEO Michael
Moroney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all assume this is a market that is going to grow,'' said
Moroney, a former venture capitalist who wanted to start his own
company. ``Nobody expects this is going to be an industry that
peters out. This is the future of how people will get their
entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows how these new startups will fare in the future,
especially as the major entertainment companies such as Sony and
America Online-Time-Warner start to muscle in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them are going to go away,'' Dube said. ``Even the
ones that do succeed, they won't succeed in their own names.
They'll be acquired and will go away.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, while there's ``certainly too many out there for
them all to succeed, the more noise, the better it is for
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
