<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-04 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4519 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BASEBALL-WEBSITE-SFCH     06-04 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-WEBSITE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 A'S WEB SITE A REAL HIT WITH BASEBALL FANS  &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ While the San Francisco Giants were building a
stadium, the Oakland Athletics were building a Web site.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Giants are selling out every game at their new
$319 million ballpark and are killing their cross-bay rivals in
attendance.
</P>
<P>
   But the A's new and improved Web site has already generated more
than $1 million in revenue from tickets, licensing and merchandise,
and the team hasn't had to spend a dime.
</P>
<P>
   The A's have already brought home more than $300,000 in revenue
from online ticket sales this year, which by the end of May matched
the total generated from online sales during the entire 1999
season.
</P>
<P>
   Also, as the airline industry has learned, the A's have found
the Web a good way to fill seats at the Network Associates Coliseum
that would normally go unsold.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, according to industry sources, the A's are getting
$667,000 from a five-year licensing agreement with ACS Sports.com,
the Baltimore company that's building up the Web presence of the
A's and eight other Major League Baseball teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to have a top-of-the-line Web site,'' said David
Alioto, the A's vice president of sales and marketing. ``With the
proximity of the East Bay to Silicon Valley, it was really
important for the A's to be out on the forefront on that.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, the A's sold about 617 tickets online per week, about
21,000 for the season, said Jim Bloom, the A's director of
marketing and communications. Since April 1 of this year, when the
team's new redesigned Web site at  &LR; www.oaklandathletics.com &LR;  went
live, online sales have jumped to 1,800 a week and the average is
still climbing.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 percent of the A's group ticket sales have come through
the Web. And the team sold seats in four luxury boxes by offering a
Mother's Day special only through the Web site, Bloom said.
</P>
<P>
   The team's overall attendance isn't strong: Before this
weekend's three-game interleague series with San Francisco that
pulled in season-record crowds and included many Giants fans, the
A's drew 397,516 fans. That was only 16,208 more than at the same
point in 1999. In one embarrassing moment in May, the A's drew
about 6,836 fans on a day that their top minor-league team in
Sacramento had 14,111.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Giants played before sell-out crowds of 40,930
every game. Through 26 dates, the Giants drew 1,064,180 fans, a
whopping 501,712 more than at the same point last year at windy
3Com Park.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing attendance for the two clubs, though, may be like
comparing apples and oranges because the lure of the new Pacific
Bell Park is responsible for the Giants' surge.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Giants have also tapped the power of the Web. During
a special weeklong sale of single-game tickets in February, the
Giants sold 176,353 seats, 67,535 of them online, said Tom
McDonald, the team's senior vice president of consumer marketing.
</P>
<P>
   And about 55 percent of tickets that the Giants are releasing a
few days before each game, seats originally held for the league,
visiting teams or other reasons, are being purchased through the
team's Web site at  &LR; www.sfgiants.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the future,'' McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   But with a far smaller season ticket base to rely upon, the A's
have to be more creative in marketing the team. Bloom said the Web
is proving to be that vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   So the team is using online newsletters, online chats with
players and expanded pre- and post-game broadcasting on the Web to
draw fans to merchandise and tickets.
</P>
<P>
   During the weekend, the A's experimented with interactive
statistics tied to television broadcasts that allow fans to, for
example, instantly learn outfielder Matt Stairs' batting average
with runners in scoring position and two outs.
</P>
<P>
   Internet analysts have predicted pro sports teams will
increasingly find new sources of revenue from the Web, especially
from online ticket sales, and the A's are helping to lead baseball
into a new high-tech era.
</P>
<P>
   A report by online research firm Jupiter Communications Inc.
predicts that by 2003, fans will spend about $3 billion a year
online on sporting goods, apparel, footwear and, most of all, game
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Because there are more games and more seats to sell in a season,
Major League Baseball has the most to gain of any of the four major
professional sports leagues, said Patrick Keane, Jupiter's senior
sports analyst. But he said the other three leagues _ the National
Football League, National Basketball Association, and National
Hockey League _ have been more aggressive on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball has really missed significant opportunities to do
things online,'' such as taking advantage of the Mark McGwire-Sammy
Sosa home run derby in 1998, to draw fans to team Web sites, Keane
said. ``Baseball is the slowest and most foolhardy of the leagues
to go online.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets have also had success selling online tickets,
according to Spiro Alafassos, ACS Sports' vice president of
content. Still, most baseball teams have been slow to use the Web,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a learning process for a lot of teams,'' Alafassos said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
