<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-ABATE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOSCOPE: BIOTECH FIRMS GO TO BAT FOR PROPOSED DEFERRED
TAX  INCENTIVES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California Gov. Gray Davis has proposed
increasing the state's R&AMP;D tax credit from 12 percent to 15
percent, a boost that will please high-tech and other business
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But to benefit from a tax credit, companies must make profits
and pay taxes. And of roughly 700 biotech firms in the Bay Area,
only a handful make enough money to take advantage of any tax
breaks.
</P>
<P>
   That's why biotech industry leaders will be looking to
Sacramento over the next few weeks, as Senate and Assembly leaders
decide whether to modify Davis's research and development
incentives to make them more useful to biotech startups.
</P>
<P>
   The forum for action will be the Assembly-Senate conference
committee on the state budget.
</P>
<P>
   Biotech execs are hoping lawmakers will sweeten the R&AMP;D pie in
one or two additional ways: first by lengthening the time companies
can carry forward their losses until they are profitable; and/or
letting money-losing companies sell their tax credits or losses to
tax-paying firms.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Ted Lempert, D-San Carlos, authored the first
proposal, which would let firms carry forward losses for 10 years.
Losses now expire after five to eight years, according to Cristin
Carty, a lobbyist for the California Healthcare Institute, an
industry group based in La Jolla, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Letting biotech companies deduct past losses amounts to a sort
of R&AMP;D credit. But execs say it often takes longer than five to
eight years to take a new drug from research, through clinical
trials and to the market, making this tax incentive worthless
because it expires before they get into the black.
</P>
<P>
   Lempert's bill, AB1774, passed the Assembly last week and
although it didn't clear the Senate, legislative rules allow it to
be considered as part of the budget mix.
</P>
<P>
   The second proposal, AB2328 by Assemblywoman Denise Moreno
Ducheny, D-San Diego, would allow money-losing biotech firms to
sell a portion of their R&AMP;D credits, as well as these same
operating losses, subject to various restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Ducheny's bill will also be included in the final conference
committee deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   But since trading tax credits would be a new idea for
California, it stands a lesser chance of making the final cut.
</P>
<P>
   Still, biotech execs are hopeful that even if the Ducheny
proposal gets axed, Lempert's legislation will make it to the
governor's desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to get something out of the state Legislature
that says it recognizes the long lead times of pharmaceutical
development,'' said CHI President David Gollaher.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO ROAD? Many states would like a piece of California's
biotech industry, but Michigan takes the cake when it comes to
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Using funds set aside from its share of the tobacco lawsuit
settlement, Michigan is promising up to $50 million in matching
grants to firms that locate new research facilities in the
Wolverine State.
</P>
<P>
   The grant program is being coordinated by the Michigan Economic
Development Corp. in Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan, lest you forget, is one of the frigid states bordering
the Great Lakes, bodies of water which thaw out each summer just
long enough so that billions of mosquitoes can breed.
</P>
<P>
   Companies receiving grants for relocating in Michigan will not
be allowed to use state funds to underwrite their bug repellent
expenses. But if you say you read of their offer in The Chronicle,
I'm sure state officials will be happy to provide complimentary
parkas emblazoned with the state's unofficial motto: ``If you don't
like snow, why did you move here?''
</P>
<P>
   BIO-X: Stanford University has begun to spend the $150 million
that Silicon Valley entrepreneur Jim Clark donated last year to
encourage experiments that combine biology with engineering and
computer science.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford has dubbed this interdisciplinary effort Bio-X, and in
announcing the first 17 research grants last week, university
authorities began spelling out how they plan to bring Clark's
vision into focus.
</P>
<P>
   After Clark made his gift, an anonymous donor kicked in another
$60 million to the Bio-X fund.
</P>
<P>
   The grants, which averaged $412,000 and totaled $7 million, will
support current and new projects including:
</P>
<P>
   -- Technology for tracking fluorescent dyes inside living
animals. Stanford pediatrician Chris Contag has created chemical
tags that can be detected through the skin, diminishing the need to
dissect experimental animals. This technology is being commercially
exploited by Xenogen, a biotech firm in Alameda, Calif. The
Stanford lab will presumably advance the state of the art.
</P>
<P>
   -- Creation of a new center to study the brain. How does a mass
of neurons create thought, speech, memory and experience? Answering
these questions will pull together specialists in instrumentation,
neuroscience, and a host of other fields.
</P>
<P>
   -- Developing a supercomputer visualization center. Clark must
love this. Creating realistic visualizations was the core of his
first business, Silicon Graphics. Stanford hopes to develop
techniques that would allow researchers to ``feel'' a single
molecule.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford has set aside $120 million to construct a new building,
named for Clark, to serve as the nucleus of the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, rival UC Berkeley is pursuing its own
interdisciplinary plan, which it calls its ``Health Sciences
Initiative.'' (Score one point for Stanford for the sexier
moniker.)
</P>
<P>
   Berkeley hopes to raise $300 million in private donations to
create new laboratories where physicists and chemists will rub
elbows with molecular biologists and mechanical engineers. One
modest donor has already contributed $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Such interdisciplinary efforts make sense given that modern
biology views living creatures as organic machines. They're built
of molecules instead of gears or wheels. They're run by genes not
software. But be they man or microbe, they're really just systems
to be taken apart, studied, repaired, perhaps even improved.
</P>
<P>
   So long as science views life as the ultimate tinker toy, why
not gather all the kids together in one room and see what they
dream up. It may be the next frontier in science and technology.
</P>
<P>
   CROP STOMPERS: A bill that would increase fines for vandalizing
experimental crops has cleared the California Assembly and is
awaiting action in the state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblywoman Helen Thomson, D-Davis, wrote AB2510 in response
to a series of incidents in which vandals destroyed genetically
engineered crops being grown by University of California
researchers.
</P>
<P>
   None of the vandals has ever been arrested, in part because the
incidents hardly seemed worth investigating since the penalties for
roughing up plants have been minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson's bill would allow the courts to fine convicted vandals
twice the value of the crop they destroyed, after factoring in the
scientific expertise and the time it took to create the seeds. As
for the damage done to the UC crops, that amount could be hundreds
of thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation passed the Assembly 67 to 6 and now awaits
action in the Senate Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Thomson's office said if the bill clears the
Senate and is signed by the governor, it would make California the
first state to create special penalties for vandalizing genetically
engineered crops.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at  &LR; abate(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
