<SLUG> BC-TECH21-NORR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TECH 21: MORE VIRUSES DUE _ ARE YOU READY?  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Last week's Killer Resume menace turned out to
be a bit overblown, but in view of the ``success'' _ from a virus
writer's perspective _ of previous attachment-borne worms like
Melissa and ILoveYou, it's safe to assume that others, possibly
even more dangerous, will be showing up soon.
</P>
<P>
   So if you care about your data and your time, doing what you can
to safeguard your system from such threats should be a top
priority. Unfortunately, even an up-to-date antivirus program won't
necessarily protect you, because the attachments these new bugs
travel in look like legitimate files; only until they've begun to
do their damage can antivirus engineers provide updates that
identify and destroy them.
</P>
<P>
   And with the emergence of ``complex polymorphic'' versions _
viruses that change some of their attributes each time they
replicate _ it's getting harder and harder for the guys in the
white hats to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   That's why computer-security experts recommend extreme caution
about attachments _ and why I wish people would stop sending them
when they could just as well put what they have to say in plain
text in the body of their message.
</P>
<P>
   I've gone so far as to set up my copy of Outlook so it
automatically fires off a nasty reply whenever it receives a
message with a file attached. It reads:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an autoreply to all messages containing attachments.
In the wake of Melissa and the Love Letter, it should be obvious
that such files are a menace to life as we know it. Unless you've
made prior arrangements with me to send an attachment, please put
what you want me to see into the body of your message _ a simple
copy and paste will do the trick _ then remove the attachment and
send the message again. If you don't, I'm probably not going to
read the attachment. (I couldn't care less about your fancy
formatting, so don't worry about that getting lost.)''
</P>
<P>
   Setting up Outlook to deliver this message was so complicated,
it would take more space than I have to explain how I did it. If
you want instructions on how to make your own version, e-mail me
and I'll send you a step-by-step guide.
</P>
<P>
   A better solution, though, is probably to install Microsoft's
Outlook E-mail Security Update, a patch for the company's Outlook
98 and Outlook 2000 programs that is designed specifically to
reduce the danger from these e-mailed viruses. Unfortunately, the
update is late _ it was originally slated for release the week of
May 22 _ but it may be out by the time you read this. You can
download it, or at least read the latest on its status, at
 &LR; officeupdate.microsoft.com/2000 &LR;   &LR; /articles/out2ksecarticle.htm. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Don't delay _ you owe it to yourself, to everyone listed in your
address book and to the community at large to do what you can to
stop this threat.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER KIND OF SELF-DEFENSE: Lawrence Lessig, the Harvard (soon
to be Stanford) professor who has emerged as a leading authority on
the new legal challenges of the Internet Age, weighed in on the
privacy issue with an interesting op-ed piece in Wednesday's Wall
Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that he shares the skepticism I expressed here last
week about the strategy pursued so far by the Federal Trade
Commission and most privacy advocates in the United States: trying
to pressure Web site operators to post ``privacy policies''
explaining what information they collect and what they do with it.
</P>
<P>
   As he puts it, ``More words won't advance privacy in cyberspace.
Consumers will simply ignore the clutter.'' He points out that many
sites already comply with the demand for posted policies _ with
pages that explain that the site operator intends to use the data
it collects about you to its own ``maximal commercial benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   But while I argued for the kind of solution Europe has adopted _
strong, clear laws limiting what kinds of information companies can
collect and what they can do with it _ Lessig doesn't have much
faith in this approach, at least in the American context. (He
doesn't spell out why in the Journal piece, but he does in ``The
Architecture of Privacy,'' an interesting, albeit 2-year-old, draft
essay posted on his Web site _
 &LR; cyber.law.harvard.edu/works/lessig/architecturepriv.pdf. &LR; )
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he focuses on the technical aspects of the problem and
possible technical solutions. The very design of the Internet, he
writes, ``makes it extremely easy for data about individuals to be
collected and profiled'' and ``extremely difficult for individuals
to know that this profiling and tracking is taking place.''
</P>
<P>
   The solution to a code problem, Lessig argues, is a ``better
code.'' Specifically, he points to the Platform for Privacy
Preferences, or P3P, a standard under development by the World Wide
Web Consortium that establishes a framework for standardized,
computer-readable privacy policies ( &LR; www.w3.org/P3P &LR; ). According to
Lessig, it ``would make it easy for companies to explain their
practices in a form that computers could read, and make it easy for
consumers to express their preferences in a way that computers
would automatically respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the fact that the standard isn't even complete yet,
I'm not convinced it gets to the root of the problem. After all, it
would be even easier for companies not to collect, sell or trade
personal information at all; the trouble is that they want to, and
I think they have to be compelled not to. Even Lessig admits his
plan is no substitute for strong privacy legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I see a lot of merit in his ``code'' approach, especially
given that there's little prospect of effective legislation passing
anytime soon. But I'm more intrigued by developing a ``better
code'' that doesn't depend on the good will of Web site operators.
</P>
<P>
   One such program that sounds promising is OptOut, written by
Steve Gibson _ the same programmer whose Shields Up security page
I've recommended previously. It's not complete yet, but a free,
limited preview is available now, and the full program, which
Gibson will sell at a price he hasn't yet disclosed, is due July 1.
</P>
<P>
   OptOut targets only one aspect of the privacy problem, but it is
one of the scariest: software that uses your Internet connection,
without your knowledge or explicit permission, to send information
about your system or your activities back to a Web site that you
previously visited.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson calls it ``spyware,'' and it is apparently more common
than you might think. Gibson is building a database of such
software. OptOut is just a 31-kilobyte application, and at the most
basic level all it does is check your PC for the presence of known
spyware programs and give you the option of removing them.
</P>
<P>
   The main OptOut page is at  &LR; grc.com/optout.htm &LR; . While you're
there, don't miss Gibson's mini-essay on ``The Ethics of Anonymous
Surveillance for Profit'' at  &LR; grc.com/oo/ethics.htm &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   THE GATE IN YOUR PALM: If you live, work or play in San
Francisco (or Boston, Chicago, New York or Washington), and you use
a Palm handheld _ or you're looking for an excuse to get one _
check out some nifty new software scheduled for release today by a
company called Vindigo.
</P>
<P>
   Packaged in separate editions for each city, the software is a
directory of restaurants, stores, movies and clubs. Two versions of
the San Francisco package are available _ one with restaurant
listings from Zagat, the well-known survey-based rating service,
the other with comparable data from The Chronicle and SFGate.com.
Both versions have nightlife listings from The Chronicle and
SFGate, plus a shopping directory provided by an outfit called
Inshop.com.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, New Yorkers and Washingtonians can choose between
versions with restaurant data from Zagat or the New York Times or
Washington Post, respectively. The New York edition has been out
since late March.
</P>
<P>
   The programs require a Palm III or later, or an equivalent unit
from a Palm OS licensee, with a minimum of 300 kilobytes of memory
free. The San Francisco version I've installed, with data from The
Chron and SFGate, takes up 330 kilobytes.
</P>
<P>
   Vindigo provides lots of useful ways to search and sort the
data, and it lets you add your own note, but two features in
particular really grabbed me:
</P>
<P>
   -- You start by telling it where you are (or intend to be), by
picking two intersecting streets from alphabetical lists.
Thereafter, at least by default, it lists restaurants in the
categories you specify by their distance from you. (If you prefer,
you can sort by name, cost or rating.) And for any place you're
interested in _ restaurant, store, theater or club _ you can tap on
a tab labeled ``Walk'' and get step-by-step directions for getting
there from the intersection you picked.
</P>
<P>
   -- The data is updated every time you synchronize your Palm with
a Windows PC that has an Internet connection. (Support for the Mac
is due later this month.) That's especially valuable for movies:
Assuming you connect to your PC regularly, it always has up-to-date
info about what's showing where and when.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, the Vindigo software is totally free _ by the time
you read this, all versions should be available for downloading at
 &LR; www.vindigo.com &LR; . To support its service, the company sells ads
that appear in your Palm _ when you're reading about a restaurant,
you might get an ad from a nearby competitor. That makes me a
little nervous, but at least the ads are discreet _ they're
text-only, and they appear only in the bottom three lines of the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   A company called Landware ( &LR; www.landware.com &LR; ) has been offering
a Palm version of Zagat restaurant ratings for 11 cities since last
summer, but it used to charge $29.95 per city for the Zagat data;
last week, probably in anticipation of the Vindigo release,
Landware announced that it's now offering data for all 11 cities
for what was the price for one.
</P>
<P>
   But the Landware offering still doesn't include entertainment
and shopping listings, it's not updated regularly and it doesn't
deliver walking directions.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
