<SLUG> BC-AMD-CHIPS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AMD ADDS SOME JUICE TO NEW ATHLON CHIP  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Advanced Micro Devices will launch a new version
of its Athlon processor Monday that could put the chip back in
front of Intel's Pentium III in the high-end PC performance race,
at least for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   The new Athlon, code-named Thunderbird, will be available
immediately at clock speeds between 750 megahertz and 1 gigahertz,
or 1,000 megahertz. Although AMD has been shipping Athlons at
similar speeds since March, the new ones will deliver better
performance in many applications because they incorporate 256
kilobytes of performance-enhancing ``Level 2,'' or L2, cache memory
directly on the chip.
</P>
<P>
   Previous Athlons came with twice as much L2 cache memory _ 512
kilobytes _ but it was located on separate chips, not on the
processor itself; that slowed down the processor's access to the
data and instructions stored in the L2 cache.
</P>
<P>
   Now that this memory is built into the chip, the chip will be
able to retrieve such information at full speed. In most situations
that makes overall performance faster, despite the smaller size of
the new on-chip cache.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's Pentium III processors have had on-chip L2 cache since
last October. That advantage enabled them to outperform Athlons
running at the same clock speed in many performance benchmarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Athlon has a superior microarchitecture, but it wasn't
outperforming the Pentium III the way it should have,'' said Keith
Diefendorff, editor in chief of the Microprocessor Report, an
influential industry newsletter. ``In fact, AMD was getting its
clocked cleaned in a lot of benchmarks.''
</P>
<P>
   The off-chip cache was the biggest reason for this performance
shortfall, so the new design should fix most of the problem,
Diefendorff said. ``I don't expect any huge changes in market
share, but it should make AMD a little more competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   The advantage could be only temporary, though. In the fourth
quarter, Intel is scheduled to release a new version of the
Pentium, code-named Willamette, that will ``go clearly ahead in
clock frequency and maybe in overall performance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunnyvale, Calif.'s AMD continues to produce some Athlon chips
with the older cache design, but will gradually switch over to the
new version, according to spokesman Byran Longmire. The transition
should be complete by the end of September, he added. The new
version will be identified in packaging and advertising by a yellow
starburst logo with the words ``performance-enhancing cache
memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Demand for the Athlon has been ``very strong,'' but AMD is
keeping pace, Longmire said. The chip has brought the company new
business from several PC makers _ most notably Gateway _ because
Intel has been unable to meet demand for its Pentium III chips.
</P>
<P>
   In April, AMD reported its best quarter ever, including sales of
more than $1 billion and net income of $189 million, well above
analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the new Athlons will be made at an AMD plant in Austin,
Texas, but others will come from the company's new,
state-of-the-art production facility in Dresden, Germany. While
chips from Austin will, like traditional microprocessors, use
aluminum for their internal wiring, Athlons made in Dresden will
use copper instead.
</P>
<P>
   While that approach improves yields at high clock frequencies,
Diefendorff said, the advantage is only marginal with current
``.18-micron'' production technologies; the real benefit will come
over the next year or two, as the industry moves to .15- and
.13-micron processes.
</P>
<P>
   Intel isn't expected to begin producing copper-based chips until
sometime next year. AMD's head start, Diefendorff said, will give
it more learning time with the new material, which involves
significant changes in production technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, Intel is very, very good at these things,''
he said. ``I'm not betting it will be a problem for them.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
