<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELCHER CLOSE TO RETURNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT MAGOLOFF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The stalwart performance turned in by the
Anaheim Angels' bullpen in Sunday's 8-7 victory against the Dodgers
wasn't enough to shift questions away from the starting rotation,
which has had only two pitchers healthy for the entire year.
</P>
<P>
   The starter closest to returning is Tim Belcher, who is
scheduled to come off the 60-day disabled list and make his first
rehab start for Triple-A Edmonton today. He is expected to make two
starts in the minors and may be ready to pitch for the Angels as
early as June 15.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Bottenfield and Scott Schoeneweis have been the only
healthy starters for the duration of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically lost our starting rotation, and we're slowly
rebuilding with Ken Hill, Tim Belcher and Jason Dickson getting
healthy,'' manager Mike Scioscia said. ``We're looking for them to
come back and contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   One starting pitcher the Angels aren't worried about is Jarrod
Washburn, who experienced tightness in his shoulder that forced him
out of his last start on May 29 after five innings. Washburn had a
poor outing against the Dodgers on Sunday, giving up seven runs on
eight hits and five walks, but his shoulder is fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no problem,'' Washburn said. ``It wasn't that bad. I
took some anti-inflammatory medicine and got some treatment, and
that knocked it right out.''
</P>
<P>
   Movin' on down: Second baseman Adam Kennedy was on a tear after
he joined the Angels at the beginning of the season, but his
numbers (.276, 4 homers, 30 RBI) have leveled off considerably.
</P>
<P>
   With Kevin Stocker's addition to the roster on June 2, Scioscia
saw the opportunity to move Kennedy, a Cal State Northridge
product, to the No. 9 spot in the batting order with Stocker taking
over the No. 2 spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a rookie I think he was pressing a little bit, so we made
the decision to drop him down in the order and hopefully that will
help him relax,'' Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia said Stocker's higher on-base percentage (.386-.322),
along with his veteran status, made him a better fit for the No. 2
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Stocker said he's been No. 2 in the lineup less than 15 times at
the major-league level but did hit there regularly in the minors.
After Sunday's game, in which he scored the winning run, he said he
would bat in any position but feels confident about being No.2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an idea when I go up to the plate about what the
two-hole is,'' Stocker said. ``You have (Mo) Vaughn behind you and
(Darin) Erstad in front of you, which is a pretty good combination
to be sandwiched between. In certain situations I know I can take
pitches. With Mo behind me, guys are going to try to come after me
and I'd see more fastballs than if I was batting in the ninth hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wants to put me in the four hole, that's fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-04-00 2351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
