</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS GIVE L.A. QUITE A SCARE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For their climactic matinee debate Sunday against the Portland
Trail Blazers, the Los Angeles Lakers had all the factors aligned
in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   They were playing at their gleaming new edifice, the Staples
Center, in front of a frenzied crowd emblazoned in gold ``I Love
LA'' tee-shirts supplied by a local television station.
</P>
<P>
   They had not lost three consecutive games the entire season, and
they were coming off two consecutive losses to the Trail Blazers in
this best-of-seven Western Conference championship series.
</P>
<P>
   They had the NBA's Most Valuable Players, Shaquille O'Neal on
their side, as well as Jack Nicholson, Dustin Hoffman, Denzel
Washington, Samuel L.Jackson, Steven Speilberg, Dyan Cannon and
various other celebs set to give them vocal support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to win,'' said the Laker owner, Jerry
Buss, moments before game time as he sat serenely in his luxury box
suite. ``I felt nervous before the fifth and six games when we
could have clinched the series. But I feel calm today because this
team always wins when it has to.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Jerry Buss was right.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers did win, as they were supposed to do.
</P>
<P>
   They beat the Trail Blazers 89-84 to advance to the NBA finals
against the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   But not before giving the entire Los Angeles basin one colossal,
gigantic, exasperating heart seizure/nervous
breakdown/hyperventilation.
</P>
<P>
   Whew!
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure ol' Doc Buss thought the Lakers would be struggling
mightily for the first 36 minutes---only to play some of the most
memorable basketball in their glorious history during the final 12
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, near the end of the third quarter when they trailed by a
71-55 score, the Lakers were on the threshold of enduring the
latest humiliation on an L.A. athletic scene that in recent years
has seen two NFL franchises, the Raiders and Rams, depart, two
baseball teams, the Dodgers and Angels, bumble and bumble, two
hockey teams, the Kings and Mighty Ducks, seldom qualify for the
playoffs, and one NBA team, the Clippers, become national
laughingstocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers had gone on an 18-2 spree during that period,
and the Lakers seemed destined to end their season in the same
disappointing manner they had the past three years since Shaquille
O'Neal joined the team.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed as though the Lakers were going to suffer the most
bitter loss since that infamous Game 7 flameout against Bill
Russell and the Boston Celtics in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed as though the Lakers were going to be victimized by
the dreaded L.A. Athletic Funk, as the Trail Blazers were doing the
impossible---making Shaquille O'Neal disappear for most of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is set up for Shaq in this game,'' said an
interested observer, Magic Johnson, beforehand. ``He'll have the
crowd on his side. This is the perfect time to prove his greatness,
and to prove that he belongs among the great players in NBA
history.''
</P>
<P>
   But most of the game Shaquille O'Neal was reduced to being
nothing more than the tallest spectator at the Staples Center,
especially during that horrendous third period when he took only
two shots and scored nary a point.
</P>
<P>
   There were even some fans headed for the exit as that quarter
came to a conclusion, with the Laker reserve guard, Brian Shaw,
drilling a three-pointer to draw his team within 13 (71-58).
</P>
<P>
   But then a strange thing happened.
</P>
<P>
   Rasheed Wallace, Scottie Pippen, Steve Smith and all those other
doughty Trail Blazers began missing shots, one after another, an
incredible 13 in a row.
</P>
<P>
   And the Lakers came storming back, as they have throughout a
season when they posted the best regular season record, 67-15, and
then scuttled Sacramento and Phoenix in the earlier playoff rounds
before coming up against the resilient Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Shaw kept making three pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant, the 21 year-old prodigy who recently gave his
Marina High fiancee a mere $100,000 engagement ring, continued to
be a whirlwind all over the court, as he scored points, grabbed
rebounds, handed out assists and energized his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, Shaquille O'Neal, silenced the previous three
quarters by Portland's double and triple teaming tactics, came
alive, making important baskets and free throws and grabbing vital
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   And, with 42 seconds left, with the Lakers holding a 4-point
lead (83-79), with the audience roaring wildly, with the Trail
Blazers stunned, Kobe Bryant lofted a pass above the basket toward
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   And Shaquille O'Neal, who has accomplished everything in the NBA
but win a world championship, who has had to live with the
can't-win-the-big-ones label that Wilt Chamberlain once had to live
with, grabbed the ball with one hand and slammed it ferociously
through the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' trauma was over.
</P>
<P>
   They had achieved a stirring comeback for the sporting ages.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers had qualified for the finals for the first time since
1991 when they faced the Chicago Bulls, and they have a chance to
win their first NBA title since 1988 when they beat the Detroit
Pistons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of fun out there,'' said Kobe Bryant after his
25-point, 11-rebound, 7-assist masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   He did.
</P>
<P>
   But I doubt all those beleaguered L.A. fans had much fun until
that final period when the Lakers went on their glorious 31-13
spree to spare themselves wide-spread ridicule and spare their
followers a summer of terrible heartbreak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
